u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-NY-DRUG-DIVERTER-NYT &LR;      08-08 0471
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NY-DRUG-DIVERTER-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
VACCO SAYS MAN LED RING IN ILLEGAL SALE OF MEDICINES 
</HEADLINE>
   (af)  
 By MONTE WILLIAMS   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ A Bronx man who is suspected of leading one of the
largest black-market prescription drug operations in the state was
indicted Friday after more than $1 million worth of prescription
medicine was found in his apartment, the authorities said.
</P>
<P>
   The suspect, Elvin Mendez, 27, is accused of running the
operation by buying prescription drugs from street-level dealers,
stockpiling them and reselling large quantities to middlemen who
then sold them to pharmacies throughout the nation.
</P>
<P>
   The street-level dealers typically either bought the drugs from
Medicaid patients for a fraction of their cost, stole the drugs
from hospitals or clinics, or enlisted the help of medical
professionals who could write and fill prescriptions, the
authorities said.
</P>
<P>
   Mendez was indicted after a six-month investigation in which
investigators said they found plastic bags stuffed with AZT, the
expensive AIDS medication, and other drugs at his Bronx apartment
last spring.
</P>
<P>
   Investigators from state Attorney General Dennis Vacco's
Medicaid fraud unit also found a large number of empty prescription
bottles, counterfeit drug manufacturers' labels, seals and
packaging inserts, the attorney general's office said.
</P>
<P>
   Mendez is charged with one count of criminal diversion of
prescription medications and prescriptions in the second degree, a
felony, and faces up to seven years in prison if he is convicted.
He was arraigned in state Supreme Court in the Bronx and was being
held in $50,000 bail. Mendez has pleaded not guilty.
</P>
<P>
   ``This increasingly common scam, known as drug diversion, costs
taxpayers millions of dollars,'' Vacco said, ``and also potentially
places the public at great risk because the drugs that are diverted
from regulated channels of distribution are often expired,
mishandled and potentially unsafe.''
</P>
<P>
   Mendez is accused of paying only a fraction of the cost for
powerful drugs. Among the drugs the authorities said they found
were Invirase and Viracept, two AIDS medications; Biaxin, an
antibiotic; Procardia, a heart medication; Prozac, an
antidepressant, and Proventil, an asthma drug.
</P>
<P>
   Pointing to inconsistencies in the laws for such offenses, Vacco
has proposed stiffer penalties for drug diversion. ``A drug
diverter who is caught selling a $1,100 bottle of medication would
be slapped with a felony,'' he said. But if Mendez had been
prosecuted solely for the $1 million worth of prescription drugs
stashed in his apartment, he would have been subject to only a
misdemeanor charge, Vacco said.
</P>
<P>
   Most prescription medications that are diverted through the
black market end up on the shelves of pharmacies, Vacco said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
