<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FHS-CEO-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GELLERT TAPPED TO HEAD FOUNDATION HEALTH
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
BY GREGORY J. WILCOX  
 c.1998 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ Foundation Health Systems Inc., the nation's
fourth-largest publicly traded managed care company, promoted Jay
M. Gellert to its top management post.
</P>
<P>
   Gellert, previously Foundation Health's president and chief
operating officer, is now president and chief executive officer,
succeeding Dr. Malik M. Hasan, who is retiring.
</P>
<P>
   One of Gellert's chief goals will be boosting member confidence
in the managed care system.
</P>
<P>
   ``The primary focus we have is managing the company so people
view us as partners with their doctors and hospitals in providing
better care, not ... giving people the impression we are depriving
them of medical care,'' Gellert said.
</P>
<P>
   Hasan will continue as chairman of the board but will resign
from that post and from the board sometime between January and May,
the company said. A new chairman will be selected at that time.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is a natural, evolutionary step in the growth of FHS. I
have, for some time, wanted to step aside as CEO,'' Hasan said in a
statement.
</P>
<P>
   Gellert credited Hasan with making Foundation Health, which has
annual revenue of nearly $9billion, a major player in its field.
</P>
<P>
   ``There are very few people in any field who have built
companies from scratch to a Fortune 500 level,'' Gellert said.
</P>
<P>
   In 1985, Hasan founded QualMed, a predecessor to FHS. Through a
series of acquisitions he built QualMed into a multistate, managed
health care company with operations concentrated in the West.
</P>
<P>
   QualMed went public in 1991 and merged with Health Net in 1994
to form Health Systems International.
</P>
<P>
   Hasan designed the company's expansion into northeastern
markets.
</P>
<P>
   Last April, the company merged with Foundation Health Corp. and
now has 4.3million members enrolled in health plans in 18 states.
</P>
<P>
   Analysts said the management change is not surprising.
</P>
<P>
   ``Jay Gellert has been running the company and doing a good
job,'' said Todd Richter, a Morgan Stanley Dean Witter Discover &AMP;
Co. analyst who has put a ``neutral'' rating on its shares.
</P>
<P>
   X X X
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
