A4224 &Cx1f; taf-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-NY-RAMIREZ-POLITICS-N     08-08 0780
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NY-RAMIREZ-POLITICS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
A BRONX POLITICAL LEADER EVOKES THE BOSSES OF OLD 
</HEADLINE>
  (js) 
 By JONATHAN P. HICKS   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Four years ago, when Roberto Ramirez became the first
Hispanic county political chairman in the state, he took the reins
of a Bronx Democratic organization whose influence was a mere
shadow of its glory days.
</P>
<P>
   Like its counterparts in the other boroughs, the Bronx
organization may never reclaim the clout it had when ``Boss''
Edward Flynn had easy access to Franklin D. Roosevelt in the 1930s
and '40s, and when Charles Buckley boasted in the 1960s of being
able to deliver 500,000 votes. But Ramirez has demonstrated that
whatever cogs of a political machine remain in the Bronx, he
commands them with a measure of control.
</P>
<P>
   In his years at the helm of ``County,'' as the Democratic
organization is known, Ramirez has achieved a degree of party
discipline unusual in the Bronx since the days of the old bosses.
His organization has kept the number of intraparty primary battles
to a minimum, raised substantial amounts of money and delivered
solid Democratic results in general elections. When the city,
despite a large Democratic edge in registration, voted
overwhelmingly last year to re-elect a Republican mayor, the
Democratic candidate, Ruth Messinger, carried only one borough: the
Bronx.
</P>
<P>
   ``In terms of results, he's got one of the most effective
organizations in the party,'' said Carl McCall, the state
comptroller, who is running for re-election this year. ``It's clear
that all the elected officials are lined up behind him. When I go
for support, I don't have to go to six different leaders. He can
pull together everyone else in the borough.''
</P>
<P>
   Ramirez plays down any suggestion that he might be the closest
thing on the political scene to the bosses of old. ``I want people
to have their say,'' Ramirez said. ``I want people to believe that
they have someone running the organization who hears their concerns
and ideas.''
</P>
<P>
   Ramirez's detractors denounce him as an autocrat unwilling to
listen to anyone who does not share his vision of how _ and by whom
_ the Bronx should be governed. Some suggest that his tireless
efforts to dissuade potential challengers to incumbents are
fundamentally undemocratic.
</P>
<P>
   None of the critics are more vociferous than Pedro Espada Jr., a
former state senator from the Bronx who is Ramirez's major
political nemesis.
</P>
<P>
   In fact, Ramirez's confrontation with Espada has now landed the
chairman in the thickest controversy of his stewardship. Espada has
accused Ramirez of using illegal tactics to pressure him to stay
out of a new race for a state senate seat. Espada claims that
Ramirez offered to ask District Attorney Robert Johnson to call off
an investigation into the finances of a health clinic operated by
Espada if the former senator withdrew his candidacy. Ramirez has
vehemently denied that he made any such threat.
</P>
<P>
   The accusation has caused a stir among Bronx politicians and
drawn attention to Ramirez's tactics in pursuing his major goal:
keeping primary battles, particularly threats to incumbents, to a
minimum. (In much of the Bronx, the Democratic nominee is all but
assured of winning the general election.)
</P>
<P>
   Several would-be insurgent candidates suggested that Ramirez
first used gentle persuasion, often calling in potential
challengers for a chat at the party's headquarters in the
Westchester Square section. He urges candidates to forgo their
electoral aspirations in the short term and work within the
organization, postponing their candidacy for another day.
</P>
<P>
   If a challenger persists in a campaign, the next step is often
to attack his election petitions. Teams of lawyers hunt for flaws
that could invalidate petition signatures, forcing the challenger
to pay for lawyers and consultants to fight back.
</P>
<P>
   Ramirez acknowledged that he sought harmony in the ranks by
urging would-be challengers to work with the organization rather
than run against incumbents, though he said his efforts relied
simply on cordial persuasion.
</P>
<P>
   ``When you have bruising primaries, where there is little
temperate discourse, people harm each other so badly that they
cannot work together after the race is over,'' Ramirez said. ``And
so, to the extent that you can avoid a primary, you try to do so.''
</P>
<P>
   Ramirez's influence reaches beyond the Bronx: he is chairman of
a statewide organization of Hispanic legislators, whose annual
conference, Somos El Futuro , lures state and national political
figures. For officials running for statewide office, the conference
is considered an important symbolic stop.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
