u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BKN-PLAYERS-PAY-NYT &LR;      08-08 0635
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKN-PLAYERS-PAY-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ARBITRATOR SETS HEARING DATE TO DECIDE IF PLAYERS GET PAID 
</HEADLINE>
   (af)  
 By MURRAY CHASS   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Negotiators for the National Basketball Association and its
players have no idea when they will next meet at the bargaining
table, but they learned Friday that they will confront each other
at the arbitration table on Aug. 24.
</P>
<P>
   John Feerick, the arbitrator for NBA grievances, set that date
for a hearing on the union's grievance over the league's failure to
pay the players who have guaranteed contracts salaries during the
league's lockout. He scheduled a second day, if it becomes
necessary, for the following day.
</P>
<P>
   During a meeting with the arbitrator Friday, lawyers for the two
sides expressed a desire to have the hearing on different dates.
The union pushed for next Friday; the league proposed a date after
Labor Day.
</P>
<P>
   But under the compromise schedule Feerick selected, he could
have a decision by Labor Day. The timing of the decision is
important because the two sides may not hold any negotiating
sessions until they know the outcome.
</P>
<P>
   ``While we had hoped for the hearing to be sooner,'' said
Jeffrey Kessler, a union lawyer, ``the importance for us is the
decision will come out significantly before the start of training
camps. We would hope to have a decision by Labor Day. That timing
works for the players, so we're happy with it.''
</P>
<P>
   The outcome of the hearing will be critical to the negotiations
for a new collective bargaining agreement because whichever side
wins, it will gain immense leverage in the bargaining.
</P>
<P>
   If the players win and the league has to pay the approximately
220 players (out of 410) while they are locked out, the cost would
be tremendous, especially if the dispute delayed the season and the
teams had no revenue coming in. The union says that players with
guaranteed contracts have salaries totaling nearly $800 million.
</P>
<P>
   A victory for the league would place greater pressure on the
players, who would stand to lose millions of unrecoverable dollars.
</P>
<P>
   Unlike major league baseball, which began putting lockout
clauses in player contracts about 10 years ago, NBA teams have
ignored that form of self-protection. Kessler said only one player,
whom he declined to identify, has a contract clause saying he would
not be paid during a lockout.
</P>
<P>
   ``There is no lockout language in other contracts,'' he said.
``They could have negotiated that clause. Since they didn't, they
are obligated to pay the players their salaries.''
</P>
<P>
   Jeffrey Mishkin, the league's chief legal officer, said the
league would have no comment on the case. ``We'll have more to say
as this thing develops,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Mishkin did acknowledge that the New York regional office of the
National Labor Relations Board has asked the league to provide a
written statement in connection with the unfair labor practice
charge the union filed last month. He said the statement would be
delivered to the NLRB next week.
</P>
<P>
   The union, which says there cannot be a lockout because the
players do not go to work until October, contends that what the NBA
has actually done is unilaterally change the conditions of
employment before the two sides negotiated to impasse. During the
lockout, teams are not permitted to sign free agents, and that is
one change, the union argues.
</P>
<P>
   The union has asked the NLRB to seek an injunction in federal
district court that would end the lockout and allow the league's
normal schedule to go forward while the two sides negotiate.
</P>
<P>
   It was an injunction won by the labor board in 1995 following a
similar charge by the baseball players union that prompted the
players to end their strike and return to work while their lawyers
negotiated a new collective bargaining agreement.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-08-08-98 0010EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
