<HEADER>
A4230 &Cx1f; tta-z
u w &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-R-CLINTON-STARR-1STLD     08-08 0938
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-R-CLINTON-STARR-1STLD-WRITETHRU-875(2TAKES)-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
JUDGE SAYS STARR'S LEAKS MAY HAVE VIOLATED RULES 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (Eds: Repeating for all needing.)  (lb) 
 By JAMES BENNET   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ A federal judge has found that prosecutors
investigating President Clinton's relationship with a former intern
may have violated federal rules by providing protected grand jury
testimony to journalists, according to court papers that were
unsealed Friday.
</P>
<P>
   In a rare ray of good news for the White House, Judge Norma
Holloway Johnson of U.S. District Court declared that Kenneth
Starr, the Whitewater independent counsel, may have broken the
ethical code governing criminal investigations, in his remarks to
reporters.
</P>
<P>
   Finding that Clinton's lawyers had compiled a persuasive list of
potential violations by Starr's office, she said in her ruling on
June 19 that the prosecutors now carry the burden of proof and must
demonstrate their innocence in a hearing to avoid contempt
citations and possible penalties.
</P>
<P>
   Starr appealed aspects of the ruling, delaying the hearing. On
Monday the U.S. Court of Appeals dealt a setback to Clinton. It
ruled that to prevent the disclosure of more secret information,
the president's lawyers could not question prosecutors themselves
during the hearing, nor subpoena documents, as Judge Johnson had
decreed.
</P>
<P>
   The appeals court did not address the substance of the
accusations against Starr, and its ruling will probably not affect
the grand jury investigation. All the court motions and decisions
related to the appeal of Judge Johnson's ruling were released
Friday by the appeals court, the District of Columbia U.S. Circuit
Court of Appeals.
</P>
<P>
   Starr has repeatedly denied that his office illegally slipped
grand jury secrets to reporters. Dozens of members of his office
submitted affidavits to the judge declaring that they had not
disclosed any protected information cited in a laundry list of news
articles and broadcasts compiled in February by David Kendall, the
president's personal lawyer.
</P>
<P>
   But in an opinion crackling with anger, Judge Johnson swatted
aside the affidavits as defining the secrecy rules ``too
narrowly,'' and complained of ``the serious and repetitive nature''
of the leaks.
</P>
<P>
   She cited comments by Starr quoted in the magazine ``Brill's
Content'' that he and his deputy, Jackie Bennett, spoke anonymously
with reporters. She challenged his quoted assertion that it did not
violate federal rules to disclose what witnesses had told
prosecutors or federal agents before they testified.
</P>
<P>
   Judge Johnson also wrote that in May, Starr publicly praised as
``magnificent'' a ruling by her against a White House claim of
executive privilege. The ruling was sealed, Judge Johnson said with
unmistakable scorn, so Starr's comment both confirmed its existence
and revealed that it was favorable to him.
</P>
<P>
   ``Confirming the existence and substance of a sealed court
ruling presents a prima facie violation'' of the rules, she wrote,
and ``a violation of the court order not to discuss the ruling.''
</P>
<P>
   In a statement on Friday, Starr said that he would provide the
court with evidence to assure it ``that we are committed to an
investigation that is conducted thoroughly, fairly, professionally,
and in full compliance with the rule of law.''
</P>
<P>
   Since January, when Starr began looking into whether Clinton
lied under oath in denying a sexual relationship with Monica
Lewinsky and tried to cover it up, the White House has complained
bitterly about press reports on the investigation's progress that
were based on anonymous sources. Fanning public suspicion of the
prosecutors, Clinton's advisers and lawyers have repeatedly accused
them of violating federal rules.
</P>
<P>
   Republicans responded by accusing the White House itself of
leaking the information to discredit the prosecutors. Under the
federal rules, witnesses before a grand jury may describe their
testimony, but prosecutors and others with direct access to it are
bound to secrecy.
</P>
<P>
   The dispute has put news organizations in a paradoxical
position. Besides the leakers themselves, reporters covering the
Lewinsky investigation are the only ones in Washington who know the
truth of the accusations against Starr. Yet because they have
guaranteed their sources anonymity in exchange for information,
they are unable to inform their readers, listeners or viewers.
</P>
<P>
   In her decision, Judge Johnson cited news reports by several
organizations, including CBS News, the New York Daily News, and The
New York Times.
</P>
<P>
   Judge Johnson's June 19 ruling was sealed, so White House
lawyers and advisers say they have stayed silent about it to avoid
committing the very transgression that so irritated her. They were
as delighted on Friday at the unsealing of the documents as fidgety
children for whom the recess bell has finally rung.
</P>
<P>
   ``For the first time in the 20-year history of the Independent
Counsel Act, a federal court has found prima facie evidence of
potential criminal wrongdoing by an independent counsel,'' said
James Kennedy, a spokesman. It is unlikely but possible that a
judge who finds that prosecutors deliberately leaked grand jury
secrets could refer them for disbarment or perhaps even criminal
prosecution.
</P>
<P>
   Kendall, the president's private lawyer, said in a statement:
``The endemic and casual disclosures of grand jury information
which have characterized the past seven months'' of the
investigation ``are highly unprofessional and utterly
indefensible.''
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE _ OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   The White House was particularly pleased with Judge Johnson's
ruling because she has been widely perceived as favoring Starr,
having rejected repeated efforts by Clinton's lawyers to assert
various forms of legal protection.
</P>
<P>
   The release of the documents followed by one day Ms. Lewinsky's
appearance before a grand jury, in which she contradicted a
previous sworn account and testified that she and the president had
had a sexual affair.
</P>
<P>
   In his own statement, Starr said that in prompting a hearing
Kendall had faced a ``minimal'' burden of proof of illegal leaks.
All he had to do was put together a list of articles and broadcasts
that referred to ``sources in Starr's office'' and made similar
attributions.
</P>
<P>
   ``Newspaper articles and media reports supporting the allegation
may be capable of various interpretations,'' Starr said. ``They may
even be erroneous.''
</P>
<P>
   In a filing with the U.S. Court of Appeals on July 10, Clinton's
lawyers went so far to as to argue that the investigation of the
prosecutors was at least as important as the investigation of the
president. The prosecutors, they wrote, ``are public servants
endowed with extraordinary power to conduct a grand jury
investigation.''
</P>
<P>
   Judge Johnson had given permission to Clinton's lawyers to
question members of Starr's office about their contacts with the
press, with the discovery process to begin on July 11. But the
appeals court, which had previously blocked the discovery while it
weighed the case, found that this approach would improperly impede
Starr's investigation into the president ``at a crucial juncture,''
and also risk the same sort of disclosure of grand jury secrets
that started the dispute.
</P>
<P>
   Instead, it ruled, Judge Johnson must conduct the hearing
herself. If she is not satisfied with Starr's argument for his
innocence, she may then take further steps, including appointing a
``special master or other individual'' to conduct a further
investigation.
</P>
<P>
   The Appeals Court wrote in its decision that charges of
violating grand jury secrecy were ``not to be taken lightly.'' It
quoted Justice Felix Frankfurter as saying that to have a
prosecutor feed reporters information is to turn the state ``into a
conscious participant in trial by newspaper.''
</P>
<P>
   Starr took no testimony Friday. But in a further sign that
Capitol Hill is girding for the eventual delivery of his report on
the Lewinsky matter, Democrats on the Judiciary Committee announced
that they had hired three more lawyers to serve on their
investigative team.
</P>
<P>
   They include Abbe Lowell, a Washington litigator and lecturer,
who will serve as chief investigative counsel; Lis Wiehl, a
prosecutor from Washington state; and Deborah Rhode, a professor of
law at Stanford University and legal columnist.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
