<SLUG> BC-SMART-KID-NYTR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BOY GENIUS' NEXT FEAT _ SLEEPING IN 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Calif., Tenn.)  (js) 
 By TIM TESCONI   Santa Rosa (Calif.) Press Democrat   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   SANTA ROSA, Calif. _ Michael Kearney, a former Santa Rosa whiz
kid who graduates Saturday with a master's degree in biochemistry,
plans to take a semester off before pursuing a doctorate degree at
Purdue or the University of California at Berkeley.
</P>
<P>
   After all he's only 14 and in no real hurry to become Dr.
Michael Kearney.
</P>
<P>
   ``I just want to take some time and be a kid for a little
while,'' said Kearney, who experts classify as ``severely gifted.''
</P>
<P>
   This brainy boy was talking in complete sentences when he was 6
months old and was reading soup can labels at 14 months. When he
was 3 he watched Jeopardy and and blurted out responses, often
before the TV contestants.
</P>
<P>
   He graduated from Santa Rosa Junior College when he was 8 and on
Saturday gets his master's degree in chemistry from Middle
Tennessee State University in Murfreesboro, southeast of Nashville.
</P>
<P>
   ``Last time I graduated I asked for a car,'' Kearney said. ``I'm
asking for one again but I don't think I'll get it because I'm
still not old enough to drive.''
</P>
<P>
   Kearney holds three Guinness world records, including being the
youngest high school graduate in the history of mankind and
finishing college at age 10. He's up for two more Guinness records:
enrolling in graduate school full time at age 11 and receiving a
master's degree at 14.
</P>
<P>
   Kearney considers himself a normal kid. His career goal is to
become a game show host. Or a geologist. Or cancer researcher.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't think there is any difference between me and other
kids my age, except I go to a different school. That's it,''
Kearney said in a phone interview this week from Murfreesboro.
</P>
<P>
   His parents, Kevin and Cassidy, say their son's brilliant mind _
in constant need of academic stimulation for his insatiable
intellect _ is both a blessing and burden.
</P>
<P>
   ``From the start, it appeared to Cassidy and me that when
Michael was not allowed to learn new things he was actually in
pain,'' said Kevin Kearney. ``We never pushed Michael, he pushed
us.''
</P>
<P>
   The Kearneys' other child, Maeghan, 13, also is ``severely
gifted'' and doing college-level work.
</P>
<P>
   When Michael Kearney was 4 he was doing fifth-grade level work.
His parents put him in a Montessori program in the Puget Sound area
of Washington state where they lived at the time. Soon after that
they moved to Santa Rosa, but moved away in the early '90s.
</P>
<P>
   When he was 5 Michael was ready for high school but no Sonoma
County school would accept a child so young. His parents taught him
at home and he earned his high school diploma when he was 6. That's
when he enrolled at Santa Rosa Junior College, the youngest
community college student ever in California.
</P>
<P>
   The Kearney family credits SRJC administrators with looking
beyond Michael's age and allowing him to enroll based on his
intellect.
</P>
<P>
   In 1993, Kearney graduated from SRJC with high honors. He then
polished off a bachelor of science degree at the University of
Southern Alabama. The family then moved to Tennessee.
</P>
<P>
   Kearney said just being a kid for the next semester includes
playing video games, shooting hoops and sleeping until noon. And
not fretting over chemical formulas and complex research projects
at Middle Tennessee State where he has been enrolled since January
1996.
</P>
<P>
   ``The research for my master's in biochemistry was heavy work
and very time consuming. I would be in the laboratory until 9
o'clock at night and sometimes until 3 in the morning. Now I'm
done,'' Kearney said.
</P>
<P>
   Although he has mastered the intricacies of biochemistry,
Kearney really wants to be a game show host _ an ambition he has
held since he was toddler. He was a game show fanatic at 8 months.
</P>
<P>
   ``I would love to be a game show host. I like the speed and how
fast you have to think,'' Kearney said. ``Besides it's so much fun
watching people screaming about winning an Amana freezer.''
</P>
<P>
   (Tim Tesconi writes for The Press Democrat in Santa Rosa,
Calif.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
