<HEADLINE>
PENALTY KICK ENOUGH FOR UNITED TO BEAT BURN, 1-0
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
 
By TROY PHILLIPS 
c.1998 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   DALLAS _ They call him El Diablo, and he played a devil of a
good game last night.
</P>
<P>
   D.C. United midfielder Marco Etcheverry, one of Major League
Soccer's do-everything rare specimens, did enough against a Dallas
Burn team intent on reinventing its season.
</P>
<P>
   Etcheverry's back-heel flick pass to Roy Lassiter drew a
57th-minute penalty kick that Lassiter converted, all D.C. United
(20-5) needed to beat the Burn (11-12), 1-0, before 9,437 at the
Cotton Bowl.
</P>
<P>
   Etcheverry perfectly manipulated an upfield chip by John Harkes.
Burn goalkeeper Mark Dodd was forced to slide-foul Lassiter, who
had plenty of room to score.
</P>
<P>
   ``You hate to lose it on a PK,'' Dodd said. ``But you know
you're going to be tested by Etcheverry. They've got attack to
spare.''
</P>
<P>
   Two-time MLS champion D.C. became the league's first club to
clinch a playoff spot and ended Dallas' winning streak at two.
Dallas has split one-goal games against MLS' top teams after
beating Los Angeles.
</P>
<P>
   ``I thought it was our best game of the season, to be honest,''
Burn coach Dave Dir said. ``I hate to say that on a losing cause.
In games like this, little things make a difference.''
</P>
<P>
   D.C. and Dallas unloaded every trick except a finishing touch in
a scoreless first half. An apparent goal by Etcheverry was negated
when officials ruled Dodd trapped a save on the line just inside
the near post.
</P>
<P>
   It wasn't the last time Etcheverry took aim or the last time
Dodd denied him. Etcheverry hammered a running shot off Dodd and
had the Dallas keeper darting all over his line on D.C. corner
kicks.
</P>
<P>
   Dodd made Etcheverry pay once for being tentative. The All-Star
midfielder had a shot lined up, but instead tapped inside to
Lassiter, giving Dodd enough time to recover for one of his seven
saves.
</P>
<P>
   While Etcheverry, Lassiter, Jaime Moreno and Ben Olsen put the
heat on Dodd, the Burn offense also struck a deliberate tone. Jason
Kreis was a visible organizer in the midfield, stepping in front of
D.C. defenders to spawn promising counterattacks.
</P>
<P>
   Kreis and Burn forwards Dante Washington and Mickey Trotman
ultimately couldn't convert. Trotman had his moments, but offsides
and an untimely shirt-tugging foul cost him.
</P>
<P>
   ``We kept fighting and fighting,'' Trotman said. ``With the guys
they've got, sometimes it's all you can do. The effort was good and
maybe it'll pay off at the end of the season.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-08-08-98 0021EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
