<SLUG> BC-HURRICANE-POLLUTION-NYTR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
POLLUTION MAY SAP HURRICANES' FORCE 
</HEADLINE>
  (lh) 
 By BRIAN FEAGANS   N.Y. Times Regional Newspaper Group   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WILMINGTON, N.C. _ If you think Hurricane Fran was at full force
when it slammed into the Carolina coast that fateful Friday two
years ago, think again.
</P>
<P>
   It would have been worse on a Monday or Tuesday, say researchers
at Arizona State University.
</P>
<P>
   The costliest storm in North Carolina history, like the infamous
weekend hurricanes Hazel and Hugo before it, was probably choked a
bit by air pollution drifting off the East Coast during the
workweek, according to climatologists Randall Cerveny and Robert
Balling Jr.. Their study is published in Wednesday's edition of the
science journal Nature.
</P>
<P>
   The duo found that average hurricane intensity over the past 50
years has been weaker for storms coming ashore at the end of the
week and on weekends than for tempests striking on Mondays,
Tuesdays and Wednesdays.
</P>
<P>
   They believe pollution particles coming out of smokestacks and
tailpipes during the workweek drift into the Atlantic and provide
tiny seeds for raindrops to form around. The rain-forming particles
help approaching hurricanes blow off some of their steam before
landfall, they concluded.
</P>
<P>
   ``Hurricanes are the biggest storms that we have on this planet,
in terms of energy and precipitation,'' Cerveny said. ``And what
we've found is that we're having an impact on them. It's a little
daunting when you start to think about it.''
</P>
<P>
   The researchers compared three sets of climate data _ daily
carbon monoxide and ozone measurements from a Canadian monitoring
station on Sable Island off the coast of Nova Scotia, daily
satellite-derived rainfall records for the Atlantic and key
measurements for Atlantic hurricanes from 1945 to 1996.
</P>
<P>
   All three databases showed a seven-day cycle, including
pronounced differences in rainfall and hurricane intensity between
the beginnings and ends of weeks.
</P>
<P>
   ``The human week is not a natural time period,'' Balling said.
``Human effect on weather is the only explanation.''
</P>
<P>
   The phenomenon also explains why Atlantic boaters are more
likely to encounter rain on a weekend and clear skies during the
early part of the week, the researchers said.
</P>
<P>
   They studied rainfall data for a 200-foot-wide band stretching
along the Atlantic seaboard from Florida to Nova Scotia. Average
rainfall peaked on Saturday and bottomed out on Monday.
</P>
<P>
   The hurricane findings were met with interest and skepticism by
one regional weather expert.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a darn interesting idea,'' said Tom Matheson, who is in
charge of hurricane warnings for the National Weather Service in
Wilmington. ``I don't buy it, but I don't not buy it either.''
</P>
<P>
   Variations in the amount of pollution along the East Coast
during the past five decades and the importance of salt crystals as
rain seeds in hurricanes gave Matheson some pause.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's amazing what you can do with statistics,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   (Brian Feagans writes for the Morning Star in Wilmington, N.C.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-08-08-98 0022EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19980808.0014 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-08-08 00:22 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4246 &Cx1f; ttx-z
r s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BBN-SULLIVAN-COLUMN-T     08-08 0737
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBN-SULLIVAN-COLUMN-TEX </SLUG>
 
McGWIRE VS. SOSA HAS HEAVYWEIGHT LOOK, `FUN' 
(For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
 
By T.R. SULLIVAN 
c.1998 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   ST. LOUIS _ Sammy Sosa walked into Busch Stadium yesterday and
saw the oversized bandage patched on a St. Louis Post-Dispatch sign
on the upper-deck facade, high and beyond the center-field fence.
</P>
<P>
   ``Wow,'' Sosa said with a smile. ``Incredible. He is The Man.
He'll always be The Man.''
</P>
<P>
   Mark McGwire certainly was the man on that night in April with
his herculean swing against Florida Marlins pitcher Livan
Hernandez. The sign wasn't harmed when the ball came crashing down,
but the bandage is still a nice touch, symbolizing a home run that
measured 545 feet and is the longest ever hit at Busch Stadium.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm just hoping to get a couple of singles,'' Sosa said,
another smile spreading across his face. ``This is going to be
fun.''
</P>
<P>
   A crowd of 47,911 thought so as well, especially the couple
thousand or more that crammed the outfield bleachers two hours
before the game in anticipation of nothing more than McGwire taking
batting practice.
</P>
<P>
   That is a shown unto itself, and the Cardinals' first baseman
didn't disappoint. In the span of 10 minutes, alternating with two
faceless teammates, McGwire hit one into the upper deck, two off
the facade, one off the scoreboard towering beyond the left-field
bleachers and visitors bullpen and two more into the grassy area
beyond the center-field bleachers.
</P>
<P>
   The crowd roared with each shot, and dozens of cameras roped off
behind the batting cage clicked away.
</P>
<P>
   ``You ought to see him take BP at Wrigley,'' Cubs catcher Scott
Servais said with a smile. ``They're lined up in the streets
outside.''
</P>
<P>
   Sosa had a firsthand view of the show, watching McGwire while
leaning on the batting cage with Cubs teammate Henry Rodriguez.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's like having the fifth Beatle,'' Cardinals pitcher Bobby
Witt said. ``You go to a place like Atlanta and the bleachers are
sold out before we even go out there. It's fun just to watch the
other team when they're supposed to be stretching and they're all
watching him take batting practice.''
</P>
<P>
   Yesterday was extra special. The Cubs were in town, which is a
big deal in St. Louis even under normal circumstances. But the
final score was only secondary in most people's minds. The Cubs are
leading the National League wild-card chase, but the Cardinals have
long since drifted out of any kind of playoff contention.
</P>
<P>
   The show yesterday was a face-to-face meeting between McGwire
and Sosa, two of baseball's celebrated three who are chasing Roger
Maris' single-season home-run record.
</P>
<P>
   This had all the aura of a heavyweight title fight, only with a
run-of-the-mill baseball game spliced in between.
</P>
<P>
   ``It reminds me of the time Nolan Ryan was going for his 300th
victory,'' Witt said.
</P>
<P>
   The pre-series buildup has been sizable. The local newspaper ran
a Sosa-McGwire story on the front page, right next to the rundown
on Monica Lewinsky's testimony in Washington.
</P>
<P>
   McGwire squirmed when the subject was broached before the game.
Home runs that is, not the ex-intern.
</P>
<P>
   ``I never look at stats until the last day of the season was
over,'' McGwire said. ``I don't even know what I'm batting. Of
course I know how many home runs and RBI I have. The home runs are
up there on this big billboard I drive by on the way to the
ballpark. The Queen Casino. It says, Home Runs: 45. Good luck Mark,
The Queen.''
</P>
<P>
   The drama was all pregame. The Cubs scored three in the first
with Sosa drawing a walk. But the Cardinals came back with 11 of
their own. McGwire contributed a key two-run single, fighting off
an inside pitch from Cubs pitcher Steve Trachsel and blooping it
into right field.
</P>
<P>
   The swing was indicative of an intelligent hitter trying to win
a baseball game rather than swing from the heels trying to break a
record.
</P>
<P>
   Party-pooper.
</P>
<P>
   Sosa followed the walk with an 0-for-3, one strikeout and a
couple of pop-ups. He wasn't trying for any measly singles.
</P>
<P>
   McGwire also went hitless in three at-bats. He batted in the
seventh with runners on second and third, but Cubs reliever Felix
Heredia walked him on four pitches.
</P>
<P>
   The crowd booed lustily. The Cardinals' 16-3 victory was hardly
satisfying. They came to see long ball, and the two heavyweight
will go after it again today with another 47,000 expected.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
