u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BBN-PHILLIES-JOHNSON-     08-08 0676
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBN-PHILLIES-JOHNSON-HNS </SLUG>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Johnson leaves Phillies impressed
</P>
<P>
   &UR; By ALAN TRUEX &LR;  &QL; 
 &UR; c. 1998, Houston Chronicle &LR;  &QL; 
Randy Johnson did not have to throw his hardest to make a shutout
look easy Friday night. His fastball was not his usual supersonic
variety; it was mostly in the 93- to 95-mph range, only
occasionally hitting 97.
</P>
<P>
   Most of the Philadelphia Phillies never had faced the sidearming
lefthanded giant before, and they were somewhat surprised by what
they saw.
</P>
<P>
   After his team lost 9-0 to the Astros, Kevin Sefcik, a
27-year-old outfielder, said, ``Everybody was talking about how
hard he throws, but I've never seen a slider that has so much late
break.''
</P>
<P>
   Sefcik caught up to a Johnson fastball in the third inning,
leading off with a double to center field while there was still no
score.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was pretty excited,'' Sefcik said. ``I thought maybe if we
get something going there .''
</P>
<P>
   But Johnson put away the next three batters, and in the bottom
of the inning the Astros battered Phillies rookie Mike Welch for
four runs. This issue was decided.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's like (Greg) Maddux,'' Sefcik said, referring to Atlanta's
pitching ace. ``You can't get four or five runs behind and have
much chance of catching up.''
</P>
<P>
   After his initial success with Johnson, Sefcik was hopeful of a
productive evening in the Astrodome.
</P>
<P>
   ``But he didn't throw me any fastballs after that,'' Sefcik
said.
</P>
<P>
   What Johnson showed was a side that many fans are unaware he has
_ more Maddux-like precision than power ball. He worked quickly
(game time: 2 hours, 21 minutes), walking only one batter and
allowing five hits.
</P>
<P>
   Philadelphia's Gregg Jefferies, who faced Johnson in the
pitcher's early days with Montreal and later with Seattle, observed
how the Big Unit has expanded his repertoire over the years.
</P>
<P>
   ``With Montreal, he was pure gas,'' Jefferies said. ``But in
Seattle, he learned to master the slider, and a changeup, too. He
and Maddux are the ultimate; unfortunately, they're both in the
National League.''
</P>
<P>
   Phillies manager Terry Francona didn't know what to make of
Johnson's performance. His team seemed mesmerized by the towering
6-10 lefthander, who was pitching before a frenzied capacity crowd
getting its first look at the new hero in town.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's good, and he's tall, and he can be intimidating,''
Francona said. ``I don't think our guys got carried away with the
hype and everything. He's good, no question about that, but it was
9-0; it wasn't a good game to judge him.''
</P>
<P>
   Welch, the antithesis of Randy Johnson, gave the visitors no
chance. He was underpowering, in the middle of the plate and in way
over his head.
</P>
<P>
   Asked about his matchup with Johnson, Welch said, ``I knew he
was pitching, but he could have a good game or a bad game. I just
wanted to go out and pitch a good game. But when I had to come in
with the fastball, I couldn't hit my spot.''
</P>
<P>
   Francona observed that while all the attention now is on
Johnson, the rest of the Astros team is first-rate.
</P>
<P>
   ``They're a good ballclub, with good players and good role
players,'' the Phillies' manager said. ``They run Billy Spiers out
there about half the time, and he finds a way to beat you. They've
been waiting for Derek Bell to have a Derek Bell year, and he's
doing it.''
</P>
<P>
   Sefcik says he thinks the crowd factor could weigh heavily in
the Astros' favor if the city unites behind the new pitcher.
</P>
<P>
   ``A crowd like that gets their team fired up,'' he said. ``They
play hard, but that's gonna make them play even harder.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was like Coors Field,'' he added, referring to the usually
sold-out home of the Colorado Rockies.
</P>
<P>
   Of course, without Johnson, the crowd would have been about half
as big. And the Astros might not have had the same enthusiasm.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's one of the best in the game, and it looks like his
teammates are real excited _ and the fans too,'' Sefcik said.
</P>
<P>
   It makes you wonder what the scene will be like when Johnson has
his good fastball.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
