<HEADER>
A4248 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BBN-ROBERTSON-COL-HNS     08-08 0760
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBN-ROBERTSON-COL-HNS </SLUG>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
With clever deals, 
good will abounds
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR; By DALE ROBERTSON &LR;  &QL; 
 &UR; c. 1998, Houston Chronicle &LR;  &QL; 
WHEN Randy Johnson joined the Astros, he didn't know much about
them or their Houston home. He hadn't done his homework, because
neither Houston nor the Astros seemed to figure in his future,
until he was told he had been sent our way.
</P>
<P>
   Still, his official posture remained somewhere between puzzled
and ambivalent. Houston? Nobody had said anything about Houston. No
matter. Johnson would be leaving his heart in Seattle, wherever he
landed. It didn't take him long, nonetheless, to see the upside
regarding his unanticipated exile to Southeast Texas, the summer's
particularly oppressive heat wave notwithstanding.
</P>
<P>
   The Astros, you see, lead the National League in runs scored. As
a pitcher, he responded favorably to that tidbit of information.
</P>
<P>
   His new mates were a tad slow to prove it to him in Pittsburgh,
but a five-run outburst in the last two innings there assured him
of his first National League victory in a decade. Manager Larry
Dierker suggested afterward the Astros might have been nervous, or
at least overeager, playing behind such an esteemed presence.
</P>
<P>
   If so, they have apparently refound their comfort zone.
</P>
<P>
   Based on Friday night's particulars, Johnson's tenure here
should be a spectacularly, and mutually, profitable experience,
however ephemeral it might prove in the end. Houston extended a
record-breaking ``howdy!'', his teammates got with the program in
kind by spotting him a nine-run lead, and in return he made the
traffic gridlock outside the Astrodome well worth the hassle.
</P>
<P>
   Watching Johnson work gives a ball fan religion in a hurry.
Suddenly, we're a city chock full of Unit-arians.
</P>
<P>
   The long, lefthanded drink of water sold 52,071 tickets in his
Houston debut, the most ever for a regular-season game, and his
performance _ merely a five-hit shutout with eight K's _ was such
that most of the folks are apt to return when he goes again
Wednesday night against Milwaukee.
</P>
<P>
   Do I hear any seconds for Gerry Hunsicker as baseball's
Executive of the Year?
</P>
<P>
   Hunsicker, who Hun-suckered the Mariners out of Johnson right
before the no-more-switching hour July 31, might even have won Jeff
Bagwell's grudging vote. No Astro was angrier about the general
manager's losing Darryl Kile to the Rockies over the offseason, but
apparently no Astro is more delighted to play behind the Big Unit _
and hitting ahead of Big Mo.
</P>
<P>
   The reeling in of Moises Alou, the first Marlins big fish to get
away, gave the Astros the NL's best every-day offense that doesn't
play half its games above the tree line. But Alou's hefty price
tag, alas, hindered Hunsicker's efforts to retain Kile's services
and D.K. wound up taking a huffy hike to Colorado.
</P>
<P>
   Bagwell, probably Kile's best buddy, didn't like it one bit. He
blasted Hunsicker for what he saw as an unacceptable gaffe, full of
deceit and dishonesty, not to mention stinginess. And then, Baggy
hit poorly early in the year, like the anger and frustration was
making his bat lead-heavy.
</P>
<P>
   Baggy was drinking _ to forget? _ in a Pittsburgh bar when he
got word Johnson had been added to the roster. He quickly bought a
round for the house and has been the happiest of campers ever
since. He drove in two runs Sunday afternoon on Johnson's behalf,
then pummeled the Phillies with two home runs and five RBIs Friday
night.
</P>
<P>
   Finally, he must see a glimmer of light at the end of the
Astros' tunnel. He realizes his team's potential, although he warns
of looking too far ahead into October.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've gotten everything we bargained for in Randy Johnson,''
he said. ``It's exciting. But let's get into the playoffs first. We
can talk about the World Series when we're in it.''
</P>
<P>
   Such talk would have been laughable even nine days ago, when
Johnson practically had Yankees pinstripes painted on his
pinstripe-shaped frame, or so we thought. Now, guys like the
Phillies' Gregg Jefferies are shaking their heads and pronouncing
the Astros the new team to beat in the NL.
</P>
<P>
   ``With him,'' Jefferies said, ``I think Houston's better than
San Diego or Atlanta.''
</P>
<P>
   And, of course, with Alou. Moises jacked No. 29 himself this
fine evening as his RBI count reached 97. Add Derek Bell's 82 and
Bagwell's 77 with a bullet, and Mr. Johnson must realize he has
come to the right place. Home Sweet Dome II.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a beautiful thing,'' Dierker said, a dreamy look in his
eyes.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
