<HEADER>
A4249 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BBN-ASTROS-HNS &LR;      08-08 0866
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBN-ASTROS-HNS </SLUG>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
2 Bagwell homers 
let Johnson breeze
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR; By JOSEPH DUARTE &LR;  &QL; 
 &UR; c. 1998, Houston Chronicle &LR;  &QL; 
Do you believe in love at first sight? Astros fans apparently do.
</P>
<P>
   From the moment Randy Johnson walked onto the field Friday
night, an Astrodome record crowd rose in support of its new hero.
Three hours later, the fans were still standing.
</P>
<P>
   Johnson, making his Dome debut, remained perfect with his new
club with a five-hit shutout and Jeff Bagwell hit two home runs to
pace the Astros to a 9-0 rout of the Philadelphia Phillies before a
sellout crowd of 52,071, the largest regular-season turnout in
franchise history.
</P>
<P>
   ``Now I know what a lot of rock stars feel like,'' said Johnson,
who received a standing ovation prior to the game while warming up.
``I got that occasionally from a couple hundred people in Seattle.
</P>
<P>
   ``When you've got 50,000 it's exciting.''
</P>
<P>
   The Astros offered customers a two-for-one deal on tickets to
the game. Johnson brought the strikeouts _ eight _ and his
teammates provided plenty of runs.
</P>
<P>
   Johnson got the `K' placards flashing after one batter when he
started with a strikeout of Doug Glanville. He did not allow a
runner past second base in his third shutout of the season.
</P>
<P>
   Since his July 31 trade to Houston from Seattle, Johnson is 2-0
with a 1.13 ERA and 20 strikeouts in 16 innings.
</P>
<P>
   ``I can't remember losing too many games when the team scored
eight or nine runs,'' said Johnson, who has gone the distance in
four of his last six starts. ``I felt kind of spoiled today.
Overall, we played great defense and had a great offense.
</P>
<P>
   ``It made my job easier to go out there and throw strikes.''
</P>
<P>
   The Astros made sure Johnson didn't have to work too hard,
belting three home runs. Bagwell hit his 24th and 25th homers and
drove in a season-high five runs. Moises Alou added a two-run homer
and Bill Spiers was 3-for-5 with two doubles and a stolen base and
scored twice.
</P>
<P>
   The night, however, belonged to Johnson. The 6-10 lefthander
said he felt a little ``overwhelmed'' by all the attention given to
his first start in the Dome.
</P>
<P>
   The Phillies know the feeling.
</P>
<P>
   Johnson, who increased his major league-leading strikeout total
to 234, struck out four of the first nine batters he faced and at
one point retired 10 in a row. Two of Philadelphia's five hits did
not make it out of the infield.
</P>
<P>
   He needed only 112 pitches, and three batters over the minimum
27, to send the Phillies to defeat.
</P>
<P>
   ``Actually I thought (bench coach) Matt Galante and I were the
masterminds of the game tonight,'' said manager Larry Dierker. ``I
don't think we gave one single (pitching) sign.
</P>
<P>
   ``When you hit home runs and pitch shutouts, you don't have to
think too much.''
</P>
<P>
   The Astros provided Johnson all the support he needed with a
pair of four-run innings to build an 8-0 lead.
</P>
<P>
   Spiers hit a one-out double to center field in the third inning
and Derek Bell walked. Three pitches and one flick of the bat
later, Bagwell sent a pitch from Philadelphia starter Mike Welch
(0-2) over the left center-field wall.
</P>
<P>
   Then Alou singled, Tony Eusebio was hit by a pitch and Ricky
Gutierrez delivered an RBI double to put the Astros comfortably
ahead 4-0.
</P>
<P>
   In the fourth, Craig Biggio led off with a walk, Spiers doubled
down the right-field line and Bell bounced out as Biggio scored.
</P>
<P>
   Bagwell drove in a run with a fielder's choice that allowed
Spiers to slide home ahead of the throw to the plate by shortstop
Desi Relaford, and Alou followed with a two-run homer, his 29th, to
put the Astros in front 8-0.
</P>
<P>
   Alou's 29th moved him into a tie with Lee May for ninth on the
club's single-season home run list.
</P>
<P>
   Welch allowed eight runs, seven hits, four walks and two home
runs in 3 innings, and was handed a ticket to Class AAA
Scranton/Wilkes-Barre after the game.
</P>
<P>
   Bagwell completed the scoring with a solo home run off Yorkis
Perez in the sixth inning.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a great thing for Houston,'' Bagwell said of the huge
turnout. ``Everybody had a lot of fun tonight. But I actually felt
sorry for the guy with all the pressure and expectations. I guess
it didn't bother him.''
</P>
<P>
   And the Phillies' view?
</P>
<P>
   ``It's not my job to rate their pitchers,'' manager Terry
Francona said. ``He's good. He's tall and can be intimidating, but
I don't think our guys got carried away with the hype. He is good
and he's hard to judge when the score gets like that.''
</P>
<P>
   After a nine-year absence, Johnson has shown a fondness for the
National League. But he said much of his early success has to do
with teams getting used to his first tour through the league.
</P>
<P>
   ``The real test will be when I pitch again in Pittsburgh and
Philadelphia,'' Johnson said. ``The first time through the league,
teams probably know my characteristics being a power pitcher but
facing somebody that throws 95 to 98 miles per hour is a different
story.
</P>
<P>
   ``They make adjustments, and I'm assuming they will the next
time I face him. I don't walk on water. In due time I'm going to
get roughed up.''
</P>
<P>
   For now, Johnson and his new admirers seem like the perfect
match.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
