<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBA-REDSOX-RANGERS-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
RANGERS STAY HOT, STOP RED SOX, 4-3
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
 
By JOHNNY PAUL 
c.1998 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   ARLINGTON, Texas _ These white-hot Rangers of August succeeded
where the sizzling Rangers of April and May failed.
</P>
<P>
   This collection beat Red Sox right-hander Pedro Martinez, and
last night's 4-3 victory at The Ballpark in Arlington required a
multitude of significant contributions.
</P>
<P>
   ``This was one of those well-played ballgames where you can't
put a finger on any one particular play that won the game,'' said
first baseman Will Clark, whose two-run, first-inning home run
against Martinez (15-4) gave the Rangers a 3-0 advantage and
perhaps established the tone.
</P>
<P>
   The victory represented the Rangers' sixth consecutive and _
more importantly _ dropped the second-place Angels 21/2 games
behind in the American League West standings.
</P>
<P>
   The contributions _ even on an evening in which Martinez
recorded a season-high 13 strikeouts during his 62/3 innings _ came
from everywhere:
</P>
<P>
   Right-hander Rick Helling (15-6) matched Martinez, one of the
league's leading candidates to receive the 1998 Cy Young Award, by
allowing only three runs on seven hits during his six-inning
appearance.
</P>
<P>
   Closer John Wetteland, who pitched for the fourth consecutive
night and fifth time in six days, recorded his 31st save by
retiring the Red Sox's Nos. 1-3 hitters in order during the ninth
inning.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's part of the job description,'' said Wetteland, who
retired first baseman Mo Vaughn on strikes to end the game for the
second time in as many nights. ``It's just nice to see that even
though I wasn't 100 percent, I still had something out there. This
would have been a very difficult one to let slip away.''
</P>
<P>
   Left-hander Eric Gunderson _ who entered this game having
surrendered six runs on seven hits, including three home runs,
during his previous three appearances _ retired the switch-hitting
Jason Varitek on an inning-ending foul pop with runners at first
and third in the eighth inning. It also required an
over-the-shoulder catch from Clark, whose back faced toward home
plate.
</P>
<P>
   Right-hander Tim Crabtree, who had not pitched during the past
five games, replaced Helling and provided 12/3 innings of scoreless
relief.
</P>
<P>
   Center fielder Tom Goodwin, left fielder Rusty Greer and third
baseman Todd Zeile also turned in defensive gems.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's what it's going to take down the stretch: Everybody
doing their job,'' Gunderson said. ``You've got to play like this
with the schedule and the teams we're playing right now.''
</P>
<P>
   The Rangers' pitching made a fifth-inning sacrifice fly ball _
actually a line drive _ off the bat of right fielder Juan Gonzalez
stand as the game-winning run after the Red Sox tied the score with
their three-run fourth inning.
</P>
<P>
   Helling issued only a walk through the first three innings
despite balls sent to the warning track by Red Sox right fielder
Darren Lewis, Vaughn and center fielder Damon Buford.
</P>
<P>
   Nevertheless, the shutout remained intact until a fourth-inning
single by left fielder Darren Bragg. The Red Sox tied the game
later in the inning with a run-scoring single by Buford and a
sacrifice fly ball off the bat of catcher Scott Hatteberg.
</P>
<P>
   Helling, though, likely deserved better than being strapped with
a three-run inning.
</P>
<P>
   Miscommunication between Greer and Goodwin resulted in a
potential fly-ball out off the bat of designated hitter Mike
Stanley being played into a long single. The ball landed between
the two outfielders. The Red Sox parlayed the extra out into one
and perhaps two extra runs after Stanley scored on Hatteberg's fly
ball.
</P>
<P>
   Vaughn, though, would also prove generous.
</P>
<P>
   His fifth-inning throwing error on a sacrifice-bunt attempt
advanced Goodwin to third and allowed Alicea reach second. Alicea
ran inside the first-base line and forced Vaughn to throw over the
top. Vaughn's throw sailed over the head of second baseman Mike
Benjamin, and Gonzalez later delivered what proved to be the
game-winning run home with his line drive.
</P>
<P>
   ``The guys played inspired all the way around,'' Wetteland said,
``and we beat one of the best in baseball.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
