<HEADLINE>
INJURY NEWS BAD FOR DODGERS
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By HOWARD BECK  
 c.1998 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ Friday came and went without an update on the
status of center fielder Raul Mondesi and his ailing back, but the
injury report the Dodgers did receive was not encouraging.
</P>
<P>
   Shortstop Jose Vizcaino (right ankle sprain) and starter Ismael
Valdes (strained stomach muscle) are both progressing more slowly
than hoped, and neither one is expected back soon.
</P>
<P>
   Vizcaino, out since June 22, was expected back within a week or
so, but manager Glenn Hoffman said the latest examination by Dr.
Philip Kwong determined it could be another three to four weeks.
</P>
<P>
   ``Just another blow for us,'' Hoffman said. ``And I'm just
feeling for him, because he's been working hard, trying to get
back.... I saw him out there moving, and he wasn't moving right.''
</P>
<P>
   Valdes, placed on the DL on July 27 and eligible to return
Tuesday, probably won't be activated for at least another week
after that. He played catch for a third straight day, increasing
his workout to about 12 minutes, but Valdes is still sore beneath
his rib cage.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's not coming along,'' Hoffman said.
</P>
<P>
   Valdes was a bit more optimistic: ``I'm improving. I'm feeling
better each day.''
</P>
<P>
   Mondesi, meanwhile, missed his second straight game. He was
examined by Dr. William Dillin at the Anaheim branch of the
Kerlan-Jobe Clinic, then went to Centinela Medical Center in
Inglewood for an MRI and a bone scan on his stiff lower back. Test
results are due back today.
</P>
<P>
   Mondesi has now missed four games and parts of two others with
the injury.
</P>
<P>
   Hoffman must wonder if he'll ever manage a game with the
Dodgers' best starting nine.
</P>
<P>
   ``They're gonna come back,'' he said of the injured parties.
``Injuries are part of the game. You just hope you can overcome
them and you can battle.... We're still not done battling.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've got some key injuries, but let's just keep our fingers
crossed on the big guy in center field.''
</P>
<P>
   Young gunned: When the Dodgers' Eric Young hit into a double
play in the third inning Friday, it marked the first time all
season he had done so, a streak of 342 at-bats, longest in the
major leagues this season.
</P>
</TEXT>
