   WILDWOOD-CASINO-CHAOS (Undated) _ For 20 years, the New Jersey
beach resort of Wildwood has been a town seething with envy. As
hotels and shops along its boardwalk have tried to survive on the
income they made three months out of the year, its more famous
neighbor to the north _ Atlantic City _ has used its neon-splashed
casinos to become a year-round mecca for tourists. Now Wildwood is
fighting back. On Thursday, Wildwood's city commissioners voted 2
to 1 to approve the transfer of a 2.5-acre municipal parking lot to
the Delaware Tribe of western Oklahoma. In return, the Delawares
would operate an Indian casino on the lot. By Iver Peterson. (With
photo.)
