<SLUG> BC-BBN-MODESTI-COLUMN-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HOFFMAN DOOMED NO MATTER WHAT?
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By KEVIN MODESTI  
 c.1998 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ Glenn Hoffman stood in the shade near the Dodgers'
dugout late Friday afternoon, surveying the scene before his team
opened the make-or-break homestand that followed the make-or-break
trip that followed the last make-or-break homestand.
</P>
<P>
   It was a rough trip. Before separate flights, the team plane had
a mechanical breakdown and an air-conditioning outage. In New York,
the equipment truck got into a fender bender. Oh, and to top it
off, the Dodgers lost three embarrassing games to the Montreal
Expos.
</P>
<P>
   Hoffman is happy to be home.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a little cooler out,'' he said, there in the shade. ``I
thought it was going to be hot.''
</P>
<P>
   But it (begin ital)was(end ital) hot. To feel it, he had only to
turn on the radio.
</P>
<P>
   There, with 50 days left in the season and the Dodgers clinging
to contention for a wild-card playoff spot, under circumstances
that always seem to spin just beyond his grasp, the heat on Hoffman
is being turned up in a most peculiar way.
</P>
<P>
   On the air, they're speculating about who will manage the
Dodgers in 1999.
</P>
<P>
   Jim Leyland? Davey Johnson? Bobby Valentine? Mike Scioscia? If
you have a telephone, you're eligible to join the debate.
</P>
<P>
   Glenn Hoffman? The name of the man in the manager's office
hardly comes up when the talk shows talk about next year. Not that
he's responsible for the Dodgers' place in the standings. He's just
(begin ital)not(end ital) coming back. That's the popular take.
</P>
<P>
   Officially, the Dodgers position is that everybody, including
Hoffman and general manager Tom Lasorda, is subject to evaluation
at the end of the season.
</P>
<P>
   And here's what's funny: On June 21, the night general manager
Fred Claire and manager Bill Russell were replaced, Lasorda was
introduced as the ``interim'' GM but Hoffman had no such qualifier
in his title. Yet the conventional wisdom was that, while Lasorda
has a chance to keep the job, Hoffman is simply a stand-in for a
Fox-friendly, high-profile manager to be named next winter.
</P>
<P>
   The theory: Dodgers management decided not to promote either
Scioscia or Reggie Smith, major-league coaches thought to be
managerial timber, because each might be too popular to easily push
aside at season's end. Hoffman, a lower-profile former Dodgers
player who had been managing the Albuquerque farm club, was the
perfect man for the job precisely because he wouldn't be missed.
</P>
<P>
   As far as Hoffman's concerned, he might be in limbo, but he's
not even sure of that. How hot is it really? Hoffman doesn't know.
He's in the shade.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm here right now,'' he said of the job. ``I'm not worried
about it. It's out of my control. What I do on the field with this
team is what I can control right now.''
</P>
<P>
   But not even that is strictly true.
</P>
<P>
   If he could control what happens on the field, would he have let
six Dodgers starters go on the disabled list, and four remain there
today, during his tenure?
</P>
<P>
   If he could control what happens on the field, would he have
asked for a revolving-door roster?
</P>
<P>
   If he could control what happens on the field, would Friday
night's game against the Pittsburgh Pirates have started, grimly,
with a Tony Womack ground ball slipping through Adrian Beltre's
legs for an error?
</P>
<P>
   The Dodgers were 36-38 when Russell was fired. They are 23-19
under Hoffman after winning 3-1 on Friday. The consensus is that
Hoffman is a good man doing a good job even if it might not be good
enough to put them in the playoffs.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't want to get into that right now,'' he said, asked if
it's fair to judge him on results, ``because I'm trying to do a job
out here with the guys I have.
</P>
<P>
   ``Injuries are part of the game that I can't control. So we've
just got to move on.''
</P>
<P>
   If he doesn't want to get into that, he also wants no part of
Lasorda's guarantee that the Dodgers will make the playoffs.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't make guarantees,'' Hoffman said with a smile.
</P>
<P>
   If he was given a mission on June 21, he thinks it was to help
the team ``get it going, somehow, some way.'' And ``I feel like
we've battled pretty well.''
</P>
<P>
   But ``the bottom line is winning,'' he admits, and if winning
means making the playoffs in October, then by next April, Hoffman
is probably going to be doing his managing in the minors again.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's pretty tough, to be evaluated on these three months,''
said first baseman Eric Karros, who thinks Hoffman has done a good
job. ``Wow.''
</P>
<P>
   That's the way it might be, though, in this job in which Hoffman
started with nothing to lose but might end up with nothing to win. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
