<SLUG> BC-BBN-DODGERS-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DODGERS DEFEAT PIRATES
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By HOWARD BECK  
 c.1998 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ Gary Sheffield's appeal of a three-game suspension
was denied by the National League, but when he returned from exile
Friday evening at Dodger Stadium, Sheffield looked appealing
indeed.
</P>
<P>
   With Raul Mondesi still out with a sore back, and the Dodgers in
dire need of a power source, Sheffield delivered two hits, a run
and an RBI in a 3-1 win over the Pittsburgh Pirates before 41,676.
</P>
<P>
   Brian Bohanon pitched a season-high 71/3 innings, giving up just
two hits and two walks, as the Dodgers mercifully ended their
losing streak at three games and kept their fading playoff hopes
alive.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a great win, it's given us a chance,'' Bohanon said.
``Everyone's counting us out. I think we can do it.''
</P>
<P>
   ``It'' being the wild-card playoff berth, which now stands five
games out of the Dodgers' reach but would have been much closer if
not for their three-game skid in Montreal.
</P>
<P>
   The disappointing road trip now behind them, the Dodgers tried
to find hope in opening a nine-game homestand that starts with six
games against bottom-feeders Pittsburgh and Florida. Of course, the
Expos were supposed to fit that category as well.
</P>
<P>
   ``We want to put all that behind us and move on. That's three
games that we'd like to forget,'' manager Glenn Hoffman said.
``We're just glad to be back and starting a good homestand right
now.''
</P>
<P>
   They're off to a nice start, in any case, thanks to Bohanon,
Sheffield and the sparkling defense of rookie third-baseman Adrian
Beltre. The 20-year-old's bat has yet to come alive, but he showed
off Gold Glove-like prowess at the hot corner, converting nine of
10 chances.
</P>
<P>
   Beltre flubbed a Tony Womack grounder to start the game, then
followed with a series of spectacular assists, including a charging
snag of Womack's sacrifice bunt down the line in the top of the
eighth inning.
</P>
<P>
   ``That one on the bunt play, you're not gonna see a better play
than that,'' Hoffman said. ``I've seen a lot of guys, but that was
pretty good right there. You've gotta go back a few years to see
some guys make that play....
</P>
<P>
   ``There were some tough hops, and he was aggressive to the ball.
That's what you like to see.''
</P>
<P>
   Sheffield and Jason Kendall, whose brawl last month led to
suspensions for both men, managed to keep the peace this time. But
Sheffield, who spent the entire Expos series at home in Florida,
was still upset Friday _ with the league, that is.
</P>
<P>
   ``I thought just by the fact they took up my time to come down
there (for the appeal hearing), maybe they wanted to review the
case. Why hear the case when your mind is already made up?''
Sheffield said. ``I didn't start the fight, and I didn't throw the
first punch.... If another man swings at you, you have to defend
yourself.''
</P>
<P>
   Sheffield's swing was still in fine form despite the layoff. He
singled in the first inning, doubled and scored the Dodgers'
decisive second run in the fourth and drove in the third and final
run with a sacrifice fly in the sixth.
</P>
<P>
   ``He must have been hitting in his backyard cage or something,''
Hoffman quipped. ``He gave us a lift in the middle of the lineup.''
</P>
<P>
   The Pirates wasted a surprisingly solid performance by the
well-traveled Todd Van Poppel, who allowed all three runs, two
earned, on eight hits in 61/3 innings.
</P>
<P>
   With the Dodgers leading 1-0 on a Charles Johnson home run,
Kevin Young drove in Pittsburgh's only run and later tied the score
with an RBI double in the fourth.
</P>
<P>
   The Dodgers took the lead back immediately, as Sheffield scored
in the bottom of the inning on a double-play grounder by Bobby
Bonilla.
</P>
<P>
   In the sixth, Eric Young reached on an error by shortstop Kevin
Polcovich, then scored on Sheffield's sac fly.
</P>
<P>
   Bohanon, the former Met who now has a 3-3 record and 2.25 ERA
with the Dodgers, did the rest.
</P>
<P>
   ``I felt good tonight,'' he said. ``Hoff and Tommy (Lasorda),
they're giving me a chance to go out there every five days and show
what I've got.''
</P>
<P>
   Which on this night, was just enough to keep the Dodgers'
postseason hopes intact.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
