<SLUG> BC-BBN-METS-ROCKIES-275&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
METS' TROUBLES VANISH IN THIN AIR 
</HEADLINE>
  (lh) 
 By JASON DIAMOS   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   DENVER _ They are the two New York Mets most likely to be booed.
But Friday night, a change of scenery made a difference for Mike
Piazza and Mel Rojas.
</P>
<P>
   Away from the not-so-friendly confines of Shea Stadium, the
embattled Piazza was 3-for-5 with a home run, a double and three
runs batted in, and he threw out a runner at second base. Piazza
raised his career batting average at Coors Field to .450.
</P>
<P>
   And then, after the Mets almost blew a seven-run lead, the
struggling Rojas, who earlier in the week had appealed to Manager
Bobby Valentine for more work, shut down the Colorado Rockies in
the seventh and eighth innings, and the Mets barely held on for an
8-7 victory.
</P>
<P>
   ``That was a big stop, as good a performance as he's had all
year in as important a game,'' Valentine said.
</P>
<P>
   Even John Franco, who has also been booed at home lately, was
able to close out his second save in his last five tries. The Mets
bailed out Rick Reed (13-7), who equaled his victory total of last
season, even though he tied his career highs in hits (12) and runs
allowed (7).
</P>
<P>
   It appeared shaky for Franco in the ninth, until he induced
Neifi Perez into lining out to shortstop Rey Ordonez with the tying
run on second to nail down his 22nd save.
</P>
<P>
   Franco extended both hands upward and looked to the sky.
``Usually a bloop hit falls in,'' Franco said. ``Finally I got a
line drive hit at somebody.''
</P>
<P>
   Piazza and Rojas had to feel the same way as the Mets (61-52)
pulled to within one and a half games of the Chicago Cubs in the
National League wild-card race.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   It is not a stretch of the imagination to believe Piazza will
wind up with the Rockies next season. Piazza, an All-Star catcher,
must have felt at home here Friday night. First of all, he was
booed. Second, he owns this park.
</P>
<P>
   Entering Friday night's game, Piazza was 42-for-95, with 11 home
runs and 34 runs batted in, at Coors Field. He hit a two-run home
run _ his 20th of the season _ in the top of the first, and then
capped a five-run second (all five runs were unearned) with a
run-scoring single up the middle, to give the Mets a 7-0 lead.
</P>
<P>
   The Mets scored all their runs with two outs, thanks to two
Colorado errors. One error _ by second baseman Mike Lansing on a
Tony Phillips grounder _ scored Brian McRae to make it 3-0. After
Edgardo Alfonzo singled to load the bases, John Olerud hit a
bases-clearing double into the left-field corner to give the Mets a
6-0 lead.
</P>
<P>
   Piazza followed with his run-scoring bouncer into center, and
the Mets were up by seven runs. Did someone say insurmountable? Not
at this altitude.
</P>
<P>
   In any other city, Reed would have coasted with such a cushion.
But no lead seems safe here.
</P>
<P>
   Reed, who had last suited up at Coors Field as a member of the
National League All-Star team last month, had faced the minimum
nine batters over the first three innings, with a little help from
Piazza, who threw out Lansing on an attempted steal of second in
the third inning.
</P>
<P>
   But then Larry Walker lined his 15th homer of the season, with a
man on in the fourth, to make the score 7-2. And in the fifth, the
Rockies strung together four consecutive two-out hits, including a
two-run homer to center by Darryl Hamilton and a two-run double to
right-center by Dante Bichette. Suddenly, the score was 7-6.
</P>
<P>
   The Mets, who were able to knock Pedro Astacio from the game,
answered with a run in the top of the sixth on Ordonez's leadoff
double off Astacio, and Alfonzo's two-out sacrifice fly off
reliever Mike DeJean. But the Rockies scored again in the bottom of
the sixth on Vinny Castilla's leadoff double and Jeff Reed's
two-out single.
</P>
<P>
   Entering the bottom of the seventh, the Mets were clinging to an
8-7 lead when Valentine decided to bring in Rojas.
</P>
<P>
   ``Mel did a great job,'' Franco said. ``He deserves a lot of
credit tonight. We're going to need Mel just as we're going to need
me and everyone else in that pen down the stretch.''
</P>
<P>
   INSIDE PITCH:
</P>
<P>
   Todd Hundley entered the game 22-for-51 (.431) at Coors Field
with six home runs and 23 runs batted in. Hundley was 2-for-4 with
a double and a stolen base and is 5 for his last 7, raising his
batting average to .217. ... John Olerud's 21-game hitting streak
is the fourth longest in franchise history. Hubie Brooks holds the
club record of 24 games in 1984. ... The Mets, who could use some
bullpen help, nevertheless passed on the former Met Randy Myers,
who went from Toronto to San Diego on Thursday in a waiver-wire
deal. The left-handed Myers has five blown saves in 33 chances this
season and a 4.46 earned run average.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
