u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-AFRICA-VICTIMS-2NDLD-     08-08 0883
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-AFRICA-VICTIMS-2NDLD-WRITETHRU-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SERGEANT PLANNED TO MAKE THE ARMY HIS CAREER 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Mo., Calif., Maine, Ga., Ky., Ind., Ga.)   (SUBS to identify third victim and insert new information, grafs
3-10 are new.)  
 (See also AFRICA-BOMBING, AFRICA-U.S., AFRICA-SCENE,
AFRICA-SECURITY)  
(lh) 
 By ROBERT D. McFADDEN   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   A 27-year-old career Army sergeant who grew up partly in the
small Missouri town where President Harry S. Truman was born and
who served in the Persian Gulf War, was identified by the Defense
Department late Friday as one of the eight Americans killed in the
terrorist explosion that tore through the U.S. Embassy in Nairobi,
Kenya.
</P>
<P>
   While State Department officials declined to release the names
of any of the dead pending the notification of their families, the
Pentagon said that one of the victims _ the only military service
member killed in the blast _ was Sgt. Kenneth R. Hobson II, a
clerical aide to the embassy's defense attache.
</P>
<P>
   Relatives identified two other victims as Arlene Kirk, 50, who
worked for the Air Force, and Molly Huckaby Hardy, 51, a veteran
State Department employee, The Associated Press reported.
</P>
<P>
   Mrs. Kirk's brother, Dennis Bradley of South Bend, Ind., said in
a telephone interview that she had just returned to Africa after
spending six weeks visiting their elderly parents in South Bend.
</P>
<P>
   Bradley said Mrs. Kirk, 50, and her husband, Robert, had spent
about three years in Kenya. Kirk was a project director for the
State Department. Mrs. Kirk had found a job as an accountant in the
Air Force's budget department about six months ago, Bradley said.
</P>
<P>
   ``She was a terrific mother and wife,'' Bradley said. ``She was
just a very supportive person, whatever was happening. She was
terrific. She was helping my parents, helping them however she
could.''
</P>
<P>
   The couple had three children. Their youngest, a girl, died from
cancer at age 5 in 1992, he said.
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Hardy, a native of Valdosta, Ga., had been waiting for
almost two months to be relieved of her embassy duties in Kenya,
her mother told The Valdosta Daily Times Friday.
</P>
<P>
   ``She was fixing to come home,'' Jayne Huckaby said as family
members gathered at her Valdosta home. ``She was supposed to be
home June 15. She was waiting for someone else to come over to take
her place.''
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Hardy had worked for the State Department for 26 years in
Brazil, Laos and other countries. She had told her mother she was
returning to the United States to stay.
</P>
<P>
   Hobson grew up mostly in Nevada, Mo., but spent time in nearby
Lamar, the Truman birthplace near Missouri's western border where
his parents and a great aunt reside, had been in the Army since
1989, and was posted to Nairobi last winter for a two-year tour of
duty. He took along his wife, Deborah, and their 2-year-old
daughter, Meghan.
</P>
<P>
   In Lamar, a community of 4,000 people, the sergeant's father,
Kenneth Hobson Sr., a Vietnam War veteran, and mother, Bonnie,
declined a request for a telephone interview Friday night. Hazel
Hicks, the sergeant's great aunt, said the parents had been swamped
and exhausted by the local news media and would say no more before
Saturday.
</P>
<P>
   But a neighbor and family friend, Leona Doyle, 72, said she had
known the sergeant since he was a boy, and she recalled a strong,
popular youth.
</P>
<P>
   Born in Lake Tahoe, Calif., on May 1, 1971, he was brought to
Missouri at an early age by his family and attended schools in
Lamar and Nevada, towns about 25 miles apart near Missouri's
western border with Kansas.
</P>
<P>
   He was known to friends as Kenny Ray, Mrs. Doyle said, and he
grew into a strapping 6-foot athlete with close-cropped dark blond
hair, a fair complexion and blue eyes. She said he played
basketball at high school in Nevada, graduating in 1987.
</P>
<P>
   Sheriff William Griffitt of Barton County also knew Hobson
through his father, a communications officer for the Sheriff's
Department, and the sergeant's wife, a former secretary for the
department. Griffitt said the youth had enlisted in the Army in
1989.
</P>
<P>
   After basic training at Fort Leonard Wood, Mo., he spent time in
a variety of posts, including stations in Germany, in the Persian
Gulf during the 1991 conflict with Iraq, at Fort Campbell, Ky., and
in Monterrey, Calif., where he was trained in the Arabic language
for translation work. He also completed military intelligence
training at Ft. Gordon, Ga., and in Washington, D.C.
</P>
<P>
   He met his future wife, a native of Maine, who was also an Army
enlisted woman. After their daughter was born, Hobson was posted to
Washington to complete his military intelligence training, and his
wife and child moved in with the sergeant's parents until the
posting to Kenya last winter.
</P>
<P>
   Mrs. Doyle, who lives two doors from the Hobson family, said the
sergeant loved the Army, and spoke often of being ``proud to be an
American.'' She said he had intended to make a career of military
service.
</P>
<P>
   ``He was a loving boy, a very caring boy and such a family
man,'' Mrs. Doyle said in a voice that broke with emotion. ``He
loved his country and his home, and we are all shocked that he's
not coming home. It's a complete shock to the community that
something like this has happened to a Lamar boy.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
