<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-08-08 02:46 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4271 &Cx1f; tth-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FBN-SEAHAWKS-SPI &LR;      08-08 0943
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-SEAHAWKS-SPI </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
YOUNG QBS MANNING, KITNA STEP INTO SPOTLIGHT 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By CLARE FARNSWORTH  
 c.1998 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   CHENEY _ Before writing off Saturday night's preseason game
between the Seahawks and Indianapolis Colts as just another
meaningless exhibition, consider what it means to the two young
quarterbacks who will start the game and the futures of their
teams.
</P>
<P>
   The Seahawks' Jon Kitna and the Colts' Peyton Manning are making
their first preseason starts after arriving at this intersection
from opposite ends of the quarterback hierarchy.
</P>
<P>
   Manning is the football equivalent of royalty. Son of a former
NFL quarterback, Archie Manning. National high school player of the
year at Isidore Newman High in New Orleans. Runner-up for the
Heisman Trophy as a senior at Tennessee. First pick in April's NFL
draft. Recent recipient of an $11.6 million signing bonus, the
largest ever for an NFL rookie, as part of a six-year contract that
could be worth almost $48 million.
</P>
<P>
   By contrast, Kitna didn't start at quarterback at Tacoma's
Lincoln High School until his senior year. He went to Central
Washington University to play baseball. He cleaned dorm rooms for
two summers while attending college in Ellensburg. He joined the
Seahawks as a rookie free agent in 1996 only because coach Dennis
Erickson saw something in him that eluded everyone else in the NFL.
He is playing for the NFL minimum of $216,000.
</P>
<P>
   ``It will be interesting to see how Jon performs. That's why
we're giving him this opportunity,'' Erickson said. ``It's a
different opportunity for him than it's been in the last two
preseasons, where he's come in with the third and second groups and
done very well. Now he's got an opportunity to play with the
starters against their starters. We'll see exactly where he's at.''
</P>
<P>
   For his part, Manning offers, ``Obviously, it will be more
physical than I've ever played against. But I think I'm ready to
handle that.''
</P>
<P>
   Don't tell Kitna or Manning that Saturday night's game doesn't
matter.
</P>
<P>
   Kitna's performance is linked short-term to the club's
still-simmering contract talks with holdout Warren Moon, and
longer-term to the future of Erickson _ who is well aware that this
is a win-or-else season for him.
</P>
<P>
   It was Erickson who dubbed Kitna the quarterback of the future,
before Kitna quarterbacked Barcelona to the World League
championship and then won his first NFL start by rallying the
Seahawks past the Raiders in December. Some in the organization
feel the Seahawks have acquired enough talent and depth in the past
two offseasons that they can win with Kitna or John Friesz. If
Kitna performs well Saturday night, it will only add to the growing
sentiment of moving on _ with or without Moon.
</P>
<P>
   In Indianapolis, the Colts are starting over.
</P>
<P>
   They have a new general manager in Bill Polian, who was the
architect of the Buffalo Bills' Super Bowl teams and then built an
expansion team in Carolina that reached the NFC Championship game
in only its second season.
</P>
<P>
   They have a new coach in Jim Mora, the former Seahawks and
University of Washington assistant and head coach of the New
Orleans Saints.
</P>
<P>
   They have a new, brighter future, and have placed it in the
hands of Manning.
</P>
<P>
   Once the game starts, however, the future will give way to the
present.
</P>
<P>
   ``The coaches on both sides are expecting the same things out of
us,'' Kitna said. ``It doesn't matter that he's getting paid what
he's getting paid and I'm getting paid what I'm getting paid, or
where we came from. All that's not going to matter once the game
starts.''
</P>
<P>
   That, in a word or a few, explains one of the things that
Kitna's coaches and teammates like best about him. The kid from
Tacoma is unaffected by all this.
</P>
<P>
   Remember, Kitna was planning to finish his student-teaching
assignment in Yakima and become a high school math teacher when the
Seahawks called in April 1996 and invited him to a workout.
</P>
<P>
   Remember, nobody knew this guy even when he was leading Central
Washington to a share of the NAIA national title his senior season.
Erickson first saw Kitna only because he went to see his nephew
play.
</P>
<P>
   And remember, even Kitna admits his performances in training
camp and preseason didn't warrant him being carried on the practice
squad his first season.
</P>
<P>
   But here he is, taking the next big step toward the future _ his
and that of his team.
</P>
<P>
   Kitna's first step, however, could look like one from the past.
He reminds more than a few of Dave Krieg, the unorthodox producer
of so many impromptu plays during his stint as the Seahawks'
starting quarterback from 1983-91.
</P>
<P>
   Like Krieg, practice is almost too restrictive for Kitna. He is
at his best when things are not.
</P>
<P>
   ``In some aspects, we are the same,'' Kitna said of the Krieg
comparisons, which he considers a compliment. ``We're both scrappy,
and I don't think he cared what people thought about him and how he
looked on the field as long as he got the job done. That was his
mentality when I watched him growing up, and that's the same
mentality I have.''
</P>
<P>
   It's a mentality that has endeared Kitna to his teammates. Kitna
is a leader without trying to be. He is at ease and in control
whether surrounded by a group of defensive backs or in the company
of his offensive linemen.
</P>
<P>
   ``I know it will be fun because Jon has a great attitude about
everything, and he is very calm and wants to make plays,'' running
back Ricky Watters said. ``I played with Steve Young (in San
Francisco) who wanted to make plays, and I see a lot of
similarities between the two.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
