<DATE_TIME> 1998-08-08 02:49 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4272 &Cx1f; tth-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BBA-MARINERS-SPI &LR;      08-08 0887
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBA-MARINERS-SPI </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MARINERS EARN RARE DOUBLEHEADER SWEEP 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By JIM STREET  
 c.1998 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   DETROIT _ Jamie Moyer surrendered a run to the Detroit Tigers
Friday night for the first time since becoming a Mariner, but
another first stood out even more.
</P>
<P>
   Raul Ibanez's first 1998 at-bat.
</P>
<P>
   Fewer than five hours after putting on a Mariner uniform for the
first time since spring training, Ibanez delivered a game-winning,
pinch-hit double with the bases loaded in the eighth inning,
propelling Seattle to a 6-3 victory in the opener of a
double-header at Tiger Stadium.
</P>
<P>
   Moyer tamed the Tigers in the nightcap, running his personal
scoreless-innings streak against them to 27 before giving up a run
that didn't really matter as the Mariners rolled to a 7-1 victory
before 29,039 fans.
</P>
<P>
   The Mariners got more good news Friday: first baseman David
Segui's knee injury is not as serious as it looked Thursday night
(see story, Page E2).
</P>
<P>
   In Friday night's nightcap, Alex Rodriguez hit his 34th homer
and came within a triple of hitting for the cycle for the second
time in 14 months at Tiger Stadium, Ken Griffey Jr. drove in two
runs and rookie left fielder Shane Monahan singled three times in
the Mariners' 13-hit assault against Tiger ace Brian Moehler and
two relievers.
</P>
<P>
   The sweep was Seattle's first since May 6, 1989 against
Baltimore.
</P>
<P>
   The M's had split their nine previous doubleheaders and might
have divided this one if not for Ibanez.
</P>
<P>
   Promoted from Class AAA Tacoma Friday in case Segui's knee
injury proved serious, Ibanez joined the Mariners without much
rest. But he used an adrenaline surge to deliver the most important
hit of the day.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was well worth bringing him up,'' manager Lou Piniella
said. ``Something like that (game-winning double) picks up the
whole team.''
</P>
<P>
   Friday's news was certainly more welcome than Thursday's. While
the M's were being rained out Thursday night and Segui's right knee
locked up, Ibanez was in Nashville, Tenn., playing most of the 13
innings in Tacoma's 2-1 loss.
</P>
<P>
   After sleeping for about two hours, Ibanez flew to Detroit early
Friday morning, unaware of Segui's injury or the Mariners' plans.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was pretty tired when I got here,'' Ibanez said, ``but I
found some energy. I think the adrenaline kicked in.''
</P>
<P>
   Ibanez watched as Mariner reliever Bobby Ayala squandered a
two-run lead in the seventh inning. He then grabbed a bat in the
eighth with the game tied and a new teammate on every base.
</P>
<P>
   ``They told me (Tiger reliever Matt Anderson) throws hard and
hit the first good pitch I saw,'' said Ibanez, referring to a chat
with his teammates. ``I got the fat part of the bat on the ball.''
</P>
<P>
   Seattle had loaded the bases on Edgar Martinez's leadoff double
and one-out walks to Russ Davis (intentional) and pinch-hitter Joe
Oliver (unintentional).
</P>
<P>
   When Tiger manager Buddy Bell changed pitchers, Piniella changed
batters, switching from right-handed hitting John Marzano to the
left-handed Ibanez. Although it was a predictable move, it also was
a bold move by Piniella, considering M's left-handed pinch-hitters
were a combined 1-for-23 this season and no RBIs.
</P>
<P>
   Ibanez, oblivious to the season-long trend, drilled a
first-pitch double into right-center, putting the M's ahead for
good. Monahan added an RBI single to center, leaving Heathcliff
Slocumb and Mike Timlin to protect the second three-run lead of the
game.
</P>
<P>
   Both got the job done. Slocumb got the win, his second, and
Timlin secured his eighth save.
</P>
<P>
   Ayala, however, prevented Jeff Fassero from winning his 11th
game.
</P>
<P>
   The Mariner starter had trouble breathing because of the high
humidity and finally departed in the sixth inning after walking
Bobby Higginson with two outs. Detroit catcher Joe Siddall had
opened the inning with his first career home run.
</P>
<P>
   ``I haven't pitched in humidity like this in a long time, and I
couldn't breathe,'' Fassero said. ``I was just trying to throw
strikes and throw as few pitches as I could.''
</P>
<P>
   Fassero said Florida is the only other place that bothered him
in the past.
</P>
<P>
   Moyer, his rotation sidekick, wasn't bothered as much by the
humidity as the Tiger Stadium pitching mound.
</P>
<P>
   ``I had horrible command of my pitches,'' Moyer said. ``The
mound is different here (than other parks) and I couldn't figure it
out until the fifth inning. But I battled through it and eventually
got into a groove.''
</P>
<P>
   It helped that the Mariners pounced on Moehler early.
</P>
<P>
   Joey Cora's leadoff single and Rodriguez's first hit, a double,
ignited a two-run first inning. Seattle tacked on three more in the
second inning with Cora, Griffey and Martinez driving in the runs.
</P>
<P>
   Moyer bobbed and weaved his way through the first four innings,
leaving the bases loaded in the first, another runner on base in
the third and pitched through a leadoff double by Geronimo Berroa
in the fourth.
</P>
<P>
   His shutout streak ended in the fifth when Joe Randa singled and
eventually scored on Higginson's sacrifice fly.
</P>
<P>
   ``I can't explain why I've had so much success against them,''
said Moyer, who has a 5-2 record and 1.94 ERA in 16 career games
against the Tigers. ``I feel they have a lot of (offensive) threats
on that team.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
