<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR; FOR SUNDAY AMs &LR;
</P>
<P>
   Here are today's top news stories from The New York Times News
Service for AMs of Sunday, Aug. 9:
</P>
<P>
   &UR; INTERNATIONAL &LR;  (``i'' code)
</P>
<P>
   &UR; AFRICA BOMBINGS &LR;
</P>
<P>
   AFRICA-BOMBINGS (Nairobi, Kenya) _ Lede-all on developments
after the bombing of the U.S. embassies. By James C. McKinley Jr.
</P>
<P>
   With
</P>
<P>
   AFRICA-U.S. (Washington) _ President Clinton said today that the
United States would not shirk from its role as world leader as a
result of terrorism, even though Americans are prime targets and
the capture of terrorists can take decades. By Jeff Gerth.
</P>
<P>
   And
</P>
<P>
   AFRICA-VICTIMS (Johannesburg, South Africa) _ After a confusing
scene at the Nairobi airport this morning, three injured employees
of the U.S. embassy in Kenya were flown to Pretoria on a South
African military airplane as other bombing victims awaited medical
approval to be transported.
</P>
<P>
   Others as warranted.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Other International &LR;
</P>
<P>
   SHIP-GRAVEYARD (Alang, India) _ After more than a million miles
of plying the world's oceans, the Milagro, a 35,000-ton,
Malta-registered bulk carrier, completed her final journey from the
Persian Gulf on a recent afternoon and dropped anchor off this
windswept point on India's northwest coast. Few maps show Alang, a
soulless spot on the coastline of Gujarat state 185 miles northwest
of Bombay. But in recent years, what had once been a
poverty-stricken village has become the world's biggest
shipbreaking yard. In the 1990s, Alang has served as the graveyard
for almost half the ships scrapped by the world's navies and
merchant marines. By John F. Burns.
</P>
<P>
   EUROPE-AIRCON (Rome) _ When Americans rushed to cool their air,
Europeans traditionally just slowed down and endured the summer
heat. But now Europeans have decided to stop going without. Indeed,
Europe is becoming a big market for the air-conditioning industry.
Sales of air-conditioners for homes and small businesses have grown
more than 20 percent over the last three years, even as they stayed
flat in the United States, and the growth shows no sign of abating.
By John Tagliabue.
</P>
<P>
   IRAN-U.S.-OIL (Baku, Azerbaijan) _ American oil companies, the
largest players on the energy-rich Caspian Sea, are expressing
growing exasperation with the White House policy forbidding
American investment in Iran. Despite an overture to Iran by
Secretary of State Madeleine K. Albright in June, the
administration has insisted that geopolitical strategy outstrips
the commercial advantages being ceded to European companies doing
business there. By Jane Perlez and Steve LeVine.
</P>
<P>
   YUGO-KOSOVO (Pornoc, Yugoslavia) _ How ethnic Albanian refugees
are faring. By Mike O'Connor.
</P>
<P>
   CONGO-REBELLION (Abidjan, Ivory Coast) _ Developments in eastern
Congo. By Howard W. French.
</P>
<P>
   BURMA-CRACKDOWN (Bangkok, Thailand) _ Tenth anniversary of the
military crackdown on student-led demonstrations. By Seth Mydans.
</P>
<P>
   CHINA-FLOODS (Shaoxing, China) _ Developments in central Hubei
province Flood as China battles the swelling Yangtze river. By Seth
Faison.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; WASHINGTON &LR;  (``w'' code)
</P>
<P>
   HEALTHCARE (Washington) _ In 1994, when President Clinton's
effort to reshape the American health care system collapsed, a
political consensus emerged from the rubble: in the future, any
such changes should be made piecemeal, one step at a time. But four
years later, the limits of that incremental approach are becoming
clear, in the view of many experts. Most immediately, Congress is
confronting demands to provide broad new consumer protections for
patients fed up with the restrictions of managed care. Lawmakers
also face a deeper, more intractable problem. Despite the passage
of several laws intended to expand coverage step by step, the
number of Americans without insurance has risen steadily, by an
average of 1 million a year. By Robert Pear. (A special report.)
</P>
<P>
   CONGRESS-REPUBS (Washington) _ Republicans in Congress left for
their summer vacation this week deeply divided, fighting themselves
as hard as they fought Democrats, and unable to fill the policy
vacuum left by the hobbled Clinton presidency. By Alison Mitchell.
</P>
<P>
   DEMOCRATS-TRUCE (Undated) _ Two long-feuding pillars of the
Democratic Party, the liberal AFL-CIO and the centrist Democratic
Leadership Council, have agreed to a detente in which they pledge
to stop attacking each other and to seek common ground to help the
Democrats this fall and beyond. By Steven Greenhouse.
</P>
<P>
   Y2K-GOVERNMENT (Washington) _ Federal agencies are reporting
progress in fixing their computers to cope with the Year 2000
problem, but some of them are exaggerating what they have done,
according to independent federal experts. By Matthew L. Wald.
</P>
<P>
   CLINTON-DNA-TESTS (Undated) _ As FBI scientists conduct tests on
one of Monica S. Lewinsky's dresses, trying to determine whether it
contains physical evidence of a sexual encounter with President
Clinton, they are employing a science that, though still sharply
debated in court, is considered highly reliable and capable of
answering a number of questions with remarkable speed and accuracy.
By Gina Kolata.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; NATIONAL GENERAL &LR;  (``a'' code)
</P>
<P>
   JONESBORO-SHOOTINGS (Jonesboro, Ark.) _ Mitchell Johnson will
turn 14 on Tuesday, the day that he and Andrew Golden, 12, will be
tried on murder charges in the shooting spree on March 24 that 5
people dead left 10 others wounded at Westside Middle School here.
Under state law, the boys must be tried as juveniles and, even if
found to be ``delinquent,'' they will be released on their 18th
birthdays unless they have committed crimes while in detention. By
Rick Bragg.
</P>
<P>
   PRISON-GROWTH (Undated) _ The nation's prison population grew by
5.2 percent in 1997, according to the Justice Department, even
though crime has been declining for six straight years, suggesting
that the imprisonment boom has developed a built-in growth dynamic
independent of the crime rate, experts say. In a new report, the
Justice Department said the number of Americans in local jails and
in state and federal prisons rose to 1,725,842 in 1997, up from 1.1
million in 1990. By Fox Butterfield.
</P>
<P>
   FUGITIVE-LAWYER (Miami) _ When Michael Abbell, a former Justice
Department extradition chief, and William M. Moran, a criminal
defense lawyer, were charged with the crimes of the Colombian drug
cartel they represented, lawyers nationwide denounced the
prosecution as a government effort to intimidate the defense bar.
In July a jury convicted them on charges of racketeering and
money-laundering conspiracy. Now some lawyers are also grappling
with a more immediate question: Where is Moran? The 59-year-old
defendant was last seen on July 17 in the federal courthouse here,
shortly after he learned that the jury had reached a partial
verdict, and he remains a fugitive. By Mireya Navarro.
</P>
<P>
   ASSASSINS (Chicago) _ Portraits of assassins are fixed in the
American mind: the deranged madman, the lonely loser obsessed with
his target, the political killer following threats with violence.
These portraits are the stuff of myth, the Secret Service has
concluded in ``Preventing Assassination,'' a new study of all 83
people who attacked or tried to attack an American political figure
or celebrity in the last 50 years. The results, recently made
available, challenge several stereotypes. By Bill Dedman.
</P>
<P>
   HAIGHT-ASHBURY (San Francisco) _ A Love Child might not
recognize the place. Here at Haight and Ashbury streets, ground
zero of the 1960s counterculture revolution, a Ben &AMP; Jerry's ice
cream store now stands on one corner, a Gap clothing store on
another. But The Haight's most compelling change is one less
discernible to the roving eye. While the now romanticized flower
children were painted as being spiritually connected by political
ideology and the haze of a marijuana high, many young people on the
same streets today share the common pain of broken lives and harder
drugs. By Michael Janofsky.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; NEW YORK &LR;  (``a'' code)
</P>
<P>
   NY-PHONE-STRIKE (Undated) _ Developments as more than 35,000
Bell Atlantic workers in New York are ready to go on strike at
midnight unless new contacts are reached with two unions, officials
say. By Steven Greenhouse.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; MOVING LATER:  &LR;
</P>
<P>
   AM-FRONTPAGE-NYT _ A description of the front page layout of the
first edition of The New York Times will move at 12:30 p.m.
