   Moving in (w) Washington and (t) travel categories.
</P>
<P>
   MARSHES _ WEST PALM BEACH, Fla. _ The $700 million state project
to clean up the Everglades doesn't offer the best working
conditions, but it is pouring money into South Florida's
construction industry _ and, water managers say, it's going
smoothly and under budget so far. The project has faced a barrage
of criticism from sugar growers and state lawmakers over projected
cost overruns (now solved, supposedly), and from some
environmentalists and Miccosukee Indian activists who consider it
an ecological sellout. We've been going through contracts and
invoices looking for waste (nothing so far), as well as trying to
quantify the economic impact. So far, it hasn't been a big boost
for the Glades' economy. (King., Palm Beach Post). 30.
</P>
<P>
   For Sunday, Aug. 9
</P>
<P>
   DEPUTY-DRIVING _ WEST PALM BEACH, Fla. _ The Palm Beach County
Sheriff's Office is using a high-tech program to reduce car crashes
by its deputies. This is the first study of its scale in the
country. The goals of the program are to identify high-risk drivers
and to modify the current training program, and to minimize the
costs of the accidents. (Masory, Palm Beach Post). 18-20.
</P>
