<HEADLINE>
SMALL TOWN MOURNS SOLDIER KILLED IN NAIROBI 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Ind., Ga., Maine)  (mk) 
 By DIRK JOHNSON   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEVADA, Mo. _ Restless in a little Missouri town set to a safe
but predictable rhythm, young Kenneth Hobson could scarcely wait to
grow up and start chasing adventure.
</P>
<P>
   ``He wanted to see the world,'' said his mother, Bonnie Hobson,
sitting on a porch suddenly filled with flowers of condolence. ``He
knew there was more to life out there, and he was determined to see
it.''
</P>
<P>
   Word came early Friday that her 27-year-old son, Sgt. Kenneth
Hobson Jr., who has a wife and a 2-year-old daughter, had been
killed in the terrorist attack on the U.S. Embassy in Nairobi,
Kenya.
</P>
<P>
   President Clinton said Saturday that 11 Americans had been
killed in the Nairobi blast. No Americans were among the victims in
a simultaneous bombing on Friday in Dar es Salaam, Tanzania.
</P>
<P>
   Only two other Americans have been identified so far. They are
Arlene Kirk, 50, a civilian Air Force employee from South Bend,
Ind., and Molly Huckaby Hardy, 51, a longtime State Department
employee who was originally from Valdosta, Ga.
</P>
<P>
   Growing up in a modest blue house at the corner of Tucker and
Austin Streets, behind a sturdy old maple tree, young Kenneth
Hobson was known as a talented, handsome and popular boy who never
wasted a minute of life.
</P>
<P>
   He loved to debate world affairs and play tennis, act in school
plays, go hiking, cook gourmet meals and paint. One of his mother's
favorite artworks was a drawing he had done from the opera La
Maison.
</P>
<P>
   In school, he was a good student. Friends complained that he
never seemed to crack the books, but always performed well on tests
and projects.
</P>
<P>
   ``He was our only child,'' the young man's mother said Saturday.
``He was my baby.''
</P>
<P>
   The telephone rang at the mother's home in nearby Lamar before
sunrise. It was her daughter-in-law, Debbie, calling from Nairobi,
and crying uncontrollably. ``He's gone,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   The soldier's widow, who is from Maine, will soon be returning
to the United States with the couple's daughter, Meghan.
</P>
<P>
   In this town of about 9,000 a bit north of the Ozarks region,
people reacted with shock and sadness that a native son had been
lost in the horrifying attack on Friday that killed more than 100
people.
</P>
<P>
   At the Quick Dine restaurant, where heaving plates of biscuits
and gravy crowded the lunch counter, Jim Dilly said it was
difficult to imagine that anyone could prove a political point by
killing innocent people.
</P>
<P>
   ``I guess there's a good reason that our people were over
there,'' he said. ``But what a shame.''
</P>
<P>
   The parents of the fallen soldier, a Gulf War veteran, were
formally notified on Friday by an emissary from the Army, who
carried a blue folder as he walked up to the family's front door.
</P>
<P>
   His father, Kenneth Hobson Sr., had been a Vietnam veteran who
was seriously injured by an explosion in that war.
</P>
<P>
   Their son ``had a lot of dreams,'' his mother said. ``And if he
had lived, he would have fulfilled every one of them.''
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   One dream was to retire from the Army at age 37, attend culinary
school and then open a bed and breakfast, perhaps in New England,
his mother said.
</P>
<P>
   Coming from a working-class family, he had joined the Army after
graduating from Nevada High School in 1989, hoping to earn money
for college. His father was a police officer in town. His mother
worked at a drive-in restaurant.
</P>
<P>
   But he enjoyed the travel of military life, and decided to make
a career of it, his mother said. Before going to Africa, he had
been given a choice of four other assignments, all of them closer
to his base in Fort Gordon, Ga. But he chose the most exotic
assignment.
</P>
<P>
   The young man told his parents he was not allowed to talk much
about his job in Nairobi. The military has described him as an
administrative specialist at the embassy.
</P>
<P>
   The Hobsons moved to Nevada from nearby Lamar when young Kenneth
was in the fourth grade, and moved back to Lamar after their son
graduated from high school. Hobson is now a deputy in the Barton
County Sheriff's Department.
</P>
<P>
   The Hobsons are a highly regarded family in Nevada, known as a
decent family that treated other people well. ``The one thing that
stuck out about the young man,'' said Doug Allard, referring to the
killed soldier, ``was how polite he was as a kid.''
</P>
<P>
   But he was not afraid to have opinions, according to his family
and others who knew him. Some people joked that he was happiest
when engaged in a passionate argument about issues.
</P>
<P>
   ''He had a great sense of humor, too,'' said his mother.
``People just liked to be around him.''
</P>
<P>
   In the ritual of compassion, a parade of neighbors and friends
lined the sidewalk in front of the Hobson home in Lamar, bringing
hugs and hams, vows of prayers and resolutions to ``keep strong.''
</P>
<P>
   Many of them told the tearful parents that their boy was a hero.
His father said, ``Anybody who wears the uniform is a hero.''
</P>
</TEXT>
