<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-AFRICA-BOMBINGS-ART-1,000(2TAKES)-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TOLL RISES AS RESCUE EFFORT GOES ON IN KENYA 
</HEADLINE>
  (ART ADV: A locator map is being sent to NYT graphics clients.
Non-subscribers can make individual purchase by calling
212-556-4204 or 1927.) 
(mk) 
 By JAMES C. McKINLEY JR.   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NAIROBI, Kenya _ Dozens of volunteers continued a slow,
desperate effort Saturday to save people still trapped under tons
of rubble from a terrorist attack on the U.S. Embassy here, as
American medical teams and FBI investigators began to arrive in two
East African capitals.
</P>
<P>
   The death toll from the simultaneous car-bomb explosions, here
and in Dar es Salaam, Tanzania, rose above 90 people and is likely
to rise even higher as the debris from a leveled seven-story
building in Nairobi is cleared away, Kenyan authorities said.
Streams of wounded overwhelmed the city's hospitals, where more
than 500 people have been admitted and more than 4,200 treated in
less than two days.
</P>
<P>
   At least 40 people, many of them secretarial students, are
believed to be buried and hope for their survival dimmed as the
hours went by. ``It is probable the death figures will go much
above this,'' the Kenyan foreign minister, Bonaya Godana, said.
</P>
<P>
   The official U.S. investigation of the bombings here and in
Tanzania, which the State Department has said were coordinated
terrorist acts, was off to a slow start. The authorities here said
the explosion was believed to have been caused by a car bomb, but
the U.S. government maintained a strict silence about its efforts
to dig out its own dead and to investigate the attack.
</P>
<P>
   The worse devastation was in Nairobi, where the volunteers
continued trying to to save at least three people believed to be
buried alive in the collapsed Ufundi Cooperative House, 30 hours
after the attack. The building took the brunt of a huge explosion
that also gutted the rear of the U.S. Embassy next door. President
Clinton said the blast killed at least 11 Americans and an unknown
number of Kenyans.
</P>
<P>
   A child was among the dead and five others were still missing,
the State Department said earlier.
</P>
<P>
   The rescue efforts were going slowly and did not seem well
organized. By late afternoon Saturday, the ad-hoc team of
volunteers, private contractors, engineers, Red Cross workers and
Kenyan soldiers were still trying to find a way to lift several
large slabs of concrete without causing a general collapse that
would doom the few people still left alive beneath.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's been slow and there is no coordination,'' complained
Aloys Okello, the 47-year-old general manager of a credit union
housed in the building. ``Everyone is trying to give his own
orders.''
</P>
<P>
   Very few details had emerged by late afternoon about the bomb
itself, or how it was detonated. Kenyan authorities said it
appeared that a car-bomb had been parked near the entrance ramp
leading to the underground garage beneath the American mission. A
blackened crater gapes amid the rubble at that point, and the blast
has warped a wrought iron fence around the building's perimeter.
</P>
<P>
   Some witnesses told local newspaper reporters they saw a man
driving a pick-up truck onto the ramp just before the explosion.
But if that was the bomber, the authorities here said it was still
unclear whether the bomber was blown up in the attack or escaped.
</P>
<P>
   ``The point of the blast seems to have been exactly at the front
of the entrance of the basement parking lot,'' Godana, the foreign
minister, said Saturday afternoon. ``It is probable that the person
tried to get into the garage and could not.''
</P>
<P>
   Only two FBI agents had arrived by late afternoon, and there
appeared to be little or no police activity at the blast site.
</P>
<P>
   U.S. officials at the embassy denied reporters access to the
building and put up a screen around it to mask their rescue
operation. They declined to say how many bodies had been found in
the embassy building, though they did say no one had been found
alive.
</P>
<P>
   Marines and other government employees could be seen digging
through the devastated offices at the rear of the building, but it
was unclear by late afternoon what they had found.
</P>
<P>
   Tensions began to rise between the American workers and tired
Kenyan volunteers who were combing the remains of the Ufundi
building next door.
</P>
<P>
   Several Kenyan rescue workers complained that the U.S. Marines
and other U.S. officials had done little to help them extricate
people from the Ufundi House and had even prevented them from
taking dead Kenyan nationals out of the embassy building and from
searching for survivors there.
</P>
<P>
   ``It is very unfair, because all of this problem happened
because of them,'' said one volunteer, Lorna Matewa, a 36-year-old
banker, who was in his second day of helping to find survivors.
</P>
<P>
   The city's seven hospitals were also struggling to cope with a
flood of injured people. More than 542 people had been hospitalized
by Saturday afternoon, including 24 in critical condition. Another
4,257 were treated for minor injuries and released.
</P>
<P>
   Godana said the hospitals were short of everything from blood to
bandages to sutures and appealed for help from overseas. ``The
sudden rush was overwhelming,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Some relief began to arrive Saturday morning as American medical
teams flew into Nairobi. An American cargo aircraft carrying 44
personnel with medical supplies, food and communiaations equipment
touched down just after 9 a.m., and a second arrived a few minutes
later with more medical equipment.
</P>
<P>
   Israel was expected to send 200 soldiers trained in rescuing
people from collapsed buildings Saturday afternoon, but they had
yet to arrive in Kenya at 2:30 p.m. Local police officials have
pinned their hopes on the Israeli army, which has vast experience
in terrorist attacks.
</P>
<P>
   In the meantime, the rescue effort at Ufundi House limped along.
Kenyan and British army engineers worked through the night to
rescue about five people trapped in the rubble. Rescue workers said
Saturday afternoon they had made contact with at least two people,
a man and a woman, in the wreckage who were still alive.
</P>
<P>
   But another man died Saturday morning on the verge of being
saved, having survived for more than 24 hours with his legs pinned
under tons of masonry. Though rescue workers could not see him,
they heard his voice and lowered water and biscuits through a hole
to nourish him through his ordeal. He died before the workers could
dig him out.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   ``We will still go on,'' said Stephen Kamau, a Kenyan army
surgeon. ``We have lost a battle but we are still going to win the
war.''
</P>
<P>
   In Nairobi, grieving people struggled to come to terms with what
had happened, as they searched the hospitals for lost relatives.
</P>
<P>
   At the City Council Mortuary on Ngong Road, crowds of people
whose relatives were missing pressed up against the main gate and
demanded entry to find out if their worse fears were true.
</P>
<P>
   Samson Maunda, a 46-year-old accountant, said he had been
looking all night for his brother, Daniel Mutinda, who was an
employee of a bank on the sixth floor of the Ufundi building. He
had visited hospitals and their mortuaries, looking among the
disfigured bodies.
</P>
<P>
   ``I have gone through all the hospitals where I could find him
alive and I have not,'' he said. ``If he was in the building at
that time, he is dead.''
</P>
<P>
   Nearby, Veronica Odhiambo, a 34-year-old teacher, was waiting
for word about her cousin, John Odhiambo. The 28-year-old
electrical engineer had been in the bank building next door to the
Ufundi house just minutes before the blast.
</P>
<P>
   ``You don't expect such a thing like this,'' she said. ``You
wonder why someone would want to do this. Even if you have a
problem with any country, why attack innocent people?''
</P>
<P>
   Inside the mortuary, the dead were laid out in ugly rows. There
were so many that some were lined up next to each other on the
floor.
</P>
<P>
   There were more than 70 bodies. One victim, a young woman in
blue jeans, had been decapitated. Several were burned into charred
parodies of the human form. Many had suffered shrapnel-like
injuries to their heads. Others appeared to be sleeping.
</P>
<P>
   The linoleum floor was covered with blood. There was no place to
step without walking over a corpse.
</P>
<P>
   Orderlies let people wander through, looking for their kin. Some
had trouble telling if they had found their family members or not.
</P>
<P>
   Outside, Pastor Wilfred Mayaka left the mortuary and put his arm
around his daughter as she wept quietly. After a long night, their
search was over. His wife, Lydia Mayaka, who was 40, lay in the
morgue among the other disfigured dead. She had worked in the
embassy as a clerk.
</P>
<P>
   ``I have lost a wife, the mother of my children. How do you
think I feel?'' the pastor said when approached by a reporter.
``Whatever you do, it doesn't help me, because I have lost a
wife.''
</P>
</TEXT>
