<HEADER>
A4343 &Cx1f; taf-z
u w &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CLINTON-DNA-TESTS-NYT     08-08 1199
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CLINTON-DNA-TESTS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
IN DNA TESTING, THE RESULTS DEPEND ON THE QUESTIONS 
</HEADLINE>
   (bl)  
 By GINA KOLATA   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   As FBI scientists conduct tests on one of Monica Lewinsky's
dresses, trying to determine whether it contains physical evidence
of a sexual encounter with President Clinton, they are employing a
science that, though still sharply debated in court, is considered
highly reliable and capable of answering a number of questions with
remarkable speed and accuracy.
</P>
<P>
   Despite early arguments over its use, lawyers and scientists
agree that properly conducted DNA analysis is convincing evidence,
though jurors are still free to disregard it, as they apparently
did in the murder trial of O.J. Simpson.
</P>
<P>
   ``Most of the time it works pretty well, particularly if you
have an ample sample,'' said Dr. William Thompson, a law professor
at the University of California at Irvine who often works with
defense lawyers and who has been sharply critical of DNA work done
in some laboratories that he says were incompetent.
</P>
<P>
   Analysis of DNA, the material in human cells that records each
person's genetic inheritance, from height to hair color, cannot
give absolute proof that a given sample came from a particular
person. But scientists can calculate the odds, and their
calculations are persuasive.
</P>
<P>
   ``If you prove it to one chance in a million or one chance in a
hundred thousand, that's better proof than most of us ever see,''
said Dr. Charles Brenner, a forensic mathematician in Berkeley,
Calif., who consults for DNA testing laboratories, mostly for the
prosecution in criminal cases.
</P>
<P>
   But the actual process of analyzing a given piece of evidence,
like the dress Ms. Lewinsky provided to prosecutors, is a
complicated matter. It is easy to cut off a tiny piece of fabric
containing a stain and then soak off any cells on that fabric.
Then, however, what is learned depends on what questions are asked.
</P>
<P>
   The FBI will not comment on how it is proceeding or what tests
it is using on Ms. Lewinsky's dress, said Jule Miller, a
spokeswoman for the agency. But others who are familiar with
forensic testing described standard methods, which for the FBI are
routine.
</P>
<P>
   It is not clear whether the tests are ongoing, or whether they
have been completed, with the results closely held. Whatever the
case, the work is probably being done in one of two FBI DNA
laboratories, most likely the one on the third floor of the J.
Edgar Hoover building, the FBI's fortress-like headquarters in
Washington. That laboratory is one of more than 20 in the Hoover
building. Others are used to test everything from paint chips to
fingerprints. Those same laboratories were used in other
high-profile cases, including that of TWA Flight 800, which crashed
near New York. In fact, evidence from that investigations remains
in the laboratories there.
</P>
<P>
   The other DNA laboratory, almost a duplicate, is in the bureau's
training complex at Quantico, Va.
</P>
<P>
   Only a decade ago, DNA testing was challenged in many courtrooms
and other forums because, critics argued, laboratories were prone
to make mistakes. But since then the debate has been muffled, and
DNA tests have been used in successful prosecutions and to allow
the Pentagon to identify remains exhumed from the Tomb of the
Unknowns.
</P>
<P>
   With the Lewinsky dress, the first task would be to look for
sperm cells. To do that, investigators like to use a ``Christmas
tree'' stain, named for the way it colors cells, said Dr. Edward
Blake, a forensic scientist at Forensic Science Associates of
Richmond, Calif. With this stain, a cell's nucleus, where DNA is
located, stains red. The cytoplasm, the jellylike material
surrounding the nucleus, turns green. Sperm are easily visible
because they have virtually no cytoplasm and so, unlike other cells
in the body, they stain only red.
</P>
<P>
   If scientists see sperm in the sample on the dress, they would
want to isolate the sperm DNA. All that is needed for a successful
DNA test is 300 sperm. Even a drop the size of a pinhead normally
contains 50,000 to 100,000 sperm, Blake said.
</P>
<P>
   With the sperm DNA in hand, scientists can test it with
molecular probes to be certain it is human DNA. If it is, they can
do the actual DNA tests.
</P>
<P>
   The quickest DNA test focuses on six genes that vary slightly
from person to person. With one of the genes, dq alpha, individuals
can have any of 28 distinct gene patterns. The other five genes
come in either three or six variants. Enumerating the list of
possible combinations of gene patterns is almost like the list of
possible combinations in a lottery. There is only one chance in
3,000 that two people, by chance, would have exactly the same
combinations of the genes, Blake said.
</P>
<P>
   It is easy to see which variant of each gene a person has.
Scientists make multiple copies of the six genes in the person's
DNA by using an enzyme programmed to copy the genes. As they do so,
they add a marker to each gene copy. Then they pour a solution
containing the gene copies over a nylon strip embedded with all the
variants of the six genes. Each gene in the solution locks onto its
matching gene in the nylon strip. And when a gene docks with its
counterpart on the nylon strip, the marker makes it light up blue.
So by looking at the blue dots on the nylon strip, scientists can
immediately see which gene variants an individual has.
</P>
<P>
   Because so much might hinge on the result of the DNA test,
forensic investigators might want to confirm it with an even more
sensitive test that looks for individual variations in repeated
segments of DNA that are scattered about like molecular stutters.
An individual's pattern of these repeated segments is essentially
unique. But the standard test to look for such a pattern can take
months. A newer test that looks for shorter repeated DNA segments
can be completed in days, Dr. Blake said. But laboratories have
less experience with it, and results from it might be more
vulnerable to challenge in court, he added.
</P>
<P>
   Forensic laboratories can also analyze cells other than sperm
that might be in a stain. If the sperm were ejaculated in a sexual
encounter, cells from the partner might be mixed in the stain, and
scientists can determine what kind of cells they are and whose
cells they are.
</P>
<P>
   Another possibility that arises in forensics is a semen stain
that contains no sperm because the man had a vasectomy, which
severs the pipeline of sperm to the seminal fluid. In that case, a
DNA analysis would be much more difficult, if not impossible.
Scientists would be unable to separate the DNA from the few male
cells in the ejaculate from the DNA of the female cells mixed in
and would have to do delicate molecular tests and then infer the
man's DNA profile. The analysis would depend on how many male cells
there were compared with female cells and whether the female DNA
totally swamped that of the male. There is no information on
whether Clinton has had a vasectomy.
</P>
<P>
   Such an analysis could be pushing the limits of molecular
biology, Blake said. And it is when such limits are pushed, said
Thompson, that lawyers and scientists start disputing results.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
