<DATE_TIME> 1998-08-08 13:12 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4353 &Cx1f; taf-z
u w &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-DEMOCRATS-TRUCE-NYT &LR;      08-08 0693
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-DEMOCRATS-TRUCE-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TWO FEUDING DEMOCRATIC VOICES CALL A TRUCE 
</HEADLINE>
   (bl)  
 By STEVEN GREENHOUSE   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Two long-feuding pillars of the Democratic Party, the AFL-CIO
and the Democratic Leadership Council, have agreed to a detente in
which they pledge to stop attacking each other and to seek common
ground to help the Democrats this fall and beyond.
</P>
<P>
   This truce between the leadership council, the Democrats'
leading centrist voice, and the labor federation, the party's most
powerful liberal voice, comes after the council and the federation
savaged each other in last year's dispute over trade legislation.
</P>
<P>
   DLC president Al From went so far as to accuse the
13-million-member union group of leading the opposition to the
president and of wanting ``to stop change in our party.''
</P>
<P>
   After White House officials warned the council that its harsh
words were undermining Democratic unity, From and AFL-CIO president
John Sweeney agreed to abide by a nonaggression pact and to seek to
forge some common positions. In the past, the two groups have
clashed not only over trade, but also over education, reducing the
size of the federal government and overhauling welfare.
</P>
<P>
   In an interview, From said, ``If we could ever bring the New
Democrats, with our broad appeal to the electorate, together with
labor and its organizational strength, we would have one big
progressive coalition.''
</P>
<P>
   Showing that it wanted to mend fences with labor, the leadership
council opposed a California measure, defeated in a June
referendum, that would have crippled labor's political clout by
requiring that unions get each member's permission annually before
spending a member's dues on politics.
</P>
<P>
   Although the two sides still clash over trade, they are trying
to find common positions on many issues, including Social Security
and charter schools, innovative public schools that are allowed to
operate free of many bureaucratic rules. In the past the leadership
council has supported wholesale changes in the schools, while
unions have been ambivalent, wanting to insure that innovative
schools did not threaten teachers' job security.
</P>
<P>
   Steven Rosenthal, the political director of the AFL-CIO,
referring to the leadership council, said, ``They make a
contribution to the Democratic Party, and so do we. And we have to
figure out where there's common ground.
</P>
<P>
   The two groups also agreed on the leadership council's call for
``expanding the winner's circle'' to help insure that most
Americans, not just a minority, benefit from increased trade and
the increased integration of the global economy.
</P>
<P>
   This agreement comes at the same time that the White House has
brought many of the party's leading moderate and liberal thinkers
together to try to forge a united voice and common themes that
would help strengthen President Clinton's legacy and would help
Democrats in this year's elections and in 2000.
</P>
<P>
   The leadership council generally backs programs that promote
market-driven solutions on economic policies. It has long fought
with the AFL-CIO and other liberal groups that are more
enthusiastic about government-sponsored programs that protect the
disadvantaged.
</P>
<P>
   The council has been one of the Democratic Party's most
outspoken voices in favor of freer trade. It fervently backed the
fast-track legislation, shelved last fall in the face of intense
labor pressure, that would have made it easier for Washington to
sign free-trade agreements with other countries. Fearing that the
legislation would drag down wages and eliminate jobs, the AFL-CIO
fought it.
</P>
<P>
   Despite the truce, many tensions remain. In the spring issue of
its magazine, the leadership council criticized ``the union
hierarchy'' for seeking ``political allies among left-wing
activists.''
</P>
<P>
   The council and the federation also disagree about the best
strategy for the Democrats in November. The leadership council
favors a moderate message that appeals to suburban middle-class
voters, a pivotal swing group. But the AFL-CIO backs a more
have-nots versus haves message that would mobilize the party's
liberal-labor base.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-08-08-98 1312EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19980808.0077 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-08-08 13:13 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
