<DATE_TIME> 1998-08-08 13:27 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4361 &Cx1f; taf-z
u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-U.N.-IMMUNITY-NYT &LR;      08-08 0773
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-U.N.-IMMUNITY-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
A CHALLENGE TO IMMUNITY FOR LOBBYISTS AT THE U.N. 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: India)  (mk) 
 By ELIZABETH OLSON   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   GENEVA _ Last year, as India's envoy to the U.N. headquarters
here was sipping coffee in the delegates' lounge, her aide pointed
out the man at the next table.
</P>
<P>
   It was Anup Chetia, leader of a separatist group in India that
had taken responsibility for the kidnapping of the envoy's nephew a
month earlier. Chetia, secretary-general of the United Liberation
Front of Assam, had gained entry to the U.N. grounds as a member of
a nongovernmental organization attending a session on human-rights
abuses.
</P>
<P>
   ``My nephew had disappeared, and here was Chetia walking around
Geneva completely free,'' the envoy, Arundhati Ghose, said
indignantly in a recent interview. ``And we were going to have him
_ a criminal _ telling us about human-rights violations.''
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Ghose wanted action against Chetia, whose group had
kidnapped Sanjoy Ghose, 37, head of a private development agency
helping villagers in northeast India. The organization insisted
that Ghose had drowned, but his body has never been found, leading
his family to believe that he was still being held by the
separatists.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was so blinded by rage, I wanted to leap over the table at
him,'' Ms. Ghose said of Chetia.
</P>
<P>
   Instead of throttling Chetia, who was later arrested in
Bangladesh on unrelated charges, Ms. Ghose began a campaign to
alert U.N. and Swiss officials to the danger of suspected criminals
and terrorists taking advantage of the legal immunity granted to
certain interest groups while in Switzerland on U.N. business.
</P>
<P>
   Thousands of such nongovernmental representatives enter the U.N.
headquarters in Geneva and New York each year. Switzerland
automatically provides visas to members of groups accredited by the
United Nations. So far, Ms. Ghose has succeeded in getting U.N. and
Swiss officials to take another look at their 52-year-old
agreement, which has been interpreted in practice as requiring
neither side to take action.
</P>
<P>
   U.N. officials maintain that Switzerland, as the host country,
gives immunity to nongovernmental organizations' staff members to
carry out their business, but that this should not shield these
people from accountability for crimes.
</P>
<P>
   Swiss officials, for their part, argue that legitimate
nongovernmental staff members have immunity from arrest, and that
Swiss police are not permitted to enter U.N. grounds to make
arrests. This would extend, the Swiss say, even to a case like
Chetia's, even though while he was in Geneva, Swiss Interpol
received a top-priority request from India for his arrest.
</P>
<P>
   Nongovernmental staff members ``need to be able to travel to and
from the host country to be able to speak freely at meetings,''
said a U.N. legal adviser. ``Otherwise, you would open the door to
abuse for anyone who criticizes a government at any meeting.''
</P>
<P>
   Bitter complaints routinely surface at human-rights meetings,
where political adversaries are often in close proximity. In the
late 1960s and early 1970s, Israelis and Palestinians continuously
swapped accusations. In the 1980s, there were demonstrations when
Washington Carrasco, a former Chilean defense minister accused of
setting up torture centers, arrived in Geneva as his country's
delegate to the United Nations.
</P>
<P>
   At recent human-rights sessions, Iraq has been represented by
Saddam Hussein's half brother, Barzan al-Tikriti, who was head of
Iraq's intelligence services before he became the country's envoy
to the United Nations. The Liberation Tigers of Tamil Eelam, who
are seeking a separate homeland in Sri Lanka, and the Tupac Amaru,
the leftist rebels from Peru, regularly attend human-rights
sessions.
</P>
<P>
   ``If the IRA or Hamas or other such groups come here, who will
protect whom?'' Ms. Ghose asked.
</P>
<P>
   In May, Algeria's U.N. delegate formally complained that he had
been approached inside the U.N. building here by three men ``who
accosted me in a violent manner and uttered insults, abuse and
death threats.'' One of the men was identified as a member of a
nongovernmental organization.
</P>
<P>
   Accreditation requests from nongovernmental organizations are
screened and approved by a U.N. panel, with 19 member countries
serving rotating terms, said Raymonde Martineau, head of the
panel's office in Geneva. Armed groups are barred, she said. To
keep matters even-handed, she noted, ``no country alone has the
right to veto an application.''
</P>
<P>
   Nongovernmental organizations insist that they have sole
responsibility for determining who is eligible for membership.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-08-08-98 1327EDT &QL; 
