<DATE_TIME> 1998-08-08 13:32 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4363 &Cx1f; taf-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-ALLIGATOR-WRESTLING-A     08-08 0997
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ALLIGATOR-WRESTLING-ART-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FROM ALLIGATOR WRESTLERS, AN EDUCATION 
</HEADLINE>
   (ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients. Non-subscribers
can make individual purchase by calling 212-556-4204 or 1927.)  
 (bl)  
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   HOLLYWOOD, Fla. _ As a crowd of Swedish tourists gathered around
Michael Johns, about a dozen 6- to 8-foot-long alligators lazed in
the corner of a sand pit. Basking in the afternoon sun, the
reptiles lay motionless, like giant fossils, many hatched from eggs
conceived in this small animal exhibition center.
</P>
<P>
   While a handler poked one of the alligators, grabbed its tail,
sat on its back and took hold of its jaws, Johns told his audience
how little energy the animals expend, how they tire easily, how
little pressure it really takes to keep their massive jaws clamped
shut. Afterward, the tourists were invited to sit on the reptile's
back for a picture.
</P>
<P>
   The demonstration was billed as a show on alligator wrestling,
but it was far removed from the riveting spectacle the term once
described.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're trying to get away from the notion of alligator
wrestling,'' said Johns, who caught his first alligator at age 7 on
a dare. ``We saw that, to remain popular, people didn't want to be
thrilled as much as they wanted to learn something.''
</P>
<P>
   From the southern Everglades to Orlando, the Florida alligator
is featured in amusement parks and zoos as a prime attraction. Yet
the reptiles no longer have the lure of the exotic that they once
commanded. Numbering about 1 million in the state, they have become
a commonplace sight in human settlements that increasingly dominate
the landscape.
</P>
<P>
   Wrestlers say that in an age of growing environmental awareness
and competition for tourists, they gear most shows toward educating
visitors about the habits and characteristics of the Florida
alligator, rather than staging a battle.
</P>
<P>
   So most shows are a far cry from the ones contrived in the
1920s, when white entrepreneurs, sensing a potential gold mine,
sought to attract tourists to the state by promoting two of
Florida's distinctive assets, Seminole Indians and alligators.
Soon, the trade flourished, as roadside shows featuring young
Seminoles wrestling alligators dotted major highways as well as
expanses of land that are now parts of downtown Miami.
</P>
<P>
   Today, it is estimated that only two dozen people still wrestle
alligators on a regular basis.
</P>
<P>
   ``Alligator wrestling is dying out, short of people who have a
true love for it,'' said Tim Williams, the director of public
relations and entertainment at Gatorland, an animal park in central
Florida. Williams has been wrestling and exhibiting alligators for
26 years.
</P>
<P>
   Tommy Taylor, who began to wrestle alligators in the 1950s, is
one of the few who still put on the occasional show. In the old
days, he recalled, wrestlers often waged battles of strength and
will in water where the key to keeping one's body parts intact was
gaining control over the animal's unpredictable jaws.
</P>
<P>
   Despite the potential danger to humans, alligators are rarely
harmed from wrestling, and state officials say that the sport has
drawn relatively little fire from animal rights advocates.
</P>
<P>
   ``If the people are responsible and they know their animal, I
don't believe there's a problem'' with wrestling, said Lyanne
Lawhead, the executive director of American Alligator Cycle of
Protection, a nonprofit organization based in Dade City, Fla.
</P>
<P>
   Taylor said that he opened the show standing in a pond where the
water reached up to his thighs, and beckoned an alligator to his
side by poking it with a pole, hoping that when the animal touches
his hand, its mouth will not be wide open.
</P>
<P>
   Securing the reptile's jaws with his hands, he said, he waits
for the alligator to wriggle violently and then tire out before
hauling it onto a sand pit. As Taylor taps its nose, a gesture that
irritates alligators beyond all measure, the reptile opens its
mouth. It is now the wrestler's choice whether to pop his head or
one of his hands in and out.
</P>
<P>
   In his 39 years as an alligator wrestler, Taylor, who now runs a
park in the Everglades, reckons that he has been bitten about a
hundred times. In his younger, more daring days, when he would
routinely slip his head into the animal's mouth, his face was
nearly crushed on two occasions by ``100 pounds of closing pressure
per square inch,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Yet at age 51 and with several hospitalizations behind him,
Taylor avows that alligator wrestling is a sport he has never
ceased to love. ``I always say that as a gator wrestler you have to
have high reflexes and a low IQ,'' he added. ``But every time I get
through a show, I know I've handled the alligator and gotten away
with it, so it's very rewarding for me.''
</P>
<P>
   And like Williams, who has been wrestling and exhibiting
alligators for 26 years, Taylor retains his fascination with an
animal that avoids humans, has a brain the size of a thumb, cannot
be trained, and, he cautions, should never be trusted.
</P>
<P>
   Williams traces his own attraction to the sport to his boyhood.
Out on a hunting and fishing expedition in the swamps, he recalled,
he was struck by the mystery and exotic beauty of an ancient animal
that sits unrivaled atop the food chain of Florida's animal
kingdom, even though it rarely eats. ``It was such a big,
powerful-looking animal,'' Williams recalled thinking.
</P>
<P>
   Still, to the crowd of Swedish tourists here at the heart of a
tiny Seminole reservation, the more mundane spectacle offered by
Johns seemed well worth the trip.
</P>
<P>
   Camilla Helman, 21, said that she was drawn to alligator shows
after she saw a television program featuring tourism attractions in
Florida. So when Johns invited his audience members to sit on the
reptile's back, she was the first to take advantage of the offer.
Laughing, she sat on the animal's scaly skin and posed as her
boyfriend took her picture.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's very exciting,'' she said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-08-08-98 1332EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
