<DOCNO> NYT19980808.0084 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-08-08 13:34 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4364 &Cx1f; taf-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FUGITIVE-LAWYER-850(2     08-08 0886
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FUGITIVE-LAWYER-850(2TAKES)-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MISSING LAWYER'S CONVICTION STIRS DEBATE 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Fla., Colombia)  (lb) 
 By MIREYA NAVARRO   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   MIAMI _ When Michael Abbell, a former Justice Department
extradition chief, and William M. Moran, a criminal defense lawyer,
were charged with the crimes of the Colombian drug cartel they
represented, lawyers nationwide denounced the prosecution as a
government effort to intimidate the defense bar.
</P>
<P>
   In July, after a retrial, a jury found the two lawyers guilty of
crossing the line between criminal lawyer and ``lawyer criminal,''
in the words of a federal prosecutor, and convicted them on charges
of racketeering and money-laundering conspiracy, but not of
drug-trafficking conspiracy.
</P>
<P>
   As defense lawyers weigh the repercussions of the case, however,
some lawyers are also grappling with a more immediate question:
Where is Moran? The 59-year-old defendant was last seen on July 17
in the federal courthouse, shortly after he learned that the jury
had reached a partial verdict, and he remains a fugitive.
</P>
<P>
   ``People are wondering if he's OK,'' said Jack King, a spokesman
for the National Association of Criminal Defense Lawyers, in
Washington. ``It's cause for some concern as to Moran's state of
mind. You know what happened to Vince Foster,'' King said,
referring to the deputy White House counsel who committed suicide
in 1993.
</P>
<P>
   Moran, who once served as a Miami-Dade County state attorney,
and Abbell, 57, a former chief of the Justice Department's office
of international affairs and later a criminal defense lawyer in
Washington, were snared in a 1995 indictment that capped one of the
United States' largest drug investigations.
</P>
<P>
   The case drew nationwide attention not only because it targeted
the Cali drug cartel and 130 of its leaders and operatives, but
also because it accused six lawyers of collaborating in the cocaine
business through their representation of cartel members.
</P>
<P>
   Three lawyers pleaded guilty to charges of money laundering and
one to obstruction of justice and conspiring to import cocaine. And
on July 20, a jury convicted Moran and Abbell, a verdict that will
be appealed but that other defense lawyers say is already having an
intimidating effect in their ranks.
</P>
<P>
   Officials with the criminal defense lawyers group said some
members were steering clear of representing the same client more
than once and of specialties like drug trafficking and organized
crime to avoid raising suspicion about legitimate work.
</P>
<P>
   ``What is disturbing about this case is that the government used
against the lawyers the very acts that lawyers do in representing
clients every day _ visiting people in jail, preparing
affidavits,'' said Gerald Lefcourt of New York City, the group's
president. ``It puts us on notice that if you really want to be
safe, keep away from these cases.''
</P>
<P>
   Edward Ryan and William Pearson, assistant U.S. attorneys who
prosecuted the lawyers, said the case sent a message only to
lawyers who step out of their advocacy role to further the criminal
interests of their clients.
</P>
<P>
   They said the jury found that Moran and Abbell shielded cartel
bosses from extradition and that they obstructed justice by
soliciting phony affidavits to exonerate the cartel leaders and by
making payments to cartel operatives who had been arrested and to
their families, to ensure that they did not cooperate with
investigators.
</P>
<P>
   Prosecutors said that those charged worked for a cartel faction
that imported and distributed over 200,000 kilos of cocaine in the
1980s and '90s. More than 80 of the 130 indicted have been
convicted either here or in Colombia, the prosecutors said,
including the cartel leaders Miguel and Gilberto
Rodriguez-Orejuela, who are serving prison sentences in their
country.
</P>
<P>
   ``Their acts allowed cartel leaders to sit in Colombia and feel
more comfortable about what they were doing,'' Pearson said of the
lawyers.
</P>
<P>
   The outcome could have been worse for Moran and Abbell. The jury
deadlocked on two drug-trafficking counts that carried a life
sentence. But the lawyers still face 20 years in prison for each of
the two convictions of racketeering and money-laundering
conspiracy, and Moran could get five more years for skipping his
$750,000 bail. Sentencing is scheduled for October.
</P>
<P>
   Moran seems to have buckled under the stress of two trials, the
first of which ended last October in an acquittal for both him and
Abbell on one racketeering charge, and a hung jury on the four
charges that the second jury considered.
</P>
<P>
   The day before he disappeared, Moran had been particularly
distressed when Judge William Hoeveler of the U.S. District Court
for the Southern District of Florida dismissed a juror for refusing
to follow the law, said Moran's lawyer, Holly Skolnick. The juror
told fellow jurors that she found some of the laws she had to apply
``silly,'' and another juror reported her to the judge.
</P>
<P>
   Lawyers for Moran and Abbell said the questioning of the jurors
was improper and would be a basis for an appeal. Ms. Skolnick said
that after that episode Moran lost hope for a fair trial.
</P>
<P>
   ``The stress and the pressure just got to him,'' Ms. Skolnick
said.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE _ OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   Moran already had a life of misfortune, Ms. Skolnick said. His
first wife committed suicide in 1967 with a gun he won at a card
game with court personnel when he was an assistant Dade County
state attorney, Ms. Skolnick said. The gun was court evidence kept
at the clerk's office, she said, and he resigned.
</P>
<P>
   He remarried, but his second wife died of cancer, leaving him
with two young children, Ms. Skolnick said. Shortly after his
second wife died, she added, Moran was arrested for drunken driving
and cocaine possession and entered a pretrial diversion program,
which he completed.
</P>
<P>
   In the 1980s, when Moran began representing drug traffickers as
Miami became the main point of entry for Colombian cocaine, his law
partner was shot and killed in front of their office. The office
was set on fire three years later by an arsonist suspected in a
series of fires in doctors' and lawyers' offices around Miami,
media accounts at the time said.
</P>
<P>
   Moran became a fugitive in July in the middle of divorce
proceedings with his third wife, Pamela Moran, to whom he was
married eight years ago. In court papers requesting a restraining
order against her husband last November, Mrs. Moran accused him of
leaving a message on her answering machine saying, ``I will kill
you,'' and of having someone follow her.
</P>
<P>
   Mrs. Moran, who also accused her husband in the court papers of
having drug and alcohol problems, said that he had abused her
verbally since 1991 and that in 1996 he told her, ``I am so out of
control that I do not know what I am going to do to myself and to
you.''
</P>
<P>
   In contrast to the subdued Abbell, who let his lawyers defend
him, Moran took the witness stand and delivered a closing argument
in the first trial, and defended himself in the second with Ms.
Skolnick as co-counsel. Often explosive and disruptive, he made the
case intensely personal; at one point he addressed each juror by
name in pleading for an acquittal.
</P>
<P>
   The defense argued that the government was trying to prove its
case with testimony from other lawyers and former clients of the
defendants who had reason to lie to get reduced prison sentences
themselves.
</P>
<P>
   At a hearing on July 30 to address the forfeiture issue, Ms.
Skolnick contended that 98 percent of the work that the government
asserted Moran did illegally was legitimate lawyering, like filing
motions or investigating cases for trial, that had to be
distinguished from criminal activity.
</P>
<P>
   ``So much of this case was defense lawyering, which was
aggressive lawyering that was not obstruction of justice,'' Ms.
Skolnick argued. Forfeiting all of the fees Moran got from the
cartel bosses, she told the judge, ``sends a very strong message
that this is an attack of defense lawyers.''
</P>
<P>
   But Scott Ray, an assistant U.S. attorney, contended that once
Moran became a member of a criminal conspiracy, as the jury had
found, none of the work was legal.
</P>
<P>
   ``Once he crossed over that line, anything he did was in
furtherance of that conspiracy,'' Ray said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
