<HEADLINE>
GOVERNMENT PROGRESS ON FIXING YEAR 2000 PROBLEM IS QUESTIONED 
</HEADLINE>
  (js) 
 By MATTHEW L. WALD   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Federal agencies are reporting progress in fixing
their computers to cope with the Year 2000 problem, but some of
them are exaggerating what they have done, according to independent
federal experts.
</P>
<P>
   The Federal Aviation Administration's progress reports are
misleading because they describe as ``repaired'' some systems for
which crucial replacement parts have not been received,
Transportation Department auditors told a congressional
subcommittee on Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   And auditors from the General Accounting Office said in June
that the Agriculture Department was reporting that 15 of its
systems were able to handle the problem ``even though these were
replacement systems that were still under development or were
planned to be developed.''
</P>
<P>
   The GAO has previously complained that some federal agencies, in
addition to issuing misleading statements, have a poor grip on the
extent of their Year 2000 problem.
</P>
<P>
   Joel Willemssen , a computer expert at the accounting office,
said that if any agencies issued misleading statements, ``in the
long term it's going to be found out.''
</P>
<P>
   The Transportation Department's inspector general spotted the
aviation agency's problem. John Meche, the department's deputy
assistant inspector general, said the FAA's score-keeping was ``not
consistent with guidance'' issued for federal agencies by the
Office of Management and Budget. Meche testified at a hearing of
the technology subcommittee of the House Science Committee.
</P>
<P>
   The FAA is trying to solve the problem by replacing its computer
systems. But the agency acknowledges that it does not know if the
new systems are free from the problem, in which dates are stored as
a two-digit number and a computer may decide that the year after
1999 is 1900. Meche said four systems under development had to be
tested.
</P>
<P>
   If the FAA's computers are initially unable to deal with the
Year 2000 problem, the agency will probably have to reduce the
total number of planes it allows to fly.
</P>
<P>
   Willemssen of the GAO said he had been told by FAA employees
that the agency had recently agreed to pay an extra $23 million to
Raytheon Co. to make sure that one new system, scheduled to go into
service next March, would function properly after December. But
Dennis Degaetano, the agency's deputy associate administrator for
research and acquisitions, disputed that figure, saying the actual
amount was $2.3 million.
</P>
<P>
   The deadline for fixing the Year 2000 problem is obviously firm,
but it is hard to determine how much time it will take to make
repairs.
</P>
<P>
   Degaetano said that the FAA was making rapid progress. In
February, he said, the agency was 17 months behind schedule, but in
the last six months it has accomplished 14 months' worth of work.
</P>
<P>
   Meche agreed that progress had been made. But he said that it
was ``way too early to start celebrating,'' and that the FAA should
begin testing its repairs immediately, to ``make a concerted effort
to give itself as much cushion as possible.''
</P>
<P>
   Agency officials have acknowledged that they need more detailed
contingency plans in case they experience widespread computer
failures. But they have repeatedly expressed confidence that their
air traffic control computers and other systems will not break
down.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
