<SLUG> BC-OBIT-STEEL-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
THOMAS STEEL, 48, LAWYER KNOWN FOR CIVIL RIGHTS CASES 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Calif.)   (bl)  
 By HOLCOMB B. NOBLE   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Thomas Steel, a San Francisco lawyer who took on some of the
most widely followed cases in California involving the rights of
free speech, freedom of religion and the civil rights of
minorities, died at a San Francisco hospital July 18. He was 48.
</P>
<P>
   He died of complications from AIDS, a family member said.
</P>
<P>
   In Steel's most celebrated case, he won a $920,000 settlement
for Brian Willson, whose legs were severed by a train at the
Concord Naval Weapons Station near San Francisco in 1987 as he took
part in a protest against the United States role in Nicaragua.
Willson was struck by a train carrying munitions for the Nicaraguan
Contras, who were supported by the United States in their fight
against the leftist Nicaraguan government.
</P>
<P>
   Steel sued the federal government, arguing that the train crew
could easily have seen Willson and other demonstrators on or
alongside the three-mile spur of track to the munitions plant and
had sufficient time to stop the train.
</P>
<P>
   The train crew members filed a countersuit, contending that it
was Willson who had inflicted damage on them. They said they had
suffered emotional distress.
</P>
<P>
   ``We believe,'' Steel told the court, ``that their lawsuit is
particularly outrageous. What they are saying is that Brian got run
over intentionally to make them feel bad.''
</P>
<P>
   The case was ultimately settled, and with the money, Willson was
fitted with artificial limbs.
</P>
<P>
   One of the first of Steel's cases to be followed widely was his
successful defense of Huey Newton, a leader of the Black Panthers,
on assault charges in Alameda County, Calif., in 1978.
</P>
<P>
   He also waged a 15-year legal battle against the FBI over
documents involving surveillance of the free-speech movement in
Berkeley in the 1960s, ultimately obtaining a court order in 1995
granting access to the documents for The San Francisco Examiner.
</P>
<P>
   A native of Yuba City, Calif., Steel graduated from the
University of California at Berkeley in 1972 and the Hastings
College of Law in 1975.
</P>
<P>
   He is survived by his partner, Dr. Milton Estes; a son, Jacob,
of Mill Valley, Calif.; his parents, Margaret and Robert Steel, of
Yuba City, Calif.; four brothers, John and Michael of Oakland,
David of New York, and Paul, of Yuba City, and four sisters, Angela
M. Steel of Orinda, Calif., Susan Medland of Phoenix, Julie Ovian
of Madison, Conn, and Mary A. Steel of San Francisco.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
