<DATE_TIME> 1998-08-08 14:14 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4394 &Cx1f; taf-z
u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-AFRICA-VICTIMS-NYT &LR;      08-08 0503
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-AFRICA-VICTIMS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
3 WOUNDED EMBASSY WORKERS AIRLIFTED TO SOUTH AFRICA  
</HEADLINE>
  (Eds: See also AFRICA-BOMBINGS, AFRICA-U.S., AFRICA-SOLDIER) 
(mk) 
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   JOHANNESBURG, South Africa _ After a confusing scene at the
Nairobi airport Saturday morning, three wounded employees of the
U.S. Embassy in Kenya were flown to Pretoria on a South African
military airplane as other bombing victims awaited medical approval
to be transported.
</P>
<P>
   Upon arrival in Pretoria, the two men and a woman were rushed to
a military hospital. A member of the hospital's medical staff
reported that the woman, identified as Mary Robertson, suffered a
broken jaw and a broken bone in her left hand.
</P>
<P>
   One of the wounded men, wearing a bandage covering a four-inch
laceration on his head, was accompanied by his Swedish wife. ``The
blast was enormous,'' he said of the bombing, but declined to give
his name. ``I have no idea what happened to my colleagues. It was
terrible. There was absolute chaos. But I'm alive, and I'm very
grateful for that.''
</P>
<P>
   The South African air force jet had been equipped to carry up to
60 casualties. But as the injured were brought from local hospitals
to Nairobi airport, a doctor on board the South African airplane
said that American officials decided that only patients in stable
condition could be evacuated. It was unclear how many of the
wounded had made it to the airport.
</P>
<P>
   Dr. Dawie Roux described a mixture of chaos and order at
Nairobi.
</P>
<P>
   ``The situation at Nairobi airport was calm and quiet, except
for the operations rooms where United States officials were trying
to sort out where the injured should go,'' Roux said. ``They were
still trying to sort out the injuries on the ground, and didn't
want to change their plans about where the injured should go.''
</P>
<P>
   A German airplane arrived in Nairobi shortly after the South
African jet, indicating that another airlift was expected, Roux
said. Bruce Wharton, press and information officer for the U.S.
Information Service, declined to identify the three embassy workers
brought to Pretoria pending notification of their families. Wharton
said two of the injured worked in the foreign commercial service,
and the third in the economics section.
</P>
<P>
   A spokesman at the South African military hospital said the
three victims would be kept at the hospital for three days. ``They
have minor injuries, mostly lacerations from the blast, but the
major factor is shock,'' the spokesman said.
</P>
<P>
   Robert Pringle, deputy chief of mission at the U.S. Embassy in
Pretoria, said that within an hour of the Nairobi blast his
consulate had spoken with the South African air force about the
need for clearance for relief aircraft.
</P>
<P>
   The embassy, which he said had ``well-oiled channels of
communication with the South African Defense Force,'' had hired a
private commercial airplane that was on its way to Nairobi when the
offer came from the South African air force.
</P>
<P>
   Pringle said cost was not discussed.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
