<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-COWBOYS-IRVIN-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
IRVIN IS AGAIN A TOPIC IN WAKE OF HORSEPLAY THAT GREW SERIOUS 
</HEADLINE>
   (bl)  
 By MIKE FREEMAN   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Every year, Dallas Cowboys wide receiver Michael Irvin shows up
at training camp in solid shape. This year was no different: he has
had an impressive camp and coach Chan Gailey has used Irvin split
wide, in the slot and even in the wingback position in some
formations.
</P>
<P>
   Irvin may be on his way to an outstanding season.
</P>
<P>
   But it seems it wouldn't be a Cowboys camp without some form of
controversy. Last year, it was Barry Switzer, then the head coach,
getting caught trying to bring a gun through an airport. This
season, it is an incident involving Irvin and the offensive lineman
Everett McIver.
</P>
<P>
   The facts that are not in dispute are these: A group of players
were getting haircuts in the players' dormitory on July 29 on the
campus of Midwestern State University, the team's training camp
site in Wichita Falls, Texas.
</P>
<P>
   Soon, Irvin and McIver, who were in the room to get their hair
cut, started roughhousing. McIver ended up with a deep cut in his
neck, near the carotid artery, one of the four principal arteries
of the neck and head. The cut, caused by barber's shears, was so
severe that he missed last week's exhibition game against Seattle.
He missed most of this week's practices, returning to camp
Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   What is in dispute are the details of how McIver was injured.
Those details could make all the difference in the world for
Irvin's immediate future and the coming season for the Cowboys.
</P>
<P>
   The Cowboys maintain that the injury to McIver, a 6-foot-6-inch,
320-pound guard, was strictly the result of horseplay.
</P>
<P>
   ``There was no fight or altercation whatsoever,'' said Brett
Daniels, a team spokesman. ``It was just an accident.''
</P>
<P>
   Daniels is regarded as one of the straight shooters in the
National Football League public-relations community, but there are
others who insist the incident was more than horseplay.
</P>
<P>
   One Cowboys player and three other people close to the situation
said that although they did not witness the incident, they were
told that Irvin and McIver were indeed at first teasing one
another, but that the teasing elevated to an all-out fight. And,
they said, McIver was injured as a result of that scuffle.
</P>
<P>
   The Midwestern State campus police have made preliminary
inquiries into the incident, said Police Chief H.G. Evans, but
since no complaint has been filed, there is nothing further his
department can do.
</P>
<P>
   ``You have to have a complaint to move forward,'' Evans said.
``We're here if the person wants to file one. We don't solicit
complaints.''
</P>
<P>
   The Cowboys have mostly been mum over what happened.
</P>
<P>
   Irvin is currently on probation for pleading no contest to a
felony charge of cocaine possession stemming from a 1996 arrest. If
Irvin commits an act of assault, or almost any other crime, that
will constitute a violation of his probation. If that happened,
Irvin could face 2 to 20 years in prison, said Ron Goethals, the
director of the Dallas County community supervision and corrections
department.
</P>
<P>
   Goethals said his office is looking into the incident and has
spoken with the Midwestern State police officials, but there is
currently little either can do.
</P>
<P>
   ``As of right now we are not aware that Michael Irvin has
violated his probation,'' Goethals said, ``but that could change.''
</P>
<P>
   But even if the police do not investigate, it is possible that
Irvin will face repercussions from the NFL.
</P>
<P>
   As a result of the cocaine charge in 1996, Irvin was suspended
for five games for violating the league's substance abuse policy.
Should the NFL decide to conduct its own inquiry of this incident
and it is found that Irvin violated the league's new violent crime
policy, he could face another suspension.
</P>
<P>
   The policy defines violent crimes as any crime involving the use
or threat of physical violence to a person or persons, the use of a
deadly weapon in the commission of a crime, possession or
distribution of a weapon in violation of state or federal law,
involvement in so-called hate crimes or crimes of domestic
violence, or crimes involving the destruction of property.
</P>
<P>
   Supporters of Irvin say he should be given the benefit of the
doubt.
</P>
<P>
   The Cowboys have put the issue behind them and are back to
focusing on football.
</P>
<P>
   And this is the most optimistic the team has been in years.
</P>
<P>
   The Cowboys have a new coach in Gailey, a rejuvenated Troy
Aikman at quarterback.
</P>
<P>
   And then there's Irvin, still one of the top _ but maybe the
most controversial _ receivers in the game.
</P>
<P>
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
