<HEADLINE>
NFL NOTEBOOK: JETS' ELLIOTT IS FIT TO PLAY 
</HEADLINE>
   (bl)  
 By MIKE FREEMAN   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   Perhaps the top physical specimen on the New York Jets right now
is offensive tackle Jumbo Elliott, who may be in the best shape of
his career.
</P>
<P>
   Elliott is coming off a knee injury from last season and is
extremely sharp.
</P>
<P>
   He seemed to be toying with the Philadelphia Eagles' linemen in
Thursday night's preseason game.
</P>
<P>
   Elliott, who is about 295 pounds, said that he was getting so
toned that recently he had to start eating more than usual so as
not to get too light.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't want to get skinny,'' he said, joking.
</P>
<P>
   If Elliott keeps up his good play, he may be getting fat in
Hawaii at the Pro Bowl.
</P>
<P>
   A Ripple Effect
</P>
<P>
   The fallout from Carmen Policy's stepping down as general
manager of the San Francisco 49ers to join billionaire banker Al
Lerner in his bid to buy the Cleveland Browns continues.
</P>
<P>
   Bill Walsh, one of the builders of the 49er dynasty, said this
week that he has no plans of rejoining his former team on a
permanent basis, even if the owner Eddie DeBartolo asks him. Walsh
had discussions with DeBartolo months ago about becoming the
general manager temporarily, but Walsh is involved in trying to
bring an NFL team back to Los Angeles.
</P>
<P>
   Also, it appears that if Lerner does get the Browns, one of his
first hires will be the talented Vinny Cerrato, director of player
personnel for the 49ers. Cerrato and Policy are close friends, and
while it is unclear what role Cerrato will have with the Browns, it
is clear that Policy will do whatever it takes to yank him from the
49ers.
</P>
<P>
   Quarterback Merry-Go-Round
</P>
<P>
   The quarterback position this past off season underwent a
drastic change as seven teams changed players. Buffalo went from
Todd Collins to Rob Johnson, Indianapolis traded Jim Harbaugh and
selected Peyton Manning with the first pick in the draft, and the
Jets cut Neil O'Donnell and gave the job to Glenn Foley.
</P>
<P>
   San Diego, Philadelphia, Baltimore and New Orleans all have new
starters.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
