<SLUG> BC-AFRICA-U.S.-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
THE U.S. WILL NOT BEND TO TERRORISTS, CLINTON VOWS 
</HEADLINE>
  (js) 
 By JEFF GERTH   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ President Clinton said Saturday that terrorism
would not make the United States shrink from its role as world
leader, even though Americans are prime targets and the capture of
terrorists can take decades.
</P>
<P>
   In his weekly radio address, Clinton also offered condolences to
the families of the 11 Americans who he said were known so far to
have died in the explosions Friday at two American embassies in
East Africa.
</P>
<P>
   ``I know nothing I can say will make sense of your loss,'' the
president said in a live broadcast from the White House.
``Americans are targets of terrorism in part because we have a
unique leadership responsibility in the world. We act to advance
peace and democracy.''
</P>
<P>
   He said that recalling American diplomats or withdrawing
American troops ``would give terrorism a victory it must not and
will not have.''
</P>
<P>
   The president went on to cite his administration's
anti-terrorism efforts, ranging from increased law-enforcement
resources to protection of computer networks.
</P>
<P>
   But he added, ``The most powerful weapon in our counterterrorism
arsenal is our determination to never give up.''
</P>
<P>
   Clinton spoke as rescue and recovery efforts continued in
Nairobi, Kenya, one of the bombing sites.
</P>
<P>
   Just a few minutes apart, the suspected vehicle bombings 400
miles from each other turned busy streets in two African capitals
into bloody piles of concrete and knots of steel. The second
bombing occurred in Dar es Salaam, Tanzania.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton reviewed the successes and difficulties encountered in
bringing terrorists to justice.
</P>
<P>
   Four years after a shooting incident outside the entrance of the
Central Intelligence Agency, he said, the gunman involved was
captured in Pakistan and convicted in a Virginia court of the
crime.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton noted how the United States had spent 16 years pursuing
a terrorist suspect in the bombing of a plane bound for Hawaii in
1982.
</P>
<P>
   Some terrorist acts against the United States remain unresolved,
the president acknowledged.
</P>
<P>
   They include the 1996 bombing of an American military housing
complex in Saudi Arabia in which 19 American airmen were killed.
The FBI, which investigates terrorist acts against American
citizens abroad, has all but stopped its investigation of the case,
officials have said.
</P>
<P>
   In closing his address on Saturday, Clinton vowed to pursue all
terrorists, ``no matter how long it takes or where it takes us.''
</P>
<P>
   At the request of the United States, the governments of Israel
and South Africa said they would also participate in the rescue
effort. The South African Air Force sent a Boeing 707 equipped to
carry as many as 60 victims to a military hospital in Pretoria, the
South African capital.
</P>
<P>
   Israel sent a search and rescue team to Kenya to help free
victims trapped in the rubble of the embassy building in Nairobi.
</P>
<P>
   The Pentagon said Defense Secretary William Cohen had spoken on
Friday with Defense Minister Yitzhak Mordechai of Israel about the
bombings in East Africa and other issues. Defense Department
officials said the conversation was routine and that Israel would
play no special role in investigating the attacks.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
