<SLUG> BC-BBO-WAIVER-WOES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WAIVER WOES: CLAIMING A GUY YOU DON'T WANT 
</HEADLINE>
   (bl)  
 By MURRAY CHASS   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   In the category of you better watch what you wish for because
you might get it, the San Diego Padres Saturday are the
questionably proud possessor of an expensive relief pitcher they
don't need.
</P>
<P>
   Though the Padres portray the Randy Myers move differently, the
prevailing view among general managers of other teams is that they
are a self-inflicted victim of a game known as waiver-claim
blocking.
</P>
<P>
   How do you play it? It's simple. All you need is a waiver wire
or a computer linked to Major League Baseball's transaction
computer. That equipment, of course, is not generally available,
which is why the game is left to the 30 general managers, many of
whom live and die by their waiver decisions.
</P>
<P>
   This is the time of season when scrutiny of waivers is most
intense because trades can be made only if players clear waivers.
For many years, general managers did not make waiver claims as the
result of an unwritten gentlemen's agreement: don't claim my
players and I won't claim yours. But in the past few seasons,
claims have become rampant, particularly the blocking claim.
</P>
<P>
   When the general manager of a contending team sees the name of a
player on the waiver wire and suspects that another contender may
be trying to get him in a trade, he will put in a claim. Because
that player then does not clear waivers, a potential trade has been
blocked.
</P>
<P>
   One general manager said 40 to 50 players had been claimed in
the first week of the month. With pitching in such great demand,
teams have especially put in blocking claims for starting pitchers
in large numbers. Not every player for whom waivers are asked is
intended as trade bait, but suspicious contenders can't be certain.
</P>
<P>
   ``Nobody wants to take a chance on having someone else get a
guy,'' one general manager said. ``They'd look like village idiots,
especially if the guy beat them in the playoffs.''
</P>
<P>
   So, according to several general managers, claims have been made
on Al Leiter, Hideo Nomo and Bobby Jones of the Mets, Curt
Schilling of Philadelphia, Chuck Finley of California, Todd
Stottlemyre of Texas, Darryl Kile of Colorado, Tim Belcher of
Kansas City, Andy Benes of Arizona, Rick Helling of Texas and Mike
Hampton of Houston.
</P>
<P>
   All of these players were pulled back when they were claimed.
When the Padres claimed Myers, they did so to keep the Atlanta
Braves from getting him and using him as the closer they need. They
succeeded so well that they wound up getting Myers themselves,
adding him to a bullpen headed by the outstanding closer Trevor
Hoffman.
</P>
<P>
   After they put in their claim, Blue Jays general manager Gord
Ash called Kevin Towers of the Padres and asked what he wanted to
do. The Blue Jays could have pulled Myers back and kept him, but
Ash couldn't wait to shed his contract, his shaky ninth-inning
pitching and his demeanor, which had not endeared him to teammates.
The teams wound up making a trade, with the Padres giving the Blue
Jays two minor leaguers (one to be named) who may never be heard
from. But the Blue Jays considered it a terrific deal.
</P>
<P>
   Two general managers, one in each league, called the development
``the block that backfired.''
</P>
<P>
   Said another, ``The one thing about that is you better be
careful what you're claiming, because you might wind up with him.''
</P>
<P>
   Like other general managers, they declined to be identified
because talking about waivers is frowned upon. Another general
manager addressed that very possibility. ``I said I'm not touching
this one,'' he said. ``I'm scared to death of it.''
</P>
<P>
   With $13,327,348 left on Myers' three-year contract, the general
manager did not want to be the one who would pay the left-hander
that hefty sum.
</P>
<P>
   Neither Towers nor Padres president Larry Lucchino returned
telephone calls.
</P>
<P>
   As for other players, general managers said two of the leading
claimers were the Mets, for the second successive season under
their general manager, Steve Phillips, and the Yankees.
</P>
<P>
   The Yankees claim so many players as a defense not just against
other teams but also against their owner, who would be livid if a
good player rode the waiver wire to another team. Other general
managers seem to be more understanding of Brian Cashman's claims
than those made by Phillips.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Mets are at it again,'' said one front-office executive.
``They seem to be waiver-claim happy. Some year they're going to
get stuck with someone.''
</P>
<P>
   A Randy Myers perhaps? &QL; 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
