<SLUG> BC-BBO-NOTEBOOK-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BASEBALL NOTEBOOK: ANDY FOX AT HOME AS A NOMAD 
</HEADLINE>
   (bl)  
 By MURRAY CHASS   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   After one whole season and part of another with the New York
Yankees, Andy Fox was unable to break into their juggernaut last
spring, so they traded him to the Arizona Diamondbacks.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was out of options,'' Fox said. ``They were going to have to
do something with me, either put me on waivers or something. I was
glad they were able to trade me and give me a chance to play.''
</P>
<P>
   Fox has actually played somewheres else. He has started at first
(10 games), second (44) and third (17) base and in left (2) and
right (7) field for the expansion team. In the process, he has
become the team's leading hitter with a .295 batting average.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm sure a lot of people are surprised with my offense,'' said
Fox, who hit .196 for the Yankees in 1996, his full season. ``That
was a big question mark in New York. I came over here and made a
few adjustments and they seem to have paid off.''
</P>
<P>
   If he didn't start hitting when he was with the Yankees, Fox
began his career of versatility with them.
</P>
<P>
   ``The chance of getting to the big leagues was to be able to do
a number of different things,'' said the 27-year-old Fox, who spent
seven seasons in the minors before playing for the Yankees. ``It
kind of carried over here. It's been nice to get a chance to play
and establish yourself as a player who can play in the big leagues.
That's been the biggest thing for me.''
</P>
<P>
   Fox's versatility has been so impressive that manager Buck
Showalter is considering having him duplicate the feats of Cesar
Tovar and Bert Campaneris by playing him at all nine positions in
one game.
</P>
<P>
   ``They've talked about that,'' Showalter said. ``We're still
trying to win some games, but it would be kind of neat to do that
because not too many people have done it. I think I can do it. It
would be a nice challenge.''
</P>
<P>
   Catching, Fox said, would represent the biggest challenge.
``I've worked out catching, but I've never caught in a game,'' he
said. Pitching? It would be trying to play catch with the catcher.
Hopefully they'd hit the ball right at somebody. I don't foresee me
putting up Maddux-type numbers.''
</P>
<P>
   The Best Deal He Could Do
</P>
<P>
   While Randy Johnson began paying for himself by drawing a record
regular-season crowd in Houston on Friday night, the Seattle
Mariners continued to endure criticism for trading the dominating
pitcher to the Astros for three minor leaguers.
</P>
<P>
   There's no question that General Manager Woody Woodward would
have been able to make a far better deal two months ago had
ownership allowed him to trade Johnson then, but when he was
allowed to act, Woodward took what he felt was the best deal
available.
</P>
<P>
   After discussions about various players, Woodward asked the
Yankees and the Cleveland Indians for specific packages that
neither team was willing to surrender.
</P>
<P>
   From the Yankees: Hideki Irabu, one of their starting pitchers;
Mike Lowell, their top minor league third baseman, and another
minor leaguer of the caliber of outfielder Rickey Ledee or pitcher
Ryan Bradley.
</P>
<P>
   From the Indians: the starting pitcher Dave Burba, reliever Paul
Shuey, second baseman Enrique Wilson and outfielder Brian Giles.
</P>
<P>
   One executive said he hoped that the Indians would be willing to
make the trade, because then he would have gone to the Yankees to
try to extract a better deal from them. He knew the Yankees did not
want Johnson to go to the Indians. But that never developed.
</P>
<P>
   The Yankees tried to change the names, as did the Indians, who
wanted to give the Mariners prospects for Johnson. In the end, the
Mariners liked the Astros' prospects more than the others. And
that's why Johnson was at the Astrodome Friday night, pitching a
five-hit shutout against Philadelphia in front of 52,071 frenzied
fans.
</P>
<P>
   Soon He'll Be Only in the 50s
</P>
<P>
   In the St. Louis Cardinals' nine games before Saturday, since
Mark McGwire hit his 45th home run, two of his teammates hit more
home runs than he did. Ray Lankford slugged three home runs and Ron
Gant two. McGwire hit none, batting 28 times without homering.
</P>
<P>
   What did the drought, his longest of the season, do to McGwire's
projection? When he hit his 45th, it was 69. Nine games later, it
was just under 64. He's almost a mere mortal.
</P>
</TEXT>
