<HEADLINE>
WEATHER 
</HEADLINE>
  (Editors: The following text accompanies the weather map for
Sunday, Aug. 9, sent to computer graphics clients of The New York
Times News Service. For information call: 212-556-4204.) 
(bl) 
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service  
<TEXT>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   NATIONAL FORECAST &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The clusters of showers and thunderstorms that have plagued the
Middle West during the past few days will gradually shift east
Sunday and Monday. Weak high-level winds will favor slow-moving
thundershowers which can drop torrential rain in a few locations.
</P>
<P>
   Abundant clouds will prevail from the eastern part of the Great
Lakes and Ohio Valley to the central and southern Appalachians.
Broken areas of showers and thundershowers will develop as a jet
stream disturbance interacts with sultry air over the region. While
most areas will have less than a half inch of rain, locally heavy
amounts will occur near the central Appalachians and Carolina
coast, where a rich supply of moist air will be drawn from over the
Atlantic.
</P>
<P>
   Partly to mostly sunny skies will prevail near the Northeast
coast as high pressure remains strong east of New England. Humidity
will increase over New England later Sunday as breezes from the
south develop.
</P>
<P>
   A weak front will promote broken clouds and a few thundershowers
from the western Great Lakes to the northern Missouri Valley.
Farther south, ample sunshine will boost temperatures into the 90s
and low 100s over most of the central and southern Plains.
</P>
<P>
   Most of the West will be very warm. Increasing high level winds
from southeast will draw moisture into the Southwestern states
resulting in scattered strong thunderstorms from the deserts of
southern California into Arizona and Utah. Elsewhere in the
Rockies, sunshine will be mixed with isolated afternoon
thunderstorms. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Focus: Sunset &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Just one week ago the sun dipped below the horizon at Barrow,
Alaska, for the first time in 83 days. Since then, the length of
daylight at the northernmost weather station in the United States
has shrunk by four hours. Daylight will continue to dwindle at
Barrow until, beginning on November 18, two months of total
darkness mark the depths of Arctic winter. Gradually, the deepening
chill in the north will act to increase the temperature contrast
between pole and equator. The storms that derive energy from these
contrasts will gradually strengthen enough to draw cold polar air
south for the winter. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-08-08-98 1428EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
