u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-GLF-SANDS-NYT &LR;      08-08 0469
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GLF-SANDS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
AT 97, AN OFFICIAL STAYS INVOLVED 
</HEADLINE>
   (bl)  
 By ALEX YANNIS   c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   He celebrated his 97th birthday on Aug. 6, but George Sands is
still a fixture at Metropolitan Golf Association events. Sands is
the oldest golf official in the United States _ and probably the
world. Sunday, he will attend the final of the Metropolitan Amateur
at Quaker Ridge in Scarsdale, N.Y.
</P>
<P>
   And he worked the Ike Championship last month at Wykagyl Country
Club, serving as an observer in the last group of the last round
and was involved in the presentations afterward.
</P>
<P>
   Sands' name and his enormous contribution to golf at the local
and national level are well-known in the area, but his name is
synonymous with the Ike.
</P>
<P>
   As he sat at Wykagyl's veranda overlooking the last green during
the two-day tournament, just about every player stopped by to shake
hands with him.
</P>
<P>
   Sands is an honorary chairman of the Ike, the stroke-play
championship of the metropolitan association. Sands and Dana Mosley
revived the tournament nearly two decades ago after its prominence
waned. The Ike was started in 1953 as a tribute to the country's
most well-known amateur golfer at the time, President Dwight D.
Eisenhower.
</P>
<P>
   Sands, fixing his blue eyes on faces, still greets everyone by
name, and he has a story to tell for just about everyone.
</P>
<P>
   Moreover, he recalled in detail the 1941 club championship he
lost at the North Shore Country Club, where he has been a member
for 78 years.
</P>
<P>
   At this year's Ike, with his 88-year-old wife, Marjorie, at his
side, Sands rode a golf cart around the Wykagyl layout, observing
Michael Deo of Oak Hill and D.J. Lewin of Ardsley. The only
accommodation Sands has made to the strokes is to give up his pipe,
which was his trademark.
</P>
<P>
   Sands could be called a trademark of the MGA. He rarely misses
an area golf tournament even though he and his wife, residents of
the East Side of Manhattan, cannot drive. Former MGA president John
Baldwin usually drives the couple to local events.
</P>
<P>
   ``I love being around the golf course,'' Sands said. ``The last
time I played was last year, but I love being around the course and
working for golf.''
</P>
<P>
   Sands has served on every committee of the MGA and was its
president in 1975. He has also served on several committees for the
U.S. Golf Association, but his pride and joy, along with the Ike,
is the Long Island Caddie Scholarship Fund, which he founded.
</P>
<P>
   In a ceremony last Tuesday night, he presented this year's 23
scholarship recipients with $1,500 each.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've put more than 450 players through college, including
more than a dozen girls,'' Sands said about the fund. ``Our first
recipient is the president now. I get great deal of satisfaction
from the scholarship fund.'' &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-08-08-98 1442EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19980808.0101 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-08-08 14:48 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4411 &Cx1f; taf-z
u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CHILE-ABORTION-NYT &LR;      08-08 1039
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CHILE-ABORTION-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ABORTION DEBATED IN CHILE, WHERE IT'S ALWAYS A CRIME 
</HEADLINE>
   (bl)  
 By CLIFFORD KRAUSS   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   SANTIAGO, Chile _ Nine years after Gen. Augusto Pinochet decreed
that abortion was a crime in Chile even when necessary to save the
mother's life, the Chilean Senate has taken up the issue for the
first time.
</P>
<P>
   Advocates of women's rights here say it is time for a change.
But in fact the bill before the Senate would only tighten
regulations by increasing prison sentences for anyone convicted of
conducting an abortion.
</P>
<P>
   Conservative opposition senators pushing the bill say they want
to crush the ``abortion industry,'' which experts say is
responsible for up to 160,000 clandestine abortions annually in
this country of 15 million people.
</P>
<P>
   But the conservatives concede that they hope to make abortion an
issue in next year's presidential election to embarrass Ricardo
Lagos, the Socialist who is leading in the polls and who has been
studiously ducking the issue.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is a moral question in which we have public opinion on
our side,'' said Sen. Hernan Larrain, the leading proponent of the
legislation who is also a close adviser to a conservative
presidential candidate. ``If we pass this in the Senate, we are
going to push this issue hard.''
</P>
<P>
   Sen. Carlos Ominami, the leading opponent of the bill and an
adviser to Lagos, said: ``Abortion is a supercharged issue in Chile
and it is a very difficult one for any progressive politician.
Don't forget this is the only country in Latin America without a
law allowing divorce.''
</P>
<P>
   At the end of an interview, he said, ``I want to make myself
perfectly clear that I do not favor legalizing abortion.''
</P>
<P>
   Abortion is illegal everywhere in Latin America except Cuba,
although it is widely practiced among all social classes. Chilean
law was consistent with abortion laws around the region until the
Pinochet regime, with conservative church allies, put family issues
at the forefront of Chilean politics.
</P>
<P>
   Chileans are particularly polarized on political and social
issues, with about one-third expressing very liberal views and
another third expressing extremely conservative views. Each sector
is represented politically, with the governing Christian Democrats
leaning toward liberal economic policies but more conservative
social policies.
</P>
<P>
   About 50 Chileans, most of them poor women, are prosecuted each
year for having or carrying out abortions. Few spend more than a
few days in jail. Conservatives say that only by stiffening the
penalties can the practice be deterred.
</P>
<P>
   There is a good chance the Senate will approve the legislation,
perhaps as early as this week. The Christian Democrats, who govern
as part of a coalition, are divided on the issue. Passage in the
more liberal lower chamber of the Chilean Congress is considered
less likely, though still possible.
</P>
<P>
   About one in every three pregnancies ends in an abortion in
Chile, one of the highest rates in Latin America, according to
estimates gathered in the early 1990s by the Alan Guttmacher
Institute, a New York-based abortion rights group. As many as 100
Chilean women die every year from botched abortions, according to
local health experts.
</P>
<P>
   Four million abortions a year _ one out of every 11 in the world
_ take place in Latin America despite its being the most devoutly
Roman Catholic region in the world.
</P>
<P>
   Abortion has always been illegal in Chile, but under a 1931 law
it was allowed in cases where a woman's life was in jeopardy. But
that law was repealed by decree in 1989 during the final months of
the Pinochet regime.
</P>
<P>
   Only El Salvador, Malta and Andorra have abortion laws as
restrictive as Chile's, abortion rights groups say.
</P>
<P>
   Under current Chilean law, a woman who has an abortion can be
sentenced to three to five years in prison. An abortionist who is
not a medical professional can be sentenced to 18 months to three
years, and a doctor, nurse or midwife can face three to five years.
But in most cases, judges have handed out suspended sentences or
allowed those convicted to serve time at night or to carry out some
kind of public service.
</P>
<P>
   Under the proposed law, abortionists who are not medical
professionals would face a minimum of five years in prison, and a
professional practitioner would face a minimum of 10 years. Judges
would have less leeway in reducing or suspending sentences. The
bill would not raise the sentences for women who have abortions,
but would encourage them to testify against practitioners in
exchange for lower sentences.
</P>
<P>
   Human rights advocates say poor women, who are by far the most
vulnerable to abortions carried out without proper medical care,
are already regularly interrogated in hospitals when they arrive in
emergency rooms with problems that appear to be abortion-related.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm worried,'' said Lidia Casas Becerra, a leading Chilean
advocate of abortion rights. ``The whole criminal justice system
would work against the poor if this bill passes.''
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Casas said that any well-to-do woman can safely have an
abortion in a private clinic or hospital for $1,000 to $2,500 _ a
price out of the range of most Chileans.
</P>
<P>
   But, she said, poor women must turn to abortionists who lack
medical training, who may charge about $200 and who use wires or
primitive rubber probes.
</P>
<P>
   Any toughening of the law, she said, could raise prices
exorbitantly for all groups and make the whole process more
clandestine.
</P>
<P>
   The debate on the bill has received scant attention in the
Chilean press despite a march on the Senate on Aug. 4 by 60 women
who support abortion rights. Some jeered from the gallery at
senators who support a tougher law.
</P>
<P>
   More than anything else, some experts say, the lack of news
coverage is a reflection of the fact that Chileans are extremely
reluctant to discuss abortion at all.
</P>
<P>
   Ominami, the adviser to the Socialist presidential candidate,
knows how touchy the issue is.
</P>
<P>
   ``Abortion,'' he said during a debate on the Senate floor last
month, pausing for effect. ``It's a strong word. It strikes a blow
to the ears. It's almost inevitable that from this subject only the
most acid discussions can surge.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
