<SLUG> BC-NJ-COLUMN-EMINENT-DOMAIN-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
COMMENTARY: AFTER TRUMP, RESTAURANT HAS A CAUSE 
</HEADLINE>
   (bl)  
 By EVELYN NIEVES   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTIC CITY, N.J. _ Sabatini's specials of the day included
veal francese ($16) and spaghetti and meatballs ($10), both with
soup and salad. These are customer favorites, and in the dining
room, the little square tables draped in white linen cloths were
filling nicely with casino employees on break.
</P>
<P>
   A platoon of Sabatinis worked the posts. Mom and Pop _ Clare and
Vincent _ greeted guests and answered the phone. Stephen tended
bar. Michael, the chef, hunkered over the stove. Charles was on
call.
</P>
<P>
   It looked as if Sabatini's, the little restaurant that beat a
powerful state agency's efforts to condemn it so that Trump Plaza
Hotel &AMP; Casino could expand its domain, was back where it was
before the fight started, five long years ago.
</P>
<P>
   But not quite.
</P>
<P>
   Life has changed for the Sabatinis. Of course, in the three
weeks since they and their two neighbors _ The Golden Island pawn
shop and Vera Coking, the widow with a rooming house surrounded on
three sides by Trump Plaza parking _ won their very public court
battle with Donald Trump and the New Jersey Casino Reinvestment and
Development Authority, they've been basking in victory. Cards,
phone calls, television crews, not to mention new customers, have
been popping by.
</P>
<P>
   But the Sabatinis are not just heroic little guys who trumped
the master of ``The Art of the Deal.'' Now they're converts to a
cause: fighting eminent domain.
</P>
<P>
   ``What our case did is send a message to the entire country that
government cannot abuse its power to seize property,'' Mrs.
Sabatini said. ``I have heard from people all over the country who
want to fight eminent domain. I've heard from a woman in
Jacksonville, Fla., a person in Toms River, and another person in a
little town near Atlantic City. These people need our help and we
will not abandon them.''
</P>
<P>
   Thanks to five years of cramming for court appearances, Mrs.
Sabatini said, she has become pretty adept at sniffing out the
legitimate cases of eminent domain, in which government takes
property for public purposes. When people call, she said, she helps
them sort out their options.
</P>
<P>
   ``From the beginning,'' she said, ``what we were fighting is how
the government can take our property, our livelihood, to give it to
a private person. If somebody wanted to buy the property and
negotiate a price, that would be one thing. But we didn't have a
choice in the matter.''
</P>
<P>
   And those were five miserable years that the Sabatinis spent
fighting for their restaurant. When the Casino Authority condemned
the restaurant and the other two properties so that Trump Plaza
could expand its parking area, create a limousine staging area and
plant a few trees _ or perhaps do something else entirely _ the
Sabatinis and their neighbors were branded as greedy holdouts by
the Atlantic City mayor and other local figures.
</P>
<P>
   During the battle, Mrs. Sabatini had two heart attacks and Mr.
Sabatini's heart developed a pronounced irregular beat. Their legal
bills mounted. ``Well into the six figures,'' Mrs. Sabatini said.
``Maybe three or four hundred thousand. We don't even know.''
</P>
<P>
   They may not have to; the State Superior Court ruling dictated
that the Casino Authority and Trump organization pay the property
owners' legal bills. But the Sabatinis aren't celebrating until the
deadline to appeal passes in a couple of weeks, Mrs. Sabatini said.
An appeal is unlikely, but the Sabatinis are still worried.
</P>
<P>
   They wonder, with good reason, what would have happened if their
case hadn't received so much attention. Many other families and
businesses in Atlantic City have moved on, quietly but reluctantly,
for casino expansion. The Sabatinis were lucky to have Donald Trump
as an adversary and a little old lady on their side.
</P>
<P>
   When the Institute for Justice, a Washington-based conservation
legal organization, joined the case two years ago, it sent faxes
regularly to reporters, keeping the case in the news. Then, last
year, Garry Trudeau created a splash for the case with a week of
``Doonesbury'' strips lampooning the big bad Trump for trying to
steal Sabatini's away.
</P>
<P>
   ``Garry Trudeau helped our message a lot,'' Mrs. Sabatini said.
``So did the Maury Povich show. I'm going to send them both
thank-you notes.''
</P>
</TEXT>
