u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FBN-COLTS-OUTLOOK-2TA     08-08 0995
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-COLTS-OUTLOOK-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PIECE BY PIECE, COLTS' OWNER BUILDS HOPE 
</HEADLINE>
   (bl)  
 By THOMAS GEORGE   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   ANDERSON, Ind. _ Peyton Manning is wearing No. 18, the same
number his dad, Archie, wore when he was the New Orleans Saints'
quarterback. It is the first time in a long time that Manning has
dressed in that number.
</P>
<P>
   In his first couple of weeks at the Indianapolis Colts' training
camp, Manning saw Tennessee fans wearing his old orange and white
jersey, No. 16, and Colts fans wearing the new one: blue and white,
No. 18.
</P>
<P>
   Old and new.
</P>
<P>
   Just where will Manning and the Colts draw the line between old
and new?
</P>
<P>
   Manning, who was the National Football League's No. 1 draft pick
last June, was preparing to make his NFL debut against the Seattle
Seahawks on Saturday night.
</P>
<P>
   ``Indianapolis is a town that really wants to be a winner,''
Manning said. ``We want to give them something to cheer about.''
</P>
<P>
   Manning is the new Colts cornerstone _ the present as much as
the future. His six-year, $48 million contract that features an
$11.5 million signing bonus is proof. Manning, 22, fresh from
college, is in transition.
</P>
<P>
   The Colts are in transition, too, but that is like saying a
pendulum swings. Of course the Colts are in transition.
</P>
<P>
   It has seemed that way since they made a circus-like midnight
move from Baltimore to Indianapolis in March 1984.
</P>
<P>
   The Colts have had seven losing seasons since then, six of them
with 11 or more losses. They have never won more than nine games in
the regular season. They have had 16 starting quarterbacks. Eight
head coaches. Great drafts (Marshall Faulk, 1994). Painful drafts
(Jeff George, 1990).
</P>
<P>
   They won the American Football Conference East title in 1987,
but only four seasons later went 1-15. They produced a magical
season in 1995, coming within one game-ending pass play of making
the Super Bowl. Just 24 months later, they lost the first 10 games
of last season. That horrific yo-yo ride came to a 3-13 conclusion,
including a 41-38 victory over the Green Bay Packers, the Super
Bowl champions at the time, and a 41-0 knockout of the Miami
Dolphins, a playoff team.
</P>
<P>
   Scan the last 14 years and the view is full of such chilling
peaks and valleys.
</P>
<P>
   Who keeps knocking the Colts' horseshoe off the spike?
</P>
<P>
   ``As a rookie three years ago I almost went to the Super Bowl,''
tight end Ken Dilger said. ``Last year we were 3-13. I asked
myself, `How can a team get so bad so quickly?'''
</P>
<P>
   Quentin Coryatt knows. He has been a Colts linebacker for the
last seven seasons.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've had three head coaches,'' Coryatt said. ``I've had four
position coaches. I'm on my third or fourth defensive coordinator.
A lot of new faces. You can't win if you keep bringing in new faces
all of the time.''
</P>
<P>
   Old and new. The Colts hope they have switched from old to new
in a few key positions for the last time for a long time.
</P>
<P>
   It starts with Jim Irsay, the owner, who took over the team
after the death of his father, Robert, in January 1997. Jim ran the
team last year, but this year his blueprint is fully in place.
</P>
<P>
   ``I have dreamed of total ownership, of what that involves,''
Irsay said, ``and now that it is here for me, I am going to build
continuity. This organization has not been able to sustain
greatness because of a lack of continuity. We want to take away the
falloff years. The revolving door with so many head coaches must
end. The foundation must be solid in owner, general manager, head
coach and quarterback. We have that.''
</P>
<P>
   To get it, Irsay brought in Bill Polian, the general manager,
from Carolina. Polian brought in Jim Mora as the head coach. Mora
had worked as a television analyst after resigning as coach of the
Saints a season earlier. And the three of them brought in Manning.
</P>
<P>
   Owner, general manager, head coach, quarterback.
</P>
<P>
   The Colts have a foundation.
</P>
<P>
   ``I am the youngest owner in the league, but I am one of the top
10 in experience,'' said Irsay, 39, who started as a ball boy for
the Colts at age 12 and worked as the team's general manager from
age 24 to 35. ``The legacy of what the NFL is about runs deep in my
blood.''
</P>
<P>
   The 55-year-old Polian brings a history of success. He helped
build the Buffalo Bills into four-time AFC champions, then started
from scratch with the expansion Panthers and in two seasons got
them into the 1997 National Football Conference championship game.
</P>
<P>
   He knows what the Colts have lacked.
</P>
<P>
   ``Last year this team had an offensive line that was untested
and the quarterbacks took a beating,'' Polian said. ``The special
teams missed kicks that could have won games and there were stupid
penalties. In four games they won the statistical battles but lost
in turnovers and lost the games.''
</P>
<P>
   In short, the Colts lacked discipline. Around the league, they
were viewed as soft.
</P>
<P>
   Enter Mora.
</P>
<P>
   Polian phoned him on a Thursday morning in late January and they
talked football for two hours. That Friday night, Polian called
back to offer the job and Mora accepted.
</P>
<P>
   Mora is intense. He grinds his players. Some say he is wound too
tightly. In New Orleans he compiled a 93-74 record that was built
on robust defense and lackluster offense. But when the Saints got
off to a 2-6 start in 1996, he held a profanity-laced news
conference and resigned a day later.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm not proud of the way it ended,'' Mora said of his tenure
in New Orleans. ``I'm not proud of quitting halfway through the
season. But I'd do it again. I had been there 10{ years. It was
probably too long. We struggled. It got to the point they were
better off and I was better off not being there.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm glad I have a second chance to coach.''
</P>
<P>
   At age 62, he doesn't intend to change his approach.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're going to be demanding and never let up,'' he said. ``I
believe players want that. And the ones that don't, you don't want
them, anyway.''
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   That is Jim Mora.
</P>
<P>
   And maybe that is what the Colts need.
</P>
<P>
   Offensively, though, there are doubts. Mora's reputation is as a
heavy-handed defensive coach and many wonder whether he can groom
an offensive talent like Manning.
</P>
<P>
   So much lies in the hands of the Colts' offensive coordinator,
Tom Moore, who worked with Terry Bradshaw in Pittsburgh and more
recently with the Detroit Lions and Scott Mitchell and Barry
Sanders.
</P>
<P>
   Mora believes Moore is a solid coach. Of course, Mora thought he
had selected the right offensive coordinator in Carl Smith in New
Orleans and that did not work.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our offense in New Orleans did not take enough chances,'' said
Torrance Small, a receiver who played for the Saints under Mora and
now plays for the Colts. ``It was not aggressive. The offensive
players weren't as good as the defensive guys but they weren't as
bad as what they were restricted to do. This offense under Tom
Moore is going to be more open and spread the ball around. People
will like it.''
</P>
<P>
   In addition to bringing in players like Manning and Small, the
Colts are counting on their eighth-year center, Jay Leeuwenburg, to
solidify the offensive line and have looked for help there via the
draft, choosing Steve McKinney and Aaron Taylor, and the signing of
seven free agents, including guard Tom Myslinski.
</P>
<P>
   Mora acknowledged that defense is a priority, but he said: ``You
also have to have balance to win a Super Bowl. We'll get the most
out of Peyton.''
</P>
<P>
   Manning was a 9-year-old in New Orleans when Mora was named the
head coach of the Saints. Later, while in high school, Manning
would come to Saints practices and throw the ball to the Saints'
receivers, including Small.
</P>
<P>
   ``I like what I see in this offense,'' Manning said. ``You take
your big shots, but all the while you concentrate on moving that
ball downfield at a pace that is steady. That way, you can't go
broke taking a profit.''
</P>
<P>
   Manning's maturity and his attitude make Irsay smile. Irsay has
a new stadium lease in Indianapolis through 2014 and more than $35
million will be spent in the next year to upgrade the Colts'
stadium and office headquarters.
</P>
<P>
   ``The foundation being laid here is causing tremors in this
city, in this state,'' Irsay said. ``But I want my footsteps to be
much louder than my words. I want us to live by what we do. I want
championships for Indianapolis. I want the Colts to be an original
mint. This is much more than a business. We are investing in and
creating a new horseshoe. It comes from the heart. And virtues from
the heart are always most important.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-08-08-98 1455EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19980808.0106 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-08-08 15:09 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
