u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-N.Y.-PORN-SHOPS-500(2     08-08 0542
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-N.Y.-PORN-SHOPS-500(2TAKES)-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GUILIANI SEEMS TO BE WINNING WAR AGAINST SEX SHOPS 
</HEADLINE>
  (js) 
 By DAN BARRY and DAVID ROHDE   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ A funereal procession of police cars crawled along a
narrow street in lower Manhattan before stopping outside the
storefront in question. More than a dozen police officers and city
inspectors conferred on the sidewalk for a moment, then filed
inside to begin a process that may become commonplace in the city
of Mayor Rudolph Giuliani:
</P>
<P>
   The sex-club shutdown.
</P>
<P>
   The procedure that was followed Thursday night had a ritualistic
feel, one that recalled the shuttering of burlesque shows by Mayor
Fiorello LaGuardia in the early 1940s. Reporters and photographers
who had been tipped off were kept at a distance, but not far enough
to obstruct their view. Neighbors shouted their support. Then, with
a police videographer recording the moment, inspectors slapped a
bright orange sign onto the front door that announced the shutdown
of a Walker Street establishment with the wink-wink name of
Angel's.
</P>
<P>
   After nearly three years of court challenges, New York City has
begun to enforce a zoning law specifically intended to curtail its
adult-entertainment industry. And although that enforcement has
generated a whole new round of court hearings that began last week,
the seemingly endless litigation has done nothing to slow the
city's resolve. Inspectors are dispatched every night into the
shadowy world of peep booths and lap dances, diligently seeking out
violations of the city zoning law.
</P>
<P>
   So far, seven live-entertainment clubs have been temporarily
shut down, while dozens of others are trying out ways to comply _
and still make a profit. Many more adult video and book stores,
such as the XXX Video Store on Reade Street in lower Manhattan,
have voluntarily locked their doors and hung out signs that say:
``Closed for Renovations to Meet City Ordinances _ Will Open
Soon.''
</P>
<P>
   But with those results have come questions. Is there enough
wiggle room in the language of the zoning law for some of the adult
clubs to bypass its intent? Will enforcement lead to the creation
of red-light districts along the fringes of struggling
neighborhoods around the city? And, ultimately, does it reflect a
triumph of Puritanism over free expression in a city that prides
itself on tolerance?
</P>
<P>
   A sign of the times, perhaps, is that Norman Siegel, the
ubiquitous director of the New York Civil Liberties Union, stands
virtually alone as an outspoken critic of the zoning law, which he
says was designed to stamp out legal activity that the mayor finds
personally offensive. He divines hope in the law's language.
</P>
<P>
   ``There are some confusing areas in the law because it is not
that specific, intentionally so,'' Siegel said. ``And maybe some of
it will create problems for the judges, resulting in that the city
won't get what it wants.''
</P>
<P>
   But many others, including some critics of Giuliani, see the
zoning law as a triumph for his administration. ``It's a
significant legislative and legal victory for city hall and our
neighborhoods,'' said the city's public advocate, Mark Green.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   (MORE) nn
</P>
<P>
   For decades, New York City grappled with how to strike a balance
between the rights of its adult-entertainment businesses and the
quality-of-life expectations of its communities. By the early
1990s, the issue had risen to the fore of the public debate:
depressed real-estate values had led to a proliferation of sex
shops in residential areas around the city and, especially, in
Times Square.
</P>
<P>
   Then, in September 1994, nine months into his first
administration, Giuliani proposed comprehensive zoning regulations
to prohibit adult video stores, X-rated theaters and topless bars
from operating within 500 feet of residences, houses of worship,
schools or one another. His proposal would essentially eliminate
the adult trade from Times Square, an area that was ripe for
redevelopment, and banish the businesses to the city's wastelands.
</P>
<P>
   ``They hurt the economy of the city,'' the mayor said then.
``They cost us jobs. They cost us money.''
</P>
<P>
   The mayor chose his words carefully. The U.S. Supreme Court has
held that sexually explicit expressions are protected forms of free
speech, as long as they are not judged to be obscene. But the
courts have also allowed municipalities to use zoning laws to
restrict the adult trade as long as they demonstrate ``secondary
impacts'' that hurt the community, such as increases in crime and
declines in real-estate values.
</P>
<P>
   And the mayor felt confident that the city could demonstrate
those secondary impacts. The Department of City Planning had just
completed a survey that outlined anecdotal evidence of the harmful
impact of the adult trade on neighborhoods. The report also
explored the experiences of other cities _ including Boston,
Seattle and Los Angeles _ in restricting adult establishments.
</P>
<P>
   ``That was the core of the problem,'' said Albert Fredericks, a
former assistant corporation counsel who helped draft the law. ``We
had to strike a balance between dealing with a serious problem
while observing the constitutional limitation and allowing some
access to this kind of entertainment material.''
</P>
<P>
   In October 1995, the City Council overwhelmingly approved the
new zoning law. But before Giuliani could gloat about another
triumph in his quality-of-life campaign, a series of court
challenges were filed _ and eventually beaten back.
</P>
<P>
   In many ways, enforcing the law in the streets of New York has
proven just as challenging as defending it in court. Inspectors now
find themselves mastering terminology such as ``completely and
opaquely concealed'' and ``discernibly turgid state.''
</P>
<P>
   The broad language of the law has also allowed for subjective
interpretation by adult businesses determined to survive. At
Billy's Topless , the dancers now wear bikini tops, as well as
bottoms that cover their buttocks; its owner argues that,
technically, he no longer is running an adult business. Other
establishments have concocted various methods _ using makeup,
latex, even Saran Wrap _ to create the illusion that the breasts of
performers are exposed.
</P>
<P>
   Causing the greatest confusion has been the law's use of the
phrase ``substantial portion'' in defining what makes a nightclub
or video store ``adult.'' Once the city acknowledged that
``substantial'' meant at least 40 percent of a store's inventory,
floor space _ or some combination of both, strip clubs and video
stores scrambled to comply.
</P>
<P>
   A wood-paneled courtroom with a drooping American flag in the
state Supreme Court building in lower Manhattan became the stage
last week for a protracted and frequently comic debate over
``substantial portion'' and other aspects of the law.
</P>
<P>
   Apparently intimidated by the courtroom's formal setting,
officers called by the lawyer representing the city sometimes
hesitated to define exactly what they meant by ``spent condom'' and
``lap dance,'' in which a dancer gyrates on a patron's lap. When
words failed them, they would imitate the gestures of the
performers.
</P>
<P>
   At first it seemed that the city might have a hard time linking
the suggestive gestures of semiclad performers to an immediate
threat to public safety. ``There is constant touching and
contact,'' one of the city's lawyers explained, in arguing the
dangers of a lap dance. ``That is how diseases are contracted. This
person goes back to his family and friends.''
</P>
<P>
   Judge Stephen Crane seemed initially skeptical and jokingly told
the lawyer that if he had such a fear of disease he should avoid
riding the subway. But by week's end, the testimony of
solicitations inside the clubs and used condoms inside and outside
the clubs had persuaded the judge to permit the temporary shutdowns
of two establishments operated by a former dancer named Madeline
D'Anthony: Angel's and the Harmony Theater.
</P>
<P>
   In the meantime, the move toward compliance continues. Last
week, Show World, the sex emporium that looms over Times Square,
ended a quarter-century of live adult performances; the
``peep-a-live'' performers have been let go, leaving only a few
adult-video booths as remnants of its stock in trade. Its manager,
Tom Simmons, said that Show World might become an arcade, or
perhaps a health club.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-08-08-98 1509EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
