<DOCNO> NYT19980808.0108 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-08-08 15:13 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4424 &Cx1f; taf-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CLARK-NAZI-NYT &LR;      08-08 0943
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CLARK-NAZI-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FORMER U.S. ATTORNEY GENERAL STRUGGLES TO DEFEND WAR-CRIMES
SUSPECT 
</HEADLINE>
   (bl)  
 By BENJAMIN WEISER   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Former U.S. Attorney General Ramsey Clark has made a
career out of representing unpopular defendants, but he faces an
unusual challenge this week at the trial of Jack Reimer, a retired
Brooklyn businessman who is accused of helping the Nazis to round
up and exterminate Jews and of lying about his background to gain
entry into the United States.
</P>
<P>
   Federal prosecutors, who are trying to revoke Reimer's
citizenship, are expected to call as witnesses several survivors of
Jewish ghettos in Poland that were liquidated by the Nazis,
including those in Warsaw, Lublin and Czestochowa. Another witness
is expected to testify about a mass execution of Jews in a pit near
Trawniki, Poland.
</P>
<P>
   Although the government has said that none of the witnesses will
identify Reimer as being at the scene of the ghetto operations or
the mass killing, they are certain to offer powerful testimony that
Clark must try to counteract.
</P>
<P>
   He said Friday that their appearances as witnesses would be
inappropriate.
</P>
<P>
   ``Everyone profoundly feels the unbelievable tragedy,'' Clark
said. But he said that Reimer's future should not be affected by
evidence ``that doesn't identify or relate him to it in any direct
way.''
</P>
<P>
   Clark said he would treat the witnesses gently and with respect.
If they do not identify Reimer, he said, he may not ask them any
questions at all.
</P>
<P>
   The government contends that Reimer participated in the
persecution and massacre of Jews. Revoking his citizenship would be
the the first step to deportation. Reimer denies the charges.
</P>
<P>
   Government lawyers declined to discuss the testimony of the
Holocaust survivors. In U.S. District Court in Manhattan last week,
the Justice Department's prosecutor, Edward Stutman, told Judge
Lawrence McKenna that their testimony would play an important role.
</P>
<P>
   ``While they will not identify Reimer,'' Stutman said, ``they
will testify to the activities of men who we shall show were under
Reimer's operational and tactical command.''
</P>
<P>
   Throughout the case, Clark has assumed the role of the underdog.
He and his 79-year-old client sit together at the defense table
without other lawyers or staff members. By contrast, Stutman has
been joined at his table by as many as six other prosecutors,
paralegals and staff members.
</P>
<P>
   Clark, 70, who was attorney general in the Johnson
administration, has said that he cannot afford to buy the daily
trial transcript or pay to fly to Europe to interview a particular
witness.
</P>
<P>
   At another point, he cited 59,000 pages of documents, many in
German and Russian, which the government had given him before
trial.
</P>
<P>
   ``We can't translate these documents,'' he told the judge. ``We
don't have money for a translator.''
</P>
<P>
   The government lawyers seem a bit frustrated by Clark's stance.
At one point Stutman told the judge that the government would even
pay for plane tickets if Clark needed to fly to Europe to interview
a witness.
</P>
<P>
   Clark has also reported threats, while minimizing them.
</P>
<P>
   Last Monday, he told the judge that he had received a call
telling him about a threat on the Internet from a group calling
itself the Jewish Defense Organization. The group's Web site bore
the statement, ``Death to Nazi Scum,'' Clark said. It also listed
Clark's home address and phone number, and promised that there
would be a demonstration outside his home.
</P>
<P>
   ``That doesn't bother me,'' he told the judge. ``I have been
going through that since 1961. But I thought the court ought to
know.''
</P>
<P>
   When the prosecutor, Stutman, offered to ask the marshals to
find an entrance to the courthouse that Clark and his client could
use without being exposed to the public, Clark sounded downright
insulted.
</P>
<P>
   ``We don't need any special way to get into the courthouse,'' he
said. ``We know how to get into the courthouse _ through the
door.''
</P>
<P>
   One of the witnesses listed by the government is a journalist,
Jeffrey Goldberg, who wrote an article in New York magazine in 1994
that quoted Reimer as denying that he was at the mass execution of
50 to 60 Jews in a pit near Trawniki.
</P>
<P>
   ``I know you will find this hard to believe _ I overslept,''
Reimer was quoted as saying in the article. He said he went to the
scene later, but by then, ``they were all dead.''
</P>
<P>
   The government is likely to use the quotation to argue that
Reimer was at the scene, and that he has given many conflicting
accounts to journalists and Justice Department lawyers and in legal
papers about his role in that massacre.
</P>
<P>
   Goldberg, now a contributing writer for The New York Times
Magazine, said Friday that he had been subpoenaed and deposed. ``In
essence,'' he said, ``they were asking me if the quotes were
accurate, and I said they were accurate.'' (Because Goldberg is out
of the country on assignment, prosecutors are expected to introduce
an excerpt from his deposition.)
</P>
<P>
   Goldberg's appearance, however, seems to have spared a former
journalist from having to show up in court.
</P>
<P>
   For a while, it looked as though Marvin Smilon, a former
reporter for The New York Post, was going to be asked to testify.
He had also interviewed Reimer and quoted him in The Post as saying
that he had overslept instead of going to the mass killing.
</P>
<P>
   But Smilon is now the spokesman for the U.S. attorney's office
in Manhattan, which is helping to prosecute Reimer, and the
prosecutors might prefer not to call one of their own to testify.
</P>
<P>
   Asked for comment about that, Smilon said, ``No comment.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
