<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBO-LIPSYTE-COLUMN-NYT </SLUG>
  
 SPORTS COLUMN: HEY, McGWIRE! BEWARE THE CURSE OF THE BABE  
 (bl)  
 By ROBERT LIPSYTE   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   If Mark McGwire has any class, sense of geopolitics and love for
baseball, he will begin hitting only for average this week instead
of for distance. Line-drive singles to the opposite field, Texas
leaguers, grass cutters in the hole, bunts. He will proclaim, with
his bat, that salvation, enlightenment, the good of the game can
only be achieved with craft and sacrifice, never with the big bang.
</P>
<P>
   He will end the season with no more than 60 home runs, just
enough to declare himself the statistical equal of Babe Ruth, which
is the best he can hope for. As a personality, a symbol of his
times, a salesman for America and its pastime, he is not even in
the same ball park as the Bambino. He is a nice guy from suburban
Los Angeles, a dentist's son. But he doesn't even have a nickname.
</P>
<P>
   There are some very good reasons for him to take my advice, not
even including the lesson of Cal Ripken, who didn't. Poor Cal, milk
on his upper lip, egg on his face. Where is he these days? He is
still going to work and doing a progressively poorer job by the
day. Is anyone carrying a Cal Ripken lunch bucket, wearing Cool Cal
Hot Corner Boots?
</P>
<P>
   The first reason for McGwire to quit while he is ahead is to
avoid the true Curse of the Bambino, which Red Sox fans, in their
eternal vanity, think is a plague on them. The Red Sox would have
come up short even with Ruth in the lineup; that's Boston. The true
curse falls on those who surpass Ruth's record.
</P>
<P>
   Roger Maris, an excellent ballplayer and an all-round decent
guy, was the first to confuse monotheism for meritocracy. If he hit
61 homers, one more than Ruth, he thought, shouldn't he be
acclaimed? Poor Roger. Just being better isn't enough. Baseball
fans, besotted with Mickey Mantle in those days, had proclaimed him
the new Ruth, not Maris. So Roger was booed and his record was
devalued.
</P>
<P>
   We were then told that Ruth's real accomplishment was his career
record of 714. Thirteen years after Maris' record, when Henry Aaron
hit his 715th home run, he was the target for racial slurs and
death threats. And we were told that the one true record was Joe
DiMaggio's 56-game hitting streak.
</P>
<P>
   The second reason for McGwire to lower the boom rate is to
strike a blow for a return to the way the game should be played,
with guile and daring, speed and savvy, instead of the lucky big
bang. We have seen, in our time, the slam dunk, the slap shot and
the home run become, instead of a desperate measure, a routine
tactic.
</P>
<P>
   There is a certain democracy to the homer _ an underdog comes
from behind with a dramatic gesture _ but it is also the equivalent
of quitting work to play the lottery after a lifetime of losing.
Soccer has yet to develop that lucky hit, although purists shudder
at the increase in booming passes from a deep defender to a
penetrating forward.
</P>
<P>
   The third reason transcends the arena. Since real life is merely
a reflection of sports, the ascendancy of the home run has had
enormous ramifications, including, among other, the development of
The Bomb and the initial stock offering; the popularity of
Native-American casinos, and the relentless search for the
all-cancer magic bullet instead of the management of individual
diseases.
</P>
<P>
   How could McGwire not want to stop pulling the ball?
</P>
<P>
   The last time I made this kind of suggestion was three years ago
when I called on Cal Ripken to take a day off so as not to break
Lou Gehrig's record of 2,130 consecutive games. I still think the
suggestion was written tongue in cheek, but the outraged reaction
convinced me for a while that I had been serious. After all, what
honor could there be in erasing the record of a man who stopped
playing merely because he had a terminal disease?
</P>
<P>
   As you may recall, Ripken ignored my advice and broke the
record, helping to revive the memory of Gehrig as more than the
name of a terrible wasting disease. Right-wing commentators, like
the part-Oriole owner George F. Will, quivered at Cal's role-model
work ethic but had little to say about the greedy corporate layoffs
and mergers that made that work ethic so remarkably difficult an
example to emulate. If Cal tried to pull a stunt like that in the
real world, he would be fired before his pension was vested.
</P>
<P>
   So Big Mac (you like that?) or Mighty Marky (animated
character?) hits 62 or 72. So what. The wise guys on the Web will
say that pitchers were grooving it for him, under orders from the
new commissioner to jack up the game. McGwire will only be beating
Maris, who has been devalued, not the Babe, who will have yet
another commercial rebirth.
</P>
<P>
   Does McGwire have the vision and humanity to check his swing and
try to save a piece of the world? As a gesture, it would be a real
home run.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
