<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GM-ASSESS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ANALYSIS: BIG CHANGES AT GM  
</HEADLINE>
  (mk) 
 By KEITH BRADSHER   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   TRAVERSE CITY, Mich. _ After three decades of decline, General
Motors remains the world's largest company, and its sheer size and
the enormous scope of its problems have prompted a succession of
executives to seek sweeping solutions costing billions of dollars _
usually with little success.
</P>
<P>
   The latest effort came last week, just after GM suffered a
crippling, nearly eight-week strike, as the company's leaders
dribbled out a succession of announcements. On Monday, the company
said that it would turn its auto parts subsidiary into a separate
company next year. On Tuesday, GM announced that it would combine
the marketing staffs of its Buick, Cadillac, Chevrolet, Oldsmobile
and Pontiac-GMC divisions, with only Saturn remaining independent.
And on Wednesday, John Smith Jr., GM's chairman and chief
executive, said that the automaker would build a new generation of
assembly plants in the United States that would use fewer workers
than current factories do, to bolt together large chunks of
vehicles built by outside suppliers.
</P>
<P>
   The three initiatives, all of which were expected at some point
but not all together last week, are significant because they would
change the way GM has done business since the 1920s. It would
become a company that designed, assembled and marketed cars and
light trucks but made few of the parts. In place of the ruthless
competition among divisions that led the company to dominance of
the domestic auto industry in the '50s and '60s, marketing managers
would be expected to cooperate and avoid duplication of effort.
</P>
<P>
   But rather than setting a new example, all three moves would
make GM a little more like the rest of the industry. The outcome of
all three strategies _and the futures of GM's 600,000 workers
around the world _ will depend on whether the company can carry out
these strategies better than its rivals. And GM has a deserved
reputation for poor implementation of grand strategies: Mediocre
middle managers and poisonous labor relations have repeatedly
scuttled the visions of leaders.
</P>
<P>
   The plan for new assembly plants, at a cost likely to exceed
$500 million apiece, is typical of GM's approach of throwing money
at productivity problems that partly reflect management problems.
In a speech here on Wednesday at the University of Michigan's
annual auto industry conference, Smith said the factories were
needed to make use of the latest trend in auto manufacturing, which
is to rely more on suppliers.
</P>
<P>
   The latest conventional wisdom, pioneered partly by GM's highly
efficient Brazilian subsidiary, says that productivity improves
when suppliers assemble large sections of cars, like dashboards,
instead of shipping crates of speedometers, radios and other parts
to be bolted together on the factory floor. GM's older factories
look like squares when viewed from above, while its new factories
will look like plus signs, so as to allow more exterior wall space
for loading docks where suppliers can deliver sections of vehicles
directly to the assembly line.
</P>
<P>
   Other automakers are also relying more heavily on suppliers. But
even after GM's announcement, few of them are convinced that they
need to build new assembly plants.
</P>
<P>
   A report last month by Harbour &AMP; Associates, an auto
productivity consulting company, said that Ford Motor Co. had four
of the 10 most efficient car assembly plants in North America and
eight of the 10 most efficient light truck assembly plants. But
Robert Transou, the Ford group vice president who has turned around
the company's manufacturing operations, said that he planned to
rely more on suppliers without building assembly plants.
</P>
<P>
   ``You can get 99 percent of the benefits without building new
plants,'' he said in an interview here on Friday. The secret to
Ford's productivity, he said, lies in constantly pursuing lots of
little efficiency improvements in each factory, and in close
cooperation between workers and management. Ford has not had a
strike since 1986.
</P>
<P>
   GM's Brazilian subsidiary relies on suppliers, but it also has
an enthusiastic work force and imaginative middle managers. By
contrast, the ranks of GM's factory managers in the United States
have changed surprisingly little in recent years and have often
shown resistance to change. GM also has the worst labor-relations
record in the auto industry, including 22 strikes since 1990. In a
possible case of industrial sabotage, a GM assembly line in
Kentucky had to be shut down in late July when a pipe was
mysteriously jammed into a conveyor belt.
</P>
<P>
   Smith said GM wanted to improve its labor relations, and so had
chosen to settle the recent strike instead of pursuing legal
battles with the union. ``What good would it do,'' he asked, ``to
win and have a disgruntled work force that wouldn't have their
heart and soul in getting us back'' to full production?
</P>
<P>
   In addition to good relations with workers, the company will
need warm relations with suppliers once it builds the new factories
and spins off its auto parts subsidiary. Ford and Chrysler already
have good relations with suppliers, because they sold many of their
auto parts factories during their close brushes with financial
disaster in the late '70s and early '80s. Suppliers share their
latest ideas for reducing costs or improving parts designs with
Ford and Chrysler, confident that the automakers will share the
resulting savings with them.
</P>
<P>
   GM's relationships with suppliers are only now recovering from
the damage done in the early '90s when Jose Ignacio Lopez de
Arriortua, a purchasing executive, renegotiated GM's contracts with
many suppliers and demanded that the company keep the savings
brought about by suppliers' innovations.
</P>
<P>
   The company's decision to consolidate most of its marketing
staffs, while leaving Saturn independent, will make it more like
Ford, which has an immense Ford marketing division for most of its
models and a small Lincoln-Mercury division on the side. But even
in marketing, GM will face an extra challenge, as it tries to
eliminate decades of rivalries within its divisions.
</P>
<P>
   The company's biggest problem is that every time it seems to be
catching up with the rest of the industry, other automakers make
further progress themselves.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm sure everything they're trying to do is in the right
direction,'' said Chris Theodore, a Chrysler vice president for
engineering. ``They've made immense progress; it's just that the
world is moving.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
