<HEADER>
A4449 &Cx1f; taf-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FBN-GIANTS-TOOMER-NYT     08-08 0956
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-GIANTS-TOOMER-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
A WHOLE NEW LOOK FOR THE GIANTS' TOOMER 
</HEADLINE>
   (bl)  
 By BILL PENNINGTON   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   When the New York Giants' season ended last year, the team's
coaches gathered to evaluate the roster. In those meetings, it was
agreed that Amani Toomer, the wide receiver the Giants had drafted
with great promise just two years ago, might not be in the team's
plans much longer.
</P>
<P>
   The Giants were going to draft two wide receivers. There was a
good chance Toomer would be cut in training camp.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's fair to say,'' Giants coach Jim Fassel said last week,
recalling the team's off-season evaluations.
</P>
<P>
   As the coaches were meeting in January, preparing their
unflattering reports of him, Toomer was at home. He remembers
watching the Denver Broncos play the Kansas City Chiefs in a
playoff game on television on Sunday, Jan. 4.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm not sure what it was about that day, but I sat there and
said to myself, `This isn't working out,''' Toomer said between
practices at the Giants' training camp in Albany, N.Y., on
Thursday. ``I'm hardly playing, they're not happy with me, and I'm
not happy. What was right or wrong didn't matter. I had to
change.''
</P>
<P>
   The Giants opened their preseason Saturday night, taking on the
visiting Cincinnati Bengals, and the same coaches who felt they
could probably do without Toomer are now calling him the team's
most improved player. Day after day this summer, a coach or a
teammate has referred to Toomer as ``a changed man.''
</P>
<P>
   Whether he is using a new, more physical playing style to battle
hefty linebackers for passes, or outracing cornerbacks down the
sideline for long touchdown passes, or running precise, clever pass
routes across the middle, Toomer has been the unquestioned star of
camp.
</P>
<P>
   ``There is something seriously wrong with you if you haven't
noticed the difference in Amani,'' Giants safety Sam Garnes said.
``He's a terror out there.''
</P>
<P>
   Quarterback Danny Kanell was watching the group of defensive
backs and wide receivers run end-of-practice sprints the other day.
These are the fleetest of Giants.
</P>
<P>
   ``I remember last year when Amani was struggling just to finish
the sprints,'' Kanell said. ``I looked up the other day and he was
racing Jason Sehorn at the front of the pack, shoulder to shoulder.
Jason is the best conditioned guy on the team.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's like a totally different man has shown up in Amani's
uniform.''
</P>
<P>
   Actually, the 6-foot-2-inch, 200-pound Toomer showed up in a
different uniform. He ditched the No. 89 jersey he wore in his
first two seasons with the Giants and has taken jersey No. 81,
previously worn by Thomas Lewis, another disappointing high draft
pick who left the team this year after four unproductive seasons.
</P>
<P>
   No one is crediting the number change for the change in Toomer.
The change has been a simple one, if you ask him, although he seems
embarrassed when asked what it's like to be a changed man.
</P>
<P>
   ``Of course, I'm the same person,'' said Toomer, who is quiet
and reserved. ``I just wasn't putting my best foot forward most of
the time. I knew I had to do a lot more and I had to be more
focused about what I wanted to achieve.''
</P>
<P>
   He also knew Fassel thought he was failing as a football player.
</P>
<P>
   ``I had to prove to him and everybody else that I did know what
I was doing,'' the 23-year-old Toomer said. ``That's what drove
me.''
</P>
<P>
   The first thing Toomer did in his make over was attend the
team's off-season strength and conditioning program every day it
was scheduled and some days when it wasn't.
</P>
<P>
   ``He worked harder than anybody,'' Fassel said. ``He worked so
hard I found myself pulling for him _ really pulling for him.''
</P>
<P>
   Toomer also took kung fu instruction in nearby Nyack, N.Y.
</P>
<P>
   ``Their training exercises really strengthened my knee,'' Toomer
said, referring to his right knee, which was surgically repaired in
1996 after he tore his anterior cruciate ligament. ``In kung fu
there are some very low stances and you need strength and
flexibility at the same time do be able to do the movements.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's allowed me to play lower on the football field. I think
I'm coming off the cuts faster.''
</P>
<P>
   But it is Toomer's more aggressive attitude in pursuit of the
football that has made the biggest impression on the Giants'
secondary.
</P>
<P>
   ``Amani is just killing people to get to the ball when it's in
the air,'' said safety Percy Ellsworth, who is a physically
imposing player himself at 6-2 and 225.
</P>
<P>
   Told of Ellsworth's remarks, Toomer laughed.
</P>
<P>
   ``A state of mind,'' he said. ``You see the ball and get to it _
pushing, pulling, tripping people _ whatever helps.''
</P>
<P>
   Chris Calloway is the dignified elder statesman of the Giants
receiving corps. Rarely highlighted, Calloway has led the team in
receiving for three successive seasons. He has also been watching
the new Toomer.
</P>
<P>
   ``I never could put my finger on what was going wrong,''
Calloway said. ``But sometimes something clicks. He's in better
shape and having the best camp of anybody. There's just no doubt
about it.''
</P>
<P>
   The next question, of course, is whether Toomer can sustain his
success in the regular season. Or is he a training-camp phenomenon?
</P>
<P>
   ``I think it will carry over into the regular season,'' Fassel
said. ``This isn't some trick, it's something built over months of
hard work.''
</P>
<P>
   Toomer said he isn't eager to re-visit his football past.
</P>
<P>
   ``If I keep doing this,'' he said. ``Then it will become a good
habit.''
</P>
<P>
   In April this year, the Giants did take two wide receivers in
the draft, Joe Jurevicius and Brian Alford.
</P>
<P>
   On the team's depth chart at wide receiver, they are behind the
other new guy in camp, No. 81, Amani Toomer.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
