<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-EUROPE-AIRCON-ART-615(2TAKES)-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
EUROPEANS' BURGEONING LOVE AFFAIR WITH AIR CONDITIONING 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (Repeating to correct slug)  (ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients. Graphic is
being sent to NYT graphic clients. Non-subscribers can make
individual purchase by calling 212-556-4204 or -1927.) 
(js) 
 By JOHN TAGLIABUE   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   ROME _ Marco Liberali decided not to fiddle around while Rome
burned. Seeking relief from Rome's tropical temperatures, the
41-year-old mechanic installed central air-conditioning in his
family's apartment on the edge of the city.
</P>
<P>
   ``What a difference it makes,'' Liberali said with the
assuredness of the newly converted. ``Humid heat is bad for you.''
</P>
<P>
   When Americans rushed to cool their air, Europeans traditionally
just slowed down and endured the summer heat. But now people like
Liberali, who got to know air-conditioning at the hotel where he
works, have decided to stop going without.
</P>
<P>
   Europe is becoming a big market for the air-conditioning
industry. Sales of air-conditioners for homes and small businesses
have grown more than 20 percent over the last three years, even as
they stayed flat in the United States, and the growth shows no sign
of abating.
</P>
<P>
   In Europe, sales of air-conditioners for homes and small
businesses, including central air units for homes, are expected to
reach $3.2 billion this year, from $2.5 billion in 1996. In the
United States, they are expected only to inch up to $7.74 billion,
from $7.73 billion in 1996.
</P>
<P>
   Credit some of the growth to the pressures of a global economy,
which are increasingly forcing Europeans to work summers. Air
pollution is also bolstering the demand for air-conditioning, and
Europeans are becoming more accustomed to it in offices and their
cars, and increasingly want it in their homes.
</P>
<P>
   But environmentalists are concerned. Air-conditioners consume a
significant amount of energy, and their emissions help deplete the
ozone layer.
</P>
<P>
   To be sure, many hurdles must fall before Europe can fully
indulge its new fondness for the big chill. Both electricity and
air-conditioners are costly, many homes lack proper wiring, home
power supplies are often weak and many Europeans view
air-conditioning as unhealthy: there is simply a bias to rely on
nature.
</P>
<P>
   Still, the trend toward a cooler Europe is clear.
</P>
<P>
   ``Above all in the whole area of small businesses and homes, the
use of air-conditioning is increasing,'' said Alfred Voss, director
of the Institute for Energy Use and Rational Use of Energy at
Stuttgart University.
</P>
<P>
   But Europe has a long way to go before air-conditioning becomes
the norm in homes. In Italy, 7 percent of homes are
air-conditioned, and in Spain 11 percent, compared with 71 percent
in the United States and more than 90 percent in Japan.
</P>
<P>
   Hotels, post offices, police stations, even hospitals, except
for operating rooms, generally do not have air-conditioning.
</P>
<P>
   So it is hardly surprising that the world's biggest
air-conditioner makers _ Japanese giants like Mitsubishi and Daikin
Industries, and American leaders like Carrier Corp., a unit of
United Technologies, and Trane Co., a unit of American Standard _
view Europe as a potential El Dorado. European companies, like
Riello and De Longhi in Italy, are jockeying to catch up.
</P>
<P>
   ``The culture of air-conditioning is spreading,'' said Carlo
Segato, head of marketing at De Longhi, a specialist in portable
and room air-conditioners.
</P>
<P>
   But as temperatures climbed over Italy this summer, the
country's Green Party, echoing warnings from environmentalists
across Europe, argued that air-conditioners, while cooling the
inside of homes, forced out warm air, raising temperatures outside.
Moreover, they argued, more air-conditioners mean more
ozone-depleting gases in the atmosphere, which contribute to global
warming. ``Turning on your air-conditioner today,'' said Fulco
Pratesi, a Green Party spokesman in Rome, ``means suffering more
from the heat tomorrow.''
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   &QL; 
nn
</P>
<P>
   The European air-conditioning market did not arrive overnight.
It was created after World War II by the companies that pioneered
the technology in the United States, including Carrier and York
International Corp.
</P>
<P>
   In the 1980s the Japanese arrived. Mitsubishi and Toshiba have
factories in Britain and Daikin has one in Belgium. And the
Japanese got a leg up by introducing small, quiet portables and
wall models suited to small European dwellings. The Americans
responded quickly. Carrier bought local manufacturers in Spain and
Italy and redesigned its products to meet European demands.
</P>
<P>
   European companies, for their part, took a chapter from the
Japanese and copied Japanese models. The Italians introduced snappy
new models at competitive prices.
</P>
<P>
   De Longhi, long a maker of room heaters, began importing Toshiba
air-conditioners in 1988, then built its own, and its engineers now
use refrigerants that do not damage the atmosphere, including a
butane mixture similar to lighter fluid.
</P>
<P>
   Air-conditioning makers must scramble to find economical
substitutes for chlorofluorocarbons, gases traditionally used as
refrigerants, which were banned by the Montreal Protocol, a 1987
treaty signed by more than 150 countries, because they deplete the
earth's ozone layer.
</P>
<P>
   Subsequent accords banned the production of the interim
substitute, hydrochlorofluorocarbons, after 2020.
</P>
<P>
   Europe's industry is under particular pressure because Germany,
Italy and Sweden, heeding environmentalists, want these gases gone
by 2000. When a company in eastern Germany first produced
refrigerators using butane in 1992, Greenpeace bought the first 10
prototypes.
</P>
<P>
   But substitutes are expensive. Sergio Zanolin, De Longhi's head
of research, said butane air-conditioners cost 10 percent to 20
percent more than conventional models. While Americans can trundle
down to a Home Depot and pick up a window unit for about $200, the
least expensive room models in Europe sell for almost $1,000
because of low production runs and expensive components.
</P>
<P>
   This year De Longhi expects to sell about $165 million worth of
air-conditioners and has even carved out a niche in the United
States. In part, sales received a boost in Europe from
air-conditioning's use as a marketing tool by stores, shopping
centers and professional offices of dentists and lawyers.
</P>
<P>
   ``The last five years have seen a revolution in light commercial
use,'' said Halsey Cook, Carrier's head of marketing in Europe.
</P>
<P>
   When automobile air-conditioning caught on in the early 1990s,
it was largely thanks to stagnant auto sales, which prompted car
makers to offer air-conditioners to attract buyers. Five years ago,
hardly any European cars were air-conditioned; now, 28 percent are.
</P>
<P>
   That may be peanuts compared with the United States, where 95
percent of cars are air-conditioned, but the market continues to
grow.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's getting started, people are buying it, and the technology
now allows it,'' said Sandro Frigerio, who follows the auto
air-conditioning market at Standard &AMP; Poor's DRI in London. He said
innovation and miniaturization now enabled auto makers to cool
small European cars without significant power loss or higher gas
consumption.
</P>
<P>
   And as Europeans grow fond of air-conditioning in cars and
dentists' offices, more want it at home.
</P>
<P>
   Not that sales have exploded. ``The domestic market is really on
the edge of a boom,'' said Jacques Benoist, director of
certification at Eurovent, an industry association established
recently in Paris to certify air-conditioning equipment. ``But it
didn't happen yet.''
</P>
<P>
   And there are many reasons.
</P>
<P>
   The first, of course, is price, which is compounded by energy
problems. In some countries, like Italy, sufficient electricity is
scarce. Typical Italian homes are equipped with smaller circuit
breakers than American homes. In Italy, a separate circuit for
air-conditioning costs as much as $400.
</P>
<P>
   Partly, Europe's reluctance can be traced to the relatively mild
climate, with little of the tropical heat that assaults cities like
Houston or Miami. Yet temperatures in Granada, Spain, or Palermo,
Italy, can easily surpass those in New York. Some experts also
point to a tendency for Europeans to favor nature over technology.
</P>
<P>
   ``When they design a building, they take greater advantage of
natural lighting and ventilation,'' said Bruce Anderson, head of
marketing in Europe for Trane, based in Tyler, Texas ``So owners
will say, `There's no reason to have air-conditioning.'''
</P>
<P>
   Such reluctance is bolstered by a conviction that
air-conditioning is unhealthy.
</P>
<P>
   Italian newspapers, which regularly advise readers how to deal
with the heat, warn against it. The weekly health insert of La
Repubblica in Rome recently warned readers that air-conditioning
could cause colds and sore throats and spread ``germs, viruses and
bacteria'' through unclean filters.
</P>
<P>
   In the United States, many experts argue the opposite. In the
recent heat wave, more than 120 deaths were attributed to the heat.
Indeed, some European doctors increasingly recommend
air-conditioning for the elderly and for people with heart trouble
and respiratory ailments.
</P>
<P>
   In response, European manufacturers have developed quieter and
more efficient models. And increased production, economies of scale
and cheap foreign imports will cut prices. In television ads,
Italian importers offer cheap Chinese air-conditioners free to
viewers who order mattresses.
</P>
<P>
   Moreover, as Europe deregulates the energy market, electricity
supplies are expected to rise, thus reducing the cost.
</P>
<P>
   In France the national utility, Electricite de France, offers
bonuses to builders who install energy-efficient heat pumps, which
warm homes in winter and cool them in summer. Italy's national
utility, Enel, now penalizes energy use by charging higher rates as
more power is consumed. ``Ten to 15 years ago, we had power
shortages,'' said Enel marketing director Roberto Formigoni. ``Now
we have lots to sell.'' So Enel is petitioning Rome's energy
authority to cut rates and increase the supply for homes.
</P>
<P>
   Antonietta Marconi, marketing director of GMC Climatizzatori,
where Liberali bought his equipment, says it cannot happen too
soon.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've been in the air-conditioning business for six years, and
prices will fall,'' she said. ``It will become like central
heating.''
</P>
<P>
   Voss, of Stuttgart University, agrees. ``With energy prices
coming down, I think it's safe to say the tendency will be for
demand for appliances like air-conditioners to continue to grow,''
he said. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
