<HEADER>
A4473 &Cx1f; taf-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-NY-POLICE-LOUIMA-NYT &LR;      08-08 0880
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NY-POLICE-LOUIMA-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
LOUIMA CASE SLOWED BY DISPUTE OVER REPRESENTATION 
</HEADLINE>
  (mk) 
 By JOSEPH P. FRIED   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ On the first anniversary of what prosecutors say was
the torture of Abner Louima by police officers at a Brooklyn
station house, the case against five officers is bogged down in a
dispute over legal representation.
</P>
<P>
   In contrast to the graphic reports of brutalization involving
Louima, a Haitian immigrant, the dispute in U.S. District Court in
Brooklyn involves the much less sensational issue of whether the
lawyers for two of the officers should be removed from the case
because of possible conflicts of interest. The lawyers are partners
in a new firm that has a contract to represent all of the city's
police officers.
</P>
<P>
   Until this issue _ which has been the focus of pretrial
proceedings for the last two months _ is resolved, matters
involving evidence and other issues that have to be dealt with
before the trial can begin will not be considered. And if the two
lawyers are replaced, the time needed for their successors to
become familiar with the case is expected to further delay the
trial, which is unlikely to start before early next year.
</P>
<P>
   The roadblock in a case that was already held up by a switch
from state to federal prosecution vividly illustrates how even the
most emotional case _ in this instance involving one of the most
politically and racially charged accusations of police brutality in
New York City in years _ can become bogged down in cerebral
courtroom skirmishing.
</P>
<P>
   But the diversion in the prosecution _ which stems from Louima's
encounter with police officers who arrested him in a brawl on Aug.
9, 1997 _ does not mean the emotions of the case are in remission.
In fact, they are expected to be intensely expressed when Louima's
family and supporters hold an anniversary vigil at the site of his
arrest, outside Club Rendez-Vous, a nightclub at 1438 Flatbush Ave.
And Louima's lawyers filed a civil lawsuit on his behalf on
Thursday against the city, the five accused officers and the
Patrolmen's Benevolent Association, the union that represents
police officers.
</P>
<P>
   According to prosecutors in the criminal case and Louima's
lawyers, four of the officers beat him in a police car on the way
to the 70th Precinct station house in Flatbush, and two of the four
tortured him there. One officer, Justin Volpe, is accused of
ramming a stick into Louima's rectum and then into his mouth,
inflicting major internal injuries, while the second, Charles
Schwarz, is accused of holding Louima down.
</P>
<P>
   They and Thomas Bruder and Thomas Wiese, two other officers
accused of taking part in the patrol-car beatings, are charged with
violating Louima's civil rights. The fifth defendant, Sgt. Michael
Bellomo, is charged with trying to cover up the beating. All five
officers are white, and Louima's civil suit charges that he endured
``ethnic and racist slurs'' during the assaults.
</P>
<P>
   The five officers insist that the charges are untrue.
</P>
<P>
   The conflict-of-interest dispute involves Schwarz's lawyer,
Stephen Worth, and Bruder's lawyer, Stuart London. Both have been
representing their clients since the case began last August. They
were retained by the officers' union, which had previously engaged
them, case by case, to represent other officers in trouble.
</P>
<P>
   When they were retained in the Louima case, Worth and London
were with separate law firms. But earlier this year they became
partners in a new firm that obtained a contract with the PBA,
effective in May, to represent all of its members facing charges in
criminal cases and in Police Department disciplinary matters.
</P>
<P>
   But the lawyers' new relationships with each other and with the
union raise ``serious conflict-of-interest issues,'' according to
prosecutors from the U.S. attorney's office in Brooklyn, who are
wary of any condition that might enable officers to appeal a
conviction with the argument that their lawyers' conflicts kept
them from receiving the most effective defense. The prosecutors
have indicated that they might seek the removal of Worth and London
from the case.
</P>
<P>
   ``The risks posed by a single law firm representing
co-defendants in a criminal case,'' reads a recent prosecution
brief on the matter, include ``the possibility that one partner
will forgo viable defense strategies beneficial to his client but
which may conflict with the strategy of his partner.''
</P>
<P>
   And citing the contract under which the new firm _ Worth,
Longworth &AMP; Bamundo _ is to provide legal services to all police
union members, the brief argues that if police officers who might
be called as witnesses at the trial wanted legal advice, ``the firm
would then be in the position of providing a defense for Schwarz
and Bruder and advising potential witnesses against them.''
</P>
<P>
   Worth and London have told Judge Eugene Nickerson that their
removal is not required because there is no conflict between the
defenses of Schwarz and Bruder, and that the two want to continue
with their lawyers. And other lawyers could be hired to advise
potential police officer witnesses, Worth and London said.
Nickerson is expected to hold a hearing on the dispute, which is
not likely to be resolved for at least another month.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
