<DATE_TIME> 1998-08-08 16:26 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4474 &Cx1f; taf-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-DISABLED-SAILING-NYT &LR;      08-08 0735
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-DISABLED-SAILING-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
(ATTN: R.I.)  
 WITH NOD TO CONNER, DISABLED SAILOR'S AIM IS TITLE 
</HEADLINE>
   (bl)  
 By BARBARA LLOYD   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEWPORT, R.I. _ It has crossed Paul Callahan's mind that he,
like his friend Dennis Conner, wants nothing to do with falling off
a sailboat.
</P>
<P>
   Conner never learned to swim, and Callahan couldn't swim if he
wanted to: he is a quadriplegic. Nevertheless, both are
championship sailors.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's why Dennis and I see eye to eye,'' Callahan said
recently. ``We both sail by instinct.''
</P>
<P>
   Callahan, 40, will represent the United States in the 1998
Hartford World Disabled Sailing Championship, which starts here
Sunday.
</P>
<P>
   The seven-race regatta includes 17 teams from 15 countries
competing in 23-foot Sonar sloops.
</P>
<P>
   The world championship calls for fleet racing. But each boat
begins with a handicap rating based on the level of each crew's
disabilities. The scale runs from 1-7, with No. 1 representing the
most severe handicap. Callahan is rated a No. 1, which makes his
success in sailboat racing even more significant.
</P>
<P>
   ``Any world championship is hard to win,'' Conner said. ``Just
the fact that Paul is winning at this level shows what kind of guy
he is.''
</P>
<P>
   For competitors with disabilities, sailboat racing requires
subtle adjustments in technique to offset their handicaps.
</P>
<P>
   Callahan has minimal movement in his arms. To compensate, he has
rigged a special steering mechanism that allows him to pull rather
than push the boat's tiller.
</P>
<P>
   His crew needs to hike out on the rail farther than normal to
make up for Callahan's inability to shift his weight on a tack.
</P>
<P>
   Keith Burhans of Rochester, one of Callahan's two crewmates, is
a double amputee who lost both legs below the knee.
</P>
<P>
   His other teammate, Richard Hughes, of Philadelphia, is a single
amputee. Both wear leg prostheses.
</P>
<P>
   As chairman of Shake-a-Leg-Newport, Callahan directs a
rehabilitative program for people with spinal-cord injuries. A
basic component of the group regimen is sailing, which allows the
disabled an opportunity to take up one of the few sports available
to them. It is how Callahan came to take up sailing five years ago.
</P>
<P>
   Two years ago, Callahan asked the New York Yacht Club, which has
an annex in Newport, if it would help out with the world
championship. In an unprecedented gesture for disabled sailing, the
club agreed. The organization plans to send a team of race experts,
including about 50 volunteers, to organize the seven-race regatta.
</P>
<P>
   ``The club feels that there are certain events in which it
should give something back,'' said George Hinman, former chairman
of the New York club's committee on competitions.
</P>
<P>
   High-profile individuals have helped out, too. Conner donated a
$25,000 Sonar sloop to Shake-a-Leg two years ago.
</P>
<P>
   Without telling Conner ahead of time, Callahan arranged for the
boat to be painted in the same red, white and blue colors as the
America's Cup yachts that Conner sailed for the Stars &AMP; Stripes
syndicate in 1992.
</P>
<P>
   When it came time for the Sonar to be christened in 1996,
Callahan began the dockside ceremony by draping the new boat in the
way that's typical for yachts with secret design innovations.
</P>
<P>
   ``What do you think this is,'' bellowed Conner, ``an America's
Cup campaign?'' Then the cloth came off, and Conner saw the paint
job. Callahan describes it as an emotional moment.
</P>
<P>
   Sports have come as easily to Callahan as fund-raising.
</P>
<P>
   Callahan was a high school all-American in basketball in
Providence, R.I. But in his junior year at Harvard University, he
slipped on a wet linoleum floor and severely damaged his spinal
cord. He has been in a wheelchair since, and he still approaches
life with the confidence of an athlete.
</P>
<P>
   Callahan has received a master's degree in business from
Harvard. He is director of the Harvard Graduate School of Business,
and commutes by car _ which he drives himself _ from Newport to
Cambridge, Mass.
</P>
<P>
   That self-assurance was evident from the moment he stepped on a
sailboat in 1993.
</P>
<P>
   ``The first day I went out sailing was extremely windy,'' he
recalled. ``The instructor said, `You seem like a skipper, so
you're driving.' After we left the dock, he wanted to go out in the
bay. But I wanted to weave in and around the other boats in the
harbor.
</P>
<P>
   ``He cringed, but said it was OK It was my baptism by fire.'' &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
