<DATE_TIME> 1998-08-08 17:14 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4489 &Cx1f; taf-z
r f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-NY-STREET-FURNITURE-R     08-08 0958
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NY-STREET-FURNITURE-REAL-3TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
STREET FURNITURE DESIGNS STUCK IN GRIDLOCK 
</HEADLINE>
   (bl)  
 By DAVID W. DUNLAP   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Some of the world's leading architects have designed
newsstands, bus-stop shelters and public toilets for New York City.
Not just models and renderings; life-size ``street furniture'' _
tall enough to walk in, sturdy enough to sit on.
</P>
<P>
   Don't look for it anytime soon, however. At least, not on the
sidewalks of New York.
</P>
<P>
   Richard Meier's street furniture can be found instead under a
grove of oak trees outside the Floral Glass &AMP; Mirror works in
Hauppauge, N.Y. The pieces designed by Josef Paul Kleihues are
arrayed around a warehouse in the northernmost Bronx.
</P>
<P>
   And in a vast storeroom in Astoria, Queens, a block from Kaufman
Astoria Studios, sit 14 full-scale bus-stop shelters, newsstands
and toilets _ lights shining, time-and-temperature signs flashing,
roll-down grates rolling _ designed by Norman Foster &AMP; Partners,
Gwathmey Siegel &AMP; Associates Architects, Polshek &AMP; Partners
Architects, Robert A.M. Stern Architects and Vignelli Associates.
</P>
<P>
   All were built in an effort to capture the proposed 20-year
coordinated citywide franchise for at least 3,300 shelters, 430
newsstands and 30 toilets. After spending millions of dollars on
their bids, however, the four prospective contractors were told
June 26 that the Giuliani administration had decided to cancel the
project.
</P>
<P>
   The official explanation was simply: ``The city is exploring
options to develop a street furniture program that would encourage
competition and greater design variation in the structures to
distinguish the city's different neighborhoods.''
</P>
<P>
   What that decision leaves in its wake is not only two dozen
imaginative, expensive prototypes, but a hard-won expertise in
designing for the streets; expertise that may yet be called into
play.
</P>
<P>
   ``Even though we're disappointed, those were well-spent
millions,'' said Stephen Feinberg, president and chief executive of
Adshel, for whom Richard Meier &AMP; Partners designed two lines of
furniture. ``What I'm designing for Boston incorporates everything
I learned in New York.''
</P>
<P>
   (Boston will soon issue a request for proposals, making it the
next big prize in the race by private contractors to furnish
American streets with amenities _ and reap the advertising dollars
that follow.)
</P>
<P>
   Last month, after New York withdrew its request for proposals,
Adshel and two other bidders, J C Decaux New York and Wall City
Design, permitted an inspection of their previously confidential
submissions by a reporter and photographer from The New York Times,
although the companies would not disclose the financial terms.
</P>
<P>
   ``New York has traditionally avoided design excellence in the
public domain,'' said the architect Charles Gwathmey, who worked
for Decaux. ``This should be an upbeat and positive signal that
there's a new vision of sidewalk amenities.''
</P>
<P>
   The proposals are extremely ambitious. And no wonder. The
winning company could have expected gross revenues between $1
billion and $2 billion over the 20-year term from the illuminated
advertising panels, against an investment of about $100 million to
build the structures, as well as the cost of maintaining them. The
winner would also have scored the promotional coup of having its
fixtures designated as New York City's official standard.
</P>
<P>
   So the bidders enlisted several prominent architects, who
produced designs ranging from fussy to futuristic, although most
relied on simple lines and metallic tones, providing enough
structural details to be interesting but not so many as to
encourage harvesting by vandals.
</P>
<P>
   By far the most ecumenical proposal came from J C Decaux and GE
Capital Services, for whom seven architects created seven distinct
designs. Besides those whose prototypes are in Astoria, the roster
included Eisenman Architects and Tod Williams Billie Tsien &AMP;
Associates.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was the city's option to pick the ones they wanted,'' said
Suzanne Davis, senior vice president of J C Decaux USA. ``They
could have picked several different selections for different
neighborhoods.''
</P>
<P>
   J C Decaux, the French parent company founded by Jean-Claude
Decaux in 1962, holds franchises in some 1,135 cities worldwide,
among them San Francisco, where it signed a contract in 1994 for
newsstands, toilets and pillar-style kiosks. For four months in
1992, Decaux operated six experimental public toilets in New York.
</P>
<P>
   The architects working for Decaux had no idea what the other
teams were up to until they traveled to Plaisir, west of Paris, to
see the prototypes under construction.
</P>
<P>
   ``They deliberately kept us free to come up with what we thought
was appropriate for New York City,'' said Susan Rodriguez, a
partner in James Stewart Polshek's office. She and Gwathmey paid a
visit last month to the Astoria warehouse, where the ruby-red
digital temperature sign on the Polshek shelter was blinking
``99.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I like your seats,'' Ms. Rodriguez said, as she inspected the
neat, square panels in the cantilevered bench of the Gwathmey
Siegel shelter. ``They didn't build ours correctly.''
</P>
<P>
   ``What do you mean?'' Gwathmey asked, turning his gaze to the
Polshek shelter a few yards away, with its barrel-shaped bench
frame. ``That looks pretty cool, hanging from that pipe.'' Ms.
Rodriguez explained that what was constructed as a flat surface was
meant to be convex.
</P>
<P>
   The distinguishing feature of the Polshek line, however, was
evident: the roof structure is connected to a steel pier by
stainless-steel suspension rods, recalling building canopies and
long-necked traffic lights, as well as the great bridges of New
York.
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   ``There is a heritage of ornamental metalwork in New York,'' Ms.
Rodriguez said. ``We were trying to capture the texture and
character.'' Plus, she said, the multifaceted building elements
would discourage graffiti.
</P>
<P>
   In the spirit of Mies van der Rohe, Gwathmey Siegel used highly
articulated steel channels and angles to create crisp, spare boxes.
One practical advantage, Gwathmey said, was that structural
elements would be interchangeable from shelter to newsstand to
toilet. ``What resulted, we hope, is not a mannered structure but a
clean, receptive, accommodative and less imposing structure,'' he
said.
</P>
<P>
   Peter Eisenman took a much different tack. He proposed an
angular Moebius strip of three-eighths-inch thick steel plates, its
bench cantilevered outward and its glass windscreen tilting inward.
The design was not intended for general use, Eisenman said, but for
exceptional civic settings like the Brooklyn Public Library.
</P>
<P>
   ``We made a spatial object that was intended to cause people to
look at it and comment on bus shelters,'' he said. ``We want people
to be more aware of their physical environment, not less aware.''
</P>
<P>
   Easily the most ornate proposal was that by Robert A.M. Stern.
Painted forest green, his fixtures are framed by colonnettes with
gold bands and capitals. Clocks nestle in the eaves of the arched
roofs. The newsstand has a canopy that recalls the Art Nouveau
style of the Paris Metro and a roll-down grate on which 32 magazine
covers can be displayed when the stand is closed.
</P>
<P>
   The goal was to echo New York's rich visual mix. ``I wanted to
make a shelter that fit into that richness and was itself rich in
details and character,'' Stern said.
</P>
<P>
   In striking contrast are the snowy, planar fixtures by Vignelli
Associates, including a shelter with a transparent roof. ``What we
wanted to do was something airy, something very open and not too
enclosed,'' Massimo Vignelli said. ``We think that these little
pieces of white furniture in the context of the city will give a
dash of happiness.''
</P>
<P>
   If anyone might have been expected to gravitate to white, surely
it would have been Meier, who practically holds a trademark on
dazzling, crystalline structures. Yet his proposals for Adshel are
somber. There is the dark-gray ``Metropolitan'' line, with
extruded, channeled aluminum columns from which a tapered roof is
cantilevered, and the black ``New Amsterdam'' line, intended to
complement historic districts and nearby landmarks with its
shallow, translucent, barrel-vaulted rooftop.
</P>
<P>
   ``What we wanted was something that wasn't visually assertive
and seemed to fit naturally into the environment,'' Meier said.
``These should be apparent but not buildings unto themselves.
Therefore, whiteness didn't seem appropriate.''
</P>
<P>
   Adshel installed the Meier prototypes outdoors, on a property
near the Long Island Expressway, where it built small stretches of
sidewalk and curb as a setting. ``We wanted to see what would
happen in a New York environment,'' Feinberg said. From stains on
the pavement after a rainfall, he learned that a sliding assembly
on the newsstand was not rustproof. ``That'll never happen again,''
he said.
</P>
<P>
   Film canisters have been spotted on the other side of the
chain-link fence. ``Our competitors have been here,'' Feinberg
said, cicadas buzzing around him. ``That's flattering.'' He noted
that engineering details cannot easily be knocked off; like a
design that permits glass panels to break safely into pebbles under
high winds before the entire shelter sails away.
</P>
<P>
   Although the Meier designs would not be appropriate for Boston,
Feinberg said, they might wind up in Brisbane, Australia or
Glasgow. Adshel is a subsidiary of the More Group of Britain, which
was acquired this summer by Clear Channel Communications of San
Antonio, after a bidding war with Decaux. Adshel has more than 450
contracts, including the shelter franchise in Westchester County.
It was recently selected to provide San Francisco with news racks,
which will carry advertising.
</P>
<P>
   Wall City Design is the U.S. division of Wall Verkehrsanlagen.
Founded by Hans Wall and based in Berlin, the company holds
franchises in some 50 cities, including the recently awarded
bus-shelter contract for St. Louis. It also operates an automatic
public toilet near City Hall.
</P>
<P>
   Its architect, Kleihues, is best known in this country for the
new Museum of Contemporary Art in Chicago. He created a shelter
with gently bowed ends and also a flat-topped structure that tapers
to a point at the ends. The fixtures might be silver or, in
historic settings, forest green.
</P>
<P>
   ``If you get the right design, a modern thing doesn't look too
modern, even in a historic district in Harlem,'' said Wall City
president Douglas Watts.
</P>
<P>
   The full-scale shelter prototype cost $50,000; the newsstand
mock-up $150,000. The structures are built of steel and coated with
a baked-on, granular powder made of polymers that creates a hard,
nonporous surface from which most graffiti can be removed with
rubbing alcohol.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is the city and you don't want anything too ephemeral,''
Watts said. ``We want potential vandals to look at something and
say, `This is bigger, tougher and stronger than I am.'''
</P>
<P>
   The fourth proposal was by Transportation Displays Inc., a
division of CBS, in partnership with Cemusa of Madrid. The
architect was Nicholas Grimshaw. The company declined to show his
designs.
</P>
<P>
   Donald Allman, the chief operating officer of TDI, allowed that
the company was ``disappointed'' but added, ``Inherent in every
procurement process is that risk.''
</P>
<P>
   The citywide franchise had been championed by Deputy Mayor Fran
Reiter before she managed Mayor Rudolph Giuliani's election
campaign and then took over the New York Convention and Visitors
Bureau.
</P>
<P>
   ``There has never been a coordinated effort to say what we want
to allow or not allow, what esthetic values do we want to bring to
street furniture,'' Ms. Reiter said in 1996. ``We don't have public
toilets in New York. We have unsightly newsstands. We have bus-stop
shelters that, while functional, are not the newest generation.''
</P>
<P>
   Briefly after her departure from City Hall, the Transportation
Department conducted follow-up sessions with the bidders. But
officials never saw the prototypes, so they had no chance to
appreciate the fact that both Decaux and Wall stocked their stands
with newspapers from Nov. 5, 1997: ``Giuliani Sweeps to Second Term
as Mayor'' (The New York Times) and ``Rudy Two'' (The New York
Post).
</P>
<P>
   Then, at a news conference in January, the mayor indicated that
the plan was in trouble. ``Is there a better and more competitive
way to do it?'' he asked. For example, he wondered, should there be
several smaller contracts, broken up geographically or divided into
different types of fixtures?
</P>
<P>
   The die was all but cast. On June 26, the bidders received a
three-paragraph letter from the Transportation Department informing
them that the request for proposals for a coordinated
street-furniture franchise (No. 84197MB039AD) had been canceled.
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   Since then, an interagency task force has been looking into the
questions that Giuliani raised. ``There is no timetable but they
are actively working,'' Deputy Mayor Randy Levine said last week.
In any case, he said, the contracts that emerge ``will not be of
the magnitude of the last RFP, where one successful bidder would
have had, in effect, the entire city.''
</P>
<P>
   Giuliani is ``a strong believer that New York is very diverse
and that we shouldn't get locked into one design, one person, one
thing,'' Levine said.
</P>
<P>
   But Councilman Walter McCaffrey, the Queens Democrat who heads
the zoning and franchises subcommittee, said the legislation and
the request for proposals already accounted for the objections
raised by the mayor, since they encouraged a variety of design and
allowed for a consortium of operators rather than a single
contractor.
</P>
<P>
   ``The two reasons given for scuttling the process are without
merit,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   McCaffrey said it would be possible for two contractors to share
Manhattan and divide the four other boroughs between them. ``This
is something that could be addressed very quickly,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, he said, because of increased ridership, some bus
stops have 50 or more passengers waiting around old, leaky shelters
without benches. ``When it rains,'' McCaffrey said, ``the people
standing out there unprotected can rightly ask themselves: `Why has
the administration delayed? Why am I standing in the rain?'''
</P>
<P>
   Other cities, inspired by New York, have been faster off the
mark. San Francisco Mayor Frank Jordan was in Manhattan in 1992 for
the Democratic National Convention, when he saw the experimental
Decaux public toilet. Two years later, his administration awarded a
street-furniture contract.
</P>
<P>
   In turn, San Francisco's street furniture caught the eye of
Boston Mayor Thomas Menino when he was there last year for the
United States Conference of Mayors. Now, his administration is a
month away from issuing a request for proposals that will cover 250
to 300 shelters, 8 to 10 toilets, and multiple newspaper racks.
</P>
<P>
   This is not to say that New York has no interesting new street
furniture.
</P>
<P>
   It is hard to miss the 140 or so stainless-steel telephone
kiosks that Telebeam Telecommunications has installed around
Manhattan. Thick, tapered legs support round-edged enclosures that
are topped by curving, illuminated canopies on radial spokes. The
design is by Rudy Fabiano.
</P>
<P>
   This summer, the Grand Central Partnership and 34th Street
Partnership have erected 76 ``wayfinding'' signs, 13{ feet high,
pointing the way to the Empire State Building, Grand Central
Terminal, St. Patrick's Cathedral and other much-sought
destinations. The signs were designed by Gresham Smith &AMP; Associates
and A.M. Sign.
</P>
<P>
   Since the early '90s, the partnerships have installed hundreds
of benches, bicycle racks, news racks, street signs, planters and
trees. Because the Giuliani administration dissolved the Grand
Central Partnership last month, however, the future of the
street-furniture initiative is unclear. Daniel Biederman, president
of both partnerships, said, ``If the BID continues in some form,
it's my expectation that whoever is running it will want to
continue working with the city on these improvements.''
</P>
<P>
   The Alliance for Downtown New York, which runs the lower
Manhattan business improvement district, has embarked on a $13.5
million streetscape improvement, including specially designed
lampposts, wastebaskets, benches and a wayfinding system. This line
of furniture was designed by Cooper, Robertson &AMP; Partners and the
Pentagram Design graphics studio.
</P>
<P>
   ``The BIDs, to their credit, have delved into this area,'' said
Municipal Art Society president Brendan Sexton, ``and shown what a
difference it can make to have an inviting bench here and there, to
clean up the newsrack disaster, to have a handsome lightpole at
pedestrian height.''
</P>
<P>
   What Sexton has seen of the coordinated street-furniture designs
is enough, he said, to make his mouth water.
</P>
<P>
   ``The vendors recruited some of the best designers,'' he said.
``We absolutely must find a way to capture this work and not lose
it. And to do so now. It's a big city to furnish. We've got to get
started.''
</P>
</TEXT>
