<HEADLINE>
NON-STAR JETS STRIVE TO WIN PARCELLS' FAVOR 
</HEADLINE>
  (mk) 
 By GERALD ESKENAZI   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Coach Bill Parcells still has many questions about
the Jets' roster, most of which probably will be answered by about
midnight next Saturday. By then, the Jets will have had another
week of two-a-days and will have played their second exhibition
game, Saturday against the Baltimore Ravens.
</P>
<P>
   But several players got off to a good start in Thursday's
opening game against the Eagles in bids to either win a job or
improve their status with the team:
</P>
<P>
   ALEX VAN DYKE: He set a collegiate record for season receiving
yardage at Nevada. He came in as the Jets' second draft choice in
1996, but under the shadow of the overall No. 1 pick, Keyshawn
Johnson. After two seasons, he has just 20 receptions _ only three
of which came last season. Van Dyke knows what is at stake.
</P>
<P>
   On Thursday, he responded with four receptions for 67 yards. He
is battling the team's fastest receiver, Dedric Ward, to become the
No. 3 receiver behind Keyshawn Johnson and Wayne Chrebet.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm in that third year,'' Van Dyke said. ``I guess I've
matured a whole lot. All that time I had to sit and watch those
games, I was growing up. You learn about what you've got to do to
get onto the field.''
</P>
<P>
   He has been one of the most diligent Jets in the weight room. He
is 6 feet, 200 pounds, and Parcells said, ``He's what an NFL
receiver is supposed to look like.''
</P>
<P>
   But Van Dyke also has to prove he has improved his
concentration. ``If we need a route at 14, he runs it at 12,''
Parcells said. ``It's attention to detail.''
</P>
<P>
   DORIAN BOOSE: Usually a team's first draft pick gets attention.
Few people in New York have noticed the defensive end, though,
because he is not a first-rounder. He was the 56th player chosen
overall after the Jets yielded their first-rounder to New England
in obtaining the free agent Curtis Martin. Boose has struggled in
camp. When someone asked Parcells last week whether Boose was
injured, the coach angrily replied: ``He's not hurt. He's getting
whipped.''
</P>
<P>
   Against the Eagles' second-stringers, though, Boose was nearly
dominant. He got a sack and was credited with another on a safety.
He was constantly creating havoc. ``Bill told me: `You don't have
to be a superstar. Just be a part. Just help us get to the Super
Bowl,''' Boose said.
</P>
<P>
   Asked about the disparity between his play in the game and on
the practice field, Boose said: ``I do slack off a little bit, but
the game is serious, it's all business. I felt good about the plays
I made, but I also made a lot of mistakes. But at least the
mistakes I made weren't the same mistakes.''
</P>
<P>
   RAY LUCAS: He is hoping to become the No. 3 quarterback, and is
learning the pro trade after playing on special teams for most of
his first two seasons. Against the Eagles, he led the team on a
touchdown drive. But he also threw an interception after the Jets
got within whispering distance of the goal line.
</P>
<P>
   ``I can't tell you the thrill of what it's like getting into a
game,'' he said. ``This was huge. Huge! But then when I got to the
goal line, I did all the wrong things. No exotic snap count, no
turnovers, no sacks, no interceptions. I did them all. So I went
from a hug from Coach Parcells to getting chewed out.''
</P>
<P>
   Lucas will get another chance, but not next Saturday. It is
Chuck Clements' turn to try to put in a claim as the third-string
quarterback.
</P>
<P>
   RICHIE ANDERSON: The running back has been in a training-camp
battle with Robert Farmer as the third tailback. But Anderson
generated 66 yards on 14 attempts against the Eagles.
</P>
<P>
   ``Yes, he helped himself,'' Parcells said. ``But Richie's got to
contribute on special teams. He's not going to be the starter.''
</P>
<P>
   SCOTT FROST: The great experiment of training camp. Parcells
just loves the idea of seeing a 6-3 quarterback who hits people.
But the rookie is not leading the Nebraska Cornhuskers anymore. He
is trying to become a strong safety as well as kickoff returner. He
brought back two a total of 41 yards. ``I thought he did some
pretty good things on specials,'' Parcells said. ``I've got to play
him more in the game now. I was fairly pleased with what I saw.
This is going to be a tedious thing. I don't think you should get
your expectations too high right now.''
</P>
<P>
   NICK GALLERY: The punter who broke Reggie Roby's records at Iowa
did two very important things in his bid to unseat Brian Hansen. He
kicked every ball well _ his four punts averaged 50 yards _ and he
produced a net average of 39.2. Parcells is looking for a net of at
least 37. Hansen has never reached that net in a career dating to
1984. Gallery will get another shot against the Ravens.
</P>
<P>
   BRYAN COX: The perpetually angry _ on the field, anyway _
linebacker is out of shape after being cut by the Bears two months
ago. He has been a force, though, and will fit in somewhere. Still,
Parcells cautioned, ``I cannot emphasize too much how we're gearing
him to Sept. 6.'' That is opening day at San Francisco.
</P>
<P>
   JEROME HENDERSON: He started 14 games at free safety last year,
but is back at cornerback. Unfortunately for Henderson, Marcus
Coleman is having an outstanding camp trying to unseat Otis Smith
at right corner.
</P>
</TEXT>
