<SLUG> BC-FBN-JETS-MARTIN-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MARTIN, FORCED TO JUST SIT, STANDS SOLID WITH PARCELLS 
</HEADLINE>
   (bl)  
 By STEVE POPPER   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   HEMPSTEAD, N.Y. _ Curtis Martin stood on the sideline, in
uniform but idle, Thursday night in the New York Jets' first
preseason game. Resting a strained hamstring, Martin had nothing to
prove to himself by hurrying back and certainly nothing to prove to
coach Bill Parcells, whose relationship with him during his time in
New England is what brought him to New York.
</P>
<P>
   That made it a far cry from three years ago when he played in
his first professional game, a preseason game against the Detroit
Lions, and received his first lesson from Parcells.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was so pumped up,'' Martin said as he hurried off to get
taped before yesterday's workout. ``It was my first game, the first
time I was going to touch the ball in a real game against NFL
players. Then I got out there and I expected to carry the ball a
couple of times. He gave me the ball eight times in a row. I was
hyperventilating.''
</P>
<P>
   Parcells laughed at the memory.
</P>
<P>
   ``He was so excited about the game and now I'm running him to
death,'' Parcells said. ``It was a fake lesson, but he learned it,
that you need stamina to play in this league. I wouldn't start a
game and do that to him, but I was trying to get him to understand
what this job was going to be like. You've got to be prepared to do
this and I had to see how much he liked this.''
</P>
<P>
   A curious way to begin what is regarded as a close relationship,
but the bond was already developing between player and coach long
before that first game. The gruff and demanding head coach pushed
Martin from the start, but instead of rebelling, Martin responded.
And when Parcells left New England last year, Martin stayed one
more season and then followed. As the first restricted free agent
the Jets ever tendered an offer sheet to, he signed a six-year, $36
million contract.
</P>
<P>
   Martin has taken a slow path back from the injury this
preseason, being careful to avoid troubles like he encountered last
season when he was hampered by an abdominal muscle tear that
required off-season surgery to correct. He is expected to
participate in a full week of practice and is very likely to play
Saturday against Baltimore. There is no rush to earn the money now,
but it was not the money that made him come.
</P>
<P>
   Ask him if Parcells had an effect on his decision and he almost
jumps at the question. ``Oh definitely,'' Martin said. ``I respect
him so much. He's a man who demands what he wants, in a proper way.
I believe that that is his style of coaching and it's great for our
team.''
</P>
<P>
   While Parcells may have been testing him at the start of his
career, he did not exactly ease up on him when the season began. As
the 74th selection in the 1995 draft, Martin became the surprise of
the season when he topped the 100-yard mark rushing in his first
game, and then tied a National Football League rookie record by
passing the 100-yard plateau nine times that year.
</P>
<P>
   ``Curtis was very young when we met him,'' Parcells said. ``With
my background, where I'm from, the kid was so nice, I was almost
suspicious. People start talking to you like this where I come
from, you kind of look at them funny, like, `What's this guy want?'
But it turned that was just the way he is. I don't know why we hit
it off. I was very hard on him, but his skin was thick.''
</P>
<P>
   EXTRA POINTS
</P>
<P>
   _ The Jets waived defensive back ANTHONY MARSHALL and wide
receiver NAKIA JENKINS on Saturday, cutting the active squad to 78.
</P>
<P>
   _ Running back DUSTIN JOHNSON suffered a nondisplaced rib
fracture and will be out two-three weeks, which, combined with his
fumble Thursday, hurts his chances of sticking.
</P>
<P>
   _ The defensive lineman ERIC OGBOGU will rest for one or two
days with a stomach muscle problem. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
