<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-LA-CRUISING-ART-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
LOS ANGELES CRUISING ENTHUSIASTS GATHER, DESPITE ROADBLOCKS 
</HEADLINE>
   (ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients. Non-subscribers
can make individual purchase by calling 212-556-4204.)  
(js) 
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ From the morning at church to the afternoon
barbecue of ribs, chicken and shish kebabs, Reginald Washington's
entire day has led up to this singular Sunday ritual, the cruise.
</P>
<P>
   Washington's car, a blue and beige Ford Bronco with gleaming mag
wheels and tinted windows, was washed and waxed in the morning. And
before he meets up with fellow members of the Hustler Nation car
club in the afternoon to caravan to the cruise, he polishes the
tires and knocks the dust off.
</P>
<P>
   As the crown jewel of the urban social scene, the cruise draws
parents and children, blacks and Latinos, teachers and students,
and gang members who set aside their rivalries for a day to
celebrate cars in the capital of car culture.
</P>
<P>
   But Washington will not be cruising the south Los Angeles
hallmark spot, Crenshaw Boulevard, glorified by the movie ``Boyz N
the Hood'' and rap music videos. Instead, he is in the parking lot
of a social services building more than 60 blocks to the south. As
with the earlier, great cruising scenes of Hollywood, the San
Fernando Valley and East Los Angeles, the authorities are cracking
down on cruising Crenshaw, remembered by one lowriding historian as
the last cruise in Los Angeles. About the only cars cruising there
now on Sunday nights are black and white, with the word ``police''
on the side.
</P>
<P>
   The Academy of Motion Picture Arts and Sciences held a 25th
anniversary party last month for ``American Graffiti,'' a
celebration of cruising and coming of age. But some Crenshaw
residents and business owners do not share the enthusiasm for the
movies' real-life counterpart, disliking the noise, the traffic and
the reputation that cruisers say is undeserved as a draw for crime.
</P>
<P>
   The police have been trying to rid Crenshaw of cruisers for at
least the last two years. It has become virtually impossible to
cruise because the police have been pulling over drivers on
Crenshaw on Sunday nights for the slightest infractions.
</P>
<P>
   But cruising endures, as best it can, by becoming more a park
than a cruise, though it moves to a nearby intersection after dark.
</P>
<P>
   Mark Ridley-Thomas, a councilman whose district includes part of
Crenshaw Boulevard, said residents in the area ``have been
pleading'' for a stronger police presence to rid the boulevard of
cruisers, citing the mess that is made on Crenshaw and in the
surrounding residential areas.
</P>
<P>
   Once he arrives at the parking lot, Washington, 29, known to
friends as Double R, and his friend, Roderick Davis, survey the
scene: muscular rap beats boom from car stereos to compete with the
busy strains of salsa as hundreds of people pass the late afternoon
into the evening flossing _ showing off _ their cars, flirting,
catching up with friends and sipping Corona beer. With the drifting
scent of marijuana in the air, some bet on dice games and hop
competitions, seeing which cars, powered by trunks full of
batteries and hydraulic suspensions, can bounce the highest.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's just about cruising,'' Washington said. ``It's
California. California swinging.''
</P>
<P>
   Losing Crenshaw disappoints Mary Sneed, a 60-year-old retired
collection agency worker better known as Moms. She has been
cruising since she was a member of the Lowriding Mamas of Compton
three decades ago. She said cruising was a positive way for young
people to channel their energy.
</P>
</TEXT>
