<SLUG> BC-OUTDOORS-COLUMN-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
COLUMN: FRUSTRATION IN NEW BRUNSWICK 
</HEADLINE>
  (mk) 
 By NELSON BRYANT   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   DAWSONVILLE, New Brunswick _ The afternoon darkened as
thunderheads moved in from the west, lightning crackled, a sudden
stiff breeze swept up the steep valley of the Upsalquitch River and
in a matter of minutes I was fishing in torrents of rain, rain so
heavy that it was difficult to cast a long line.
</P>
<P>
   Neither my guide, Gerry Thomas, nor I made any suggestion about
going ashore to huddle under a tarp or to return to Two Brooks
camp. We were engaged in a final effort to catch an Atlantic
salmon, a goal that had eluded us for four days.
</P>
<P>
   There were salmon in our stretch of the river, although not as
many as the previous week. Five days before our group _ the others
were Joan Wulff, Marian Heiskell, Kathryn Fuller, Peter Maas and
our hosts, Joseph Cullman III and his wife, Joan _ had landed at
the Charlo airport in New Brunswick. We were greeted by Joe's
nephew, Edgar Cullman Jr., and his group, who had just come from
several days of superb salmon angling at Two Brooks camp on the
Upsalquitch. When we arrived, both the Restigouche and the
Upsalquitch, its tributary, had risen three feet. In spite of the
high water, we all fished from Joe Cullman's Runnymeade Lodge on
the Restigouche that night.
</P>
<P>
   Sharing a canoe with Joe, Kathryn Fuller had just begun to cast
when a grilse seized her offering, cavorted about and escaped. (A
grilse is a salmon that returns to its natal stream after only one
year at sea. The average size is about four pounds.) Joe then
caught a grilse and lost two other fish. The rest of us did
nothing.
</P>
<P>
   On the flight to New Brunswick, I had told Joe Cullman that I
intended to release all the fish I caught. This was a big
commitment for one who has always regarded the angling experience
as incomplete without bringing home a fish for the table. To angle
solely for the pleasure of outwitting one's prey has always seemed
to me to be effete, leaving no room for a token food-gathering
ritual.
</P>
<P>
   I went to be with good friends and to once again visit the
Upsalquitch, an intimate river of infinite charm. Lacking humility,
it never occurred to me that I might fail to release fish because I
could not catch them. My decision had been prompted by the parlous
state of North American stocks of the species, which are at their
lowest, so low that all commercial netting of salmon has been
halted and the recreational fishing limits severely curtailed.
</P>
<P>
   In New Brunswick, all adult salmon must be released; the daily
limit is one grilse, and one must stop fishing after a grilse has
been killed. One must also stop after two fish, grilse or salmon,
or both, have been set free.
</P>
<P>
   As the days went by _ I spent most of them at Two Brooks _ a
pattern began to develop. Fishing pools that I had flogged only a
few hours before with no success, the other members of the group
consistently caught grilse or salmon. When this happened with Joan
Wulff I was not distressed. An accomplished salmon fisher, former
champion fly-caster and widow of the legendary Lee Wulff, she
possessed, I knew, more salmon fishing savvy than I.
</P>
<P>
   Peter Maas was another matter. Although he fishes with a fly rod
infrequently, he has a knack for encountering salmon that are
willing to take. Maas caught a salmon and a grilse our first day at
Two Brooks, and when I returned the following evening his canoe was
already at the dock. Climbing the steep steps to the camp, I peered
inside, beheld Peter sitting at the writing desk in the cavernous
main room, and was smitten with envy. On the desk is the camp's
angling log in which guests record their catches. Peter, I knew,
had gone with the camp's manager, Lee Marshall, to the very spot
where I had raised a fish that morning.
</P>
<P>
   An author with an investigative bent, Maas could have been
checking the log for the catches of others in previous weeks, but
there was an air of triumph about him. He was logging in a
12-pounder that he had taken on a Black Dose.
</P>
<P>
   In nearly 20 years of fishing at Two Brooks and Runnymeade, I
had never failed to bring salmon home. Now, I was unable to catch
one in order to let it go.
</P>
<P>
   On one of my Two Brooks mornings, Joe Cullman and I went out in
the same canoe with Gerry. Joe refused to fish. ``We've got to get
you a salmon,'' he said. ``I'm just an observer.'' On that
occasion, I rose and pricked a fish that would not rise again.
</P>
<P>
   That afternoon, Kathryn Fuller joined Gerry and me. We went to
the lower end of the Two Brooks waters at Rock Pool where Joan
Wulff had taken two grilse the evening before. I predicted to
Kathryn that we would be successful, but failed to take into
consideration the pall of failure that came with me.
</P>
<P>
   We raised nothing and saw one fish, a grilse that disdainfully
broke water three feet from the canoe. Kathryn didn't seem to mind.
As president of the World Wildlife Fund, she has little time for
fishing and was happy for the chance to sharpen her fly-casting
skills. She returned to Runnymeade and, free of my influence,
promptly caught a 17-pounder, the largest salmon taken by anyone on
our trip.
</P>
<P>
   On our last evening together after the tempest abated, Gerry and
I visited most of the Two Brooks pools. When it became too dark to
see well enough to change flies we headed back to camp through
swirling skeins of mist having failed to raise or see a single
salmon.
</P>
<P>
   I later learned that Bill Taylor, president of the Atlantic
Salmon Federation, caught a grilse on his second cast at Two Brooks
the following morning and his wife, Suzanne, caught a salmon and a
grilse in her first half-hour of fishing.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-08-08-98 1724EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
