u f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CALIF-REAL-768&AMP;ADD-NY     08-08 1224
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CALIF-REAL-768&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
THE ART OF MAKING A HOUSE APPEAR SELLABLE 
</HEADLINE>
  (kd) 
 By VERNE G. KOPYTOFF   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service  
<TEXT>
<P>
   ORINDA, Calif. _ It was obvious that the shag carpeting had to
go if the luxury hillside home was to sell for the maximum price
possible. But probably few people would have thought to replace the
dark-colored bedspreads with lighter-colored linens, hide a
shelf-full of liquor bottles and remove personal photographs from
the family-room wall.
</P>
<P>
   These were just some of the ideas that Jenifer Brunk and her
partner, Gray Hynes, noted while touring a very-1960s-era home that
they were preparing for resale after its owner, an elderly widow,
had died. In their experience, many potential home buyers like
luminous bedrooms, look poorly upon alcohol and are distracted by
personal photographs.
</P>
<P>
   Such are the considerations of professional stagers like Ms.
Brunk and Ms. Hynes, whose business, Improve to Move, based in this
wealthy community 25 miles east of San Francisco, is to decorate
houses that are about to be offered for sale. Hired to accentuate a
home's value, stagers often violate traditional interior-design
rules to emphasize the positives of a house in a style that keeps
potential buyers focused on the space and not the furnishings.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have our work cut out for us,'' said Ms. Brunk, after
walking through the house and deciding to repaint, remove dated
wallpaper and replace unattractive furniture with rented pieces.
``If you leave the house like this, your asking price is going to
be less and the time on the market is going to be more.''
</P>
<P>
   Staging exists in several cities around the country such as
Washington, Los Angeles Miami and some New York City suburbs, Here,
the service is generally performed in upper-middle-class and
wealthy neighborhoods where homes sell for at least $400,000.
</P>
<P>
   The cost of staging to a homeowner varies depending on the
amount of work. A consultation, in which a stager walks through a
home and offers advice, can cost as little as $200, while hiring a
stager to manage a miniature remodeling and furniture overhaul can
exceed $50,000.
</P>
<P>
   Lonna Trosclair, who owns a hillside home in Oakland, hired a
stager earlier this year partly because her house, with four
bedrooms, three baths and a basement apartment, was far larger than
those of her neighbors. Potential buyers who compared the price of
her ranch to others in the area, she worried, might mistakenly
believe they were getting a bad deal. In the end, the stager put
dishes and a pasta-sauce bottle on the basement unit's kitchen
table so that the apartment would have a lived-in look. In the
living room, the stager thinned out the furniture, installed rented
neutral-colored chairs that would appeal to a broad public, and
placed the couch facing the window to emphasize the glorious view
of the city and San Francisco Bay.
</P>
<P>
   ``I let her put away furnishings that were my favorites,'' said
Ms. Trosclair, whose home sold after 10 days on the market for the
full asking price of $670,000. ``You just have to have faith.''
</P>
<P>
   Of course, informing a homeowner that some of the decor should
be removed requires diplomacy. If done incorrectly, some homeowners
can feel insulted by the implication that they have bad taste.
</P>
<P>
   Some furnishings that are almost always removed include stuffed
animal heads, guns and art with nudity that some potential buyers
may find offensive. Stagers also recommend that homeowners put away
personal possessions like family photographs and portrait paintings
that may draw attention from the house.
</P>
<P>
   ``When I'm talking to a client, I don't say `Get rid of all this
clutter,' '' said Stephanie Biorn, a stager from Palo Alto.
``That's too harsh. What I tell my clients is that you live in a
home much differently than how you should sell it. So we move out a
lot of the furniture and provide a neutral background to show off
the space.''
</P>
<P>
   There are also cases when stagers conceal the negative. For
example, Ms. Brunk and Ms. Hynes suggested putting away a portable
microwave in the house that they toured recently because it would
remind potential buyers that the kitchen did not have a built-in
one.
</P>
<P>
   In another house that they had already staged, the two women had
placed a potted plant in front of a patched hole in the wall that
had yet to be painted.
</P>
<P>
   Stagers also frequently decorate empty houses _ usually just the
public areas and master bedroom _ when the owners have moved out.
The same is usually true when they decorate a model home for a
developer. The theory is that most potential buyers have
difficultly imagining their possessions in an empty room.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE _ OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   Traditionally, real estate agents have been the ones who offered
clients basic advice about decorating a house for sale. Now, some
real estate agents refer their clients to stagers instead for more
sophisticated evaluations.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think it is the best money a seller can spend,'' said Malin
Giddings, a real estate broker at Tri Coldwell Banker in San
Francisco who specializes in luxury homes. ``If a homeowner is
going to retire and this is their last big sale, then I make a very
strong presentation for them to use a stager.''
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Giddings said that most homes could use at least a little
staging before going on the market, even those originally decorated
by an interior designer. She believes so much in the benefits of
staging that she said ``it is a crime'' for real estate agents not
to inform clients about seeking professional decoration advice.
</P>
<P>
   How much impact staging can have on the sale of a home is
difficult to determine. Obviously a clean, attractive house that
does not require repairs is going to impress potential buyers more
than one with chipped paint and grime.
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Trosclair, who sold her home in Oakland, was generally
positive about hiring a stager and said she would do it again.
</P>
<P>
   ``You never know that it is worth it,'' she said. ``But the
results were certainly good.''
</P>
<P>
   If a staged house sells quickly, homeowners must still pay the
entire term of a furniture-rental contract, typically carrying a
minimum two-month term.
</P>
<P>
   Many stagers caution homeowners against having unrealistic
expectations of enrichment if they choose to stage their house.
Moreover, homeowners are not guaranteed a dollar-for-dollar return
on their investment in staging.
</P>
<P>
   ``People have this misconception that if you stage a home well
it will give you $100,000 more,'' said Carla Karsant, a stager from
Oakland. ``There are a lot of things that have to come together to
make staging a home successful.''
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, some staged houses do not sell at all. In such cases,
stagers typically lay the blame on factors that are outside their
control. For example, one stager told of a hillside home that did
not sell because of building-code problems and a multi-level design
that required walking up a lot of stairs. Another stager told of a
house with a horse stable that was too customized to appeal to a
broad public.
</P>
<P>
   Then there is the fundamental problem of price, said Claudia
Ellinghaus, owner of Escrow Garden and Staging in Oakland. No
matter how attractive a home looks, she said, ``if it is grossly
overpriced, staging isn't going to do a thing.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
