<SLUG> BC-DEATH-LAWSUIT-KAN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WIDOW WHOSE HUSBAND DIED AMID SERIES OF PATIENT DEATHS AWARDED
$450,000 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By WILL SENTELL  
 c. 1998 Kansas City Star  
<TEXT>
<P>
   COLUMBIA, Mo. _ A widow was awarded $450,000 Friday by a federal
judge who said officials at a Columbia hospital failed to ensure
her husband's safety amid a series of mysterious patient deaths.
</P>
<P>
   U.S. District Judge Nanette K. Laughrey ruled officials at
Truman Memorial Veterans Hospital were negligent in the 1992 death
of Elzie Havrum.
</P>
<P>
   His wife, Helen, filed the wrongful death lawsuit.
</P>
<P>
   Helen Havrum and several family members in the courtroom wept
for several minutes after Laughrey announced her ruling.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are just kind of in shock,'' son Gary Havrum of Fulton said
in a telephone interview later.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are just reflecting on this situation,'' he said. ``It's
just been a very stressful period of time.''
</P>
<P>
   Laughrey said hospital officials didn't take adequate
precautions even though staff members noticed a pattern of
unexplained deaths in spring 1992 in Ward Four East, especially
when nurse Richard A. Williams was on duty. Havrum died in the same
ward while Williams was working.
</P>
<P>
   ``At a minimum, given what was at stake, the VA was negligent,''
Laughrey said from the bench after a two-week trial.
</P>
<P>
   Hospital officials could have taken Williams off the night
shift, provided another employee to work with him or taken other
steps in reaction to the mysterious pattern of patient deaths, she
said.
</P>
<P>
   ``The first and foremost concern should be patient care, not
Richard Williams,'' the judge said.
</P>
<P>
   Laughrey said a ``preponderance of the evidence'' in the civil
lawsuit made her believe Williams was responsible for Havrum's
death.
</P>
<P>
   When asked about the trial's outcome Friday, Williams said by
telephone from St. Louis, ``I have no comment.''
</P>
<P>
   Williams, who now lives in the St. Louis area, told a reporter
in the past that he ``didn't become a nurse to mercy kill or to
determine when someone would die.''
</P>
<P>
   Gary L. Campbell, director of the hospital, said in a prepared
statement that hospital officials hoped the ruling ``will be able
to bring closure to this situation.''
</P>
<P>
   Elzie Havrum died at 66 after being admitted for shortness of
breath.
</P>
<P>
   Helen Havrum said that although she first thought her husband
died of natural causes, by fall 1992 she had heard reports of a
high rate of deaths in Ward Four East.
</P>
<P>
   For five years, the FBI investigated the rash of deaths at the
veterans hospital. Of the 55 persons who died between March and
August 1992, 45 died while Williams was on duty. A doctor's
analysis had shown that patients were 10 times more likely to die
under Williams' care.
</P>
<P>
   But earlier this year, the FBI said it could not prove a crime.
</P>
<P>
   Havrum's case marked the first time that any of the deaths at
the veterans hospital have been aired in a courtroom. But no one
would speculate Friday on whether her case would prompt more civil
lawsuits.
</P>
<P>
   Stephen Hill, U.S. attorney for the Western District of
Missouri, said no decision has been made on whether government
attorneys will appeal the ruling. Hill said he thought government
attorneys showed Williams was not responsible for Havrum's death
and that Havrum did not die by a codeine overdose, as Helen Havrum
alleged.
</P>
<P>
   Despite Laughrey's comments, the federal statute of limitations
prevents a new federal look at any role Williams might have had in
the deaths, Hill said.
</P>
<P>
   And it's unlikely the case will prompt criminal charges. Boone
County Prosecutor Kevin Crane said Friday that he has no plans for
the case.
</P>
<P>
   Criminal cases require more stringent proof than civil cases.
</P>
<P>
   Laughrey's conclusion that Williams appeared responsible for
Havrum's death ``would not equip me with any more evidence in a
criminal case than I had before she made the decision,'' Crane
said.
</P>
<P>
   During closing arguments, attorneys representing the hospital
disputed Havrum's claim that her husband died from a codeine
overdose. James C. Bohling, an assistant U.S. attorney, said that
lawyers for Havrum failed to prove that codeine killed her husband.
</P>
<P>
   ``This again is speculation,'' Bohling said. ``Speculation is
not evidence.''
</P>
<P>
   Hospital officials carefully reviewed patient deaths and
``nothing was picked up,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   ``Those individual cases were not considered to be remarkable,''
Bohling said. ``Each of those was considered by a physician to be a
reasonable death.''
</P>
<P>
   He added, ``I think it is clear from the evidence that this
hospital did its job.''
</P>
<P>
   But John Kurtz of Kansas City, Havrum's chief attorney, said FBI
officials concluded in a report that ``concentrations of codeine
found were at the lower end of the fatal range.''
</P>
<P>
   Laughrey said she believes Havrum had more codeine in his body
than from just taking a few Tylenol 3 tablets.
</P>
<P>
   Kurtz also dismissed government arguments that hospital
officials imposed rigorous quality controls over hospital
operations.
</P>
<P>
   ``Murderers kind of deviate from standard procedures,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Laughrey ruled in favor of the government on Havrum's claims of
medical malpractice, saying they were filed too late and were not
proven.
</P>
<P>
   Gordon Christensen, a doctor at the veterans hospital who called
public attention to the series of deaths, said he was pleased with
the trial's outcome.
</P>
<P>
   ``To my mind the only right answer is to do exactly what she
did,'' he said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
