<SLUG> BC-BOMBING-VICTIM-KAN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MISSOURI COUPLE REMEMBER SON WHO DIED IN KENYAN BOMBING 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By MATTHEW SCHOFIELD  
 c. 1998 Kansas City Star  
<TEXT>
<P>
   UNDATED: When Bonnie Hobson learned early Friday that a
terrorist bomb half a world away had killed her only child, she
couldn't help but think back to the note.
</P>
<P>
   It arrived at Hobson's home in Lamar in southwest Missouri no
more than a week ago by electronic mail. Her son, Sgt. Kenneth R.
Hobson II, 27, had been stationed in Nairobi, Kenya, since early
April. The note was happy, joyous. And it left her without worries
for his well-being.
</P>
<P>
   Sure, he was a career soldier with the Army, and that can always
mean danger. He'd been in the Persian Gulf War as an engineer.
</P>
<P>
   But he'd joined intending to get a college degree and retire in
20 years. These days he was the equivalent of an office manager at
the U.S. Embassy in Nairobi. His duties were to understand the
labyrinthine world of military forms, to know immediately which
forms went with which occasions. He filed and sorted and kept the
office running.
</P>
<P>
   It was a safe job and a good fit for him, his mother thought.
Sgt. Hobson was not at all the kind who lived for danger, who would
take silly risks.
</P>
<P>
   He was a thinker.
</P>
<P>
   In high school in Nevada, Mo., when other boys played football
and basketball, he lived to play tennis and to debate issues. Above
all, he loved to pick a topic and argue it.
</P>
<P>
   ``His favorite debate was always the one he had going,'' Bonnie
Hobson recalled Friday afternoon. ``He was happiest when he had a
good argument going. He was a real brain child.''
</P>
<P>
   His high school speech teacher, Tim Gore, remembered him as a
mature, thoughtful young man.
</P>
<P>
   ``He was a good student,'' he recalled. ``He'd stand his ground
when making a point, but he was never one to cause trouble. He was
one to mull over a topic, to analyze it and think hard before
reaching a conclusion.''
</P>
<P>
   In addition, his mother remembered his artwork, much of which is
still around the house.
</P>
<P>
   ``Oh, he could pick anything he wanted and draw it,'' she said.
``He was wonderful.''
</P>
<P>
   In part, it was that intellectual curiosity that convinced him
to join the Army after graduating from high school in 1989. He
wanted to travel, to see the world.
</P>
<P>
   ``When they finally called him and told him where he could go,
they offered him three places,'' she recalled. ``I can't even
remember the other two, but he said he wouldn't consider them, that
the other two were not places to raise a family.''
</P>
<P>
   Kenya wasn't perfect, but he was excited about it, she said.
</P>
<P>
   And when she took her last look at him, an electronic image he'd
sent with his note recently, he still looked happy.
</P>
<P>
   The contents of the note were simple. During some a recent time
off, he, his wife, Deborah, and their toddler daughter, Megan, went
on a walking safari in the Kenyan countryside. The highlight was
the wildlife, especially seeing honest-to-goodness giraffes. The
electronic photograph showed the family and the giraffes.
</P>
<P>
   Bonnie Hobson said it was hard to believe a life that seemed to
be going so well could be over so quickly.
</P>
<P>
   She said she didn't know what came next. When will his widow and
child arrive back in the United States? When will his remains be
sent back? What she should do about funeral arrangements?
</P>
<P>
   Her husband, Kenneth Hobson Sr., told The Associated Press he
was angry about his son's death, about the fact that terrorists
were able to get to another American embassy.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is going to keep going on constantly,'' he said.
``They're not going to stop this.''
</P>
<P>
   He also said that eventually his son's ashes would be scattered
over the Pacific Ocean off the coast of Big Sur, where he met
Deborah.
</P>
<P>
   ``He was adamant about that,'' his father said. ``If anything
happened to him, that's what he wanted.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
