<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-08-08 17:34 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4523 &Cx1f; kan-z
r a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BREAST-CANCER-2TAKES-     08-08 1003
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BREAST-CANCER-2TAKES-KAN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ATTITUDES ABOUT BREAST CANCER HAVE COME A LONG WAY IN 15 YEARS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By DIANE CARROLL  
 c. 1998 Kansas City Star  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LEAWOOD, Kan. _ Fifteen years ago few people talked publicly
about breast cancer. After all, that would have forced them to say
the word ``breast,'' and that was just too embarrassing.
</P>
<P>
   Even eight years ago, when Christine Brunswick was diagnosed
with the disease, attitudes hadn't changed much.
</P>
<P>
   Women were dying, but no one seemed to notice.
</P>
<P>
   Brunswick was aghast.
</P>
<P>
   ``The drugs I received were the same ones women had received 15
years earlier,'' said Brunswick, now vice president of the National
Breast Cancer Coalition in Washington. ``I said, `Wait a minute. We
haven't gotten any further than that?'''
</P>
<P>
   Today, though, progress is clear.
</P>
<P>
   Federal funding to fight breast cancer has increased 600 percent
since 1991, when the coalition formed and began demanding more
money from Congress.
</P>
<P>
   And the number of people participating in the National Race for
the Cure Series _ a private fund-raiser _ has increased almost
tenfold this decade, to about 500,000 this year.
</P>
<P>
   Attitudes about breast cancer also have turned around.
</P>
<P>
   ``If you go back five or even 10 and certainly 15 years ago, you
couldn't talk about it to anyone,'' said Mary Putnam, chairwoman of
Kansas City's fifth annual Race for the Cure, which was held Aug. 9
in Leawood.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was like a female disease...that you had to keep in the
closet. Now you don't.''
</P>
<P>
   One of the early leaders in the cause was Nancy Goodman Brinker.
</P>
<P>
   In 1982, Brinker started the Susan G. Komen Breast Cancer
Foundation in Dallas in memory of her older sister. Komen died in
1980 at age 33, leaving a husband and two children in Peoria, Ill.
</P>
<P>
   In an interview this week from Dallas, Brinker recalled a
conversation with her sister a month before she died.
</P>
<P>
   ``She looked at me one night and said, `Isn't this awful?'
</P>
<P>
   ``I said `Yes.'
</P>
<P>
   ``She said, `When I get better, I want you to help me do
something so other women and their families don't have to go
through this.' &UR; ''
</P>
<P>
   At that moment, Brinker said, she decided to spend the rest of
her life working toward a cure.
</P>
<P>
   The breast is the leading cancer site among American women, and
breast cancer is second only to lung cancer in cancer deaths. It is
the leading cause of death for women ages 35 to 54. About 44,000
women and 300 men are dying each year of the disease, a number that
has dipped slightly this decade because of early detection.
</P>
<P>
   In the 10 years that the U.S. was fighting the Vietnam War,
58,000 men and women died in the fighting. In the same period,
breast cancer killed 330,000 women, according to information from
the Komen Foundation.
</P>
<P>
   Brinker put her foundation together with $200 in grocery money
and a shoe box full of names of people to contact for
contributions.
</P>
<P>
   ``I would go to corporations to raise money, and they would
blush,'' she said. ``It was a time when you realized, `My gosh, we
can't even talk about this.' Literally, people would not be
responsive.''
</P>
<P>
   Brinker came up with the idea for the Race for the Cure to
benefit her foundation. The first 5-kilometer, or 3.1-mile,
walk-run took place in Dallas in 1983 with 800 participants. This
year the combination 5-K race and 1-mile walk-run is being held in
86 cities; 500,000 participants are expected.
</P>
<P>
   ``Everyone told me it (the race) was crazy, that it wouldn't
work,'' Brinker said. ``But I thought it would be good to do a
sporting event so survivors could bond and see there is hope.''
</P>
<P>
   The race brought in $23 million in 1996, the latest year for
which figures are available. Seventy-five percent of the revenue
raised stays in the cities in which the races are held; the rest
goes to the foundation for research and other advances.
</P>
<P>
   The foundation, which has raised more than $100 million since it
was formed, is growing at an amazing rate, Brinker said.
</P>
<P>
   The Komen Foundation, as well as grass-roots organizations such
as the National Breast Cancer Coalition, gave the breast cancer
movement its start, said Pamela Dougherty, legislative
representative for the American Cancer Society's governmental
relations office in Washington.
</P>
<P>
   The coalition got the attention of Congress, Dougherty said.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was a group of women not willing to be pushed or kept in
the closet any longer,'' Brunswick said. ``We were out there
demanding more money for breast cancer research, and that had never
been done before. Nobody had actually gone up to the U.S. Congress
and sat in front of them.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think we put a face to the disease.''
</P>
<P>
   Kansas City, Mo., has had its own triumphs with the Race for the
Cure, which began here in 1994.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was really more successful than we ever expected it to be
right out of the chute,'' said Paula Porsch, one of three women who
got the race off the ground. ``It's phenomenal, the numbers they
are expecting this year.''
</P>
<P>
   Organizers say they are ready to handle many more participants
than the 5,600 they had last year.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our goal had been 7,500, but given the way the race has been
exploding around the country, we're planning for 9,000,'' Putnam
said. The number of participants in the June race in Washington,
for instance, increased 44 percent, statistics from the Komen
Foundation show.
</P>
<P>
   The races are growing because of people like Sharon Snowden of
Kansas City.
</P>
<P>
   This is the third year the 34-year-old breast cancer survivor
will participate. Snowden has beaten breast cancer twice, she said,
and wants to do what she can to make others aware of the importance
of early detection.
</P>
<P>
   She'll be at the finish line, timing the racers who care about
how fast they complete the race.
</P>
<P>
   About 500 of this year's participants are expected to be
survivors, visible in pink T-shirts and pink visors. Some of them,
such as Donna Valponi Brookhart, are in the midst of battling their
disease now. MORE
</P>
<P>
   LEAWOOD, Kan. _ their disease now.
</P>
<P>
   Brookhart is chairwoman of the race's survivors committee. She
took the post in 1997, after she had beaten the disease once. This
spring her breast cancer recurred. She had a mastectomy June 4 and
started chemotherapy July 10. Last weekend she attended Kansas
City's first breast cancer survivors luncheon, which she helped
organize.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm doing great,'' Brookhart said. ``I think it's important
for survivors to go to the race, to go to the luncheon and take
advantage of these opportunities so we can celebrate life together.
</P>
<P>
   ``There are still a lot of messages in our society that say if
you have cancer, you can't survive.''
</P>
<P>
   That's not true, she said, and survivors need to keep reminding
one another of that.
</P>
<P>
   When breast cancer is confined to the breast, the five-year
survival rate is more than 95 percent. The rate drops
significantly, though, when the cancer spreads beyond the breast.
</P>
<P>
   The drugs being developed now to fight breast cancer are
encouraging, those in the fight said, but a cure still seems far
away. That's why they keep talking about early detection.
</P>
<P>
   ``So many of us, even though we know we should be doing monthly
self-breast exams, don't do them,'' Putnam said. ``And that is the
key.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-08-08-98 1734EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
