<DOCNO> NYT19980808.0144 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-08-08 17:35 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4525 &Cx1f; kan-z
r f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-HEASTER-COLUMN-KAN &LR;      08-08 0599
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HEASTER-COLUMN-KAN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ARGUMENTS FOR TAX RELIEF ARE GROWING STRONGER 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JERRY HEASTER  
 c. 1998 Kansas City Star  
<TEXT>
<P>
   UNDATED: The best arguments for a tax cut are decelerating U.S.
growth, stock market uncertainty and global economic problems.
</P>
<P>
   Although the catalyst for tax-cut initiatives has been the
promise of substantial federal budget surpluses, tax relief would
be justified in any event.
</P>
<P>
   The latest Gross Domestic Product estimate showed the annual
rate of economic growth plunging from 5.5 percent in the first
quarter to 1.4 percent during the April-June period. Some
economists have begun to warn that a recession is possible in the
second half of the year, with a recession defined as two
consecutive quarters of GDP shrinkage.
</P>
<P>
   The stock market began to anticipate the growth slowdown
signaled by the preliminary second-quarter GDP report after topping
out at record levels July 17. Since then the stock market has been
poleaxed by earnings disappointments, recession talk and cautionary
congressional testimony by Federal Reserve Chairman Alan Greenspan.
</P>
<P>
   While the stock market's correction isn't an altogether bad
thing and has been expected and predicted, fiscal stimulus for the
economy in the form of a tax cut is more than justified. This holds
despite Greenspan's misgivings about healthy growth's potential for
reigniting an inflationary surge.
</P>
<P>
   Michael Schuyler, senior economist at the Institute for Research
on the Economics of Taxation, suggests that using the surplus to
finance a tax cut is preferable to paying down the national debt. A
properly designed tax cut, he said in a recent ``Congressional
Advisory,'' could both extend and rejuvenate the current economic
expansion and boost individual incomes while encouraging savings
and investment.
</P>
<P>
   The key, he indicated, is getting the surplus back into the
hands of individuals who will use the money to consume and save.
Paying down the debt might achieve the same result, but the
probability of this happening is not nearly as certain if
Washington keeps control of the money.
</P>
<P>
   The Capitol Hill focus is on House Speaker Newt Gingrich, Budget
Chairman John Kasich and Ways and Means Chairman Bill Archer, who
are the main players. The numbers being bandied about are huge in
absolute terms, but not nearly as impressive when considered as a
percentage of total federal revenue over a decade of projected
surpluses.
</P>
<P>
   To the extent hundreds of billions worth of proposed tax cuts
could extend the economic expansion, it would be healthy not only
for Americans but also for the rest of the world. Over the next few
years, most of the world's economic fortunes will be heavily
dependent on U.S. prosperity. The Asian crisis won't begin to
improve until Japan works out at least some of its financial system
problems, which will be at least a couple of years.
</P>
<P>
   On the other side of the world, next year's introduction of
Europe's common currency, the euro, promises a prolonged period of
adjustment that can be expected to slow growth on the continent.
This also will have the effect of making a continued strong U.S.
economy critical to Europe getting through its monetary system
changes with a minimum of turmoil.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, there is also the specter of the economic drag some
analysts say will result from computer glitches when 2000 arrives.
How severe the so-called Y2K problem will be is anybody's guess,
but it almost certainly will create some temporary interruptions in
the flow of both U.S. and global commerce.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
