<SLUG> BC-JJ-WHALE-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DIEHARDS CLING TO J.J.
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
BY BROOKE OLSON  
 c.1998 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ Sea World has given up.
</P>
<P>
   The Coast Guard has all but given up.
</P>
<P>
   The marine biologists have given up.
</P>
<P>
   The orphaned gray whale, J.J., has fallen off nearly everyone's
radar since she ditched her tracking transmitters within a week of
her March release.
</P>
<P>
   Nearly everyone, that is, except a small legion of whale
watchers sailing up and down the California coast looking for the
mischievous whale.
</P>
<P>
   ``We keep a close eye out for her _ we have pictures up in the
boats and we would assume J.J. would be a very friendly whale,''
said Don Hedden, better known as Captain Don. ``If we ever saw her,
we'd shut down the boat and see if she'd come over to us.''
</P>
<P>
   Captain Don runs daily excursions to the Channel Islands from
Santa Barbara's Stearns Wharf in search of J.J. and other whales.
</P>
<P>
   J.J. gained fame when she became stranded about 1 1/2 years ago
near Venice Beach but was rescued and nursed back to health at Sea
World. In March, she was released into the Pacific Ocean off San
Diego Bay.
</P>
<P>
   At one point, J.J. grabbed daily headlines and potential
sightings were posted on a J.J. Web site on the Internet. J.J.'s
site hasn't been updated since April 3 and Sea World officials are
at a loss to recall when they last heard news of the whale they
miraculously nursed back to health last year.
</P>
<P>
   ``I get e-mail, I get phone calls, I get letters just about
every day,'' said Keith Yip, Sea World's general curator who
oversaw J.J.'s recovery.
</P>
<P>
   ``But I really have no idea where she is _ none of the sightings
have ever been confirmed and it's a big, big ocean out there,'' he
said.
</P>
<P>
   That's not stopping people like George and Veronica Erter, who
are spending their summer aboard different whale watching vessels
along the Pacific Coast.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a needle in a haystack _ that's for sure,'' said
Veronica. ``We love looking at all the marine mammals and think
that we may just get a glimpse of J.J.''
</P>
<P>
   The Erters, both high school teachers in Salem, Ore., share the
passion for J.J. ``My wife and I have this intense fascination with
the whale,'' George Erter said.
</P>
<P>
   Sightings of mammoth blue whales have been a nice diversion for
the Erters, but for them, J.J. is the primary focus of the search.
</P>
<P>
   ``You never know,'' George Erter said, with a smile. ``It may
just happen.''
</P>
<P>
   X X X
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-08-08-98 1816EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
