<DOCNO> NYT19980808.0148 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-08-08 18:16 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4537 &Cx1f; ttc-z
r a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BLUE-WHALES-LADN     08-08 0547
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BLUE-WHALES-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
EARTH'S LARGEST MAMMELS ENJOY SUMMER OFF CALIFORNIA COAST
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
BY BROOKE OLSON  
 c.1998 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ It has the heart the size of a Volkswagen Bug. Its
tongue is heavier than an African elephant.
</P>
<P>
   It's the largest animal on Earth _ and it resides just off the
coast of Southern California.
</P>
<P>
   The blue whale's immense presence along California's Channel
Islands has drawn the attention of researchers and whale
enthusiasts. Thought to feed on the krill, little shrimp-like
creatures that line the islands, the whale population has exploded
in the past five years.
</P>
<P>
   On any given day, Channel Island boaters can see as many as 20
blue whales feeding in the bay.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're definitely getting a lot more sightings of these whales
in the last few years,'' said Joe Cordaro, southwest region
coordinator of National Marine Fisheries.
</P>
<P>
   ``We just don't know why these whales are hanging out there _ it
appears that it's a popular feeding area for them,'' he added.
</P>
<P>
   Although their presence puzzles researchers, the appearance of
these great cetaceans dazzles boaters.
</P>
<P>
   On a recent Tuesday morning, passengers crowded the front of the
whale watching boat Rachel G.
</P>
<P>
   The engines on the 90-foot long boat had been cut to neutral and
the passengers leaned over the rail in silence, straining to catch
a glimpse of the blue whale.
</P>
<P>
   ``There _ over there!'' shouted one passenger, pointing off in
the distance.
</P>
<P>
   A tall, straight stream of air was catapulted 20 feet into the
air by the whale's blowhole. Within seconds, the blue-gray,
streamlined body broke the surface of the water.
</P>
<P>
   ``They're absolutely beautiful,'' gushed Kim Biese, a Wisconsin
native who was spending her summer working on the boat.
</P>
<P>
   They are also incredibly large. The whales can grow as long as
100 feet and can weigh as much as 100 tons. On land, the whale
would be crushed to death by its own weight.
</P>
<P>
   But size isn't a precursor to savagery. These toothless
creatures are some of the most gentle creatures in the world.
</P>
<P>
   ``Mother nature in her wisdom made these whales toothless,
docile and friendly,'' said boat Captain Jerry Winingar.
</P>
<P>
   ``One time we had this group of schoolchildren on the boat and
the whale swam up to the side of the boat and just floated on by,''
he said.
</P>
<P>
   ``She was bigger and longer than the boat, but there was nothing
scary about her at all,'' Winingar said.
</P>
<P>
   The whales were thought to feed in the polar waters during the
summer months and were found mainly in the Antarctic from May to
September.
</P>
<P>
   In the past decade though, researchers noticed that the whales
are spending their summer months in the more temperate climates
just off the coast of Santa Barbara.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's a lot of food there _ we know that much,'' Cordaro
said. During the summer feeding season the blue whale gorges
itself, consuming an astounding 4 tons or more of food a day. This
means it may eat up to 40 million krill daily.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've seen as many as fourteen different blue whales out in
the bay area at any one time,'' said Don Hedden, owner of Capt.
Don's whale watching tours. ``I can only imagine how many krill are
out there.''
</P>
<P>
   X X X &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
