<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-08-08 18:53 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4553 &Cx1f; taf-z
u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-AFRICA-HOSPITAL-NYT &LR;      08-08 0638
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-AFRICA-HOSPITAL-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HOSPITAL STRUGGLES TO SAVE LIVES OF BOMB VICTIMS 
</HEADLINE>
   (See also AFRICA BOMBINGS, AFRICA-SOLDIER, AFRICA-U.S.,
AFRICA-VICTIMS, AFRICA-VICTIMS-LIST)  
(lb) 
 By TIM WEINER   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NAIROBI, Kenya _ The grievously maimed and the walking wounded
filled the wards, corridors and intensive-care beds at this
nation's largest hospital, and doctors, nurses and technicians were
strained to their limits Saturday as they struggled to treat the
victims of the car-bomb attack on the U.S. Embassy here on Friday.
</P>
<P>
   ``This place was filled with blood,'' said Henry Njoroge, an
X-ray technician at Nairobi's Kenyatta National Hospital, which
treated 1,600 people in the hours after the blast and has admitted
257 other victims. ``We treated so many who were unconscious and in
shock, and we were shocked ourselves.''
</P>
<P>
   Kenyatta Hospital is running out of X-ray film, respirators,
sterile gloves, pain-killing drugs and other basics, hospital
administrators and technicians said. A remarkable public response
has helped the hospital staff cope. Hundreds of people have donated
blood, food, blankets and bedsheets. Doctors and medical students
have been working around the clock.
</P>
<P>
   Still, the Red Cross said Saturday that there were blood
shortages at some of the seven hospitals treating more than 4,000
wounded, and handwritten signs taped on Kenyatta Hospital's cement
walls appealed for blood donations.
</P>
<P>
   But brain surgeons and other experts, and heart monitors and
other high-tech equipment will be needed to save the lives of the
most seriously injured, particularly those with head injuries,
nurses and doctors said.
</P>
<P>
   On Friday morning, the 10-story hospital, about two miles from
the U.S. Embassy, trembled with the force of the explosion. Within
10 minutes, hundreds of people, their faces torn by flying glass
and their bones shattered by the blast and the debris, began
streaming into Kenyatta Hospital's front doors, driven by ordinary
Kenyans who pitched in to help, as well as by ambulances. Doctors
in private practice and off-duty medical students arrived minutes
later.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was very overwhelming,'' said Kepha Maroro, a 21-year-old
medical student at the University of Nairobi. ``There were so many,
we didn't know who to attend to. We were so few and the numbers
were so large. If someone could walk, we could not attend to
them.''
</P>
<P>
   With only three hours of sleep in the 36 hours since the
explosion, Maroro was on his way to get some aspirin for himself,
so he could stay on his feet.
</P>
<P>
   On the 7th floor of the hospital, Alice Mothoni, a 34-year-old
government clerk, lay on a metal bed in a room with six others. She
was on the 16th floor of a building next to the U.S. Embassy when
the first blast went off. She and her co-workers rushed to the
windows, and the second blast shattered glass that badly cut Miss
Mothoni's face.
</P>
<P>
   In the intensive-care unit on the first floor, doctors and
nurses were struggling to save lives Saturday evening. In one crib
was a tiny girl with a shattered head, who was listed on a sheet of
paper as ``unknown African child.''
</P>
<P>
   ``We need more machines, more respirators, more gloves,'' said a
nurse in the intensive-care unit.
</P>
<P>
   Three blast victims died in the operating room here Saturday,
and five more who were in the intensive-care unit died, the nurse
said.
</P>
<P>
   Kenyatta Hospital's spokesman, Stephen Mureithi, said that
Nairobi had never experienced anything as devastating as the
explosion on Friday, and that the collective shock had not worn
off.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have been touched by horror,'' he said. ``There you are,
walking down the street, no worries at all, and suddenly you are in
a hospital, with broken bones or a broken skull. But the public
response _ we have coped.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
