<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-LONGSTAY-HOTELS-REAL-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
REAL ESTATE: EXTENDED-STAY HOTELS EXTEND THEIR POPULARITY 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Conn., Mass., Ill., Ga.)  (lb) 
 By ELEANOR CHARLES   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   In recent years, the hotel industry has scrambled to respond to
an increasingly mobile business community. Companies sending
employees on assignments that could last from two or three days to
two or three years were clearly underwhelmed by traditional hotel
services and rates.
</P>
<P>
   Enter the extended-stay lodging concept offered by at least 19
companies currently operating about 1,000 properties nationwide.
</P>
<P>
   Guests are typically offered a 250- to 450-square foot
accommodation with a bedroom, living room or living-room area,
fully equipped kitchen, housekeeping service and a work station
with two phone lines and outlets for computer equipment.
</P>
<P>
   The larger and more expensive units may include two separate
bedrooms and two baths, Jacuzzi, living room and two TVs and VCRs,
with the hotel's facilities including a swimming pool, exercise
room and 24-hour concierge.
</P>
<P>
   Most extended-stay hotels are found in suburban areas where
established corporate centers supply their customer base. In
Connecticut _ a natural target with its concentration of corporate
headquarters _ there are six existing extended-stay hotels with 632
units. Seven more with a total of 1,051 units are under
construction or projected through 1999, according to Smith Travel
Research in Hendersonville, Tenn., and individual hotel companies.
</P>
<P>
   An $8 million, three-story Homestead Village has broken ground
on a 3.6-acre parcel along Route 7 in Norwalk, Conn., with 129
rooms of 260 to 400 square feet. Rates are expected to range from
$209 to $419 a week or slightly higher.
</P>
<P>
   An application to build a second Homestead Village on Long Ridge
Road in Stamford, Conn., was rejected last month in a 3-2 vote by
the Planning Board, reinforcing a universal concern among
developers that the metropolitan New York region is tougher to
penetrate because of neighborhood resistance and complex zoning
regulations.
</P>
<P>
   ``We explored Stamford for two years, and had lots of input from
adjacent homeowners,'' said Matt Whelan, vice president of
acquisitions and development for Homestead. ``They were supportive,
but unfortunately some residents from farther away were not as
receptive. Based on the trucking and commercial use that's there
now, we thought we were bringing an improvement.''
</P>
<P>
   The proposed site, a three-acre parcel in a residential zone,
has been occupied since prezoning days by Crystal Rock, a
water-bottling company, and by a vacant restaurant. Objectors to
the hotel fear that Long Ridge Road with its many office buildings
is shifting from a residential to a commercial area.
</P>
<P>
   Rick Redniss, president of Redniss and Mead, Stamford
development consultants for Homestead, is re-evaluating its
position and may reapply. ``The city is clearly underserved,'' he
said. ``We have hundreds of apartments that are being used as
extended-stay units _ some are being rented annually by
corporations, some by extended-stay providers who sublet them to
corporations, taking them off the market for people who need
housing.''
</P>
<P>
   Homestead Village, founded in 1992, has 95 operating properties
in 26 states and 74 more under construction or planned. Its newest
ventures are to rise on a site on Tremont Street in Boston and
three sites in New York, on 55th Street between Madison and Park
avenues, West 40th Street opposite Bryant Park and 45th Street near
Third Avenue.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are very excited about this,'' said David Dressler Jr.,
co-chairman and chief investment officer. ``In Manhattan there are
many fabulous hotels, but very few alternatives for extended-stay
customers. Our customers tell us that they need us to be there.''
</P>
<P>
   The current high occupancy rates of extended-stay hotels, a type
of lodging that has been in existence since the '70s, are
encouraging construction both by fledgling companies and by
traditional behemoths like Marriott and Holiday Inn.
</P>
<P>
   Occupancy nationwide through May of this year was 78 percent,
compared with 76.2 percent for the entire year in 1992, according
to Smith Travel Research. Occupancy at all hotels was 59.6 percent
in 1992 and 62.2 percent through last May.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are up to 146,000 rooms across the country, and between
60,000 and 80,000 are being built annually,'' said Peggy Berg,
president of the Highland group, a hotel consulting company in
Atlanta.
</P>
<P>
   A negative perception of extended-stay hotels sometimes
surfaces, said Ms. Berg of the Highland Group, when ``zoning boards
throw up horrible specters of 1960s motels that are not up to code
and will rent to anybody.''
</P>
<P>
   But objections of that kind have not been voiced in Stamford.
Norman Lotstein, speaking for the city's Downtown Special Services
District, said ``extended-stay hotels are patronized by people who
are heavy users of restaurants, theaters and shops.''
</P>
<P>
   ``We believe they are better served by locating downtown where
those things are easily accessible,'' he added.
</P>
<P>
   The South and Southwest have been the most fertile ground for
building extended-stay lodgings to date, but development is
expanding in California and the Northeast, where costs are higher
but the customer base is commensurately richer.
</P>
<P>
   The extended-stay hotel, which is cost effective for companies
needing to temporarily put up employees on assignment, trainees and
relocated, house-hunting employees, is gaining ground particularly
in accommodations for middle-management and construction employees.
</P>
<P>
   Corporations base the quality of hotels on the salary of the
employee. Someone making $50,000 a year will not be accommodated at
the same level as someone making $150,000 a year and most
upper-echelon executives, according to extended-stay operators, are
still booked into the finest traditional hotels with restaurants,
room service and elegant furnishings.
</P>
<P>
   Rates vary geographically and according to amenities, from $40 a
night to over $200 a night, with discounts for stays of five days
or more. The industry defines an extended stay as a minimum of five
days.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE _ OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   Rates at Homewood Suites in Windsor Locks, Conn., are $139 a
night for up to four nights, $114 a night from five to 11 nights,
$99 a night from 12 to 19 nights and $89 a night thereafter. Open
since 1990, Homewood has 132 suites in six buildings and extras
that include an outdoor pool, Jacuzzi, basketball court, daily maid
service, complimentary dinner for dining between 5 and 7 p.m.,
complimentary beer, wine and continental breakfast.
</P>
<P>
   Lisa Crinella, the manager, said, ``We get people in training on
projects for Konica, the copier and camera company; Asea Brown
Boveri, a power-generation company, the U.S. Postal Service and
other companies in the area.'' Homewood Suites has been in
existence since 1989, when it opened in Omaha, Neb.
</P>
<P>
   The first Connecticut property to be built under the banner of
Extended Stay America, a Fort Lauderdale, Fla., company, is a
91-unit building scheduled to open in Farmington in November as a
Studio Plus Deluxe Studio Hotel. Work will start in Danbury on the
104-unit Extended Stay America Efficiency Studios, and the company
has a site under contract in Shelton for 104 rooms. Rates will
range from $199 to $399 a week.
</P>
<P>
   Between 1986 and 1996 Marriott, a player in virtually every
segment of the hospitality market, built five Residence Inns in
Connecticut _ in Windsor, Meriden, Mystic, New Haven and Shelton. A
sixth will open in Danbury early next year and a seventh is
projected to open in Manchester next spring. Rates are $159 a night
up to four nights, and $139 from four to 11 nights, compared with a
single rate of $175 a night at the traditional Stamford Marriott
hotel.
</P>
<P>
   Marriott put extended-stay hotels into the downtowns of major
cities early on, opening Residence Inns during the last decade in
Chicago, Atlanta, Dallas, Denver, New Orleans and Minneapolis,
among other places. Its Washington and Beverly Hills Residence Inns
will open this year.
</P>
<P>
   Jack DeBoer, chairman and chief executive officer of Candlewood
Suites in Wichita, Kan., built the Residence Inn system before it
was sold to Marriott in the mid-'70s. ``I was an apartment builder
looking for a way to enjoy hotel income,'' he said. ``The hotel
market was much deeper than I thought.'' He later co-founded
Summerfield Suites and 18 months ago opened the first of 40
operating Candlewood Suites, with 35 more under construction.
</P>
<P>
   Popular as it is, the concept doesn't suit all companies. Candy
Racine, a supervisor at Carlson Wagonlit Travel in Rolling Meadows,
Ill., said ``AT&AMP;T has little use for extended-stay hotels. Most of
their travel is short-term.''
</P>
<P>
   GE Capital and Xerox in Stamford responded to inquiries about
their use of extended-stay hotels by saying that they use them from
time to time, but they were not sure how much or by whom they were
used. Hotel operators attribute such reticence to corporations'
wishing to avoid an appearance of endorsing extended-stay hotels at
the expense of traditional hotels.
</P>
<P>
   Holiday Inns, a division of Bass Hospitality in England since
1990, is the latest entry into this market with a product called
Staybridge Suites. The first hotel is expected to open in November
in Alpharetta, an Atlanta suburb, with 119 studios and one- and
two-bedroom suites. ``You can expect a burst of Staybridge activity
nationwide in the next 18 months,'' said James Anhut, vice
president of Staybridge Suites.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
