<SLUG> BC-BBN-ALNOTES-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    American League Notes
 &HT;    By I.J. Rosenberg
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   East
</P>
<P>
   Toronto's Roger Clemens may want out after this season, upset
that the team appears to remain in a rebuilding mode. ``If ...
trying to win is put on the back burner, then they're wasting their
time and I'm wasting my time,'' Clemens said. ``If that's the case,
my choice is to go closer to home, to Texas or Houston.''
</P>
<P>
   Notes: With Mo Vaughn expected to be in a different uniform next
season, look for the Red Sox to make a run at soon-to-be free agent
Mike Piazza. ... The Yankees could win 100 games before September.
They will have to go 24-7 this month to do so and so far are 6-2.
... New York's Darryl Strawberry has tied a major-league record
with two pinch-hit grand slams in a season. Davey Johnson of the
Phillies and Mike Ivie of the Giants both did it in 1978. ... In a
game Wednesday, Orioles third baseman Cal Ripken Jr. laid down just
the fifth sacrifice bunt of his career. ... Don't expect Jimmy Key
to do a lot of pitching down the stretch for the Orioles. The
left-hander still is bothered by an inflamed rotator cuff that kept
him out for 2 1/2 months. ... The Devil Rays will have a big choice
at third base next season, whether to go with Wade Boggs, who will
be going for his 3,000th hit, or up-and-coming ex-Brave Bobby
Smith.
</P>
<P>
   Central
</P>
<P>
   The Indians might be on track to win another division title, but
Wall Street has little faith in them. Their stock, which came out
at around $15 a share and is traded on the Nasdaq, has dropped more
than 43 percent. ``We're disappointed but not discouraged,'' said
Ken Stefanov, the club's chief financial officer. ``We see this as
a long-term, capital play.''
</P>
<P>
   Notes: Showing how times have changed in Cleveland, when
reliever Doug Jones made his first appearance there in 1991,
attendance at old Cleveland Stadium was 3,785. When he came back to
the team late last month, Jacobs Field held 43,055. ... White Sox
starter James Baldwin has a 8-0 record in indoor parks. ... The
Tigers are still hopeful they can get right-handed closer Todd
Jones through the waivers process and trade him. ... Royals GM Herk
Robinson admitted, ``We were asking a lot,'' from the Braves for
closer Jeff Montgomery. The Royals wanted either prospect Bruce
Chen or Odaliz Perez, and the Braves said no. ... Minnesota
public-address announcer Bob Casey will work his 3,000th game
today. That's more than 37 years of service.
</P>
<P>
   West
</P>
<P>
   The Mariners might have gotten more for Randy Johnson if they
had not waited until the deadline to move him. They had been
offered Hideki Irabu, outfielder Ricky Ledee and third baseman Mike
Lowell by the Yankees but balked. They also could have had
outfielder Brian Giles and infielder Enrique Wilson from the
Indians. In the end, they had to settle for three prospects from
the Astros.
</P>
<P>
   Notes: Shane Monahan, a recent callup for the Mariners, is the
grandson of NHL great and former Atlanta Flames coach Boom Boom
Geoffrion. ... Texas has benefited from the acquisition of starter
Esteban Loaiza, acquired from Pittsburgh on July 17. In his first
two appearances with the Rangers, Loaiza has a 1-0 complete-game
win and an eight-inning effort in which he allowed two runs. ...
Monday was embarrassing for Oakland's Mike Oquist, who became the
first pitcher since Milwaukee's Bill Travers in 1977 to allow 14
earned runs in a game. A's manager Art Howe on the five-inning
performance: ``Life is cruel; I was bleeding with the kid.'' That's
three more earned runs than Atlanta's Greg Maddux has allowed since
June 2. ... Speaking of Howe, expect the A's to can him after the
season and replace him with Bob Boone, now a scouting assistant
with the Reds.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
