u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BBN-BRAVES-NOTEBOOK09     08-08 0627
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBN-BRAVES-NOTEBOOK09-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Glavine: Maddux wins Cy Young
 &HT;    By Thomas Stinson
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ Most concession speeches come around midnight on
Tuesdays. Tom Glavine made his Saturday around lunchtime.
</P>
<P>
   ``Let's face it,'' he said. ``Doggie's gonna win it.''
</P>
<P>
   Greg Maddux has won the Cy Young award? It's early August, 46
games to play, maybe nine more starts each. Both Glavine and Maddux
have 15 wins and Glavine has a better win percentage. And Maddux is
a projected winner?
</P>
<P>
   Said Glavine, ``Gotta be.''
</P>
<P>
   Glavine's comments come after his first shutout of the season
Friday night, while he is in the midst of a 6-1 run and his ERA
down to 2.47, which is .08 lower than when he won his Cy Young in
1991. He cannot pitch much better. He lone shortcoming may be that
Maddux is around.
</P>
<P>
   ``Seeing what (Maddux) has done year in and year out, he helped
me in my special year I had,'' said John Smoltz, the 1996 winner.
``But to win the Cy Young, it's supposed to be kind of a
once-in-a-lifetime thing. Well, yeah, I won one. Here's a guy who
(can) win five.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm doing my best to stay in it,'' said Glavine. ``Believe me,
I know if I'm going to win, some way I'm going to have to end up
with three, four or five more wins. He's got a better ERA (1.53 to
2.47), more shutouts (a NL-high five to one), more complete games
(nine to two). I would think that if it ended right now, he'd win
it. I kind of hope from here on out, if I can keep it interesting
and keep myself in contention, it will be good for our team.''
</P>
<P>
   The Braves staff has talked about the benefits of intramural
competition but there may not be a better example than how Maddux
and Glavine are driving themselves right now. Working 1-2 in the
rotation most of the year and exclusively since the second week of
June, the pair have lost back-to-back starts only once all year
(July 11-12 at Florida) and just generated back-to-back three-hit
shutouts.
</P>
<P>
   ``With Glavine, it's almost like match-play,'' said Smoltz.
``You want to go out and do well but when you're playing with
somebody who's at the top, it makes it that much harder.''
</P>
<P>
   Maddux, for the record, has not been impressed by any of this,
as veteran Dog-o-philes might expect.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's hard enough to win without worrying about a bunch of
other stuff,'' Maddux said. ``Cy Young? Yeah, I'd like to win. Who
wouldn't? It's nice. But it's not an issue yet. It's something
after the postseason, where you're sitting around in December, you
hope to get a phone call. That's it, you know?''
</P>
<P>
   Springer update
</P>
<P>
   Russ Springer still feels the knot in his right elbow where he
received his cortisone shot Thursday but he hopes to do some light
tossing today just to see where he standsfour days into his 15-day
stint on the disabled list.
</P>
<P>
   ``If everything goes right, then I'm supposed to throw off the
mound either the third or last day (Wednesday or Thursday) in San
Diego,'' he said. ``But at the same time, it's not something where
we have to rush anything.''
</P>
<P>
   Springer is not eligible for activation until Aug. 21.
</P>
<P>
   Weiss sits
</P>
<P>
   Shortstop Walt Weiss passed the first stress test, playing seven
straight games after sitting out nearly two weeks with a sore left
quad. In reward, manager Bobby Cox let him sit Saturday after a
night game. Weiss has hit .321 since returning to the lineup and
after the two-week break, plus playing in this current spate of
fast games, Weiss remains fresh.
</P>
<P>
   ``Just the length of the games with this team is a big
difference,'' Weiss said. ``The games in Colorado were so long, it
felt like you played a 250-game schedule.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
