<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    On Deck: San Francisco Giants
 &HT;    By Thomas Stinson
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   When: Today at 8:05 p.m.
</P>
<P>
   Where: 3Com Park at Candlestick Point.
</P>
<P>
   TV/radio: ESPN, WSB 750-AM.
</P>
<P>
   Probable starting pitchers: RHP John Smoltz (10-2, 3.14; 10-13,
4.11 lifetime vs. Giants) vs. RHP Mark Gardner (8-5, 5.13; 5-5,
3.77 lifetime vs. Braves).
</P>
<P>
   Notes: Smoltz, who has the league's best winning percentage at
.833, goes after his sixth straight victory. He has not lost on the
road since May 17 in Houston, when he began to suffer the elbow
pain that landed him on the DL six days later. Since returning from
the DL June 20, Smoltz is 6-1 with a 2.54 ERA. He has allowed a
.254 average and 101 hits in 106 innings but has struck out 102, a
rate of 8.7 strikeouts per nine innings, an amazing feat given his
elbow troubles. Over his previous five seasons, Smoltz had averaged
8.6 strikeouts per nine. He will be wary of Giants outfielder Ellis
Burks, who has a .400 career average against him with two homers in
15 at-bats. Gardner is 7-3 in his last 15 starts and probably
deserves better. Since the All-Star break, the Giants have lost in
four of his five starts, three of those losses coming in the last
at-bat. He is 2-1 against Atlanta is five starts as a Giant. He
drew no decision at Turner Field May 2 (three runs and nine hits in
six innings) in a game San Francisco lost in extra innings. Braves
outfielder Michael Tucker, who is in search of a break-out game,
will be glad to face him. Tucker is 3-for-7 (.429) lifetime against
Gardner with two homers.
</P>
