A4569 &Cx1f; tad-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BBN-INSIDE-BASEBALL-C     08-08 0500
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBN-INSIDE-BASEBALL-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Balance in the Bronx
 &HT;    By I.J. Rosenberg
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA -- Before canceling the postseason and handing the World
Series title to the New York Yankees, this fact should be pondered:
Since 1989, the team with the best record in the major leagues has
not won the Series.
</P>
<P>
   On the other hand, these Yankees, an amazing 53 games over .500,
are special. They are playing at an incredible .739 clip. If they
continue to play at the same pace, they will blow away the all-time
record of 116 victories by four _ although they would not have the
best all-time winning percentage.
</P>
<P>
   They also could reach 100 victories by going 18-33 the rest of
the season. Despite Boston's 66-47 record, which is good enough to
lead the league's other two divisions, the Red Sox trail the
Yankees by 17 games.
</P>
<P>
   It has been years since baseball has seen a team with this kind
of balance.
</P>
<P>
   When New York lost four of its first five games this year, there
was talk of firing manager Joe Torre. Talk about premature.
</P>
<P>
   ``It has been an incredible run, when you think about it,''
pitcher David Cone recently told the Sacramento Bee. ``This team is
relentless. I've never been on a team like it. Nothing distracts
them from winning ballgames.''
</P>
<P>
   And it's a team without a lot of big stars.
</P>
<P>
   Their biggest, center fielder Bernie Williams, has been hurt for
part of the season. No player started in the All-Star Game. Darryl
Strawberry leads in homers with 21.
</P>
<P>
   ``There are no outs in that lineup,'' former Angels designated
hitter Cecil Fielder said.
</P>
<P>
   New York does not rely on the home run; instead, it finds ways
to manufacture runs. Typical power hitters Paul O'Neill and Tino
Martinez have shortened their swings and are hitting to the
opposite field.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a lot easier to go into a slump when you're sitting
around waiting for a three-run homer,'' Torre told the Bee. ``We're
a line-drive, contact team. We get a lot of walks and put the ball
in play.''
</P>
<P>
   The pitching is solid. The Yankees' rotation might not be as
good as the Braves' at the top, but it is deeper. Rafael Mendoza is
in the bullpen. The five starters _ Cone, David Wells, Andy
Pettitte, Hideki Irabu and Orlando Hernandez _ have a combined ERA
of 3.43. Closer Mariano Rivera has 29 saves in 32 opportunities and
has walked just seven in 42 1/3 innings.
</P>
<P>
   The defense has been consistent with a .982 fielding percentage,
which ranks in the top half of the league.
</P>
<P>
   But the biggest difference between this team and those of the
past is the clubhouse atmosphere. Everyone gets along, and owner
George Steinbrenner has had few complaints.
</P>
<P>
   The Yankees are aware of the playoff woes of teams with the best
record.
</P>
<P>
   ``We could win 150 games and lose 12,'' summed up shortstop
Derek Jeter, ``but if we don't win the World Series, then what's
the point of the season?''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
