<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBN-NLNOTES-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    National League Notes
 &HT;    By I.J. Rosenberg
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   East
</P>
<P>
   Based on his past, Kevin Millwood is going to have some kind of
future. Of the Braves' five starters, he is going to be the only
one to have a winning record after his first two seasons. Millwood
is 17-9 during his two years. John Smoltz was 14-18, Denny Neagle
7-12, Greg Maddux 8-18 and Tom Glavine 9-21.
</P>
<P>
   Notes: Even though John Franco is 37 years old, 0-6 with a 4.36
ERA and has blown four of his last seven save opportunities, the
Mets signed him to a two-year extension worth $6.15 million. ...
Since returning from offseason surgery, Todd Hundley of the Mets
has 15 hits in 69 at-bats. ... The Mets called off negotiations
with Mike Piazza on a long-term contract until after the season,
because they realize he does not want to return to New York. They
also think he's not worth $100 million. ... Anyone wondering
whether John Smoltz is back at full strength should check his
record since the All-Star break: 5-0 with a 2.02 ERA. ... In eight
of Curt Schilling's 11 losses, the Phillies have scored two runs or
fewer. ... Right now, the defending champion Marlins have an active
payroll of $5.8 million. They also are paying $7 million to injured
pitcher Alex Fernandez.
</P>
<P>
   Central
</P>
<P>
   Craig Biggio's 494-game consecutive game streak came to an end
Wednesday. Now second behind Cal Ripken and his 2,592 games is
Albert Belle at 285, followed by Vinny Castilla (201), Neifi Perez
(186), Jeromy Burnitz (171), Scott Rolen (129), John Olerud (127),
Chipper Jones (120), Kenny Lofton (118), Ken Griffey Jr. (116) and
Kevin Young (116).
</P>
<P>
   Notes: Mark McGwire might be the leading candidate for MVP
honors, but before his two-RBI single Friday night, the last
non-homer RBI hit that he had came on June 7 against the Giants.
... John Mabry filled in for McGwire in the No. 3 hole and at first
base Wednesday and homered. ... A sign that times are getting
better for the Astros: On Monday, two days after trading for
Seattle's Randy Johnson, the club's Internet site had 434,000 hits.
... The one statistic that shows just how poorly Cubs shortstop
Jeff Blauser is playing: His slugging percentage is .298. Last year
it was .482. That's a big drop, considering Blauser moved to a much
more hitter-friendly park (Wrigley Field) than Turner Field.
</P>
<P>
   West
</P>
<P>
   Why would the Padres, who already have one of the best closers
in baseball and a solid bullpen from top to bottom, acquire Toronto
closer Randy Myers? They were concerned if they didn't, the Braves
would, so San Diego was willing to swallow the $14.5 million left
on his contract for what will likely be the most expensive setup
man ever in baseball. If the Padres make it to the World Series, no
one will even bat at eye at the money.
</P>
<P>
   Notes: Rockies pitcher Jamey Wright hit his first career homer
Wednesday. ``I don't even hit homers in pitchers' batting practice
in Coors Field,'' he said. ``I definitely wasn't looking for one.''
... The Dodgers are 23-19 since manager Glenn Hoffman took over for
Bill Russell on June 22. ... The Dodgers' acquisition of Carlos
Perez and Mark Grudzielanek from Montreal pushed their payroll to
$61 million. ... The Dodgers have had 47 different players on their
roster this year. ... Kevin Brown's 11-game winning streak for the
Padres is the longest in the majors this season. Yet it is San
Diego's Andy Ashby who is pushing Greg Maddux for the Cy Young
Award. Ashby, a 15-game winner, has walked just three in his last
eight starts. ... The Giants play great baseball on Sunday, Monday
and Tuesday with a combined record of 34-13. They are 28-40 the
rest of the week.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
