<SLUG> BC-RAC-HAMBLETONIAN-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MUSCLES YANKEE WINS THE HAMBLETONIAN  
 (HLW) 
</HEADLINE>
   By ALEX YANNIS   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   EAST RUTHERFORD, N.J. _ Muscles Yankee didn't surprise anyone by
capturing the 73rd edition of the $1-million Hambletonian on
Saturday in the bright sunshine at the Meadowlands. The victory
gave the driver John Campbell his record fifth success in the most
prestigious event in harness racing.
</P>
<P>
   ``To win more Hambletonians than anyone is very special,''
Campbell said after piloting Muscles Yankee to his fourth
consecutive triumph and fifth in six starts this season, justifying
his reputation as the best 3-year-old trotter.
</P>
<P>
   Campbell vaulted Muscles Yankee into the lead just after the
halfway point and was never threatened the rest of the way,
covering the mile in 1:52.2. The time was the second fastest in the
classic's history, only one-fifth of a second off the stakes record
set by Continentalvictory in 1996.
</P>
<P>
   Muscles Yankee, the son of Valley Victory, finished three
lengths ahead of David Raymond, giving the trainer Chuck Sylvester
the top two finishers and his third title as a trainer in the
ultimate event in harness racing.
</P>
<P>
   It was the first Hambletonian victory for the owner Bill
Perretti. ``I've waited 20 years for this,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Sylvester also trained two other horses in the race, Silver
Pine, who broke stride at the halfway point and finished ninth, and
Armbro Rotary, who finished last in the field of 10.
</P>
<P>
   Sylvester said that Muscles Yankee raced a great mile. ``When he
was asked to go, he did just that,'' Sylvester said about
Campbell's decision to make his move to the top of the field around
the halfway point.
</P>
<P>
   Campbell agreed. ``He responded very well when I asked him to
step to the front, he said. ``He felt very strong and I felt real
confident. He's never shown any quitting in any of the starts in
his life.''
</P>
<P>
   Sylvester said that Muscles Yankee would race in the Yonkers
Trot, the second leg of the triple crown, on Aug. 29 and he would
take him to the third leg, the Kentucky Futurity, on Oct. 9. The
last trotter to win the triple crown was Super Bowl in 1972.
</P>
<P>
   The driver Luc Ouellette finished sixth in the Hambletonian with
Giant Keeper, but he still had a successful afternoon. Ouellette,
32, captured the Hambletonian Oaks behind Fern and drove the
winners in the Oliver Wendell Holmes and the United States Pacing
Championship.
</P>
<P>
   Driving Fern to victory in the $500,000 Hambletonian Oaks was
not the biggest victory of the season for Ouellette. He won the
biggest race of his career last month when he guided Day In A Life
to victory in the $1 million Meadowlands Pace.
</P>
<P>
   Red Bow Tie took the $100,000 U.S. Pacing Championship in
1:49.1, matching the stakes record. Browning Blue Chip captured the
$141,000 Oliver Wendell Holmes for 3-year-old colts and geldings in
1:50.3 and handed Artiscape his first loss of the season.
</P>
<P>
   Moni Maker, who dominated the $500,0000 Breeders Crown with a
world-class performance recently after victories in Europe earlier
in the season, captured her second consecutive $300,000 Nat Ray
Final, an open race for trotters, to polish off her
horse-of-the-year season. She posted her eighth victory in 13
starts and was such an overwhelming favorite she paid $2.20 for a
$2 wager.
</P>
<P>
   The $400,500 Mistletoe Shalee for three-year-old pacing fillies
was captured by Galleria, who covered the mile in 1:50.4 and paid
$7.40 for $2. Galleria took the lead at the three-quarter mark and
held on to beat Panned Out by a nose.
</P>
<P>
   Since this was the culmination of the season at the Meadowlands,
the the season's leading owner, trainer and driver were honored on
Friday night. Bob Glazer's Peter Pan Stables was honored as the
leading owner for the fourth consecutive year, Brett Pelling
extended his record with his sixth trainer's title and Campbell led
the standing as the leading driver.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
