<SLUG> BC-BBN-BRAVES-MAIN09-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Braves launch 20-hit attack
 &HT;    By Thomas Stinson
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ This isn't a road trip. Thus far, it's a joy
ride.
</P>
<P>
   The Braves made 42-year-old Danny Darwin look like the tired old
man he is, raking him for seven quick runs and then weathering a
mid-game uprising to beat the Giants 14-6 Saturday. Now 2-0 on this
nine-game western excursion, Atlanta sends out John Smoltz against
Mark Gardner tonight for the sweep and if anything, it should be
noisy. The Braves have now scored 47 times in their last five
games.
</P>
<P>
   Javy Lopez, Andres Galarraga and Greg Colbrunn each hit two-run
homers and Keith Lockhart and Andruw Jones added solo shots to
spike a season-high 20-hit attack. But this one ended early, the
Braves sending 27 men to the plate in the first four innings,
racking Darwin (7-10) for 10 hits (five doubles and two homers). It
was 9-0 before the Braves recorded their 11th out.
</P>
<P>
   The happy recipient was Kevin Millwood (13-6), who won for the
fourth time in his last six decisions. Millwood pitched four strong
shutout innings (extending a Braves scoreless streak to 22 innings)
before walks and some two-out bat work led to five Giants runs,
chasing Millwood after just six innings.
</P>
<P>
   The issue became so moshed in the late stages that the Giants
batted out of order in the sixth, when they scored three times and
the Braves dugout was so glazed over, it never noticed until it was
too late. Rich Aurilia, substituting for Jeff Kent, walked and
eventually scored, even though he hit in Joe Carter's spot, when he
was subsituted for J.T. Snow.
</P>
<P>
   Had the Braves realized Aruilia had batted out of turn, the team
could have appealed, by Rule 6.01 (a) and Aurilia would have been
out. But Cox, who had to want to get home as quickly as any of the
39,174 assembled, never protested and the run counted. Who knew?
</P>
<P>
   Galarraga had three RBIs with a double and his 35th homer, the
highest total by a Brave since David Justice's 40-homer season in
1993 and the most by a Brave first baseman since Hank Aaron hit 47
in 1971. Lopez's homer was his third in his last three games,
giving him six RBIs in his last 14 at-bats.
</P>
<P>
   The last starting position player to log a hit, Andruw Jones
made it count with a homer to left off Rich Rodriguez, the Giants
fourth pitcher.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
