<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-RAC-WHITNEY-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
AWESOME AGAIN CAPTURES A SLOW WHITNEY  
 (HLW) 
</HEADLINE>
   By JOSEPH DURSO   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   SARATOGA SPRINGS, N.Y. _ Awesome Again, who won the Jim Dandy
Stakes at Saratoga as a 3-year-old last August, returned to win the
Whitney Handicap on Saturday by three lengths over Tale of the Cat,
and added another level to his career by remaining undefeated at 4.
</P>
<P>
   He allowed Tale of the Cat to set a slow pace for almost a mile,
but did not let the speedy Cat steal the race. As they turned for
home, with the seasoned Pat Day biding his time, Awesome Again
collared Tale of the Cat, passed him after a brief duel and widened
his lead as they flew home with six other horses in pursuit.
</P>
<P>
   This was the 71st running of the Whitney, one of the landmarks
of racing at Saratoga, and a crowd of 30,665 watched it on a
shining and sunny afternoon. The crowd followed form at the betting
windows, making Awesome Again the 8-5 favorite and Tale of the Cat
next at 2-1. And that's the way they finished. Crypto Star, the
fourth favorite, followed three lengths farther back in third
place, and Frisk Me Now, the third choice, was next in fourth.
</P>
<P>
   ``If there was no Awesome Again in the race,'' observed John
Forbes, the trainer of Tale of the Cat, ``we would have won.''
</P>
<P>
   But there was an Awesome Again in the race, and he won it with
all his skills flying. He won for the fourth straight time at a
mile and an eighth, he won for the second time in three starts at
Saratoga and he won for the third time this year with no losses. In
his last race, he even outran Silver Charm, winner of last year's
Kentucky Derby and Preakness. He also ran his career record to six
victories in nine starts, and he has run in the money eight times.
</P>
<P>
   ``He just ran a great race,'' said Patrick Byrne, who trains the
star colt for Frank Stronach, of Canada. ``The fractions were a lot
slower than we anticipated, but Pat did a great job positioning
him.''
</P>
<P>
   Day's great job consisted mainly of not letting Tale of the Cat
slip away on an easy lead.
</P>
<P>
   ``They were walking out there,'' Day said, ``so I had to stay
real close to the lead. At the three-eighths pole, my horse was so
relaxed I didn't know if we were out of the race or if he was just
loafing. When I realized he had a lot left in him, I knew we were
in the driver's seat.''
</P>
<P>
   This is how slow the fractions were: the first quarter-mile in
25 seconds, the half-mile in 48 4/5, the mile in 1:37. But that was
when Day decided the slow-motion had to end, so he guided Awesome
Again past Tale of the Cat and steered him home under a hand ride.
</P>
<P>
   At the finish, Awesome Again was clocked in 1:49 3/5, nearly
three seconds slower than the track record. He paid $4.80 for a $2
bet to win, and went home with $240,000 of the purse of $400,000,
raising his career earnings close to $1.5 million.
</P>
<P>
   When he switched jobs last winter, Byrne surrendered his role as
trainer of Favorite Trick, the Horse of the Year. But he inherited
Awesome Again and Touch Gold, whom he considers the star of the
stable.
</P>
<P>
   Tale of the Cat usually sets the pace, but it's usually fast.
This time, he set the pace, but it was slow. It was only his second
start after a nine-month layoff caused by a bone ailment, and he is
still considered precocious and promising. He has won four of his
seven starts, and has always seemed ahead of his class.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
