<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BOMBS-WHO-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GROUP CLAIMS RESPONSIBILITY IN BOMBINGS
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By DAVID L. MARCUS  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Who did it?
</P>
<P>
   As FBI investigators picked through the wreckage of powerful car
bombs in the capitals of Tanzania and Kenya, the government's
terrorism experts in Washington pieced together information about
the methods and possible motives behind the horrifying attacks.
</P>
<P>
   A possible breakthrough in the case occurred Saturday, when a
mysterious group called The Liberation Army of the Islamic
Sanctuaries claimed responsibility. The group threatened more
attacks to drive American and Western troops from Muslim countries.
</P>
<P>
   The group offered just enough details to give credibility to the
claim. In a statement sent to Qatar's al-Jazirah Satellite Channel,
it said the Nairobi bombing was carried out by two men from Mecca,
Saudi Arabia, while an Egyptian staged the Dar es Salaam attack.
</P>
<P>
   Calling itself ``Islamic holy warriors from all countries of the
world and who belong to all Muslim people,'' the group said it was
retaliating for the occupation of Islamic holy sites in the Arabian
peninsula by US forces.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Islamic Army for the Liberation of Holy Places announces
its absolute determination to chase the American forces and
pronounces its resolve to strike at American interests in all
places until all its objectives are met,'' the group said, an
apparent reference to the US military presence in Saudi Arabia,
Kuwait, and other Gulf states.
</P>
<P>
   But terrorism experts cautioned that the group might be trying
to exaggerate its importance by taking responsibility for one of
the most serious anti-American acts in years. Or the group might be
trying to deflect attention from the real mastermind. Perhaps the
Liberation Army does not exist, the specialists said.
</P>
<P>
   Several terrorism experts said a prime suspect is Osoma bin
Laden, a wealthy Saudi exile who has called for a Holy War against
the United States. Bin Laden, who was recently living in
Afghanistan, is a suspect in two bombings in Saudi Arabia that
killed 24 Americans in 1995 and 1996.
</P>
<P>
   Officials and independent analysts said the attacks were
overseen by experienced terrorists because no one has ever attacked
two American embassies simultaneously before. The terrorists also
knew enough to locate soft targets in neighboring countries _
embassies that do not have security walls and shatterproof windows
that the US has required on federal buildings since 1985.
</P>
<P>
   Specialists said these explosions are chilling because, in an
age of biological and chemical weapons, the attackers used
relatively unsophisticated car bombs with materials that are
apparently widely available.
</P>
<P>
   ``The fact that this was a coordinated attack on two embassies
in a few moments suggests a significant organization or national
backer,'' said Jerrold Post, director of the political psychology
program at George Washington University. ``But this is not a
technical masterpiece, not a highly complicated operation.''
</P>
<P>
   One US official who has served in high-risk areas said it is
also possible that the real masterminds may never come forward. He
said the attackers might have miscalculated, thinking they would
kill more Americans than Kenyans and Tanzanians.
</P>
<P>
   But anyone with a basic knowledge of US embassies knows that
only 20 to 30 percent of the employees are Americans, he said.
</P>
<P>
   ``Let's say this was done by an Islamic Jihad group,'' he said,
``They say they are showing solidarity with the third world against
America, but who did they kill mostly? People from Kenya and
Tanzania, and that is not going to help their cause.''
</P>
<P>
   At George Washington University, Post said that the nature of
terrorism has changed in the past couple of decades. ``In the early
days of terrorism, the goal of the act was to draw attention to the
group,'' Post said. ``As fundamentalist terrorism has been on the
increase, they don't need to have a headline in the paper. They
say, `God knows.'''
</P>
<P>
   With hardly any news about the investigation into the bombers'
identities, rumors were common in Kenya and Tanzania. In Nairobi,
for example, people told unconfirmed stories a Friday morning
shootouts between suspicious-looking men and US Marines.
</P>
<P>
   But US Ambassador to Kenya Prudence Bushnell refused to
speculate on the investigation. Asked if she had any theories about
the reason behind the bombings, Bushnell answered, ``Theories?
None. Do you have any?''
</P>
<P>
   &UR; ufauthor &LR;
</P>
<P>
   Globe correspondent Andrea Useem contributed to this report from
Nairobi. Material from Reuters was also used.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
