<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-08-08 19:41 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4575 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BARNICLE-COLUMN-BOS &LR;      08-08 0327
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BARNICLE-COLUMN-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SUBSTANCE OF BARNICLE COLUMN AFFIRMED
</HEADLINE>
  (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By CINDY RODRIGUEZ  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   A Boston Globe internal review has confirmed the substance of an
Aug. 4 Mike Barnicle column regarding a Roxbury triple murder three
decades ago.
</P>
<P>
   In the column, retired Boston police officer Edward Walsh was
quoted describing the crime as a slaying of three young women
allegedly by John Martorano, a gangland figure and FBI informant.
</P>
<P>
   According to a Jan. 7, 1968 story in the Globe library, Herbert
Smith, 47; Elizabeth F. Dickson, 19; and Douglas Barrett, 17, all
of Roxbury, were found shot to death on Jan. 6, 1968, in a car on
Normandy Street. No record of any arrests in the case could be
found Saturday.
</P>
<P>
   Barnicle's column quoted Walsh as saying the homicide involved
three girls. Walsh told the Associated Press Saturday that he told
Barnicle he believed the victims were girls. He also said the rest
of the column accurately reflected what he said.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; el.5l &LR;  An initial Globe accuracy check could find no record of
such a killing involving young women. The Washington Post reported
that on Friday, and several other media followed the story.
</P>
<P>
   That column ran two days after Barnicle's ``I Was Just
Thinking'' column, in which eight jokes apparently came from a
best-selling George Carlin book without attribution. The resulting
controvery culminated in the Globe asking for Barnicle's
resignation.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; el.5l &LR;  The columnist has refused to resign. He met with Globe
publisher Benjamin B. Taylor on Friday, but neither Barnicle nor
Taylor have commented on the outcome of the meeting.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; el.5l &LR;  Saturday, Globe Managing Editor Gregory L. Moore said:
``We believe a triple murder reported in Barnicle's Aug. 4 column
did occur, although the genders of the victims apparently were not
accurately described.'' Barnicle could not be reached for comment
Saturday.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-08-08-98 1941EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19980808.0165 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-08-08 19:44 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4576 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BOMB-NAIROBI-BOS     08-08 1423
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BOMB-NAIROBI-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MORE THAN 150 PEOPLE STILL MISSING AFTER AFRICA BLASTS
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By DAVID L. MARCUS AND ANDREA USEEM  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   NAIROBI _ Rescue workers desperately burrowed with heavy
machinery, shovels, and their bare hands Saturday in an attempt to
free people from rubble of terrorist bombings at the US embassies
in Kenya and Tanzania as the death toll rose to 147 and the number
of injured soared above 4,000.
</P>
<P>
   Teams of American searchers, doctors, and intelligence
specialists fanned out across the bomb sites in Nairobi and Dar es
Salaam, trying to save lives while preserving fragile evidence that
could indicate who organized the simultaneous attacks. The two
capitals were scenes of frenetic activity, as emergency operations
expanded, and stunned silence, as hope for finding more survivors
faded.
</P>
<P>
   More than 150 people are still missing.
</P>
<P>
   A day after the powerful blasts, the effort to find survivors
proved almost as fruitless as the effort to find the mastermind of
the double attack.
</P>
<P>
   In the Persian Gulf country of Qatar, a group calling itself
``The Liberation Army of the Islamic Sanctuaries'' took
responsibility and threatened more attacks on Americans if US
troops remain in the Gulf and the Middle East. But terrorism
specialists said it is too early to evaluate the information.
</P>
<P>
   In Kenya, the toll of dead Americans rose to 11, including the
child of an embassy employee, with five still missing. Americans
were not killed in Tanzania, but several Tanzanians who worked at
the embassy were dead or unaccounted for.
</P>
<P>
   Rescue workers plucked a survivor from the rubble of a Nairobi
office block nearly 36 hours after the building crashed around him.
</P>
<P>
   Another man trapped in the wreckage of the office building for
24 hours died while being rescued.
</P>
<P>
   ``We could only see his hand, everything else was crushed,''
said Ketan Banjara, 26, an American resident born in Kenya who
helped with the effort. ``He was so patient, only saying `I am
hurting' sometimes. Then he stopped saying anything.''
</P>
<P>
   One bomb was believed to have exploded in a vehicle in a parking
lot next to the embassy in Nairobi, which was monitored by
closed-circuit television cameras. They could provide importance
evidence, but US Ambassador Prudence Bushnell said she did not know
whether the cameras or film survived the blast.
</P>
<P>
   The FBI said its top priority is to determine the type of
vehicle and explosive used, which spokesman Frank Scafidi said
``can be like a fingerprint of who did it.''
</P>
<P>
   Terrorism specialists at the Central Intelligence Agency, the
FBI, and other agencies sorted through reams of reports about past
threats as well as profiles of terrorists, officials said. While
many of the specialists focused on Middle East groups that have
used car bombs in similar attacks, officials said they had not
ruled out terrorists from Sudan, Yemen, and other countries.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's a real reluctance to start fingering people when we
don't know everything,'' one official said.
</P>
<P>
   At the White House, President Clinton received updates from his
national security adviser, Samuel R. Berger, throughout the day. In
the afternoon, Clinton convened a meeting with his top advisers,
including Secretary of State Madeleine K. Albright and Defense
Secretary William S. Cohen, to discuss the mission of looking for
survivors and identifying the bombers.
</P>
<P>
   The State Department took the lead and about 35 officials from
the military, the Federal Emergency Management Agency, and
intelligence agencies gathered behind locked doors to share their
findings.
</P>
<P>
   Albright, who arrived on an overnight flight after canceling a
vacation in Italy, stopped in to thank the sleepless employees, an
aide said.
</P>
<P>
   American military doctors and nurses from the Ramstein Air Base
in Germany and the Prince Sultan Air Base in Saudi Arabia arrived
in Nairobi and Dar es Salaam and set up emergency clinics. Marine
antiterrorism units flown in from Bahrain and Tampa secured the
bomb sites and a Foreign Emergency Support Team, with FBI agents
and rescue workers, arrived in Nairobi from Andrews Air Force Base.
</P>
<P>
   Authorities in suburban Washington appealed for blood to send to
Kenya, where the number of injured was four times greater than
expected a day before.
</P>
<P>
   A planeload of 118 Israelis trained in urban search and rescue
arrived with equipment for monitoring sounds of humans caught in
wreckage and eight rescue dogs, but for most of the day, the
Kenyans had little equipment other than a crane and some other
earth moving machines. They used their hands to move pieces of
concrete and their voices to communicate with the trapped
survivors.
</P>
<P>
   Beneath the buzz of volunteer rescue workers and journalists, a
dull silence settled over the normally bustling street corner, now
cordoned off by Kenyan security forces. Radio hand-sets crackled,
glass crunched underfoot, and the whine of a chainsaw emerged from
the embassy, where military personnel searched floor by floor for
more bodies.
</P>
<P>
   Kenyan police and army personnel sat wordlessly in chairs pulled
from the wreckage.
</P>
<P>
   By early afternoon, hospitals had treated 4,149 people for
injuries, Bonaya Godana, Kenya's minister for foreign affairs, said
at a press conference. ``Terrorism has been brought to our
doorsteps,'' Godana said. ``We had not considered antiterrorism a
priority.''
</P>
<P>
   Dozens of bodies were thought to be still inside the Ufundi
Cooperative House, a five-story building that collapsed after the
midmorning bomb blast. At least 50 buildings were damaged,
authorities said, and US officials said the embassy suffered so
much structural damage that it would have to be razed.
</P>
<P>
   Beside the 11 American citizens confirmed dead, 14 Kenyan
embassy staff were killed, Bushnell said at a press conference.
Appearing tired and dispirited and wearing a thin grey bandage over
her lip, Bushnell said, ``Saturday morning, at about 10:40 a.m.,
literally thousands of people came face to face with evil.''
</P>
<P>
   Bushnell was meeting with Kenya's minister for trade, Joseph
Kamotho, a block from the embassy when the blast went off. Bleeding
from minor cuts and bruises, she walked down 21 flights of stairs
before coming out to see the destruction around the embassy.
</P>
<P>
   ``The result'' of this attack ``is broken hearts, shattered
lives, shock, dismay, anger, and most of all, incredible sorrow,''
she said. Leaning into the microphone and pausing to draw her
breath, she added: ``I can only hope that out of this depth of
sorrow ... that (there will be) some rich little seed that will
help all of us human beings to just stop it. Just stop hurting each
other like this.''
</P>
<P>
   About a mile outside of the city, in the suburb of Parklands,
the office of the United States Agency for International
Development was an oasis for Americans. In the large office, which
was not damaged, Americans from all branches of the military and
State Department dashed in and out, sometimes stopping to hug one
another. Staff members worked out the logistics of arriving
American missions, comforted families of the dead, and arranged for
the air evacuation of injured staff.
</P>
<P>
   Three injured American embassy staff, who could walk, were flown
to South Africa last night. Other injured staff will fly to Germany
later this weekend.
</P>
<P>
   In addition to the search and rescue crews, Bushnell announced
that more than 100 US officials were arriving in Nairobi by late
last night: 33 members of a medical assessment team, 19 members of
a medical evacuation team, 60 FBI personnel and other
investigators, 37 members of a disaster relief team, 50 Marines,
and 27 other military personnel.
</P>
<P>
   The Americans were eager to tell relatives and friends that they
had survived, and to share their grief. An older staff member put
down a phone somberly: ``I just had to call Washington and tell
them that someone I know is dead.''
</P>
<P>
   Americans who work at the embassy said they were still stunned
by the enormity of the bombings. The main danger in Kenya was
supposed to be street crime.
</P>
<P>
   ``Because of the all the work, we have not had time to ponder
the terrible losses,'' said Chris Scharf, the US press attache.
``There is no one here who has not lost a friend, an acquaintance,
or a colleague. But if you want to get everything done, you just
can't think about it.''
</P>
<P>
   &UR; ufauthor &LR;
</P>
<P>
   Marcus filed from Washington, Useem from Nairobi. Material from
the Associated Press was also used.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
