<TEXT>
<P>
   ATTENTION EDITORS: The following photos are part of tonight's
New York Times Photo Package, moving Saturday 8/8/98. Photo clients
will automatically receive these photos via AP's PhotoExpress or
may download them from either the Wieck Photo Database in Dallas at
972-392-0888 or from NYTPhotos on Newscom at 305-448-8411.
Non-clients can make individual purchases by calling 212-556-4204.
</P>
<P>
   (NYT7) NEW ROCHELLE, N.Y. -- Aug. 8, 1998 -- GLF-SANDS, 8-8 --
George Sands, who celebrated his 97th birthday on Aug. 6, at the
Wykagyl Country Club, in New Rochelle, N.Y. Sands is the oldest
golf official in the United States -- and probably the world. ``I
love being around the golf course,'' says Sands. ``The last time I
played was last year, but I love being around the course and
working for golf.'' (Susan Farley/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT6) LITTLE FALLS, N.J. -- Aug. 8, 1998 -- BBO-ARATON-COLUMN,
8-8 -- Pete Rose Jr., signing autographs at a New Jersey Jackals
minor league game at Yogi Berra Stadium, in Little Falls, N.J.
Rose, who finally got a taste of the big leagues last season with
the Cincinnati Reds, was handed his minor league walking papers
this season by the Pittsburgh Pirates. ``I'll just swallow my
pride,'' Rose says. (Norman Y. Lono/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT5) LOS ANGELES -- Aug. 8, 1998 -- LA-CRUISNG, 8-8 -- The
ritual of cruising Crenshaw Boulevard in Los Angeles, now takes
place in a parking lot, because of a crackdown by the Los Angeles
Police Department. The police have been trying to rid Crenshaw of
cruisers for at least the last two years. As the crown jewel of the
urban social scene, the cruise draws parents and children, blacks
and Latinos, teachers and students, and gang members who set aside
their rivalries for a day to celebrate cars in the capital of car
culture. (Jill Connelly/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT4) SAN FRANCISCO -- Aug. 8, 1998 -- HAIGHT-ASHBURY, 8-8 --
Beth, 18, is part of the new generation on the streets of The
Haight in San Francisco, ground zero of the 1960s counterculture
revolution. A native of Austin, Texas, she sleeps in a park and
begs for money. While the now romanticized flower children of The
Haight were painted as being spiritually connected by political
ideology and the haze of a marijuana high, many young people on the
same streets today share the common pain of broken lives and harder
drugs. (Darcy Padilla/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT3) HOLLYWOOD, Fla. -- Aug. 8, 1998 -- ALLIGATOR-WRESTLING,
8-8 -- Paul Simmons, an alligator handler, selects an alligator for
a wrestling demonstration at a wildlife park in Hollywood, Fla.
Alligator wrestlers say that in an age of growing environmental
awareness and competition for tourists, they gear most shows toward
educating visitors about the habits and characteristics of the
Florida alligator, rather than staging a battle. (Gary I.
Rothstein/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT2) ROME -- Aug. 8, 1998 -- EUROPE-AIRCON, 8-8 -- An Italian
family investigating air-conditioners at the Cucciolo housewares
store in Rome. Unlike the past, when Europeans traditionally just
slowed down and endured the summer heat, many who are now used to
air-conditioned cars and workplaces increasingly want to cool their
homes as well. In Europe, sales of air-conditioners for homes and
small businesses, are expected to reach $3.2 billion this year.
(James Hill/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT1) ALANG, India -- Aug. 8, 1998 -- SHIP-GRAVEYARD, 8-8 -- A
migrant worker stripping a ship's metal for scrap, in Alang, India.
Once a poverty-stricken village, Alang has become the world's
biggest shipbreaking yard. In the 1990s, Alang has served as the
graveyard for almost half the ships scrapped by the world's navies
and merchant marines. (John F. Burns/New York Times Photo)
</P>
