<HEADER>
A4598 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BBO-BBNOTES-CLEMENS-B     08-08 2804
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBO-BBNOTES-CLEMENS-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
A CLEMENS RETURN? JUST ASKING 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By GORDON EDES  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Yes, Gord Ash said, the Red Sox called about Roger Clemens
before the trading deadline.
</P>
<P>
   ``Once word got out on the street that Roger might be
available,'' said Ash, the general manager of the Toronto Blue
Jays, ``we received a lot of inquiries from a lot of clubs. The Red
Sox were one of them.''
</P>
<P>
   Clemens was one of the few big-ticket Blue Jays who was not
moved by Ash in a house-cleaning in which they traded closer Randy
Myers, third baseman Ed Sprague, starting pitcher Juan Guzman, DH
Mike Stanley, and utilityman Tony Phillips.
</P>
<P>
   ``No matter what people think of Roger in Boston,'' Ash said,
``we were not going to give up a pitcher of his caliber for
`maybes.' We were looking for veterans who were visible and
prominent, and we didn't get that.''
</P>
<P>
   The Blue Jays came close with one club. Rangers GM Doug Melvin
made a strong pitch for Clemens but in the end decided he wouldn't
give up starting left fielder Rusty Greer. Instead, while literally
working two phones simultaneously, Melvin swung deals within
minutes with the Cardinals for starter Todd Stottlemyre and with
the Marlins for third baseman Todd Zeile.
</P>
<P>
   ``If we had traded Rusty,'' Melvin said, ``we would have just
been creating another hole.''
</P>
<P>
   Zeile already has made a big impact both offensively and
defensively for the Rangers. He hit home runs in his first two
games, converted seven chances against the Red Sox on Thursday, and
took away extra bases from Mike Stanley with a diving stop Friday.
Stottlemyre won his first start for the Rangers and will face John
Wasdin of the Sox tonight.
</P>
<P>
   In Toronto, meanwhile, both Ash and Clemens have come under
withering criticism. Ash, a former groundskeeper for the Jays who
has worked in almost every capacity for the club over the last 20
years, is being held accountable for the performance of a team that
was marketed this season under the slogan, ``Bring It On,'' but
never was in contention.
</P>
<P>
   Clemens, meanwhile, has been held up to ridicule by Toronto
columnists for saying that he wanted to bring a winner to the city
yet had his agents ask Ash to explore trading him to a contender.
</P>
<P>
   ``Roger was and is frustrated,'' Ash said from his SkyDome
office Friday. ``Obviously, he has been a tremendous competitor and
performer for us. He has aspirations for this ball club, and once
more they didn't come together.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's of a mixed mind. On one hand, I understand his desire and
need to be with a winner. He sees his career winding down. But this
has also been a very comfortable place for him and his family.
</P>
<P>
   ``We were never in a situation like Seattle (with Randy
Johnson), where we had to move him no matter what. He has two more
years left on his contract.''
</P>
<P>
   Ash would not rule out trading Clemens this winter. That, he
said, will depend on the direction the organization intends to
take, which will be determined in meetings with ownership in the
coming weeks.
</P>
<P>
   He defended the deals he did make. With Guzman, he said, the
Blue Jays didn't want to be locked into a $5 million salary next
season, especially when they felt Kelvim Escobar was ready to step
into the rotation. He had only good things to say about Stanley,
both as a person and as a player, but moving him enabled the Jays
to make Jose Canseco strictly a DH and summon Jose Cruz Jr. back
from the minors.
</P>
<P>
   Phillips was worth moving for the pitching prospect they got
from the Mets in return, while the club had decided it wouldn't
pick up the salary option on Sprague for next season.
</P>
<P>
   Myers was a salary dump, freeing them from a $12 million
obligation to a closer who did not perform up to expectations.
</P>
<P>
   At this point, Ash said, the Blue Jays would like Canseco to
return next season as DH.
</P>
<P>
   ``He gave us no reason this year not to be interested,'' Ash
said.
</P>
<P>
   Whether they can afford him remains to be seen. The Blue Jays
have some hard decisions to make, especially with the Canadian
dollar falling to 65 cents US, the lowest point it has ever been,
according to Ash.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's pretty clear in the American League East,'' Ash said,
``that if you're going to be a contender, you've got to spend big.
The Yankees spend big, the Orioles are not going to change their
approach, and Boston has stepped up big.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're not capable of spending that kind of money. I can't
dream of having a $60 million or $70 million payroll. We have an
issue unique to ourselves and one other club (Montreal). The
Canadian dollar is sinking every day. That's not an excuse, that's
a fact of life.
</P>
<P>
   ``We can't operate on the basis of significant losses. For us to
spend $50 million on payroll, that really means we have to take in
$75 million to pay that.''
</P>
<P>
   And that's not happening, not with attendance and TV ratings
down from the early '90s.
</P>
<P>
   The Blue Jays' situation has some calling for a savior, and
there are people who think they know exactly the man who fits that
bill: Pat Gillick, the original architect of the club who almost
certainly will leave the Orioles after this season.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a rumor that won't go away,'' Ash acknowledged. ``Pat has
a reputation of a genius, a guru here, and deservedly so. People
think he can come back and fix it. If that is being thought of,
it's by people above me.''
</P>
<P>
   For now, Ash's bosses have expressed their support for the GM,
and the likelihood of Gillick coming back would seem to be a long
shot.
</P>
<P>
   Ash confirmed that when the Blue Jays were in Boston and he was
trying to close the deal for Stanley, Sox GM Dan Duquette wouldn't
meet with him, even though the men bumped in the hallway leading to
the pressbox. Instead, Ash met with Duquette's aide, Lee Thomas.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's not a big deal,'' Ash said. ``I don't know if Dan has a
problem with me, and I don't know why, if he does. But the bottom
line is getting the transaction done. Lee acted as the broker, like
when you're buying a house and going through a realtor.''
</P>
<P>
   ___ &QC;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Bob Starr &LR; , the former Red Sox broadcaster who also was a
sports anchor on WBZ-TV and the voice of Patriots and Boston
College football, was called the ``best radio announcer I've ever
heard'' by  &UR; Bob Costas &LR; , &UR;  &LR; who worked at KMOX in St. Louis when
Starr was there.
</P>
<P>
   ``He was a good baseball announcer,'' Costas told the St. Louis
Post-Dispatch after Starr's death last week at 65, ``but he was a
great football announcer. Bob Starr was a warm and decent man.''
</P>
<P>
   Current Sox radio announcer  &UR; Joe Castiglione &LR; , &UR;  &LR; who was Starr's
broadcast partner when he was here, said that when Starr was with
the Angels,  &UR; Reggie Jackson  &LR; insisted that Starr be on the air to
call his 500th home run.
</P>
<P>
   Starr, whose father laid oil pipes in Oklahoma, played football
at Kansas and while he was in the Army, he played baseball against
 &UR; Joe Morgan &LR; , &UR;  &LR; the former Sox manager. Starr had hopes of signing a
contract with the Pirates, but GM  &UR; Branch Rickey  &LR; didn't offer him
a contract. As Castiglione tells it, Starr heard about an opening
at a local radio station, but was hesitant to apply.
</P>
<P>
   That's when his father stepped in. ``Well, you can talk, can't
you?''  &UR; Harry Starr  &LR; said to his son. ``There's not much more to it
than that.''
</P>
<P>
   With Bob Starr, of course, as with  &UR; Jack Brickhouse &LR; , &UR;  &LR; the Spink
Award-winning broadcaster who did both Cubs and White Sox games and
died last week of cardiac arrest at age 82, there was so much more.
They will be missed.
</P>
<P>
   ___ &QC;
</P>
<P>
   Sox pitching coach  &UR; Joe Kerrigan  &LR; said  &UR; Pedro Martinez's
 &LR; fastball Friday night was the type you see from him just a few
times all season. But Martinez was too strong and rushed his
delivery early, and was hurt by  &UR; Will Clark's  &LR; home run on a
3-and-0 pitch. On 32 previous occasions in which Clark faced a
3-and-0 pitch, he'd swung just three times, making two outs and
fouling off a pitch. Sox manager  &UR; Jimy Williams  &LR; yelled from the
dugout, ``He's swinging, he's swinging,'' to no avail ...  &UR; Cecil
Fielder &LR; , &UR;  &LR; designated for assignment by the Angels last week, told
friends last weekend that he expected something to happen when the
Red Sox were in Anaheim. He hinted at some friction with manager
 &UR; Terry Collins &LR; , &UR;  &LR; even though Collins called Big Daddy one of the
classiest professionals around. What the Angels are left with now
is a left fielder ( &UR; Garret Anderson &LR; ) &UR;  &LR; playing right field, a third
baseman ( &UR; Dave Hollins &LR; ) &UR;  &LR; playing first base, a first-year pro
( &UR; Troy Glaus &LR; ) &UR;  &LR; playing third base, and a former catcher ( &UR; Todd
Greene &LR; ) &UR;  &LR; available to play left field, first base, DH, and pinch
hit, a role the veteran Fielder wasn't eager to accept ... It's not
a question of whether ousted Red Sox farm director  &UR; Bob Schaefer
 &LR; will get another job in baseball. It's a matter of which job he
intends to take. He's already been contacted by a number of clubs.
Some Schaefer allies say he tried to do too much with the Red Sox
and needs to delegate more duties in the future ... A key to the
success of  &UR; Hideki Irabu &LR; , who looked like he might be a  &UR; George
Steinbrenner &LR;  folly last season? The New York Times last week paid
tribute to Irabu's interpreter,  &UR; George Rose &LR;  (Holy Cross Class of
'88). Rose went to Japan a year after graduating to teach English,
became fluent in Japanese, and has been at Irabu's side all year
... Don't look now, but the Sox and Orioles meet six times in the
last 12 games. The Orioles, 12 games under .500 at the All-Star
break, were 21-5 since then as of Saturday. There's no overstating
what an inspiration  &UR; Eric Davis  &LR; continues to be to cancer
patients. Davis, who last season had surgery for colon cancer and
has undergone chemotherapy and radiation treatments, has led the
Orioles' surge with a 23-game hitting streak that began with a
grand slam against the Red Sox right after the break. He has hit 10
home runs during the streak, the longest of his career, and the
Orioles are now quietly negotiating a two-year contract extension
with the outfielder ... There's little doubt that the Padres'
decision to claim Myers on waivers was a ``Hollywood Squares''
move: They took Myers to block him from going to the Atlanta
Braves. The stunning aspect of the move, of course, is that the
Padres are obligated to pay Myers a guaranteed $12 million for the
next two seasons, plus $1.1 million for the rest of this season.
That's a ton of dough for a setup man, which is the role Myers will
assume for closer  &UR; Trevor Hoffman &LR; . But the Padres, who face an
important stadium vote in November, were ecstatic to deny the
Braves a potential closer, while picking up a lefthander in the
pen, which they needed. Myers was the Padres' closer back in '92.
``We like this deal better than Randy Johnson,'' San Diego GM
 &UR; Kevin Towers  &LR; said. ``We didn't have to mortgage our future. And
it shortens our games to six or seven innings.''
</P>
<P>
   ___ &QC;
</P>
<P>
   High praise from former MVP  &UR; Ken Caminiti  &LR; of the Padres for
Phillies third baseman  &UR; Scott Rolen &LR; : ``I guarantee that he hasn't
reached his full potential. He is a player who is an All-Star and a
MVP. He not only can carry a team. He can carry a team to a
championship.'' ...  &UR; Jim Thome's  &LR; broken pinky finger may have
postseason implications for the Red Sox. Without Thome for the next
4-5 weeks, the Indians will be hard-pressed to maintain a better
record than the AL West-leading Rangers. If the Red Sox win the
wild card, they'll meet the division winner that has the next-best
record to the Yankees. Thus, if the Rangers pass the Indians, the
Sox will open the first round of the playoffs Sept. 29 at The
Ballpark in Arlington ... Pirates pitcher  &UR; Jason Schmidt &LR; , &UR;  &LR; who
began the season 8-1, is now 8-9. The Pirates pitcher who had a
similar winless streak was  &UR; Tim Wakefield &LR; , &UR;  &LR; who was 0-9 over 13
starts for the Bucs in 1993. Schmidt is unhappy about what he
perceives as a nonchalant attitude toward losing on the part of his
teammates. ``Every day it's the same thing,'' he said. ``You come
in, and everybody's rah-rah, like we won 10 in a row.'' ... Tough
National League debut for former Sox farmhand  &UR; Joe Hudson &LR; , who
went to the Brewers 10 days ago in a deal for minor league
infielder  &UR; Eddy Diaz &LR; . Hudson faced seven batters Friday night for
Milwaukee. Six of them scored in the Reds' 12-run explosion, the
biggest inning ever against the Brewers. Hudson threw 27 pitches,
just eight for strikes. ``It was a tough situation for him,''
Brewers manager  &UR; Phil Garner  &LR; said. ``He came in with no breathing
room and he had a tough outing.'' ... The Cubs have some interest
in  &UR; Gary Gaetti &LR; , &UR;  &LR; the soon-to-be 40-year-old Cardinals third
baseman who was designated for assignment Saturday. But he has some
contract incentives that might cause the Cubs to pass ... Former
Sox pitcher  &UR; Ken Brett &LR; , &UR;  &LR; who pitched in the '67 World Series as a
19-year-old and was a broadcast partner of Starr's, had a brain
tumor removed this spring. Brett, 50, has returned to the broadcast
booth for fX after undergoing radiation treatment. ``Mine is a good
story,'' Brett told the Los Angeles Times, ``because I'm not going
to die. I lost some hair, but I can live with that.'' ... New
Dodgers pitcher  &UR; Carlos Perez &LR; , &UR;  &LR; who was torched in a 9-0 loss to
his former team, the Expos, still has pain in his right
(nonthrowing) shoulder stemming from a car accident in Montreal in
which he ran into a light pole. It restricts how much Perez turns
in his delivery.
</P>
<P>
   ___ &QC;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Wade Boggs  &LR; is not going to reach 3,000 hits this season, nor
is he going to get the 500 plate appearances needed to guarantee
his contract with Tampa Bay for 1999. That raises questions about
what is to become of the 40-year-old third baseman, who gave his
hometown expansion franchise a big slice of credibility but also
knows that rookie  &UR; Bobby Smith  &LR; will play more third base next
season. The Devil Rays have an option for Boggs in '99 but won't
say whether they plan to pick it up. Boggs came into the weekend
121 hits shy of 3,000. ``Would he have a chance to get 3,000 hits
if he's back next year? Yeah, he probably would,'' Tampa Bay
manager  &UR; Larry Rothschild  &LR; said. ``Does that mean Bobby Smith
doesn't play as much as he needs to play? I couldn't let 3,000 hits
get in the way of that. But yet I'll still be very aware of where
Wade is and what has to be done, just because it is such a
tremendous milestone. It's good for the organization and good for
baseball in general for people to follow. I can't think of a more
thrilling time than what you would see here when he got close.''
... Despite an unbelievable stretch in which he hit nine home runs
in 30 at-bats, including a pinch-hit grand slam in the ninth inning
to tie a game the Yankees went on to win, 10-5,  &UR; Darryl Strawberry
 &LR; still may have his playing time cut. Yankees manager  &UR; Joe Torre
 &LR; maintains that when  &UR; Chili Davis &LR;  is healthy enough to return to
the lineup during the next homestand, he will serve as the regular
DH. Strawberry may get an opportunity to play left field if his
left knee allows him enough mobility ...  &UR; Larry Herndon &LR; , &UR;  &LR; fired as
the Tigers' hitting coach and replaced by  &UR; Toby Harrah &LR; , &UR;  &LR; was the
last man in a Detroit uniform who had a link to the club's most
recent championships: their world title in 1984 and East Division
crown in 1987. He hit the decisive homer in Game 1 of the 1984
World Series and in the final-day, regular-season showdown with
Toronto in 1987 that put the Tigers in the playoffs. No Tigers
player or coach goes back with the club even to 1994 ... Do you get
the impression that Williams, who refused to bump  &UR; Steve Avery
 &LR; from the Sox rotation, was less than wild about the team's trade
for  &UR; Pete Schourek &LR; ? Perhaps Williams figures that if Schourek
could be a big contributor down the stretch, the Astros, who are
trying to win the NL Central, never would have let him go ...
Planning for post-Mo? The Sox are discussing moving  &UR; Dernell
Stenson &LR; , &UR;  &LR; the 20-year-old, lefthanded-hitting outfielder who leads
Double A Trenton in home runs, to first base ...  &UR; Shane
Spencer &LR; , &UR;  &LR; the Yankee rookie who filled in for  &UR; Paul O'Neill
 &LR; Friday night and went 5 for 5: ``I never had five hits in my life.
Not even in Little League.'' ... Orioles ace  &UR; Mike Mussina  &LR; has
flirted with a perfect game twice within the last year: 25 outs in
a row last season, 23 last week until Tigers rookie  &UR; Frank
Catalanotto  &LR; doubled into the right-field corner with two outs in
the eighth inning. ``Everybody thinks doing something like this is
disappointing,'' Mussina said. ``I don't know why that is.
No-hitters and perfect games are unique experiences. I'm just happy
that I could pitch as well as I did. I'm not here to be a guy who
throws five no-hitters and wins 400-some games. I'm here to pitch
and compete and do what I can.''
</P>
