<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HKN-NHLNOTES-STEVEHEINZE-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HEINZE SHOWS HIS HAND 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By NANCY L. MARRAPESE  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Steve Heinze jokes that for an unemployed hockey player, he's
very busy this summer.
</P>
<P>
   He has been working out regularly at Mike Boyle's Sports
Acceleration North in Burlington, he recently became engaged, and
he's been playing golf and participating in charity events. The one
thing he hasn't done lately is negotiate with the Bruins, who own
his rights.
</P>
<P>
   Heinze, a Group 2 (restricted) free agent, and his
representative, Steve Mountain, have taken a rather novel approach
to negotiations: They told the truth right out of the gate. The
28-year-old right wing is asking for a two-year contract for $1.15
million next season and $1.3 million in 1999-2000. They don't want
any more, but Heinze said he won't take any less. He didn't go in
asking for the moon. He asked for exactly what he thought he should
earn.
</P>
<P>
   It was a risky move, considering most players go in asking for
much more than they want, knowing that when the contract is finally
resolved, they will have to settle for less. Most teams, likewise,
offer less than they're willing to pay, and the sides come to an
agreement somewhere in the middle.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm being as honest as I can be,'' said Heinze. ``I can
probably make more on the open market, but I also realize I play
for the Bruins. I'm an honest guy; I believe that's what I deserve
to get paid. It's consistent with the team and the league, and
(management) didn't hit that number (with their offer). Were they
way off? No. But they weren't at it.
</P>
<P>
   ``You always hear the word `loyalty,' and it's thrown around a
little bit too easily, I think. It is a business. I would love to
be loyal to this team if I thought they'd be loyal to me on all
levels. Once you're under contract to the Bruins, there is a lot of
loyalty and you wear that B and you wear it with pride. Every
summer when you don't have the B on and you're unemployed, it's
kind of on a different level. We're going in with the number we
want, and we're not going to move. If it goes right up to camp,
then it will be decision time.''
</P>
<P>
   For the last couple of years, Heinze has signed one-year
contracts and had no leverage in negotiations either because his
statistics didn't support a big salary increase or, in the case of
the 1996-97 season, he was limited to 30 games because of injuries,
though he scored 17 goals. Last season, Heinze was the club's
fifth-leading scorer with 26 goals and 46 points in 61 games and
made $650,000.
</P>
<P>
   With the Bruins having so many free agents to sign this summer,
including leading scorer Jason Allison and defenseman Kyle McLaren,
Heinze said he's not sure what's going to happen.
</P>
<P>
   ``If everybody gets settled before camp, and I'm the only guy
hanging out, it's different than five of us hanging out,'' said
Heinze. ``If there are five of us, do they cave in to Allison
because he has the most points? Do they cave in to me because I've
been here longest? It will be up to Harry (Sinden).
</P>
<P>
   ``I've never seen it happen, so I don't know. I've seen Cam
(Neely hold out); I've seen Glen Wesley do it. But that was
different than the Al Iafrate fiasco. I don't know how Harry would
handle it.''
</P>
<P>
   This time, Heinze believes he has the leverage to support his
demands. He and Mountain negotiated with the team right up until
the arbitration filing deadline. Heinze opted not to file, saying
he didn't want to put his future in the hands of a third party and
the process was too much of a crapshoot, anyway. The fact is, too,
that there were few comparable players that Heinze could use to
support his unusual position.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think it's going to be a hard-fought battle because we do
have a bit more leverage,'' said Heinze. ``Not that we caved in the
last few years, but we really didn't have a bargaining chip of 26
goals and things like that. We're talking higher numbers than we
talked in the past, and obviously that will be more intense.''
</P>
<P>
   Heinze feels he has given in the last couple of years and this
time, it's the club's turn.
</P>
<P>
   ``You always want to make what everybody else is making and be
the high-paid guy,'' said Heinze. ``I knew I was good enough to do
it with that 17-goal season in 30 games. I wanted to get paid as a
30-goal scorer, but with past precedents and what I only did for 30
games, it was understandable that the Bruins wouldn't pay me as a
30-goal scorer.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was frustrating but in the same sense, it was somewhat
understandable that they would go that way. I wouldn't say I was
overjoyed with the deal, but I was content, I guess. I don't think
if you talk to anybody, they've ever been overjoyed with a deal in
Boston. They deal hard and they don't give it away, from Ray
Bourque right on down. It's a business and they deal with it that
way.''
</P>
<P>
   With Dmitri Khristich and Rob Tallas scheduled for arbitration
hearings this week and the Bruins' other free agents up for new
pacts, Heinze is not sure when he and the Bruins will get back to
the table. He expects that it could go right down to training camp
or beyond. He is prepared to sit if necessary.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'd love to stay here, but if push comes to shove, I
understand I can move on,'' he said. ``Now I know I'm good enough
to score in this league on any team that wants to have me.
</P>
<P>
   ``I definitely want to stay here. I wouldn't want to hold out,
but if it comes to that, yeah, I'm prepared to. I do like it here
as long as I'm going to get a chance to play. It is still a game,
and I'd play it for $5 if everybody in the league was getting paid
$5 to score 26 goals.''
</P>
<P>
   If there is a criticism of Heinze, it's that he has been a
streaky player. After a good regular season, Heinze had zero points
in six playoff games against the Washington Capitals.
</P>
<P>
   ``That damn team _ I never score against them,'' he said. ``One
game, I had eight shots on net. I don't think I played terribly
bad. My minutes didn't decrease. I don't think (coach Pat Burns)
was unhappy with my efforts. It's just that the damn puck wouldn't
go in the net. (Washington goalie) Ollie (Kolzig) was standing on
his head.
</P>
<P>
   ``Obviously, I've had some highs and lows. It's something I've
always tried to work on. I'll have five or six games with no goals
then five or six in a row scoring goals. Harry has mentioned that
in negotiations, he wants more consistency.''
</P>
<P>
   Despite the current stalemate, Heinze is optimistic that he will
be back playing for Boston and will get what he wants.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've actually been pretty relaxed so far this summer,'' he
said. ``When (camp) gets closer, maybe I'll think about it more.
I'm good enough to play in this league. I don't want to sit out a
whole year. I don't want to be what's-his-face from Pittsburgh,
Petr Nedved. I'm not asking for that kind of money, so I don't
think it will come to that.
</P>
<P>
   ``Things tend to work out. That's why I have an agent. That's
why you pay him, so he can lose sleep over it.''
</P>
<P>
   ___ &QC;
</P>
<P>
   Reading the news out of Western Canada, it's hard to say whether
the saga of Vancouver star  &UR; Pavel Bure  &LR; is a soap opera or material
for a suspense novel. Bure has said he doesn't want to play for the
Canucks anymore. That stuff happens all the time. But with Bure,
it's more bizarre. The moody Russian said he's tired of being in
the limelight, that fans in Vancouver won't leave him alone. He
wants to be traded to a contender and wants a shot at the Stanley
Cup. Think he can do that in a vacuum? If you want to be traded,
fine. No big deal. It's hardly unprecedented in any sport. But if
he wants out for the reasons he says and wants to play in a cave so
no one knows him, Bure should realize that no one will pay him the
approximately $8 million a year he is due to make now. This
ridiculous situation is the headache of new GM  &UR; Brian Burke &LR; , &UR;  &LR; who
has to decide where to trade Bure. Burke, no shrinking violet, told
Bure and anyone else within earshot that he will trade Bure to
whatever team gives him the right deal, and if he doesn't get it by
the time the season opens, then Bure will be suspended if he
follows through on his threat to sit out. Can anyone say, ``Too big
for your britches,'' in Russian? No one put it better than Flyers
GM  &UR; Bobby Clarke &LR; , &UR;  &LR; who said, ``If he wants to get lost, tell him
to go back to Moscow.'' ... Speaking of Clarke, he minced no words
when discussing Flyers captain  &UR; Eric Lindros &LR; , &UR;  &LR; who is rumored to
be on the trading block. ``If you want to be the highest-paid
player in the game or close to it, you've got to play that way,''
Clarke told the Philadelphia Inquirer. ``You're not a kid anymore.
He's 25 years old, and he's been in the league six years. It's
time. If you're going to pay him $8.5 million (Lindros's salary for
the upcoming season), you hope to get more games out of Eric. And
better games. ... You can't keep paying someone on potential.'' ...
The Maple Leafs announced last week that  &UR; Rick Ley  &LR; has been hired
as assistant coach to  &UR; Pat Quinn  &LR; and  &UR; Terry Simpson &LR; , &UR;  &LR; an interim
assistant coach for two years, would not be retained.
</P>
<P>
   ___ &QC;
</P>
<P>
   Looks like Colorado goalie  &UR; Patrick Roy  &LR; may have to throw his
jersey in the dryer to shrink it before the start of the season.
The league has announced it will crack down on all the goalie
equipment, not just the pads and blockers it regulated last year.
Now jerseys, pants, chest protectors, and arm pads will be
targeted. Eventually, catching gloves will be regulated. According
to the new rules, the jersey may not be wider than 29 inches across
the chest, 30 across the hips, 9 at the wrist, and 14 from the
front of the shoulder to the back. No inserts or additions may be
made and the shirt can't be longer than 32 inches. The pant legs
will be restricted to 11 inches across the thigh. While the Players
Association was in on the new restrictions, not all the players
were ecstatic, especially Buffalo netminder  &UR; Dominik
Hasek &LR; , &UR;  &LR; who &UR;  &LR; won the Hart Trophy as Most Valuable Player the last
two years. ``Amazing,'' Hasek told The Sporting News. ``A goalie is
named MVP for the first time since 1963. Then he wins the award
again. And now everyone in the league wants to change the rules
because they say goaltenders are cheating. The next thing you know,
they will prevent us from leaving the goal crease, they'll reduce
the size of equipment to the size our kids use, and maybe even make
us play without a mask.'' The fact is, this isn't a safety issue.
Give someone an inch, they'll take a mile. The NHL has decided to
take back the mile. ``I can't say we didn't see this coming,'' said
Toronto's  &UR; Curtis Joseph &LR; , &UR;  &LR; who was part of a group of netminders
who met near Ottawa to discuss the situation. ``You probably
couldn't absolve anyone of wearing some form of illegal equipment,
although shoulder pads like the ones  &UR; Garth Snow  &LR; wears and
sweaters like the kind Patrick Roy and  &UR; Trevor Kidd  &LR; wore last
season were obviously illegal to almost everyone. With the pads he
had on last year, Trevor Kidd could almost cover the whole net.''
... 62 days to Opening Night.
</P>
</TEXT>
