u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BKO-RYAN-COLUMN-BOS &LR;      08-08 0988
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKO-RYAN-COLUMN-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
USA STOPPED SHORT OF GOLD 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By BOB RYAN  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATHENS _ There was a 10-point lead with 3:09 to go. And then
there was nothing but self-destruction, agony, and, ultimately, the
numbing shock of seeing a 6-foot-10-inch forward named Serguei
Panov drive three-quarters of the floor to sink an easy layup with
2.9 seconds remaining that gave Russia a 66-64 victory in the World
Basketball Championships.
</P>
<P>
   There is no doubt the United States thought it had Saturday's
semifinal game won when Jimmy King tomahawked one home on a
two-on-one fast-break feed to make it 64-54 with 3:09 to go. It was
a fatal miscalculation.
</P>
<P>
   ``There was still a three-minute game left. They played like a
veteran team, and we played like a young team,'' sighed David Wood,
who badly wanted a gold medal to validate his vagabond basketball
existence over these past 10 years.
</P>
<P>
   But he will have to settle for a bronze, at best. The gold is
going elsewhere. In the mini-game that mattered, Russia outscored
the United States, 12-0. It wasn't just a giveaway, either; the
winners must have done something right.
</P>
<P>
   There will be justified talk about calls and non-calls and it is
true, as Rudy Tomjanovich said, that, ``It was a horrible display
of one-sidedness.'' by the officiating duo of Slovenia's Izstok
Rems and Argentina's Paul Chavez.
</P>
<P>
   But it is also true that the US blunders in the final three
minutes would not have mattered had Sergei Babkov not made them pay
with two monster threes, or if the 28-year-old Panov, one of seven
Russian players who had been twice thrashed by the omnipotent NBA
stars four years ago in Toronto, had not had the basketball brains
to ignore coaching instructions to feed the rampaging Babkov (30)
and take it to the rack himself.
</P>
<P>
   ``That definitely surprised us,'' said Wood. ``The guy made a
great play.''
</P>
<P>
   As a final sad coda, Wendell Alexis almost made a better one.
The US resident graybeard (34) sank a potential 35-foot game-winner
in response to Panov _ but it was clearly a tick or two after the
clock had moved to 0:00.
</P>
<P>
   Even then, Rudy had a legitimate lament, because someone on the
Russian team had touched the ball after Panov's shot, and in this
game, that's a no-no.
</P>
<P>
   ``Earlier in the tournament,'' Rudy pointed out, ``we got a
technical for doing that. There should have been one then.''
</P>
<P>
   How do you say ``fat chance'' in the World Basketball
Championships language of your choice?
</P>
<P>
   The embattled US was not going to get this, or any other call,
in those painful final three minutes, and Rudy knew it.
</P>
<P>
   ``Let's face it,'' he said. ``We had to overcome some horrible
calls. But from the start we knew what we'd be up against, and I
told our guys we couldn't use the referees as an excuse. We had a
margin, and it just wasn't big enough.''
</P>
<P>
   The US would have won if it had kept its head, and remembered
where it was. Michael Hawkins plays right here in Greece, so he
should know. He should know that if the score is tied (64-64) and
you stick your off-hand out as you make a move, an experienced
player such as Russia's Vassilij Karassev is going to execute a
classic phony flop, and that he will get the call. That's precisely
what happened with 10 seconds left.
</P>
<P>
   But to dwell on the officiating inequities down the stretch is
to likewise ignore the fact that Hawkins had two good looks at
threes (1:37 and 1:04) and he missed them, and that Babkov had his
own looks at a pair of vital threes, the first when trailing by 6
and the second when trailing by 3, and he buried his.
</P>
<P>
   ``We made mistakes,'' sighed Rudy T, ``and they took advantage
of their opportunities. Babkov was a player on a mission, and we
had no answer.''
</P>
<P>
   Adding to the Russian saga was Babkov's absence during the first
10:38 of the second half. Sometime in the midst of torching the US
for 20 first-half points, the smooth Russian guard sustained a
sprained ankle. When he made his first appearance of the second
half, his team was down 8, 58-50.
</P>
<P>
   Until those final three minutes, the US was on its way to an
ultimate team triumph. The no-name, multi-rejected, off-Broadway
substitute for our pampered NBA idealogues were winning a game
against a good international foe with just one man _ starting
center Gerard King (oh, sure, you remember him) in double figures,
and that was 10.
</P>
<P>
   There were times you'd say to yourself, or perhaps the guy next
to you, ``How are they doing this?,'' because it never felt like
they were ahead, and because Babkov was firing away with impunity.
</P>
<P>
   ``I played with him in Spain last year,'' said Wood. ``He'll do
something like that once every five games.''
</P>
<P>
   But the US was finding a way. They'd have a little run here and
they'd make a steal there, and people such as King, Ashraf Amaya,
and Alexis were holding the Russians to one shot. And when King
echoed those Fab Five memories with that big slam, the championship
game was within sight.
</P>
<P>
   Now they must pull themselves together for a bronze medal game
against Greece.
</P>
<P>
   ``We basically shot ourselves in the foot,'' said Amaya. ``This
is what some people back home thought we were going to do. We had a
chance to make people eat crow.''
</P>
<P>
   There had been a growing concern among the Europeans that a US
victory here would have been nothing less than a catastrophe for
the sport. The thinking was it is one thing to lose to pedigreed
NBA stars with the seven- and eight-figure incomes and the bulging
portfolios, and another thing to lose to guys who specialize in
attending tryout camps, or who are just pretty good players in
Europe.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are not Yugoslavia; this is the very best team we have,''
lamented one Russian observer.
</P>
<P>
   It's a nice team, and it's going to play for the gold Sunday.
The US squad is going to want those last three minutes back
forever.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
