</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-NFLNOTES-BRUCEARMSTRONG-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ARMSTRONG NOT READY TO GIVE IN 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By NICK CAFARDO  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR; SMITHFIELD, R.I. _ This time, the heartache lasted longer than
it used to, just as all the other aches are starting to for Bruce
Armstrong.
</P>
<P>
   Losing has always hurt Armstrong, who for so many years was the
very best player on some very bad Patriot teams. Even in some of
the darkest years, he never seemed able to accept that his team was
going to lose and lose and lose some more, and that caused him
great pain and frustration, which cannot be said of all his former
teammates.
</P>
<P>
   But last season's ending was different somehow. The pain was
deeper and the ache lasted longer, and Armstrong now knows why.
</P>
<P>
   The calendar made it different. Armstrong is getting old _ or,
at least, older _ in a job that has no respect for aging.
</P>
<P>
   ``The first time I ever thought about the end coming for me was
after the Pittsburgh (playoff) game,'' the six-time Pro Bowl tackle
explained. ``That was bad. It took me a week _ ah, 10 days _ to get
over it. I always thought we'd win that game. Even on the last
drive, I thought we'd win and go on to the (AFC) championship game.
</P>
<P>
   ``After all those years when you knew your season would be over
on Dec. 17 or something, it was difficult to accept. We had every
intention of changing our history in the Pittsburgh game, so to
lose, 7-6, on the last series ... it gave such a sense of finality
to the season.
</P>
<P>
   ``After I went home, I kept thinking about it. I couldn't forget
the game. Then it came to me what it was. I knew for the first time
what the end would be like for me. It was a rough week or 10
days.''
</P>
<P>
   Eventually, Armstrong got over it, just as he has gotten over so
many other losses in his 11 years in New England. It's gone now, if
not quite forgotten, and he is back at 32 to try to do a little bit
more this time. To try a little bit harder not to lose the last
game of this season.
</P>
<P>
   He is trying to do that while wearing a walking cast. There is a
bone in his leg that seems ready to give in and needs constant
shoring up, like a steep hill next to the house that needs a
retaining wall to keep it in its place. Armstrong is wearing that
cast wherever he goes, but he's also playing football the same way
as always _ intensely and with purpose.
</P>
<P>
   That's the way he intends to play tonight against the Minnesota
Vikings in an exhibition game that he could certainly skip but
won't because to do that as 33 approaches is to court your own
demise.
</P>
<P>
   But there is more to his decision than survival, just as there
was more to that loss in Pittsburgh than there seemed at first.
Simply put, you don't take days off if you want to become a
seven-pineapple guy.
</P>
<P>
   In this year's media guide, every Patriot who has gone to a Pro
Bowl in Hawaii has the blue outline of a pineapple next to his
name. Drew Bledsoe has three of them. Ben Coates has four. But no
one except the Dole Company has more pineapples in New England than
Armstrong, so he goes to work with a slight limp to keep them and
the victories coming in the hope that one day he will have a season
when his team is out of games before it's out of victories.
</P>
<P>
   ``I remember what those first years were like,'' Armstrong said
of the seasons between 1987 and Bill Parcells's arrival in 1993.
``If I'd had to spend my entire career that way, my only
accomplishment would be you made a lot of money. You wouldn't have
achieved anything. I didn't know that before.
</P>
<P>
   ``Had we won (the Super Bowl) two years ago, it might be
questionable if I'd be playing. But we didn't. That's why I wanted
to come back here and get better. You can't assume you've got 14 or
15 years to win it. I'm shooting for now.
</P>
<P>
   ``It would be rough to play all your life and never win a
championship, but I never won one in high school or college so I
know there's no guarantee.''
</P>
<P>
   There is only work and hope and the firm knowledge that, as you
get older, the pain gets worse when you lose and there's only one
way to avoid it.
</P>
<P>
   ``At some point, you gotta make a drive like the one we didn't
make in Pittsburgh,'' Armstrong said. ``Someone has to make The
Catch like Dwight Clark did for the 49ers or The Drive like John
Elway did for Denver. At some point, you've got to escalate
yourself from the rest.''
</P>
<P>
   Personally, Bruce Armstrong did that a long time ago. Now, in
his 12th season of professional football, he has but one hope for
his newest and perhaps most talent-laden team. He hopes they're
ready to join him.
</P>
<P>
   ___ &QC;
</P>
<P>
   Speculation that Patriots tight end  &UR; Ben Coates  &LR; could be the
first test case of the league's new anti-violence policy has been
overstated. First, it would apply only if Coates is convicted of
the assault charge he faces. The mere fact that he was involved in
a driveway altercation with a former girlfriend is not, in itself,
enough to compel commissioner  &UR; Paul Tagliabue  &LR; to fine or suspend
Coates. Secondly, and perhaps most important, the NFL Players
Association has never agreed to the policy's language, although it
supports the intent. ``We are not going to comment on any specific
case, but everybody is interested in making sure violence off the
field is not a part of NFL football,'' said  &UR; Doug Allen &LR; , &UR;  &LR; the
union's assistant executive director. ``But the policy itself is
not something the union has agreed to or signed off on. The
discretion the commissioner has in this area is a function of the
language in the basic agreement, not the new policy. We are
confident Paul will exercise that authority appropriately. The
commissioner has taken a deliberative and responsible approach in
deciding issues before him concerning drug policy cases, so we're
not suggesting we don't have confidence in him with this new
policy. We do. We don't oppose the notion, either, but we have
never agreed to its language so we don't feel our members can be
held to the strict language of that policy, because we didn't agree
to it.'' ... In his time, special teamer  &UR; John Henry Mills &LR;  has
played linebacker, fullback, and tight end but never for long in
first Houston and now Oakland. The six-year veteran began saying,
``I have skills,'' a few years back when asked what position he
played, since not even he could describe exactly what he did for a
living. Eventually Mills parlayed ``Mills has skills'' into a
charitable foundation of the same name. Last week he was seen at
Raider training camp wearing a cap with ``Skills, Inc.'' on the
front, and when he couldn't get a license plate reading SKILLS
(already taken, by someone else with skills, one supposes) he
settled for 5KILL5. Close enough ... While the multifaceted Raider
offense is set at the skill positions, Oakland is still looking for
a right guard. Four players have been tried there this summer, but
neither  &UR; Scott Whittaker &LR; , &UR; Derrick Graham &LR; , &UR; Darryl Ashmore &LR; , nor
 &UR; Gennaro DiNapoli  &LR; has asserted himself. DiNapoli is a rookie who
was given work with the first team last week ... Old friend  &UR; Pat
Harlow  &LR; reports that his back is fine after another operation but
says his new blond hairdo might not play in New England. ``Out here
it's trendy,'' Harlow said of the Bay area. ``Back in New England,
you're a jerk.'' ... 49ers coach  &UR; Steve Mariucci  &LR; is publicly
saying the right things about AWOL left tackle  &UR; Jamie Brown &LR; , &UR;  &LR; but
privately he was seething last week when Brown did not show up for
the first exhibition game after it was announced he would not play
because of a recurrent hamstring and groin problem. Brown told no
one he wouldn't be at 3Com Park to watch the Niners play the
Patriots. He apologized to his teammates, claiming he was
``frustrated.'' Mariucci is frustrated as well. He traded a
second-round draft pick to Denver for Brown, who had done little
with the Broncos but show promise. ``I am going to allow him to
prove to us he is what we hoped he would be,'' Mariucci said. ``I'm
going to give him an opportunity to work his way back in. When he's
ready to contribute, he'll be given every opportunity and we'll
leave it at that.'' A minute later Mariucci said, ``We had _ have _
starting expectations for him. Now that's not necessarily a given.
You know, you don't hand a guy that unless he performs to that
level, and he will be given every opportunity to show, and
hopefully that occurs soon.'' Two minutes later he was praising
 &UR; Dave Fiore &LR; , &UR;  &LR; who handled the position against the Patriots and
will do the same this weekend in San Diego. Fiore had not started a
game since he was at Hofstra in 1995.
</P>
<P>
   ___ &QC;
</P>
<P>
   On Tuesday,  &UR; Jerry Rice  &LR; participated in his first full-speed
workout of the summer and beat at least one young cornerback deep.
He also slipped and fell several times without any aftereffects to
his surgically repaired kneecap, which was broken last season when
he unwisely tried to come back too soon from an early season
injury. The 49ers have said Rice will not play in any of their
exhibition games, but Rice has told friends he might test himself
Aug. 23 at home against Miami because the game will be on natural
turf. To give you an idea of just how cautiously Rice is being
handled, at one point Tuesday cornerback  &UR; Tony Blevins  &LR; unwittingly
bumped into Rice during a seven-on-seven drill and said, ``Sorry, I
didn't know it was you.'' Rice is notorious for his workout fervor
and is not happy about the restrictions on him but is trying to
cope. ``I'm not comfortable with it, but Steve is going to make the
decision,'' Rice said. ``I feel it's always good to get some kind
of timing before that first game. But if I have to go in a little
sluggish and work my way through it, I will. I just hope that I go
out there and everything comes back without thinking about it.''
After 11 Pro Bowl seasons, Rice should be on safe ground ... Former
49ers tight end  &UR; Brent Jones  &LR; got his baptism by fire as a
journalist when he visited the Raiders' training camp as a
correspondent for CBS. As Jones walked by Raiders owner  &UR; Al
Davis &LR; , &UR;  &LR; he heard Davis mumble something about calling security.
Jones tried to explain by saying, ``Mr. Davis, I'm now with CBS,
covering the AFC.'' Davis snapped back, ``I know who you're with.
It's the other thing'' _ i.e. being an ex-49er _ ``I wonder about,
and why they let you in.'' Jones was once critical of the way Davis
ran the Raiders in comparison to the way  &UR; Eddie DeBartolo  &LR; ran the
49ers. The Raiders have had a longstanding territorial feud with
the 49ers and their former club president,  &UR; Carmen Policy &LR; , which
reportedly is the reason the two refuse to play a quite logical
preseason game ... Speaking of Policy, he seems to have saddled up
the right horse after resigning his $1.5 million-a-year job as
president of the 49ers. Policy recently joined forces with  &UR; Al
Lerner &LR; , &UR;  &LR; the credit card billionaire, to form one of an expected
half-dozen groups trying to buy the new Cleveland franchise. The
NFL has hired the investment banking firm Goldman Sachs to review
the proposals, and it won't hurt that Lerner has had a long-term
relationship with at least one of Goldman Sachs's top executives
and is a friend of former Browns owner  &UR; Art Modell &LR;  (he flew Modell
on his private plane to Baltimore when Modell was making his escape
plans from Cleveland). Although some NFL owners were peeved when
Policy quit the 49ers because they believe he's trying to convince
other potential bidders to pull out (and thus drive the price
down), he is well-known and respected among the owners who will
approve the winning bid. In other words, slam dunk for Policy as
long as the numbers are big enough on Lerner's offer sheet.
</P>
<P>
   ___ &QC;
</P>
<P>
   It's interesting that reports of a background check requested by
the Jacksonville Jaguars and Chicago Bears into a group called
Champions for Christ came only after Bears executive  &UR; Ted Phillips
 &LR; grew exasperated over the holdout of running back  &UR; Curtis Enis
 &LR; and called a Jaguar executive to inquire about an agent he knew
little about. Enis had dumped his original agents last month and
signed with  &UR; Greg Feste &LR; , &UR;  &LR; who is a friend of several members of
Champions for Christ and had never negotiated a major NFL contract.
When a clause in the contract became a sticking point, Phillips,
who thought he'd nearly closed the deal with Enis's original
agents, called the Jaguars because they have an unusual number of
players affiliated with the religious group. Now, suddenly, the
Bears and Jaguars say their concern is not Enis's holdout but that
players may be giving too much money to the group. ``We've never
had a complaint from a player about them,'' an NFLPA union source
said. ``I don't think that's what's motivating this. It has
everything to do with Enis not being in camp and not that anyone is
afraid he'll give too much money to Champions for Christ.'' The
union has monitored the negotiations, and although it concedes that
Feste has been a little more aggressive than some agents, it
insists he is not ``coming out of left field.'' ... Miami coach
 &UR; Jimmy Johnson  &LR; has been pleasantly surprised by the play of No. 1
draft choice  &UR; John Avery &LR; , who came from Mississippi with the
reputation of being a small, quick, third-down type back who could
not take enough of a pounding to play regularly. He reportedly has
shown enough in training camp to begin running with the first team
and remains in a battle with veteran  &UR; Karim Abdul-Jabbar &LR; , &UR;  &LR; who
scored 15 touchdowns last season but averaged only 3.2 yards a
carry ... You've got to like the attitude of new Vikings owner  &UR; Red
McCombs &LR; , who is nothing if not an optimist. After first being
rebuffed when he tried to buy the franchise, McCombs hung tough and
closed the deal after novelist  &UR; Tom Clancy  &LR; lost his hunt for real
cash. After McCombs's $250 million offer was finally accepted, he
looked at his new property and declared, ``I think this team has a
very good chance of winning every game on the schedule.'' Don't
they play the Packers and Buccaneers twice? They do, but you have
to like his attitude. McCombs also said he would not consider
moving the Vikings despite the fact he is a Texan who also owns the
San Antonio Spurs and is unhappy with the Metrodome lease, which he
says is one of the NFL's worst. Why does everyone's lease become
``one of the NFL's worst'' a couple of years after it's signed?
Well, in McCombs's case, consider this: The Vikings pay the city of
Minneapolis $1 million a year for control of their luxury suites,
receive only 10 percent of the concessions and none of the signage
fees, and pay the city a 10 percent tax on ticket sales ... Anybody
seen  &UR; Curtis Martin  &LR; lately? The Jets haven't. Martin continues to
struggle with hamstring and hip woes ... Actor  &UR; Dennis Quaid  &LR; has
been studying the passing form of the 49ers'  &UR; Steve Young  &LR; to
prepare himself for a role as a lefthanded quarterback in a film
called, ``Any Given Sunday.'' When Mariucci was asked what he
thought of Quaid's passing form, he said, ``He can't throw a cat
out of the house.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
