<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-PATRIOTS-VIKINGS-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
VIKINGS WILL PROVIDE FAST LESSON FOR JONES 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By NICK CAFARDO  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   SMITHFIELD, R.I. _ Tebucky Jones: fast-forward.
</P>
<P>
   The acceleration of Jones's professional career has begun, and
the Patriots' rookie cornerback will be taken to new, challenging
heights tonight at Foxboro Stadium, when he'll be up against a very
talented Minnesota Vikings receiver corps, with the distinct
possibility he'll have to cover Randy Moss, the 6-foot-5-inch
rookie from Marshall.
</P>
<P>
   Jones has received plenty of reps with the first team in the
past few days, covering both Terry Glenn and Shawn Jefferson,
winning some battles and losing others. In any event, he's winning
brownie points for effort and toughness.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's a very physical player,'' said Jefferson. ``Once he
understands the receivers in the league and what they do and don't
do, he's going to be a tough corner in this league. He's learning
as he goes along right now, but he's been impressive.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think we've all tried to help him a little bit with
different pointers, and he's not afraid to ask questions like, `Why
did you do that move?' and things like that.''
</P>
<P>
   Jones is almost fully recovered from the hamstring problem that
plagued him earlier in camp, but still can't completely turn on the
burners and show his 4.3 speed. But the Patriots continue to hope
that Jones makes enough progress between now and the start of the
regular season to earn a starting role.
</P>
<P>
   ``Right now he's as green as a pea,'' said defensive coordinator
Steve Sidwell. ``He's done some good things and he's learning fast,
but right now that position is a real question mark for us. No one
has been able to take the job yet.''
</P>
<P>
   Not Jones nor last year's No. 1 choice, Chris Canty.
</P>
<P>
   ``Chris has made great progress and his attitude is so much
better than a year ago,'' said Sidwell. ``The job is there for the
taking, and Chris could be the one who takes it. But right now that
hasn't happened.''
</P>
<P>
   There will be an interesting juxtaposition in Foxborough tonight
as Jimmy Hitchcock, the cornerback traded by the Patriots as they
placed their faith in Jones, plays for the Vikings.
</P>
<P>
   The bulk of the action is liable to be on the right side of the
field, as Drew Bledsoe is likely to throw the ball often to
Hitchcock's side, while the Vikings' Brad Johnson is expected to
test Jones and Canty often.
</P>
<P>
   Bledsoe has had a strong week of practice; the timing of his
passes seems much sharper than a week ago.
</P>
<P>
   ``You can see some things cleaning up,'' said coach Pete
Carroll. ``The passing game has shown some good signs. Drew has
been on the money for the most part, and I'm hoping we can carry
that into the game. He has to feel the live rush and get the ball
up in time. We look like we're progressing.''
</P>
<P>
   After a subpar effort against the 49ers a week ago, the Patriots
placed a lot of emphasis on the running game. In San Francisco,
they averaged only 2.8 yards a carry, far short of the 4 yards
they're hoping for. Tonight they expect to give the bulk of the
running load to the Shaws, Sedrick and Harold.
</P>
<P>
   Sedrick Shaw had gains of 6 and 9 yards last week but averaged
only 3 yards per carry. The Patriots will be looking for him to
turn the corner and get the ball upfield more.
</P>
<P>
   The Patriots are more and more impressed with the straight-ahead
running of Harold Shaw, who had an excellent week in practice and
is quickly moving up the depth chart while No. 1 pick Robert
Edwards's groin heals.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's an opportunity that I need to take advantage of,'' said
Harold Shaw. ``You get to this level, you don't have much time to
show what you can do, so you'd better go all out all the time and
open some eyes.''
</P>
<P>
   The 6-foot, 230-pound sixth-round pick out of Southern
Mississippi could very well wind up being the sleeper in the
Patriots' draft. He's already proven to be a punishing type of
runner, and his style makes it easier for the offensive line to
run-block.
</P>
<P>
   Many eyes, too, will be on veteran offensive tackle Bruce
Armstrong, who is wearing a brace on his right leg to protect what
could be a broken fibula. The Patriots say Armstrong is doing well
with the brace and they don't believe they are taking any
unnecessary risks by letting him play.
</P>
<P>
   Still, there should be significant playing time for second-year
tackle Ed Ellis, who at 6-6, 347 pounds has really come on. The
soft-spoken Ellis has been nasty in practice all week, including
getting involved in an altercation with safety Larry Whigham.
</P>
<P>
   Carroll, who has spent entire afternoon practices on special
teams, is hoping to see the fruits of that emphasis with strong
play tonight. He has been looking for a few good head hunters and
appears to have them on cover teams this year.
</P>
<P>
   Carroll expects his first offense to stay on the field for
almost a half or until a pattern of success develops, which it
never did in the 21 plays Bledsoe was involved in against the
49ers.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-08-08-98 2008EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
