<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-08-08 20:10 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4607 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FBN-PATRIOTS-MCGINEST     08-08 1868
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-PATRIOTS-MCGINEST-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FIRED UP MCGINEST READY TO FLATTEN FOES 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By MICHAEL MADDEN  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR; SMITHFIELD, R.I. _ Coaches might swallow 10 or 20 or more of
their whistles if they could concoct from scratch _ and then bottle
_ that silent trust that binds the defense of the New England
Patriots. It is the intangible of all intangibles, that unspoken
bond, that oneness, that chemistry, that trust in each other that
needs to be there for the job to be done.
</P>
<P>
   The offense of the Patriots doesn't have it the way the defense
does. And neither is there that silent trust between the offense
and the defense, as was much too clear in the final eeks of last
season.
</P>
<P>
   On the New England defense, there seem to be no individuals,
even though there are many very good individual players. Ty Law is
a very good player, but he talks team; Willie Clay is very good,
but he talks team; the same with Lawyer Milloy and the linebackers
in front of him, Ted Johnson, Chris Slade, Todd Collins, and Tedy
Bruschi. The silent trust among them is huge; they all have eyes to
see a good thing building but very few ``I's'' to disrupt it.
</P>
<P>
   And up front, on the line, there is Willie McGinest. The tone
and tenor of Pete Carroll's defense is to attack, and no one
attacks more than the Elephant Man himself, defensive end Willie
McGinest.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our thing as a defense is just to stay sound, make plays and
keep our offense on the field,'' said McGinest. ``The big thing is
to be the aggressor, to attack. We're always in the attack mode.''
</P>
<P>
   Which is what McGinest has been in camp, chasing down Patriot
quarterbacks, even getting involved in a scuffle on Thursday,
attacking, attacking, attacking _ and doing it loudly.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're all pretty vocal on defense because we all understand
each other on defense so well,'' said Milloy, a safety. ``We don't
have one particular leader of the group.''
</P>
<P>
   But, Milloy went on, ``Willie's one of the more vocal leaders of
the group. Willie kind of speaks for the defense when we have our
team meetings, you know, that kind of leader. But, as far as the
huddle is concerned, every one has something to say when they want
to say, and every one listens because we have respect in that
huddle. But Willie can be vocal.''
</P>
<P>
   This time last year, and well into the season, though, McGinest
was uncommonly quiet, bothered by injuries (hamstring and knee),
and it was not until December that McGinest was himself. And not
coincidentally, it was in December that the Patriot defense bonded
and became one of the NFL's best _ if not the best.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was hurt last year and it took me a while to get back,''
said McGinest. ``But then (the knee) started to get better and we
started to play very well and it just seemed to carry over and
over. And now we're a lot further along than last year. I think
we're going to be even better.''
</P>
<P>
   Milloy, like other Patriots, noticed ``how much it really hurt
Willie not to be there early last year with the injuries he had.
This year Willie wants to be with us from beginning to end and it's
showing in a lot of ways, especially his attitude toward the game
right now.''
</P>
<P>
   The turning point
</P>
<P>
   The Patriot defense had been reasonably solid, but erratic late
in games, through the 1997 season until the team arrived in
Jacksonville last Dec. 7.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's when it really turned around for us,'' said McGinest.
``I don't think Jacksonville had lost at home for something like
three seasons, but that's when guys started making a lot of plays
and we finally seemed to understand what we had to do. Our defense
had been doing all right, but that Jacksonville game was when we
took a stand.
</P>
<P>
   ``That was a perfect time for us to try and play a perfect
game.''
</P>
<P>
   The best word to describe what happened to the defense last
December is that it ``clicked.'' Using an untold variety of schemes
and blitzes, the defense had the Jacksonville, Miami, and
Pittsburgh offenses almost completely off balance, leaving
quarterbacks such as Mark Brunell, Dan Marino, and Kordell Stewart
confused more often than not. The return of McGinest to full health
was a key to the New England defensive surge.
</P>
<P>
   ``Now, this year, we've got the same system and guys are a lot
further along in understanding it,'' said McGinest. ``We're not
really confused and we're putting a lot of stuff together and now
everybody's on the same track; the difference is it's happening a
lot earlier this year.''
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, for the first time in franchise history, the Patriots
could be known first, last, and foremost as a defensive team,
conjuring up images of Steel Curtains and cries of ``Dee-fense'' in
Foxboro Stadium. Indeed, if the Patriots don't find a running game,
the defense had better be as good as it was last December and
January.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've got something special here,'' McGinest said. ``And as
long as we keep progressing, and understanding what we're doing,
and doing it all together, then we'll be a good defense.''
</P>
<P>
   Getting stronger
</P>
<P>
   McGinest plays the ``Elephant'' position, lining up at defensive
end opposite the strong side of the offense, often going against
the tight end. Ray Hamilton, his defensive line coach, compares
McGinest to players of Hamilton's era, a combination of the very
quick former Patriot defensive end Tony McGee and the strong 49er
end, Fred Dean. As for ``Elephants,'' Hamilton said McGinest is up
on that high shelf with Charles Haley.
</P>
<P>
   ``The thing about Willie is that he really, really works hard,''
said Hamilton, ``and he really, really wants to be good. And during
the offseason this year we talked to Willie about improving the
strength of his lower body. Willie was already very strong in his
upper body but in order to get his rush going a little quicker, he
needed to increase his leg strength. And Willie came into camp a
lot stronger in his legs and you can see it already. He's
stronger.''
</P>
<P>
   McGinest already had a quick rush but now, said Hamilton, ``He
can push those tackles back a little more and, if you can combine
the strength move along with his speed move, he can keep (an
offensive lineman) guessing all day.''
</P>
<P>
   Best of all, said Hamilton, ``This is the healthiest Willie has
been since he's been here. He hasn't missed a day. I mean, last
year at this time I didn't even have him. He got hurt, then he came
back and he got hurt, and even when he came back again, he was
still hobbling. It wasn't until December that he got going, and
when Willie's going, he's just a blur. To be as big and as strong
as he is, and to be as fast as he is, he is ideal for the Elephant
position we play him.''
</P>
<P>
   As his teammates say, so does Hamilton that ``McGinest is a very
active guy in there (the huddle) with his mouth. He's revving up
his teammates, but it also revs himself up. He's such a competitive
guy; he wants to win every snap.''
</P>
<P>
   Furthermore, said Hamilton, McGinest is more comfortable this
season playing on the tight end. Last year, said Hamilton,
``Because it was new to him, he was being aggressive but he wasn't
quite getting it done the way we wanted to get it done. But this
year is like night and day.''
</P>
<P>
   The Patriots' approach toward the Elephant position is very
simple, said Hamilton:
</P>
<P>
   ``We think that when a defensive lineman is on a tight end it's
a mismatch. He should kill the tight end every play. Last year,
Willie was thinking too much about his responsibility, but this
year he's just manhandling the tight end.''
</P>
<P>
   McGinest, of course, started out his career with the Patriots as
a linebacker ``but that was a waste of his pass-rushing skills
there,'' said Hamilton. ``So we felt we'd put a few pounds on him,
line him up at end and have him come a-humming.''
</P>
<P>
   For years, if not decades, it has been the Patriot offense that
has been forced to rescue the defense by scoring points. By the end
of last season, though, the situation had been reversed and the
frustration of some defenders toward the offense was well known.
</P>
<P>
   In a horrible loss last December to the Steelers in OT at
Foxborough, and then two wins over the Dolphins and finally the 7-6
loss to Pittsburgh in the playoffs, the Patriot defense kept
getting better and better while the offense was getting worse and
worse. By season's end, it was clear to fans that New England's
defense not only had to stop the other team, but also had to score
TDs itself if the Patriots were to win, the offense being beset
with injuries to key players.
</P>
<P>
   Alas, some on the Patriot defense felt the same way.
</P>
<P>
   ``We understood that for us to be a successful team, we were
going to have to go out and stop people and make plays and
turnovers and cause fumbles and keep our offense in position to
score,'' said McGinest.
</P>
<P>
   Asked how the defense views the offense today, McGinest said,
``We don't control what the offense does. All I know is that as
soon as we start worrying about what Drew (Bledsoe) and the rest of
the guys are doing, then it takes away from us. I mean, the offense
has a new coordinator, a lot of new things and new players, and I'm
sure by the time we get to Denver (for the opening game) they
should be all right.''
</P>
<P>
   No need to even voice the words: McGinest is sure the defense
will be all right.
</P>
<P>
   A defensive alliance
</P>
<P>
   Chris Slade and McGinest have been the closest of pals since
McGinest arrived with the Patriots in 1994, a year after Slade. The
word ``close'' would be an understatement to describe their
friendship; on the field or off, McGinest and Slade seldom are far
apart.
</P>
<P>
   ``We had heard of each other _ I knew of him and he knew of me _
but we'd never met until Willie came to camp,'' said Slade. ``We
hit it off right away. It was like we complemented each other; he
was looking for the same thing I was looking for and we had the
same type of style, we were the same type of guy on the field. You
know, a pass-rush guy.
</P>
<P>
   ``We just clicked from the jump, you know? It was like one of
those `love at first sight, friends at first sight' kind of thing.
</P>
<P>
   ``The big thing about Willie is he's a `go-hard guy' all the
time, very competitive on the field. Willie's so competitive and
he's got such a great work ethic. Willie's the kind of guy you
really want to have on your team when it's time to go to war. You
can always count on him to be there for you.''
</P>
<P>
   So much for the sanitized newspaper version. Slade then laughed
and gave a more playful view, saying, ``Willie's kind of a loud guy
_ too loud, real obnoxious loud _ he always wants everybody to know
who he is.''
</P>
<P>
   Which is?
</P>
<P>
   ``He's got a tough side to him, but he's also a gentle guy at
the same time,'' said Slade. ``You know what I mean? Willie puts on
an image that he's a real tough, street-kind of guy _ which he is _
but really he's very generous and sensitive and caring.''
</P>
<P>
   The two used to have a friendly wager each year.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was over whether Willie or me would get the most sacks,''
said Slade. ``But one time we did that, we kind of jinxed ourselves
and neither of us got any sacks for a few weeks, so this year we're
not going to do that.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-08-08-98 2010EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
