<DATE_TIME> 1998-08-08 20:12 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4608 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BOX-BOXNOTES-TYSON-BO     08-08 2605
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BOX-BOXNOTES-TYSON-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
EXPERT ESCAPE ARTIST STRIKES AGAIN 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By RON BORGES  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Mike Tyson told the world the truth about himself recently, but,
as has been the case throughout much of his life, the world didn't
want to listen.
</P>
<P>
   The truth is, Tyson doesn't want to fight anymore but the world
can't accept that, just as it still can't accept that Evander
Holyfield twice destroyed Godzilla with relative ease and will do
it again if the occasion presents itself. The world hears one thing
but believes another.
</P>
<P>
   The world wants to tell itself that Tyson's sudden, angry
display of temper in front of the people he was supposedly pleading
with to have his boxing license reinstated was a sign of his animal
lust for confrontation. It wants to believe his expletive-laced
explosion was about anger and frustration and pent-up rage, the
kind of rage that can earn you big money in a boxing ring.
</P>
<P>
   That's what the world wants to believe because the portion of it
interested in boxing has invested a lot of time, money, and psychic
energy in that fiction and would rather it not be exposed for what
it has always been _ a Halloween ghost story with punch.
</P>
<P>
   Tyson's eruption in front of the New Jersey Athletic Control
Board July 29 was really a search for a way out, which is the way
he has taken most of his life and the way his long line of enablers
has let him go time and again.
</P>
<P>
   That pattern continues today with a new set of advisers, veteran
fight manager Shelly Finkel, and music impresarios-turned-fight
guys Irving Azoff and Jeff Wald. Together they allowed Tyson not to
face what he needed to face, which was the truth of what he did to
Holyfield's ears on June 26, 1997, in a Las Vegas ring.
</P>
<P>
   They allowed him a way out of going back to the scene of the
crime and asking for his license back, the same license Nevada
revoked after he tore a chunk of Holyfield's ear off rather than
take another long beating from the heavyweight champion of the
world.
</P>
<P>
   Tyson was looking for a way out of the ring that night, an
action predicted 24 hours earlier by his former trainer, Teddy
Atlas. Tyson took it and learned nothing from it.
</P>
<P>
   When he insisted on seeking a license in New Jersey, he was
looking for a way out of having to go back to Nevada and beg for a
chance to go to work. Finkel provided that by claiming his fighter
might have a better chance of being reinstated elsewhere because
Tyson's former promoter, Don King, has influence in Nevada and
might try and use it.
</P>
<P>
   This implies that King has little influence in New Jersey, where
he was just relicensed as a promoter only weeks after beating
federal insurance fraud charges for the second time. If Finkel
believes King has no influence there, he must also believe in the
Tooth Fairy.
</P>
<P>
   When Tyson slammed his hand down on a table near the end of a
three-hour hearing and refused to read a prepared closing
statement, he knew what he was doing.
</P>
<P>
   When his attorney, Anthony Fusco Jr., tried to calm him by
telling the board, ``How many times does one individual have to be
asked, `Are you sorry for what you did?''' Tyson interrrupted his
lawyer and said loud enough for the board to hear, ``Why do I got
to go through this (expletive) all the time?'' When he said those
words, he knew what he was doing.
</P>
<P>
   It was all as orchestrated as the punches Tyson used to throw in
precise combinations in the days when many thought he was a
wrecking ball. This was no display of unbridled rage, but Tyson is
smart enough to know that's how the world would look at it.
</P>
<P>
   This was the act of a career con man looking for a way out of
something he doesn't want to do anymore, which is fight to make
other people rich. As Tyson rounded his shoulders and sunk his neck
into them, his eyes reduced to beady slits, he resembled a rat with
his tail between his legs, scurrying to find an exit from a long
tunnel he'd been running down for too long.
</P>
<P>
   For most of his life, Tyson has been a fighter who conned
people. He has been a powerful puncher who could pressure others
but couldn't take the pressure himself. The few times he was put
under it, he snapped or caved in because, as Holyfield put it
perfectly before their first fight, ``Pressure busts pipes.''
</P>
<P>
   After a year suspension, Tyson is now under that pressure again.
Although he has assets, he has no cash, according to people who
should know. He needs money, and the only way he knows how to get
it is to fight, but he doesn't want to fight, for a simple reason.
</P>
<P>
   Nearly every heartache Tyson has ever had came from fighting.
Sure, he's made hundreds of millions of dollars, become world
famous, and dragged himself out of the ghetto through boxing, but
he's also become the target of public ridicule, a convicted rapist,
a social misfit, and a failed fighter who lost his honor in a
boxing ring.
</P>
<P>
   I have spent more than a little time around Tyson since he
became a professional fighter. I do not claim to know him _ how can
you know someone who doesn't know himself? _ but what I do know is
that this has always been a man living a lie.
</P>
<P>
   Tyson is a man who talks of how much he loves his children yet
is seldom in the same state with them _ even now, when he's free to
live where he wants.
</P>
<P>
   Tyson is a man who had a homecoming parade and party after
leaving prison. The parade was through the streets of Harlem, where
he never lived one day of his life.
</P>
<P>
   Tyson is a man who claims Holyfield kept butting him, when every
tape of those fights shows Tyson, not Holyfield, leading with his
head. Holyfield simply refused to back up when charged as so many
of Tyson's victims had before him.
</P>
<P>
   Tyson is a man who repeatedly has claimed he is ``sorry for what
I did,'' to Holyfield, yet every time he's said that, he's almost
immediately claimed Holyfield butted him in both fights and he then
``snapped,'' which is another way of saying he wasn't responsible.
</P>
<P>
   That's always been the bottom line with Tyson. He's never
responsible. He's always the victim. He's always ``poor Mike.''
</P>
<P>
   He's broke, but that's King's fault.
</P>
<P>
   He's convicted of rape, but that's the fault of the young woman
and a bad lawyer, not to mention a racist society.
</P>
<P>
   He lost badly to Buster Douglas, but that was the fault of a
referee who couldn't count.
</P>
<P>
   He lost to Holyfield, but that was the referee's fault or his
trainer's fault.
</P>
<P>
   He was disqualified the second time for twice biting Holyfield,
but that was Holyfield's fault.
</P>
<P>
   He got his license revoked in Nevada, but that was Nevada's
fault.
</P>
<P>
   Now, I believe, Tyson is hoping he won't get that license back
in New Jersey because then he will have an excuse not to face what
he has to face and he'll have someone else to blame.
</P>
<P>
   He won't have to face Holyfield, or the fishbowl existence
boxing has turned his life into, or King, or the bloodsuckers who
will replace King, or the media who hound him. He won't have to
face any of that, and, best of all, he'll have an excuse for his
latest misfortune.
</P>
<P>
   He'll blame the New Jersey Athletic Control Board. He'll say
he's a victim, and he knows the world will believe him because it
doesn't want to know the truth any more than he does.
</P>
<P>
   The funny thing, though, is that Tyson told the world the truth
not long after his outburst in New Jersey. After the proceedings in
Newark ended, he was taken into a conference room by his handlers
and when he came out Tyson signed autographs and told reporters,
``I never lost my cool.''
</P>
<P>
   He was telling you the truth then, folks. A con man never loses
his cool. He just does what he has to do and says what he has to
say to avoid facing the truth. The world should understand that
about Tyson because he's been doing that for a long, long time, and
a year off couldn't change that.
</P>
<P>
   As Tyson's old guru, Cus D'Amato, used to say, ``A guy born
round don't die square.''
</P>
<P>
   ___ &QC;
</P>
<P>
   Main Events promoter  &UR; Dino Duva  &LR; was in federal court last week
with his newest fighter, International Boxing Federation
welterweight champion  &UR; Felix Trinidad &LR; , &UR;  &LR; to do battle with King,
Trinidad's former promoter. Duva claims Trinidad's deal expired
June 11 and that an extension clause King included in the middle of
a bout agreement for a fight with  &UR; Troy Waters  &LR; is not valid. Duva
has a lot riding on this because the multimillion-dollar agreement
he signed with HBO to televise Trinidad fights was contingent on
Duva proving Trinidad was free to enter into a promotional deal
with him by Aug. 21. Without HBO's millions, Duva could not sign
Trinidad, who wants no part of returning to King's stable but may
have no choice if he loses. The judge hearing the case is  &UR; Lawrence
McKenna &LR; , &UR;  &LR; who just presided over the government's failed insurance
fraud case against King. McKenna listened to several hours of
arguments from Duva's lawyer,  &UR; Pat English &LR; , &UR;  &LR; and King's longtime
representative,  &UR; Peter Fleming &LR; , &UR;  &LR; and is expected to rule
expeditiously. ``Don inserted what appeared to be an
inconsequential sentence or two in the Waters bout agreement that
was different from Trinidad's multifight agreement with King,'' a
source close to the case said. ``Those sentences extended the deal,
but there's a legal question whether or not he can do that.'' ...
Featherweight champion  &UR; Prince Naseem Hamed  &LR; finally appears set to
fight  &UR; Kennedy McKinney  &LR; on Halloween night, but not at Madison
Square Garden as originally planned. The fight is headed to  &UR; Steve
Wynn's  &LR; newest Las Vegas hotel, which has yet to open. The date has
already been reserved with the Nevada State Athletic Commission,
but the Garden reportedly has the right to match Wynn's price.
Don't count on it ... Veteran referee  &UR; Mills Lane  &LR; continues to
negotiate with Fox network for a job as a ringside commentator. If
he accepts that position, his career as a referee would be over,
according to both Lane and Nevada Athletic Commission executive
director  &UR; Marc Ratner &LR; . ``Mills is 60 years old and I think he's
looking long-term,'' Ratner said. ``If he gets a long-term contract
with Fox and goes full-time, he wouldn't be allowed to referee in
Nevada because it would be a real conflict. He understands that and
accepts it.'' ... The America Presents card in El Paso Friday will
decide who fights for the vacant World Boxing Council super
lightweight title. No. 1 contender and former WBC lightweight
champion  &UR; Miguel Angel Gonzalez  &LR; takes on two-time IBF junior
lightweight champion  &UR; John John Molina  &LR; in one bout, and assuming
Gonzalez survives that match, he'll square off with the winner of a
12-round elimination bout between No. 2 contender and former IBF
junior welterweight champion  &UR; Kosta Tszyu  &LR; (20-1-1) and No. 3-rated
ex-IBF lightweight champion  &UR; Rafael Ruelas  &LR; later this year. It
would be Gonzalez's third try at the 140-pound title. He vacated
the lightweight title to move up and challenge  &UR; Oscar De La Hoya
 &LR; and lost a lopsided 12-round decision. Then he fought  &UR; Julio Cesar
Chavez  &LR; to a controversial draw when they met for the vacant title
in March ... In case you missed it (and you probably did),
heavyweight prospect  &UR; Ike Ibeabuchi  &LR; (18-0) returned to the ring
last month for the first time since he upset  &UR; David Tua  &LR; and
stopped  &UR; Tim Ray  &LR; in one round. It was good to see Ibeabuchi back
after a tortured time in his private life when he was found to be
suffering from manic depression. That led him into a near-fatal car
accident that some believe was a suicide attempt and an assault on
the young son of his ex-girlfriend when she left him on the same
day. Ibeabuchi spent a brief time in a Texas jail while the matter
was sorted out. He was seen as a rising star after he upset Tua but
has slipped from the public consciousness of late.
</P>
<P>
   ___ &QC;
</P>
<P>
   The same week Tyson announced he would seek a license to box in
New Jersey, a federal appeals court reinstated a $4.4 million
judgment against him won by his former trainer,  &UR; Kevin Rooney &LR; .
With interest, it comes to $7.6 million, and Tyson reportedly
doesn't have the money. Tyson announced his decision to return to
boxing 48 hours after the ruling. Rooney had this to say about his
ex-fighter's financial plight: ``He says he's broke but he's got
things to sell. He can sell a house and a few cars. Way I figure
it, he's made $180 million since he dumped me. Ten percent of that
is a lotta house.'' ... Chavez was ordered to appear before the
Nevada State Athletic Commission medical board July 31 to have his
cut eye examined by a plastic surgeon to avoid a repeat of the
fiasco when he lost his first meeting with De La Hoya on cuts and
later claimed he'd gone into the fight already cut. Ratner,
executive director of the commission, &UR;  &LR; said Chavez was found 100
percent healthy ... Little-known Danish heavyweight  &UR; Brian
Nielsen &LR; , &UR;  &LR; who holds the even lesser-known International Boxing
Organization heavyweight title, has shifted his training to  &UR; Janks
Morton's  &LR; gym in Washington, D.C. Despite a hand injury, he hopes
he can get himself into the big-money heavyweight sweepstakes in
the US. Nielsen ballooned to nearly 300 pounds while unable to
train because of hand problems.
</P>
<P>
   ___ &QC;
</P>
<P>
   Probably few people watched  &UR; Vinny Pazienza  &LR; and  &UR; Glenwood Brown
 &LR; do battle recently, but it was a fight  &UR; Rocky Graziano  &LR; and  &UR; Tony
Zale  &LR; would have appreciated. This was not a fight for big money or
a world title. It was just two professionals battling with all
their hearts to show the other what the word ``fighter'' means. In
the end, Pazienza won the way he has so often _ not because of his
skill but because of his will. After three rounds, his nose was
broken, he had been knocked to one knee, and soon after was also
cut above the eye. This led Brown to wrongly conclude _ as  &UR; Dana
Rosenblatt  &LR; once did _ that, ``When I hit Vinny with that left hook
in the third, I thought it was all over. But he showed what a great
champion he is by coming back. I hit him with some great shots and
he took them.'' With the fight dead even, Pazienza came out for the
final round and landed 66 of 113 punches. Had this been a 12-round
world title fight, that pace would have yielded 1,356 punches and
792 connections. That is what people have so long paid for with
Pazienza. He now hopes to convince IBF super mid-dleweight champion
 &UR; Charles Brewer  &LR; to give him a title shot by the end of the year
before he calls it a career ... After denying a report from this
corner weeks ago that he was contemplating a comeback, former super
middleweight champion Irish  &UR; Steve Collins  &LR; has confirmed that he
is plotting to come out of retirement if he can lure  &UR; Roy Jones
 &LR; into the ring. Collins retired 10 months ago but is now seeking a
tuneup fight with old British rival  &UR; Chris Eubank &LR; , &UR;  &LR; who was just
stopped by cruiserweight champion  &UR; Carl Thompson &LR; . Jones's people
are talking with representatives of Collins as well as  &UR; Gianfranco
Rocchigiani &LR; . Eubank would seem a safe start. He's lost four
straight world title fights and is considering retirement himself
... Here's one of the more unusual statistics you're going to find.
Massachusetts middleweight  &UR; Adrian Brown &LR;  is undefeated but has yet
to win a fight. Brown has fought to a draw in each of his first
three bouts ... On a recent card in Hyannis, undefeated  &UR; Billy
Rollins  &LR; (11-0-2) was engaged in a bloody battle with New York's
 &UR; Scott Lopeck &LR; . The timekeeper became so engrossed in the action
that he forgot to ring the bell. Rollins was knocked out 48 seconds
after the third round should have ended. The decision was
eventually changed to a no-contest.
</P>
