</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-HOLLEY-COLUMN-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WHAT'S A FOOTBALL FAN TO DO IN AUGUST? WORRY 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By MICHAEL HOLLEY  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   It is too early to worry about the Patriots. Everyone who cares
about the team is supposed to know that by now, right? We aren't
even halfway through August, there are still stories in the paper
about New England humidity, General Parcells and his Jets won't be
in Foxborough until October, and we have yet to see the Pats play
in two of the flimsy events that the NFL likes to call preseason
games.
</P>
<P>
   No one frets about football in August. Except, maybe, a chronic
worrier. Which is another way of saying that if this were my team,
I'd never leave the house unless accompanied by an entourage of
Patriot supporters. That way a calming peer group would be in place
when I went into my inevitable problems-of-the-Pats-inspired August
frenzy. Then again, maybe I wouldn't want my entourage around too
often because they just might be wearing, say, a Pats hat and
T-shirt, which would remind me why I was worrying in the first
place.
</P>
<P>
   It is too early to worry. I truly believe that. But two days ago
Pete Carroll stood at a podium in Smithfield, R.I., and calmly said
that his team doesn't have a go-to running back. He also said: ``I
would like to see one guy take the position. I don't know if that
will happen, though. We'll have to wait and see ...''
</P>
<P>
   Doesn't that make you nervous?
</P>
<P>
   It wouldn't be so bad if Carroll were doing the wait-and-see
thing with Terrell Davis, Barry Sanders, and Eddie George competing
for the top spot. But we're talking about, primarily, second-year
man Sedrick Shaw and rookies Harold Shaw and Robert Edwards _ who
just happens to be hurt. All are fighting in a vacuum formerly
known as a solid Curtis Martin/-Sam Gash/-David Meggett/-Keith
Byars backfield. Those runners are gone now, which leads us to
believe that Bob Kraft, Bobby Grier, Carroll, et al must have a
blessed pact with the football gods. Why else would a team allow
its starting and backup backs to walk away with no proven runners
to replace them?
</P>
<P>
   The big story of camp last week was Harold Shaw, a sixth-round
draft pick from Southern Mississippi whose favorite player was a
fellow Mississippian, the great Walter Payton (OK, that's one less
worry: the man has good taste). Harold Shaw, though, is the
anti-Sweetness in that he barrels toward collisions rather than
darting away from them.
</P>
<P>
   Linebacker Todd Collins still remembers a pop Shaw laid on him
early in training camp. We thought Collins would bring some
serenity to the pack of worriers when he was asked if Shaw reminded
him of anyone. He didn't have to say anything outrageous. But a
reference to Chris Warren wouldn't have been bad. So, how about it,
Todd? Harold Shaw reminds you of ...
</P>
<P>
   ``Harold Shaw,'' Collins said.
</P>
<P>
   Oh.
</P>
<P>
   Carroll was asked if the quality play of such a late-round pick
surprised him.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's a pretty good sixth-round pick in Denver,'' the coach
said, referring to All-Pro and Super Bowl MVP Davis.
</P>
<P>
   Uh-oh. With that comment, I'm now worried about Pete Carroll.
But it's only temporary.
</P>
<P>
   Last year, the coach was listed as a team unknown. He had gone
6-10 in his only season as a head coach (with the Jets) and was
replacing Parcells. There were many times when Carroll had that
awkward New Guy look about him. That was a drastic contrast to the
savvy Parcells, whose five best press conferences could be shown on
Classic Sports. You knew Carroll had his own ideas, but you also
knew he didn't want to walk into the locker room with too much
bravado. Especially with a team that had just gone to the Super
Bowl and wasn't losing any major contributors.
</P>
<P>
   Those who have been around Carroll this summer have said he is
more confident. And, they say, the man whom Gash and others ripped
for being too laidback has been less hesitant to lash out at
players.
</P>
<P>
   So who are we to worry? It's silly. It's only August. We haven't
even spotted the first tourist driving toward Western
Massachusetts, talking about the wonders of fall foliage. And just
because the Patriots are holding auditions for a lead runner
doesn't mean they won't be able to run the ball. As long as Bruce
Armstrong is on the offensive line, no Pats fan should be
concerned.
</P>
<P>
   Yes. Bruce Armstrong. The same Bruce Armstrong who, news reports
tell us, could be playing with a broken fibula in his left leg.
Armstrong is a tough man. He is also human. Most humans who do
office jobs would not be able to go to work from September until
January with a problematic fibula. Now imagine what it's like to
throw your body into 300-pound linemen who view you as the sole
nuisance between them and Drew Bledsoe. They aren't concerned about
your fibula or your pain. They want the QB. If Armstrong goes down,
Bledsoe loses his best protector; the young backs lose one of their
best providers; and the team loses a chunk of its offensive soul.
</P>
<P>
   Well, at least the team still has its defense. There's not much
to worry about there. As long as you are willing to ignore right
cornerback. Tebucky Jones may be one of the best corners in the AFC
midway through the season. But, by then, the Patriots will have
already played four games against AFC East teams. Steve Israel is
fast _ and hurt. Jones is fast, talented _ and inexperienced at the
position. But you knew the guy was no lightweight corner when he
got into a tangle with Ben Coates and didn't have to be carted out
of Bryant College. And Chris Canty? Canty is, uh, ahem, well ... We
hear Chris Canty is a gifted rapper. In the spirit of that, am I
the only one who hears Public Enemy's Chuck D. singing, ``I've got
so much trouble on my mind ...''?
</P>
<P>
   Maybe it is too early to worry. Maybe Parcells should be
worrying. He's the one who says he hates penalties and turnovers,
even though he has walking advertisements for both on his team in
the persons of Bryan Cox and Vinny Testaverde. It is too early to
worry. I'm convinced of it. But, I was just wondering, how often do
you pray?
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-08-08-98 2013EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
