<DATE_TIME> 1998-08-08 20:14 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4610 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-TEN-WTASTOP-FERNANDEZ     08-08 1206
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TEN-WTASTOP-FERNANDEZ-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FERNANDEZ CONTINUES TO BEAT THE ODDS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By KEVIN PAUL DUPONT  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR; Mary Joe Fernandez will be 27 years old next Wednesday, still
young, even if nearly a lifetime removed from turning pro at age 14
when she was all baseline and braces.
</P>
<P>
   Some 13 years later, and about $5 million in winnings to the
plus, she will be here this week competing in the Boston Cup, the
Corel/WTA stop that officially begins Monday at Babson College, the
first women's tour stop in Boston in 14 years.
</P>
<P>
   Once one of the game's brilliant ingenues, the 5-foot-10-inch
Fernandez now has reached senior status in the valley of the
volleys. Only recently back on tour after undergoing offseason
wrist surgery, her shot revitalized and her legs sharpened by a new
workout routine, she has no plans to move permanently to the
sidelines soon.
</P>
<P>
   ``Before I had endometriosis in 1993, when I was 21 or 22, I
thought I'd be out at 24, max,'' recalled Fernandez, whose painful
bout with scar tissue around her ovaries, ultimately leading to
surgery, proved to be only a temporary setback. ``You know how that
goes: I hit 24 and then it was another number.''
</P>
<P>
   Recently, said Fernandez, she talked with Billie Jean King about
what was the right time to bid goodbye to her game.
</P>
<P>
   ``And she said to me, `Mary Joe, you have to take it year by
year,''' said Fernandez. ```Look at Martina (Navratilova),' she
said. `She retired five times.' What it comes down to is you have
to evaluate it year by year. Both Martina and Billie Jean were well
into their 30s. She gave me some good advice: `Just play and see
how you feel.' And really, I think that's the best answer.''
</P>
<P>
   It may be difficult for some to fathom Fernandez being on this
side of the playing curve. Only weeks after turning pro in February
1986 she was running around Wimbledon as another of the world's
hard-hitting wunderkinds. Women were getting in the game as girls,
seemingly showing up with their games stronger and ever more
aggressive.
</P>
<P>
   Even before turning pro, Fernandez became the youngest player
(eight days beyond her 14th birthday) to win a US Open match when
she dumped Sara Gomer in '85. Triumphs such as that led to her
decision while at Sacred Heart Catholic School in Coconut Grove,
Fla., to carry her school books in one arm and sling a racket for a
living with the other.
</P>
<P>
   ``Everybody is different,'' said Fernandez, recently reflecting
on her decision to turn pro at such a young age. ``There's no
simple answer, because everyone matures and grows at a different
pace. It was right for me to turn pro at 14, but I made a point to
stay in high school and graduate at 17 _ I'm very pro-education;
because you never know what's going to happen. It worked for me,
but it's not the norm.
</P>
<P>
   ``Whoever the child is, he or she has to love the game of
tennis. I'd say that's the most important part. It's a great game,
a wonderful game, but it's a difficult one, too, full of hard work
and sacrifices. If the person doesn't absolutely love it, it might
not be the best decision.''
</P>
<P>
   Fernandez will be joined here by a smattering of the world's top
names, including top seed Amanda Coetzer (ranked No. 8 in the
world), Anke Huber (18), Lisa Raymond (19), and Elena Likhovtseva
(24). It was about this time seven years ago that Fernandez briefly
nosed ahead of Navratilova in the rankings, to No. 4 overall,
making her the highest-ranked American, other than Chris Evert or
Navratilova, since 1980.
</P>
<P>
   Recently, Fernandez has slipped to No. 50 in the world, after
finishing No. 10 last year with a triumph in the German Open and
nearly $770,000 in prize money. She only recently returned to
competitive play, following nearly a seventh-month layoff after
December surgery that repaired a torn ligament in her right wrist.
</P>
<P>
   It took 14 months of playing in pain to convince Fernandez it
was time to call a timeout and tend to the injury.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was taking anti-inflammatories and cortisone, but the pain
was too much,'' recalled Fernandez, reached at her home in Miami
last week before she flew to Boston Friday. ``It was after the
third cortisone shot that the doctor said, `That's it, you can't
have any more shots.' So there was no choice. I know exactly how I
did it. I hit a ball late _ a ball that I thought was going out,
but at the last second I decided to hit it. I could feel something
snap. The surgery was simple, done with a scope, and just a small
incision, but it's taken some time to recover.''
</P>
<P>
   For six weeks after the surgery, Fernandez wore a cast, followed
by another six weeks in a splint. The pain dissipated quickly, but
lingering soreness and little range of motion kept her off the
court and in the training room. She still carries a ball of putty
wherever she goes, kneading and squishing her way back to full
strength and free movement.
</P>
<P>
   Initial results have been promising: After Boston, she'll head
to Montreal for the du Maurier Open (Aug.17-23), a stop she added
only after initial playing results were promising.
</P>
<P>
   ``The one positive out of this is that I finally had time to get
in good shape,'' said Fernandez. ``You lose conditioning when
you're out on the road, competing all the time. But this gave me
the time to lift some weights, run my sprints, to get in as good a
shape as possible for my return.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've never been a big fan of working out, but the time away
helped me establish a goal that I want to be more consistent with
it now. You don't want to get too tired or too sore, but you can
work in some weights, some lunges, some sprints after a match _
things you should do to stay in top playing shape.''
</P>
<P>
   The view from the sidelines also helped Fernandez rediscover her
enthusiasm for the game.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's amazing, but you can get stuck in the day-in, day-out of
playing professionally,'' she said. ``There is no break in the
schedule, so it's like one long year out there on the road. It gets
tiring when there's no time to regroup, get a fresh start. You go
to your matches, you live in a hotel and that hotel food gets old
after a while. But when you're not playing, you realize that you're
lucky to do what you do, and I do feel lucky. It can be hard, but
on the other hand, the pluses outweigh the negatives.''
</P>
<P>
   The Fernandez who takes the court at Babson this week will look
much the same as the Fernandez who broke in a lifetime ago. Her
game, however, looks different.
</P>
<P>
   ``The girls who come in now are a lot stronger and faster than
when I broke in,'' she said. ``I think I've adjusted well over the
last decade. I'm definitely not a power player, but I've tried to
find a way to compete. I was always known as a baseliner, but as
I've gotten older I'd say I'm more aggressive; I take more chances.
I've got more of an all-court game now, and as you get older you
know more strategy.
</P>
<P>
   ``The game has changed a lot since I turned pro. Monica (Seles)
made it more of a power game in the late '80s, more than the
Martina and Chrissy days. Then, in the last five years, the overall
depth of women's tennis has improved. It's not just the top 10
players anymore. It's the top 100.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
