<SLUG> BC-GLF-GOLFNOTES-PGACHAMPIONSHIP-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SAHALEE AWAITING FIRST MAJOR TEST 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JOE CONCANNON  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR; Sahalee. This former agricultural town some 25 miles east of
Seattle becomes golf's capital this week as the 80th PGA
Championship is contested at Sahalee Country Club.
</P>
<P>
   The last time a major professional championship was staged north
of San Francisco was in 1946, when Ben Hogan beat Porky Oliver in
the match-play final of the PGA Championship at Portland (Ore.) GC.
The PGA also was held at Manito G&AMP;CC in Spokane in 1944, when Bob
Hamilton took a 1-up victory over Byron Nelson.
</P>
<P>
   Davis Love 3d, who will defend the championship he won at Winged
Foot in dramatic fashion a year ago, has not yet seen the course,
but the two most discussed questions are whether Love can repeat
and whether Masters/British Open champion Mark O'Meara can become
the first player since Hogan in 1953 to win three majors in a year.
</P>
<P>
   Love, who missed Media Day at Sahalee in June because of back
problems, has talked to PGA regular Rick Fehr about the course.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's filled me in on what a great golf course it is and how
difficult it is,'' says Love. ``He's told me about how deep the
rough's getting and how they've trimmed back some trees that really
didn't affect the play of the golf course _ made it open up a
little bit for the gallery but didn't make it any easier on us.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm very excited about defending my championship. I've planned
my whole golf career trying to win a major championship, and then
to have that dream come true at Winged Foot has been a great
experience to me.''
</P>
<P>
   O'Meara, who defeated Brian Watts in a four-hole playoff to win
the British Open last month at Royal Birkdale, has had an
exceptional year in becoming the oldest player to win two majors in
the same year.
</P>
<P>
   ``I realize that winning doesn't happen that frequently in this
game because the talent is so good,'' says O'Meara. ``I play to
win. Your pride is such a huge thing, and for me the win at the
Masters was a tremendous victory because of the way I held up
coming down the stretch and making the putt on the 72d hole.
</P>
<P>
   ``That was in itself a big relief, knowing I had crossed that
hurdle. Golf is a little bit of good breaks here and there. When
you win, that's what it takes. Breaks have to happen, and I think
that any player who wins a tournament realizes that the good luck
has been on his side that week.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think that what really has helped me over the last few years
is to realize I have to hang in there. I don't think I necessarily
always hit it perfect, and I may not have the perfect golf swing. I
use past experience to my advantage, so when I'm near the lead I've
been able to finish off the deal.''
</P>
<P>
   This is the Pacific Northwest, where trees and moisture are
prevalent. August is supposed to be the second-driest month of the
year in Greater Seattle, but who knows? The rough will be grown to
4 inches, and the trees will come into play on errant tee shots. It
sounds a tad like Valderrama in Spain, where the US team was beaten
by the Europeans in last year's Ryder Cup.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'll always enjoy being called the PGA champion,'' says Love.
``I really don't want this year to end. We were just so lucky to
get it in with all the bad weather. Everything just came pouring
down on me in that last burst of rain, and I was trying very hard
to keep my emotions in. I know sometimes I don't look like I'm
happy or excited on the golf course, but I was trying to stay very,
very focused on just hitting the golf shots and getting to the
clubhouse without having an emotional breakdown.''
</P>
<P>
   The first professional at Sahalee was Paul Runyon, who won PGA
Championships in 1934 and 1938 and will attend a press conference
at the site Tuesday at the age of 90. Rees Jones, who has been
known as the US Open Doctor ever since he presided over the
restoration of The Country Club for the 1988 tournament, has done
some minor work with Sahalee's 59 bunkers and a few tees. Just
think narrow, rough, trees aplenty, and a few lakes. That's Sahalee
CC, all revved up for its first major championship.
</P>
<P>
   ___ &QC;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Richard Connolly Jr. &LR; , the heart and soul of the Francis Ouimet
Scholarship Fund as director of the annual Ouimet Memorial
Tournament and past president of the fund, has announced the
establishment of the Connolly Family Scholarship within the Ouimet
structure. Connolly grew up as a caddie at Woburn CC, where  &UR; Ernie
Doherty  &LR; inspired him and hired him to help run the course through
Connolly's high school (Malden Catholic) and college (Holy Cross)
years. He encouraged present Brae Burn superintendent  &UR; Don Hearn
 &LR; to get into the business, and Hearn became president of the Golf
Course Superintendents Association of America. ``I was a Ouimet
Scholar,'' he says. ``The best experience I ever had was being a
caddie. It's the lessons you learn, watching how people act on a
golf course. I have two sons ( &UR; Richie &LR; ,  &UR; Ryan &LR; ) who caddie (at
Concord CC) and a third son ( &UR; Kevin &LR; ) who plays, and he's 10.'' ...
The City of Boston has opened up bids for the operation of the
William Devine GC at Franklin Park. The course went into decline in
the late 1980s but was reborn when the city entered into a
seven-year agreement in 1989 with Community Golf Course Management
Corp. and  &UR; Bill Flynn's  &LR; Franklin Park GC Inc. The lease ended in
March 1996. The city received $242,979 of the $5,623,300 gross
revenues taken in between 1990 and 1997, according to a Boston
Finance Commission Report dated Jan. 20, 1998. The concern is to
protect the Franklin Park Golf Course Guardians Inc., which the
report states is ``a nonprofit group comprised of area residents
and longtime users of the golf course. The Guardians are active in
the community and contribute to it. The role of the Guardians is
important to the community. The golf course was closed in most of
the 1980s. It was the perseverance of neighborhood people and
people who had played the golf course for years that led to its
restoration.'' There are three Boston-based groups expected to bid
for the job of running the operation, and one is expected to be
named next month.
</P>
<P>
   ___ &QC;
</P>
<P>
   The three Bay State qualifying sites for the US Amateur are
Tedesco CC (Monday) and Shaker Hills and Berkshire Hills (Tuesday).
The Tedesco entrants include recent Massachusetts Amateur champion
and CVS Charity Classic participant  &UR; James Driscoll &LR; .  &UR; Frank Vana
Jr. &LR; , who won the Ouimet Memorial, is at Shaker Hills.  &UR; Jim
Salinetti &LR; , &UR;  &LR; who won the State Amateur a year ago, is in the group
at Berkshire Hills. Four from each of the sites will qualify ...
 &UR; Matt Kuchar &LR; , &UR;  &LR; who was a media favorite at the Masters and US
Open, has decided to remain an amateur and return for his junior
year at Georgia Tech. ``He was very close (to turning pro),'' says
his father,  &UR; Peter Kuchar &LR; . ``Whenever you're feeling pressure, the
best thing you can do is to take a step back. It was a decision
that did not come easily, and one we now feel comfortable with.''
...  &UR; Justin Rose  &LR; jumped into the pro ranks after finishing tied
for fourth at the British Open, where Kuchar missed the cut ... The
B.C. Open is feeling the jerk strings of the PGA Tour. This unique
event, usually held in the fall, will be played opposite the
British Open for at least three years starting in 2000. They
decided to stick it out without ever having the benefit of a major
corporate sponsor. ``We're going to be on Tour, we're not going to
be kicked off,'' said former B.C. Open tournament director  &UR; Alex
Alexander &LR; . &UR;  &LR; ``They didn't want us to leave.''
</P>
</TEXT>
