<HEADLINE>
GORDON PERFECTS GET-RICH-QUICK ROUTINE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By MICHAEL VEGA  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   ``Wow!'' said Jeff Gordon when apprised of his $1,637,235 payday
after winning last Saturday's Brickyard 400.
</P>
<P>
   Wow is right. Except for perhaps, ``Can I have that in large
bills, please?,'' what else was there for Jeff Gordon to say after
his windfall at Indianapolis Motor Speedway?
</P>
<P>
   The rich get richer ... and richer ... and richer.
</P>
<P>
   With the biggest payout of this NASCAR Winston Cup circuit
season, Gordon bolstered his career earnings to $20,297,547 and
became the first driver to capture the Winston No Bull 5 $1 million
bonus. Gordon is eligible for another $1 million bonus, along with
the other top five Brickyard 400 finishers _ Mark Martin, Bobby
Labonte, Mike Skinner, and Dale Earnhardt _ at the next Winston No
Bull 5 race, the Mountain Dew Southern 500 at Darlington, S.C.,
Sept. 6.
</P>
<P>
   Gordon, you'll recall, also won the Winston Million last season
with a victory at Darlington.
</P>
<P>
   But it all seemed like pocket change compared with Gordon's
victory at Indy.
</P>
<P>
   ``Indianapolis is already a special race,'' said Gordon, a
native of Pittsboro, Ind., who also piloted his No. 24 Dupont
Chevrolet into Victory Circle at Indy in the 1994 inaugural
Brickyard 400. ``It never seemed like we had it in our hands 'til
the end. But when they put up the big money in a race, this team
just seems to step up to the plate. It's not just the money, it's
the prestige.''
</P>
<P>
   Certainly, dangling a $1 million bonus over a race can add an
immeasurable amount of intrigue, but where was the suspense _ or,
for that matter, the prestige _ in a race that ended under caution?
To many observers, the fact that NASCAR allowed the 160-lap race to
end under caution _ taking three laps to clear Jimmy Spencer's
wrecked car from the track _ was a travesty. It led to yet another
caution, the ninth and final of the race, on a single-file restart
on Lap 158 when Joe Nemechek's car made contact with Jeff Green's
on the front stretch and set off a chain-reaction wreck.
</P>
<P>
   Gordon, as a result, cruised to the checkered flag at a pace
well below the race average of 126.770 miles per hour.
</P>
<P>
   If anyone had reason to gripe about the way the Brickyard 400
ended, it was Martin, who finished runner-up to Gordon and remained
second to him in the Winston Cup point standings, 2,897-2,825.
</P>
<P>
   But if you were to ask Martin whether NASCAR should explore ways
to end races under green, you might be surprised by his response.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't think there's anything wrong with the way it is now as
long as it's consistent, which at least the Brickyard finish was _
consistent with a typical NASCAR Winston Cup race finish,'' said
Martin during a weekly Winston Cup teleconference last Tuesday.
``Saturday was consistent with what we've seen in the past, and I
don't think there's anything wrong with it. It works in some
people's favor and against other people, and you just have to hope
that you're on the receiving end and not on the losing end.''
</P>
<P>
   While Martin and the thousands of NASCAR fans who paid good
money to watch wound up on the losing end, it was Gordon who wound
up on the receiving end. Again.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's definitely sweet to come to Indianapolis and win,'' said
Gordon, who stands a pretty good chance of getting his seventh
victory of the season after winning the pole position (his sixth of
the season) for Sunday's Budweiser at the Glen in Watkins Glen,
N.Y. ``I actually shut off the engine when I came down pit row so I
could hear the crowd cheering. It's an awesome thing to hear,
especially when we go to other places (and get booed). I love
coming here, it holds so much prestige. It makes winning here that
much better. For me, winning is my way of giving something back to
them.''
</P>
<P>
   ___ &QC;
</P>
<P>
   The split between New Hampshire International Speedway and the
Indy Racing League seemed inevitable, so it came as no surprise
when the parties went their separate ways last Tuesday, leaving the
1-mile oval without an open-wheel racing date. Why has open-wheel
racing struggled in New England while NASCAR Winston Cup has
enjoyed nothing but success at NHIS? It seems that NASCAR has
simply built a bigger following. Championship Auto Racing Teams
came and went after failing to draw more than 50,000 in its
four-year stint at NHIS. The IRL, meanwhile, fared worse, with
attendance declining from 24,000 to 20,000 in its third and final
year. But the real reason for the parting of the ways was simple:
There didn't seem to be enough promotion _ by either track owner
 &UR; Bob Bahre  &LR; or the IRL. In the end, the IRL didn't want to sink
more money into a losing proposition and wound up pulling the
sponsorship it had promised NHIS, leaving the Bahres to take a
substantial financial hit. That was the last straw.
</P>
<P>
   ___ &QC;
</P>
<P>
   Retiring CART driver  &UR; Bobby Rahal  &LR; will make one of his more
sentimental stops on his self-styled farewell tour _ Rahal's Last
Ride _ at Mid-Ohio for Sunday's Miller Lite 200, the last race in
Ohio for the native Buckeye. Rahal attended his first race at
Mid-Ohio in 1963 and watched his father,  &UR; Mike &LR;   &UR; Rahal &LR; , compete.
``I just remember continually washing the dust off my dad's car,''
recalled Rahal, who often returned to the track during his college
days at nearby Denison University to watch Can-Am and Formula 5000
races. ``I won the Lumberman's race here, I've won IMSA races here,
I've won SCCA races here, I've won Championship Car races here. I
just have great memories of this track. Great history.'' Asked if
he would get emotional, Rahal said, ``I'm not sure I'll get misty,
but I'm not making any guarantees.'' ... IRL driver  &UR; Billy
Boat &LR; , &UR;  &LR; who suffered a fractured leg and pelvis in a wreck at NHIS
June 28, was back in the car for a tire test at Atlanta Motor
Speedway July 28-29 and hopes to be back racing for the next IRL
event at Pikes Peak, Colo., next Sunday. ``It felt good to get back
into the race car,'' said Boat, driver for legendary car owner
 &UR; A.J. Foyt &LR; . ``Within five laps at Atlanta, I was running 215. I
don't think the accident hurt my confidence at all. The only thing
it does hurt is the longer you are out, the more apt you are to be
a little rusty when you get back. That is why it was important for
me to get back as quickly as I could.'' ... NASCAR Craftsman Truck
Series driver  &UR; Boris Said  &LR; made quite an impression by qualifying
fifth-fastest for Sunday's Bud at the Glen. Substituting for
injured Winston Cup driver  &UR; Jimmy Spencer &LR; , &UR;  &LR; who was released last
Monday from Methodist Hospital in Indianapolis after suffering a
concussion in the Brickyard 400, Said went 119.780 m.p.h. on his
pole qualifying attempt. ``I wish the circumstances surrounding
this opportunity were different, because I don't like the fact that
Jimmy is hurt,'' Said said. ``That aside, I feel like this is
Christmas. This will be my first NASCAR Winston Cup race, and I'm
excited about the opportunity.'' ... NASCAR Featherlite Modified
driver  &UR; Jan Leaty  &LR; suffered much more serious injuries last week at
NHIS than were first reported by officials at Concord Hospital.
Leaty, of Williamson, N.Y., crashed during qualifications for the
Pennzoil-VIP Discount 100 and suffered a basal skull fracture and a
stable neck fracture, but no paralysis. He remains hospitalized in
guarded condition ... Officials of the American Red Cross and New
Thompson Speedway in Thompson, Conn., are calling upon race fans to
participate in a blood drive Aug. 14 at Scranton Motors in Vernon,
Conn., for 6-year-old  &UR; Clarissa Ingram &LR; , &UR;  &LR; a leukemia patient who is
need of blood donations and a bone marrow transplant. For
directions to Scranton Motors, call 860-872-9145.
</P>
</TEXT>
