<SLUG> BC-SOC-GALAXY-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GALAXY WINS ON JOLLEY'S GOAL
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By SCOTT FRENCH  
 Long Beach Press-Telegram  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Steve Jolley couldn't have chosen a better moment for his first
Major League Soccer goal, a last-minute header that tagged the
happiest of endings to the 90 minutes of frustration the Los
Angeles Galaxy endured Saturday afternoon in Chicago.
</P>
<P>
   Soaring above two defenders at the far post to nod home a
flicked-on cross from Mauricio Cienfuegos, Jolley who has emerged
as a defensive force in captain Dan Calichman's absence presented
L.A. with a dramatic 2-1 victory over the Fire before 37,122 at
Soldier Field, extending its lead in the Western Conference to 15
points and placing it on the verge of clinching a playoff berth.
</P>
<P>
   It was one of just six shots the Galaxy (18-6, 52 points)
managed in a physical, defensive affair that provided their
attacking players little opportunity to create but saw one of the
finest performances this season by L.A.'s defense.
</P>
<P>
   Second-place Chicago (13-10, 37), which dropped its fifth
straight game and fell to 0-6 without injured playmaker Peter
Nowak, also struggled on attack, finding space in L.A. territory
only in the second half and using it with little success.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is the way teams in a rut turn things around: play good
team defense,'' said defender Robin Fraser. ``We dug in and battled
and pulled out a win like this. We've been losing the close games,
but when we dig in, we can pull them out.''
</P>
<P>
   It was much like the first two meetings between the teams, both
Chicago wins: Slow-paced, with the Fire content to shut down space
while trying to poke holes in L.A.'s defense. With Soldier Field's
long grass neutralizing Cobi Jones' and Welton's speed and former
Galaxy midfielder Chris Armas shutting down Mauricio Cienfuegos,
there was little the Galaxy could accomplish.
</P>
<P>
   ``I feel good about the fact that we won,'' said Coach Octavio
Zambrano, ``but we should have controlled the game a lot better in
the later stages. I'm not entirely pleased with how we managed the
game. We have experienced guys who should know how to do this. I'm
going to have to talk with them.''
</P>
<P>
   The first two scored were on own goals, the first a header by
Chicago defender Francis Okaroh that should have been enough for a
Galaxy win. It came off a free kick from midfield by Martin Machon
that cleared Carlos Hermosillo at the edge of the Fire box. The
ball took one bounce, and Okaroh under some pressure from
Hermosillo tried to head the ball to Jorge Campos, his goalkeeper.
Campos, as is his custom, had come out of his nets and was cleared
by Okaroh's header; he scrambled back late and the ball beat him
inside the far post.
</P>
<P>
   The win L.A.'s second in a row after losing four of five
appeared assured until the 89th minute, when Danny Pena returned
the favor, knocking a cross from Zak Ibsen on the right wing into
the Galaxy net.
</P>
<P>
   Jolley's heroics arrived seconds later, after Zach Thornton had
replaced Campos in the nets (an effort to replace Okaroh, who'd
suffered bruised ribs) and as Campos searched for red shorts on the
sideline.
</P>
<P>
   Cienfuegos earned a free kick near the corner flag, then booted
the ball to the far post. Paul Caligiuri got his head to it,
sending it to the far post, where Jolley rose above two defenders
to nod it into the net.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm pretty ecstatic,'' Jolley said afterward. ``You can't ask
for a better situation to score your first goal. ... I think the
good man upstairs was definitely looking out for me.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-08-08-98 2259EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
