<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBN-SOSA-POWER-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CUBS' SOSA THE POWER SURPRISE OF THE '98 SEASON
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By T.R. SULLIVAN 
c.1998 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   ST. LOUIS _ Sammy Sosa was attending the Toronto Blue Jays'
Dominican Baseball Academy when Rangers scout Omar Minaya
intercepted him. Sosa, just 17 at the time, had a weekend pass to
go home to San Pedro de Marcoris. Instead, Minaya sneaked him on a
baseball field for a tryout.
</P>
<P>
   ``I remember he didn't have much power, but the ball jumped off
his bat,'' Minaya said. ``He was 5-9, 5-10. If you liked him, he
was 6-foot. He was really skinny and thin, fragile. You looked at
him and you knew the kid was malnourished.
</P>
<P>
   ``But I liked the way the ball jumped off his bat. It would get
through the infield quickly. It would die when it got into the
outfield, but that was because he was weak and malnourished. A lot
of the kids are that way down there.''
</P>
<P>
   Minaya, remembering that summer day in July 1985, was impressed
enough to offer Sosa $3,000 to sign with the Rangers. Sosa wanted
$4,000. They settled for $3,500.
</P>
<P>
   ``He stuck to his principles. I liked that,'' Minaya said. ``He
was very aggressive. Everything he did, he did with aggressiveness
and with confidence.''
</P>
<P>
   Minaya thought Sosa would be a good major-league baseball
player. He never suspected he would one day join Mark McGwire and
Ken Griffey Jr. in pursuit of Roger Maris' single-season home run
record. But Sosa has risen from the slums of the Dominican Republic
and has overcome his wild-swinging habits to become one of
baseball's premier power hitters, having hit his 44th home run
yesterday against the St. Louis Cardinals.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's going to be a challenge, but I just want to finish strong
and help my team into the playoffs,'' Sosa said.
</P>
<P>
   Said Minaya, now the New York Mets assistant general manager,
``I'm proud of him. You look at those other guys, McGwire and
Griffey. They were both first-round draft picks. This is a kid who
was signed out of a poor area of a poor country. I mean, we're
talking about a third-world country. Now he's being mentioned with
those guys. That's pretty amazing.''
</P>
<P>
   The Cubs signed Sosa to a four-year, $42.5 million contract
extension last summer, allowing him to move his family into the
same Chicago apartment building where Oprah Winfrey lives. That's
more than a step up from San Pedro de Marcoris, where he had to
shine shoes and sell fruit on the street corner to help his family
survive.
</P>
<P>
   ``I remember Joaquin Andujar, Julio Franco, George Bell, they
all had beautiful homes,'' Sosa said. ``They were always in the
middle of a crowd. I remember thinking it would be nice to live
like that.''
</P>
<P>
   When Minaya first met Sosa, the player's stepfather was ill and
couldn't work, so Sosa's mother had to toil at a number of odd jobs
to support seven children. Sosa's biological father passed away
when Sosa was very young.
</P>
<P>
   ``Sammy was the hope of the family,'' Minaya said. ``When he was
in the minors, he was supporting his whole family on $850 a month.
They're a very close-knit family and he had to carry them on his
back. But he was always a confident, happy, aggressive,
street-smart person. He had an idea how to survive, and he was very
intelligent. He forced himself to learn English quickly.
</P>
<P>
   ``The people in the neighborhood shielded him from all the bad
stuff. Athletes are protected there because people can see they
have a chance to make something for themselves and get out of
there. People would say, don't touch him, this guy is going
somewhere.''
</P>
<P>
   Sosa did get somewhere, but he has not forgotten where he came
from, particularly since he talks to the president of the country
on a regular basis. He donated 250 computers to Dominican Republic
schools and set up the Sammy Claus Foundation to provide Christmas
presents to poor children, both there and in the United States. He
also invested in a new major shopping center in his old
neighborhood, where none had existed before.
</P>
<P>
   ``People said, `You're not going to make money there,' '' Sosa
said. ``I said this is not about money, this is about giving back
to the community.''
</P>
<P>
   Now he's giving back to a community that already has enough
shopping centers and computers. What Chicago really wants is for
Sosa to lead the Cubs to their first World Series since 1945. The
Cubs are currently on top in the National League wild-card
standings.
</P>
<P>
   Sosa prefers to focus on the playoff chase and let McGwire and
Griffey worry about the Maris chase. But the Cubs' success, and his
surprising bid to hit 61 home runs, have fed off each other. Sosa
has found it's easier to hit on a winning team, rather than trying
to carry a last-place team by himself.
</P>
<P>
   ``Definitely,'' Sosa said. ``I used to try to carry the team all
by myself but not any more. I would try to hit two home runs in one
at-bat and if you do that, you're never going to do what you're
supposed to do. When you're on a winning team, you don't have to
worry about that. It's more fun. You can come to the ballpark early
and focus on your job.''
</P>
<P>
   Sosa averaged 34 home runs the past four seasons without any
real power hitters batting behind him to protect him. The best the
Cubs could do for support in those years was Luis Gonzalez, who hit
15 home runs in 1996.
</P>
<P>
   Pitchers discovered it was stupid to throw him a strike,
especially since he'd swing at almost anything within a foot of the
strike zone anyway. He led the majors with 174 strikeouts last
year, a team record.
</P>
<P>
   Bases on balls never appealed much to Sosa, who learned long ago
like so many others in the Dominican Republic: You can't walk off
the island.
</P>
<P>
   Sosa also indulges in an occasional fantasy, wondering what
would have happened if the Rangers hadn't traded him and he was
batting in the same lineup with longtime buddy Juan Gonzalez.
</P>
<P>
   ``He'd have more than 118 RBI right now, I can tell you that,''
Sosa said with a smile. ``But I'm comfortable with what I have
now.'
</P>
<P>
   That's because the Cubs got serious last off-season and traded
for Expos outfielder Henry Rodriguez, who has 27 home runs. Manager
Jim Riggleman also changed his lineup, moving Sosa into the No. 3
spot, making Mark Grace the cleanup hitter and batting Rodriguez
fifth.
</P>
<P>
   Grace has never hit with much power, but he's batting .321 with
a .411 on-base percentage, which Riggleman thought would be ideal
between two free-swinging sluggers.
</P>
<P>
   Once Sosa got comfortable in the lineup, he took off. He hit 20
home runs in June, a major-league record that jumped him right into
the middle of the Maris chase.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've never seen anybody have a month like that,'' Grace said.
``It was incredible.''
</P>
<P>
   ``He'll tell you he's got better hitters hitting behind him,''
Cubs coach Billy Williams said. ``But I think security \Rof a
long-term contract\S changed Sammy more than any of us. Some guys
get long-term deals, they start coasting. Sammy worked harder. He
put in more time, accepted more responsibility.''
</P>
<P>
   Sosa has worked particularly hard in abandoning his life-long
free-swinging habits, but he's not going to fulfill hitting coach
Jeff Pentland's goal of 100 walks.
</P>
<P>
   But he's on pace to draw 68 walks, which would be a career-high.
The .308 batting average and .374 on-base percentage that he has
after yesterday's game will also be career highs.
</P>
<P>
   ``I used to go to the plate, swing at two or three pitches and
that was it,'' Sosa said. ``Not anymore. Now I'm more relaxed and
disciplined. I look for my pitch. I try to hit to right field. I
have a better idea of what I'm trying to do.''
</P>
<P>
   ``If you want to attach the word discipline to that you can,''
said Riggleman. ``He is taking more pitches. But Sammy has done
great things every year and it's extraordinary that he's been able
to accomplish more things this year. I think it's just a process of
year after year of hard work and maturity culminating in what he
has done this year.''
</P>
<P>
   In doing so, he has become a huge hit at Wrigley Field, where he
takes steps on the field blowing kisses to his mother, flashing a
``V for victory'' sign in honor of the late great Harry Caray and
exchanging all kinds of salutes with the fans in the right-field
bleachers. Part of his ritual is beginning each game by throwing a
baseball into the stands.
</P>
<P>
   ``Sometimes I'm having a bad day and people are yelling at me,
`Don't worry Sammy,' '' Sosa said. ``They're trying to lift me up,
make me feel good. That makes me think, go up to the plate and try
hard to pay them back.''
</P>
<P>
   He's done that with the home runs. A bigger payback would be the
National League pennant flying once again over Wrigley Field.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
