<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-RODEO-HALL-OF-FAME-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
JUSTIN RIDES LOVE OF WEST, COWBOYS INTO RODEO HALL
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By BRETT HOFFMAN 
c.1998 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   It was a bone-rattling night at the Fort Worth Stock Show Rodeo
in the early 1960s when cowboy Bill ``Good Times'' Federson bounced
off a bronc and hobbled out of the arena, leaving fans questioning
how Federson got branded with that upbeat nickname.
</P>
<P>
   Moved by compassion, a wealthy Fort Worth boot manufacturer
named John Justin carried Federson to the Fort Worth Petroleum
Club, where Justin was a member. For several days, Federson soaked
in a whirlpool, receiving sports medicine equivalent to what a
Dallas Cowboys running back gets after a Sunday pounding.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was like a lot of injuries _ it wasn't that serious _ he
just needed a little help so he could continue riding, and he ended
up doing well in the rodeo,'' Justin said of Fort Worth's renowned
Southwestern Exposition and Livestock Show Rodeo.
</P>
<P>
   When the 81-year-old Justin was inducted yesterday into the
Prorodeo Hall of Fame in Colorado Springs, Colo., the sport
enshrined its greatest friend alongside some of its greatest
competitors.
</P>
<P>
   The Hall of Fame added Justin to the ``rodeo notables'' category
for accomplishments such as creating Justin Heeler, which provides
sports medicine physicians and facilities at professional rodeos,
and the Cowboy Crisis Fund, which has offered financial assistance
for cowboys who have sustained serious injuries.
</P>
<P>
   Closer to home, perhaps Justin's most notable contribution to
Fort Worth was heading a late 1980s fund-raising campaign that
garnered $3.5 million to help build the Will Rogers Equestrian
Center in Fort Worth. Since then, the center, which has three
indoor arenas, has wrangled several major shows _ including this
week's American Quarter Horse Association youth championships _
from other cities.
</P>
<P>
   ``Mr. Justin loves the Western tradition,'' said Bob Watt, the
Fort Worth Rodeo general manager who worked closely with Justin on
the fund-raiser. ``He's the most unusual person with no arrogance
about him. Anything that has to do with supporting an aspect of the
Western tradition, he's totally dedicated.''
</P>
<P>
   Added legendary 1950s cowboy Jim Shoulders: ``I'm glad John
never decided to take up bull riding when I was competing. If he
had, he would have been tough to beat because when he makes up his
mind to do something, he's very determined. When he becomes your
friend, he's very loyal.'' A cowboy haven For many years, Justin's
home was filled to the brim with cowboys, including Shoulders, when
they were competing in the Fort Worth rodeo, traditionally staged
each January and February.
</P>
<P>
   After a rodeo performance ended on those cold winter nights,
cowboys dragged in at all hours to rest their bronc-busted bones.
</P>
<P>
   Justin has fond memories of running a boardinghouse.
</P>
<P>
   ``I remember one occasion when we had several dogs at our
home,'' Justin said with a big grin. ``A cowboy came in late one
night and it was very dark in the house. He thought he opened a
container of sandwich spread, but instead it was dog food. He put
it on a sandwich and seemed to like it OK. But the next morning, we
all realized that he had eaten the dog food.''
</P>
<P>
   As the sun rose over Fort Worth's wooded rolling hills each
morning, Justin's wife, Jane, who attended the induction ceremony
yesterday, prepared breakfast for competing cowboys.
</P>
<P>
   ``One morning, Jane was frantically running all over the house,
room to room, sticking her head in the doors,'' Justin said. ``I
said, `Jane, what are you doing' She said, `I'm getting a head
count of cowboys so I'll know how many eggs to break.'''
</P>
<P>
   Though Justin was never a prize-winning rodeo competitor, many
athletes sought his help, especially when the entry books were
about to close at the Fort Worth rodeo.
</P>
<P>
   ``When a cowboy would see that he was about to miss the deadline
for entries, he'd ring me up and say, `Would you sign me in?'''
Justin said. ``I'd go over and put in the $40 so he wouldn't miss
an opportunity to ride.''
</P>
<P>
   But on one very rare occasion, Justin decided to enter the Stock
Show Rodeo in an event dubbed the wild horse race. The event
featured teams of three competitors. Each team was assigned to a
hold, saddle and ride a wild horse.
</P>
<P>
   ``I decided to enter while we were having a rodeo party,''
Justin said. ``I think a fellow named Jack Daniels told me to
enter.'' A cowboy's refuge Justin is revered for taking the bull by
the horns in terms of organizing and funding desperately needed
programs that aid major-league rodeo's Dukes of Hazzard.
</P>
<P>
   For 17 consecutive years, the Justin Heeler physicians and
on-site facilities have provided assistance to ailing cowboys at
rodeo arenas nationwide. When Justin began the program in the early
1980s, there were virtually no training rooms at rodeo arenas.
</P>
<P>
   ``Used to be, when a guy got hurt, they'd hobble out of the
arena and nobody would pay attention to them,'' Justin said.
``They'd have to take a cab to the hospital.''
</P>
<P>
   Today, two mobile sports trailers and two permanent facilities
provide assistance at about 140 Professional Rodeo Cowboys
Association shows. J. Pat Evans, a former team physician for the
Cowboys, and Don Andrews, the program's director, are credited for
the program's inception.
</P>
<P>
   In recent years, the sports medicine program began providing
assistance for Professional Bull Riders shows. Dallas physician
Tandy Freeman is scheduled to attend almost all the association's
24 Bud Light Cup Series shows this season. Freeman also regularly
provides assistance at a permanent training room at the weekly
Mesquite Championship Rodeo.
</P>
<P>
   ``Before John started the sports medicine programs, if you got
hurt at the rodeo, you'd go into the clown's quarters and find what
little medicine and bandages you could,'' Shoulders said. ``Now,
they have these nice training rooms. I know this makes the cowboys
mad, but sometimes I go in and call it the sissy room while the
guys are taping themselves up.
</P>
<P>
   ``But in all seriousness, I know that it does them a lot of good
to have a place to get help.''
</P>
<P>
   At the Mesquite Championship Rodeo Friday, Freeman and the
Justin Sportsmedicine team carried Weatherford bull rider Pace
Newman out of the arena on a stretcher after Newman was bucked off
and stepped on by bounty bull Dodge Durango. Newman sustained a
broken leg and was transported to a local hospital.
</P>
<P>
   When former world champion Jerome Davis was paralyzed from the
chest down after breaking his neck at the PBR tour stop in Fort
Worth in March, the sports-medicine team rushed in and assured that
Davis was transported carefully to a hospital.
</P>
<P>
   Though rodeo is a rough-and-tumble sport, career-ending injuries
are rare. In most occasions, the sports-medicine team's work keeps
competitors on the road.
</P>
<P>
   ``The doctors who work for them are very knowledgeable much
about rodeo,'' said six-time world all-around champion Ty Murray of
Stephenville, who competes in all three bucking stock events. ``If
you injure your arm, they know how exactly much pressure a bull
would put on your arm if you were to continue riding, and they can
give you accurate advice on whether you should compete.
</P>
<P>
   ``They also help educate you on how to tape, how to stretch and
how to exercise an injury. And things like that make a big
difference.''
</P>
<P>
   Former world all-around champion Dave Appleton of Arlington said
he remembers when the team helped him continue competing at the
Cheyenne (Wyo.) Frontier Days in the mid-1980s despite sustaining a
small break in a leg bone.
</P>
<P>
   ``I had some really good horses drawn, and I needed to keep on
riding,'' Appleton said. ``Without their help, there's no way that
I would have kept on competing. They worked on me constantly for
four days and they loaned me equipment to take to my hotel room.
All that helped keep the swelling down. I was able to continue
riding, and I won the rodeo.
</P>
<P>
   ``You can liken the Justin Heeler program to a mobile repair
shop. If we have a bent fender, they fix it and put us back in the
race.'' A cowboy recovery Three years ago, Justin faced perhaps the
biggest challenge of his life when doctors found that he had
leukemia. But he bucked the odds after undergoing rigorous
treatment at the M.D. Anderson Medical Center in Houston.
</P>
<P>
   ``When I first went to the doctor, I asked, `What will happen if
I don't take the treatments,''' Justin said. ``The doctor said,
`Well, you'll only have about 60 days to live.' I said, `When can
we start?'''
</P>
<P>
   For the first year, doctors banned Justin from attending rodeos.
When the 99th Stock Show Rodeo began in 1995, Justin addressed the
crowd by phone on opening night.
</P>
<P>
   But when the Stock Show celebrated its 100th anniversary the
next year, Justin rode in the grand entries and has continued to do
so.
</P>
<P>
   ``I recently got a computer printout from my doctor that said he
has treated eight different patients in my condition in recent
years,'' Justin said. ``The statistics show that five of them have
died, and the three other people have lived for 10, 18 and 38
months. I'm the guy who has lived 38 months. When I first went in
for treatment and the odds of recovery were so slim, I told them
the doctor I was going to beat it and make him famous.''
</P>
<P>
   He did beat it, and 81-year-old John Justin might be one of the
most famous people in and around rodeo never to bust a bronc.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-08-08-98 2321EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19980808.0191 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-08-08 23:23 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4840 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BBN-JOHNSON-ASTROS-HN     08-08 1880
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBN-JOHNSON-ASTROS-HNS </SLUG>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
Astros' Johnson prefers to deflect praise to family, team
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR; By CARLTON THOMPSON &LR;  &QL; 
 &UR; c. 1998, Houston Chronicle &LR;  &QL; 
The minute Randy Johnson enters a big-league ballpark, he's the Big
Unit _ the most intimidating pitcher of his era.
</P>
<P>
   He's a man who forces some of the best hitters in the game to
take a day off while using almost every explanation imaginable,
stopping just short of claiming ``the dog ate my uniform.''
</P>
<P>
   Get him on the subject of his family, and Johnson turns
downright cuddly. Son, husband, father, brother, pitcher,
superstar, music lover, photographer; these are the many faces of
Randy Johnson. But there's no doubt what generates the biggest
smile and the most joy.
</P>
<P>
   Above everything else, he's a devoted family man.
</P>
<P>
   The way Johnson sees it, his job _ burning a catcher's hand with
a 98 mph fastball _ is nothing compared to the job his wife, Lisa,
does every day with their three children. In his book, she's the
Most Valuable Player of Team Johnson.
</P>
<P>
   ``Baseball revolves around my family, which I think it should
for any professional athlete,'' said Johnson, who is 2-0 with a
dazzling 1.13 ERA in his first two starts as an Astro. ``Obviously,
it's nice paychecks and a lot of freebie stuff.
</P>
<P>
   ``But the other side of it is being away from my family, and
that's probably the hardest part. My wife is the one who has to
deal with waking up in the middle of the night and taking care of
the kids. I've said, comically, that I could sleep in until one
o'clock and get room service. She's the one who has to be there 24
hours a day.''
</P>
<P>
   Nevertheless, Lisa, Samantha (3 years old), Tanner (2) and
Willow (two months) are constantly in his thoughts, and deservedly
so considering he credits them with playing a big part in his
escalation to the top of his profession.
</P>
<P>
   Earlier in his career, Johnson was his own worst enemy and
easily his own biggest critic. His emotions were about as difficult
for him to control as his blazing fastball used to be. Sometimes,
he probably didn't know where either was going.
</P>
<P>
   Then he met Lisa, and the truly important things in life began
to fall neatly into perspective. That, coupled with the Christmas
Day death of his father in 1993, had a lot to do with shaping the
man Astros fans hope will help lead the team to its first World
Series.
</P>
<P>
   But who is Randy Johnson? What makes him so complex yet so
simple? What makes him a pit bull on the days he pitches but a
teddy bear when approached by autograph seekers at the Galleria,
where he did some shopping on the eve of his Astros home debut?
</P>
<P>
   There he was _ all 6-10 of him _ striding through Houston's
biggest shopping mall as if he were a kid who had just been dropped
off by his mom. Being recognized as the one and only Big Unit was
the least of his worries.
</P>
<P>
   Not surprisingly, he was spotted.
</P>
<P>
   ``I got a haircut, so it couldn't have been the hair,'' cracked
Johnson, whose quick wit should be as much a part of his reputation
as strikeouts. ``Maybe it was the height.''
</P>
<P>
   Ah, the height. That's where everything begins with Johnson, who
along with former Mets pitcher Eric Hillman are the tallest players
in major-league history. It causes stares, and it's the first thing
people notice when they see him coming their way. It's even more
unique to see someone Johnson's size stuffed into a baseball
uniform.
</P>
<P>
   Freak show? Hardly. Considering the way Johnson pitches, his
performances are more like a thrill show.
</P>
<P>
   But Johnson has always known there was a certain appeal to his
size.
</P>
<P>
   ``I realize I'm an oddity being 6-foot-10,'' he said. ``But I'm
really no different than (teammate) Shane Reynolds.''
</P>
<P>
   Johnson is humble that way. He's only been an Astro for eight
days, but he's made one thing clear during the short time he's been
on the scene: He doesn't like special attention or anything that
detracts from the team.
</P>
<P>
   Perhaps Johnson feels so strongly on the subject because he
wasn't always the definition of dominant.
</P>
<P>
   Growing up in the small Northern California town of Walnut
Creek, Johnson was just another kid playing a game of street ball.
He pretended to be former big-league pitcher Vida Blue, who starred
for the Oakland Athletics and San Francisco Giants, but he never
entertained any real thoughts of following in his hero's footsteps.
</P>
<P>
   ``I never envisioned playing professional baseball,'' said
Johnson, the youngest of six children. ``Growing up 40 minutes east
of Oakland, Vida Blue was a pitcher I always watched, but that's
about as far as it went. A lot of people say they want to be a
professional athlete, but very few of them go on to do it. I feel
very lucky and gifted to be blessed with a good fastball.''
</P>
<P>
   That much was obvious in high school. While not as dominant as
he is today, Johnson clearly remembers throwing harder than most of
the kids in his two-high school town. Suddenly, playing baseball
for a living didn't seem so far-fetched.
</P>
<P>
   ``As I got into high school _ my junior and senior years _ I
realized scouts were watching me and that there was some interest
in my ability,'' Johnson said. ``There were also some colleges. At
that time I realized I might have a chance to go farther. I started
concentrating on learning how to pitch instead of just being a
thrower like I had been in the past.''
</P>
<P>
   The Atlanta Braves drafted Johnson in the third round out of
high school in 1982, but he decided to attend the University of
Southern California instead. After three years of watching him
pitch for the Trojans, big-league scouts were on Johnson's trail
again.
</P>
<P>
   The Montreal Expos picked him in the second round of the 1985
draft, beginning his career in professional baseball. Johnson spent
a year each at Class A Jamestown (N.Y.), Class A West Palm Beach
(Fla.), Class AA Jacksonville and Class AAA Indianapolis before the
Expos thought he was ready to make his major-league debut in 1988.
</P>
<P>
   ``During that span of four years, I got a lot of coaching and
developed more into a pitcher,'' Johnson said. ``(Pitching coaches)
Rick Williams and Joe Kerrigan took me under their wings and gave
me extra tutelage. When most of the guys were done for the day, I
stayed an extra hour to get more work.''
</P>
<P>
   It paid immediate dividends.
</P>
<P>
   Johnson was 3-0 with a 2.42 ERA in his first taste of the big
leagues. He opened the following season with the Expos but was sent
back to Indianapolis. Coincidentally, the Expos were at the
Astrodome at the time of Johnson's demotion.
</P>
<P>
   Later that season, he was traded to Seattle, where his career
would eventually began to soar. Johnson won 133 games in 9{ seasons
with the Mariners, and in Seattle he was close to one of his other
loves: rock music. Seattle is famous for the grunge sound, and
several groups emerged from there during the 1980s and 1990s.
Johnson, who plays the drums, became friends with members of
Soundgarden and Bush among other local bands.
</P>
<P>
   It was also in Seattle where he met Lisa and experienced the
birth of their three children. Most of his friendships in baseball
were established during his tenure with the Mariners, which is one
of the main reasons it was difficult for him to leave them.
</P>
<P>
   Johnson, who is eligible to become a free agent at the end of
the season, knew his days in Seattle were numbered when the
Mariners decided against offering him a contract extension. It
began an ugly saga that lasted through most of this season and led
to his giving the media the silent treatment for 1{ months because
he thought the contract issue was becoming a distraction for the
team. Some in the media had begun to question Johnson's desire,
which didn't sit well with him at all.
</P>
<P>
   ``I have a lot of mannerisms out there,'' he said. ``I slap my
chest with my glove and get real animated. If I didn't do that,
people thought that I wasn't into the game. Well, I haven't done
that in my two starts (with the Astros), but I think I've pitched
pretty well.
</P>
<P>
   ``That doesn't mean I'm not into the game. It's just something
that kind of flows out of me. When I get in a routine, it all comes
natural. I'm just as much of a competitor as the next guy. I don't
like to lose. That's why it was so hard in Seattle. People are
always saying you have to put all of that stuff behind you, but
it's not that easy.''
</P>
<P>
   Talk began to surface about Johnson being moody and volatile.
Was that just a case of the Big Unit being misunderstood?
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm not a shy person, but people have said I'm a loner,''
Johnson said. ``I kind of keep to myself, I don't make a lot of
noise, and I don't cause any trouble. I just kind of do my own
thing.''
</P>
<P>
   Especially on days when he's pitching.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's a different story,'' he said. ``My wife doesn't even
come up to me on the days I pitch. I'm trying to fit in right now,
but if I'm pitching, don't be surprised if I give you a dirty look
and growl at you.''
</P>
<P>
   Beginning to comprehend Johnson means understanding and
accepting that he has no desire to be a one-man show. He's already
warned against expecting miracles of biblical proportions, and he's
been quick to praise the work of his new teammates and stress the
significance they will play in the Astros' quest for October glory.
</P>
<P>
   With a Cy Young Award on his mantel and a long history of
success to his credit, Johnson is no stranger to media attention.
But even he has been overwhelmed by the volume of reporters who
have scurried from the woodwork to stick a microphone or notepad in
his face since the Mariners traded him to the Astros last week.
</P>
<P>
   The effect at the box office has been similar.
</P>
<P>
   Johnson's Astrodome debut attracted 52,071 fans to the Dome for
Friday's game against the Philadelphia Phillies. It was the largest
regular-season crowd in Astrodome history.
</P>
<P>
   ``All of this attention is kind of embarrassing,'' said Johnson,
34. ``I'm sure it will stop, but hopefully the hype will stay here
for the team. You don't often get the opportunity to be in a city
where you have a championship-caliber team. There should be
35,000-40,000 people here every night. I know it's not in
everyone's budget, but for those who it is, come out and support
us, because this is exciting.''
</P>
<P>
   The Astros' main reason for acquiring Johnson was the fact he
gives them a bona fide staff ace who can match up with any starter
in the majors. That's a valuable commodity to have in the playoffs.
But don't think for a minute the Astros weren't cognizant of
Johnson's drawing power.
</P>
<P>
   Johnson isn't uncomfortable with his status as an attraction,
but he wouldn't feel comfortable playing for a team that only
wanted him for that purpose. He knows that isn't the case in
Houston, where the Astros are just as hungry for a championship
ring as he is.
</P>
<P>
   ``If that were the case, I'd almost feel like a three-ring
circus, and I'm in the middle ring,'' he said. ``I guess it's a
novelty going to a game when you can watch a guy strike out a lot
of people, much like it's fun to watch Mark McGwire have a chance
to hit a home run farther than you've ever seen. But I'm still a
little overwhelmed by all of the attention.''
</P>
<P>
   One can assume the lights never shined this brightly in Walnut
Creek.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
