<SLUG> BC-BBN-METS-ROCKIES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
METS BEAT ROCKIES, 4-3  
 (HLW) 
</HEADLINE>
   By JASON DIAMOS   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   DENVER _ Armando Reynoso is the antithesis of the power pitcher.
Just ask Darryl Hamilton, who Saturday described Reynoso's fastball
as ``his dead-fish pitch.''
</P>
<P>
   But there is no doubt that Reynoso can pitch, regardless of how
hard he can throw. And Saturday afternoon, as Reynoso's former
manager, Don Baylor, said, ``Armando pitched an Armando game.''
</P>
<P>
   Behind seven strong innings from Reynoso _ in his first game
back at Coors Field since he played for the Rockies from 1993-1996
_ and a gutty relief performance from Turk Wendell, the Mets held
off the Colorado Rockies, 4-3, to clinch their first winning series
here in four seasons.
</P>
<P>
   The victory was the Mets' 14th in their last 20 games and their
second in a row in a place that has never been very kind to them.
More important, the Mets (62-52) pulled as close as half a game and
.003 percentage points of the Chicago Cubs in the National League
wild-card race.
</P>
<P>
   ``That would be really good news if we each had one more to
play,'' Mets Manager Bobby Valentine said. ``But there is still a
long way to go.''
</P>
<P>
   Knowing the Mets, who have won their last four games by one run,
it should be exciting. The Mets won Saturday with the help of a
two-run home run from Edgardo Alfonzo and two doubles from the
red-hot John Olerud. Olerud is the National League's leading
hitter, at .346, and he extended his hitting streak to 22 games,
the longest in the league this season and two off Hubie Brooks'
club record.
</P>
<P>
   But there was no way the Mets could have won without the
performances of Reynoso and those who followed him. Reynoso (3-0)
allowed 10 hits in his seven-plus innings, but gave up only two
earned runs in one of the toughest parks to pitch in in all of
baseball.
</P>
<P>
   ``It just shows you what you can do with an 86 mile per hour
fastball,'' Valentine said. ``And that's when the wind's at his
back.''
</P>
<P>
   Baylor said: ``He scattered 10 hits. That's the way he
pitches.''
</P>
<P>
   Wendell, meanwhile, came in in the set-up role for one of the
few times this season, in relief of Dennis Cook, who only faced one
batter, with the Mets up, 4-2, runners on first and second and one
out in the eighth. A Mike Piazza passed ball (on a Wendell slider
that broke the wrong way) and a Mike Lansing ground-ball single to
left, and it was a one-run game.
</P>
<P>
   But with runners on first and third, Wendell caught Jeff Reed
looking with an 0-2 fastball for the second out of the inning, then
induced pinch-hitter Derrick White into an inning-ending force-out
at second base.
</P>
<P>
   John Franco pitched a scoreless ninth, retiring Dante Bichette
on a popout to second with a runner on first for the final out.
Franco's 23rd save and second in as many days left Reynoso, whose
earned run average over 22 innings this season is a spartan 0.82,
undefeated in 1998.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was not really strange,'' Reynoso said of pitching at Coors
Field. ``I just tried to pitch the way I know and the way I know
them, too. They got a lot of base hits and I had a lot of runners
on base. But I always got out of problems with not much damage.''
</P>
<P>
   Coming in, Reynoso, 32, had not allowed an earned run in 15
innings this season, after missing more than a year due to arm
troubles. But the Rockies scored a run off their former teammate in
the bottom of the first to erase a 1-0 lead.
</P>
<P>
   In the third, however, Alfonzo lofted his eighth home run of the
season, a two-run shot over the scoreboard in right for a 3-1 Mets'
lead.
</P>
<P>
   An inning later, the Colorado left-hander Bobby Jones (no
relation to Bobby Jones in the Mets' rotation) delivered a two-out,
run-scoring single off Reynoso to make it 3-2.
</P>
<P>
   But the Mets rallied. With two outs in the top of the fifth,
Olerud lined an inside fast ball into the right field corner for
his second double. Piazza followed with a hard grounder to third
that glanced off Castilla's glove and into left field, the error
scoring Olerud for a 4-2 lead.
</P>
<P>
   Reynoso made it look easy. He set the Rockies down on five
pitches in the bottom of the fifth, retired the side on seven
pitches in the sixth, then retired the side in order on six pitches
in the seventh. His pitch count was only at 89 heading into the
eighth.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was amazing,'' Jones said later. ``He jammed guys with an
85 mile per hour fast ball.''
</P>
<P>
   As it turned out, Reynoso would not record another out. But
Cook, Wendell and Franco were able to bail him out _ something the
Mets' bullpen had had trouble doing before this road trip.
</P>
<P>
   Cook said, ``That's the way it's supposed to work.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
