<HEADER>
A4850 &Cx1f; taf-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BBA-YANKS-ROYALS-NYT &LR;      08-08 0808
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBA-YANKS-ROYALS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
YANKS BEAT ROYALS, 14-1  
 (HLW) 
</HEADLINE>
   By BUSTER OLNEY   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Forfeiting to the Yankees would be more beneficial
than playing them, a rival American League manager suggested
earlier this season. A forfeit is neat and clean, while playing the
Yankees is messy and depressing, serving only to confirm their
greatness _ and just how crummy you are by comparison.
</P>
<P>
   The Kansas City Royals had won 6 of 7 games before coming here,
playing good baseball in the estimation of their manager, Tony
Muser. But in three games over two days against the Yankees, the
Royals have been wiped out by a composite score of 36-5. Playing
before 45,975 at Yankee Stadium Saturday, the Yankees drubbed
Kansas City, 14-1 _ the third time in the last six days the Yankees
had scored 14 runs.
</P>
<P>
   The Yankees are 83-29, they have won three straight games, their
snowball is careering down the mountainside of this 162-game
schedule and there does not appear to be any way to slow them down.
Think about this: The last time they played a game without holding
a lead was June 28, against the Mets at Shea Stadium. They have
held a lead in 37 consecutive games. They are relentless.
</P>
<P>
   ``It becomes a morale factor,'' said Muser, who is very
competitive by nature and not the manager who talked about a
forfeit. ``We were playing pretty good coming in here, and we
couldn't have felt any better about ourselves. I can tell you this:
The New York Yankees have put us in a different frame of mind.
</P>
<P>
   ``Overall, we haven't accepted the challenge like I would like.
We have a game left, and I hope tomorrow to come out and play
better baseball. It looked like we were maybe going to turn the
corner today, in the first five innings.''
</P>
<P>
   Kansas City turned the corner in the fifth, trailing Orlando
Hernandez by 1-0 _ and then got smothered under an avalanche of
Yankee runs. One run in the fifth, six runs in the sixth, three
runs in the seventh and three more in the eighth. Jorge Posada
drove in a career-high six runs, Scott Brosius hit a three-run home
run and Chuck Knoblauch smashed his 15th home run.
</P>
<P>
   This does not seem like baseball anymore. This is Nebraska
against Prairie View in football; the Cornhuskers rush for 650
yards, the Yankees are averaging 10.1 runs per game over their last
seven games.
</P>
<P>
   The Yankees lead the American League in earned run average
(3.57). They have allowed the second-fewest unearned runs (27), and
have committed errors in only 1 of their last 10 games. They are
averaging 6.1 runs per game, while allowing 3.8.
</P>
<P>
   Hernandez (7-3) stifled the Royals, as David Cone and David
Wells had in Friday's doubleheader.
</P>
<P>
   ``That probably is as good as starting pitching as we've seen in
three consecutive games all season,'' Muser said. ``And as good as
offensive production as we've seen all season.''
</P>
<P>
   The Yankees are so far ahead now in the American League East
that they will spend the rest of the regular season chasing records
and smoothing wrinkles before the post-season.
</P>
<P>
   Hernandez allowed 10 runs and 13 hits in Anaheim on July 29, and
the next day Mel Stottlemyre, the Yankees' pitching coach, spoke to
him about pace.
</P>
<P>
   Pitchers tend to be more effective if they work quickly,
Stottlemyre told him; their fielders' reactions are sharper.
Hernandez had fallen into the habit of working slowly, of nibbling
at the edges of the strike zone.
</P>
<P>
   Eager to learn and agreeable to whatever the Yankees have asked,
Hernandez increased his pace and aggressiveness, as if he had
traded in an Edsel for a Porsche.
</P>
<P>
   Saturday, Hernandez would throw a pitch and then take the throw
from Posada, the catcher, as he was returning to the rubber. He
worked quickly enough that in the second inning, some of the Kansas
City batters began stepping out, trying to disrupt Hernandez's
tempo.
</P>
<P>
   But they could do nothing to adjust to his repertory, which was
more varied and better deployed than in any of his previous 11
appearances. Often passive with his fastball before, Hernandez
fired his fastballs inside repeatedly Saturday, creating a major
problem for the Kansas City hitters, who were preparing for his
breaking pitches.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was the best stuff he's had,'' Posada said. ``It was the
best I've seen him throw.''
</P>
<P>
   The Royals' Scott Leius and Mendy Lopez struck out on fastballs,
with the ball buried deeply in Posada's glove when each started his
swing.
</P>
<P>
   The five right-handed hitters in the Kansas City lineup
sometimes fell backward as they swung at Hernandez's sidearm
slider, which was accentuated by the shadows drifting across the
sky during the late afternoon game.
</P>
<P>
   The Royals mustered just four hits in eight innings against El
Duque, who struck out seven.
</P>
<P>
   And Sunday Kansas City faces Andy Pettitte. Relentless.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
