<DATE_TIME> 1998-08-08 23:41 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4852 &Cx1f; ttx-z
r s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-REEVES-COL-TEX     08-08 1416
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-REEVES-COL-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>


</HEADLINE>
 
NEWS MEDIA AND THE McIVER STORY 
(For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By JIM REEVES 
c.1998 Fort Worth Star-Telegram
<TEXT>
<P>
   Dale Hansen, the Dallas-Fort Worth WFAA/Channel 8 sports anchor
whose reporters took the early lead in advancing the real story
behind the Everett McIver situation in Wichita Falls, is missing
the point when he says on the radio that the local papers haven't
been as aggressive in handling the story because they're running
scared of the Cowboys.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's an attitude among the media that `We don't want to
take on the Cowboys, we certainly don't want to take on Michael
Irvin and any lawsuits and we don't want to take on the fans,'''
Hansen contends. ``Should we be careful? Absolutely. But that
doesn't mean you don't pursue the story as aggressively today as we
did three years ago.''
</P>
<P>
   He may be closer on the last point than the first two. Maybe
what we're afraid of is being wrong and further destroying
credibility with the fans. Maybe we actually learned something from
the last time almost everyone went crazy over a story about Michael
Irvin.
</P>
<P>
   That something may have more to do with being cautiously fair
than with concern about lawsuits or stepping on Jerry Jones' toes.
</P>
<P>
   Granted, there's an argument to be made that when the
Star-Telegram reported that Irvin was involved, the story could
have been played on the section cover instead of Page 5. The reason
it wasn't was because 95 percent of the story was a rehash of what
had already been reported and it was an editor's decision to keep
it inside.
</P>
<P>
   Irvin's name was surfacing for the first time but with no real
particulars about how he was involved. It was Hansen and his team
who then followed up with details about a haircut and scissors and
ending with McIver sustaining the cut on his neck.
</P>
<P>
   That this story has been more radio talk show-TV talk driven
rather than a made-for-newspaper story is inarguable. The Cowboys'
shutdown of information has made it extremely difficult to advance
the story from a newspaper reporting standpoint.
</P>
<P>
   The talk shows, meanwhile, don't have to have new information to
speculate and talk the issue to death, and they have.
</P>
<P>
   What is being forgotten in the debate over the media's handling
of the story _ and don't you know Jones is loving that red herring
_ is that the Cowboys, who spent so much time and money to change
their image, now are clearly involved in an unseemly coverup,
apparently to protect Irvin.
</P>
<P>
   It won't last. It can't.
</P>
<P>
   Any man who's ever been to a barbershop knows there's one thing
that barbers _ and new rumors indicate there may have been two of
them in that dorm room _ do even better than cut hair.
</P>
<P>
   They talk....
</P>
<P>
   You've got to like the attitude new starting pitcher Todd
Stottlemyre brings to the Rangers. When Stottlemyre was in Toronto,
baseball writers there regularly got up a pot each spring, wagering
on which of the Blue Jays' pitchers would hit the first home run
when the team played National League opponents during exhibition
season. Stottlemyre heard about the pool, asked whether he could
get in and always selected himself as the Blue Jays' pitcher who
would be first to swat one out of the park. ...
</P>
<P>
   Uh oh. Coming over to the ``S-T'' might force columnist Randy
Galloway into the computer age whether he likes it or not.
Galloway, who once vowed that his editors would have to pry his
ancient Underwood portable typewriter out of his cold, dead
fingers, was issued a state of the art laptop the other day, and
his eyes started rolling like a slot machine.
</P>
<P>
   A TV producer at The Ballpark congratulated Galloway on his move
but complained that he couldn't get the ``S-T'' delivered to his
home in Garland.
</P>
<P>
   ``No problem,'' answered Galloway, being the high-tech, '90s guy
that he is. ``You can just call me up on the ``intercom.'''' On the
information superhighway, some are 18-wheelers and some of us are
just roadkill. ...
</P>
<P>
   You think Cowboys defensive line coach Jim Bates doesn't like
No. 1 draft pick Greg Ellis? ``He has all the intangibles, all the
things you look for in an athlete,'' Bates says. ``He's got size,
he's got arm reach, he's got power, he's got good speed, and
mentally he's a very intelligent and a very competitive person.
He's got all the ingredients to make a good player.''
</P>
<P>
   Now if Ellis could just get a preseason sack.
</P>
<P>
   ``You never know when the light's going to go on for a rookie,''
Bates says. ``Sometimes it takes a half a year, sometimes a couple
of years for a youngster to come into his own and be as good as he
can be.''...
</P>
<P>
   Never mind Rusty Greer for Roger Clemens. If the Rangers had
really wanted ``The Rocket,'' it would have taken Greer, Darren
Oliver and top prospect Ruben Mateo. That's two outfielders who'll
be starting here in 2000, plus Oliver for a 36-year-old
right-hander. Yep, I'd love to have Clemens starting twice against
the Yankees in the playoffs, too, but that one makes me pause for
some deep thought. ...
</P>
<P>
   I'm still thinking. ...
</P>
<P>
   I didn't have a chance to spend as much time with legendary golf
writer Bob Green and his wife, Ivy, as I would have liked, but on
those occasions when they visited at Colonial the past few years,
Bob was invariably upbeat, congenial, gentle and kind, despite the
cancer that finally took his life.
</P>
<P>
   It was no surprise when Green was buried in Weatherford last
week that golfer Lanny Wadkins, Tom Kite's wife, Christy, and PGA
officials John Morris, Lee Patterson, Marty Caffey and Chris Smith
were in attendance at the services. ...
</P>
<P>
   Cowboys coach Chan Gailey entertained his old high school coach
from Americus, Ga., Johnny Hightower, last week in Wichita Falls
and said he has a soft spot for high school coaches in general.
</P>
<P>
   ``High school coaches impact our society maybe more than any
other group because they impact athletes,'' Gailey says, ``and
athletes in general, men and women, are the ones who become
society's leaders as they go on down the line.''...
</P>
<P>
   Running back Emmitt Smith says the Cowboys can't allow
themselves to use the fact that they're implementing a new offense
as an excuse to start slowly this season.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm not someone who believes that just because it's our first
year \Rwith a new offense\S that we have to start slow,'' Smith
says. ``We don't have to start off 0-and-6. We are professionals. I
expect everybody to go out there and do their jobs. You give them
the playbook, then you iron out the little mistakes so you can make
the big plays happen.''...
</P>
<P>
   A double dose of bad news arrives from the Rangers' training
camp in Port Charlotte, Fla. Joan Santucci, owner along with
husband Frank of Charlie's Raw Bar, a favored dining spot for
players, writers, club officials and fans, lost her battle with
cancer last week. She had dreamed of someday opening a Charlie's
close to The Ballpark in Arlington. Our hearts go out to Frank, her
family and her many friends. ...
</P>
<P>
   This on the heels of reports that the famed ``776'' roadhouse at
El Jobean, refuge of baseball writers and club officials alike, has
closed it doors. Sigh. Things will never be the same there again.
...
</P>
<P>
   The Rangers' search for a left-hander for the bullpen is at
least semicritical, as Mo Vaughn's homer off Eric Gunderson on
Thursday night attests. Which makes it at least semi-interesting
that the Rangers allowed Randy Myers to slip through waivers to San
Diego. Myers would have been the perfect lefty setup man for John
Wetteland, but general manager Doug Melvin balked at picking up
Myers' $6 million a year contract, which runs through next season.
``That's a little stiff for a setup man,'' Melvin says. ...
</P>
<P>
   The Rangers' GM is very high on Rangers farmhand Mike Venafro,
the left-hander promoted to Oklahoma from Tulsa, but don't look for
him before September. ...
</P>
<P>
   Montreal left-hander Carlos Perez was on Melvin's list of
pitching possibilities as the trade deadline approached but along
with a high asking price, there were concerns about team chemistry.
...
</P>
<P>
   Forget Viagra, get me some of whatever Albatross had been
eating. When he departed for that Great Stud Pasture in the sky
last week, the magnificent harness-racing champion had sired 2,546
offspring. And counting. Do we even need to ask how he died?
</P>
<P>
   And then there was this headline in the official Rangers' notes
package the other night: ``Wives Auction Tomorrow.'' No word on
which wife attracted the highest bid or who bought her.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-08-08-98 2341EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
